{ @@HeaderStart@@The king and other weak points@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. --
{ One typical consequence of a delay in development is that the king becomes exposed to an attack. When the enemy pieces start gathering around the monarch, and his fellow forces remain immobilized, the battle usually turns into “play against one goal”  (to use soccer language)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1 The King and Other Weak Points"]
[Black "Ma.Carlsen-S.Dolmatov Moscow 2004 Reti’s Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ Instead of entering the Dutch Defence with  2.d4  , White prepares e2-e4, striking at the light squares. }
2... d6
{ The natural  2...Nf6  can be met by the gambit  3.e4  fxe4  4.dxe4  Nxe4  5.Bd3  Nf6  6.Ng5  with attacking prospects. }
3. e4 e5 4. Nc3 Nc6 { Black appears to be in a safe position; however... } 5.
exf5 Bxf5 6. d4
{ A key move that clears the centre before Black gets castled. Now the king's bishop can be developed actively to c4 or b5. }
6... Nxd4
{ 6...e4  seems preferable, trying to keep the position closed when behind in development. Here White can choose between  7.d5  and  7.Ng5  d5  8.f3  hitting the black pawn chain, with interesting prospects in both cases. }
7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Qxd4 Nf6
{ The greedy  8...Bxc2  probably wasn't even considered by Dolmatov, since  9.Bc4  followed by O-O and Re1 looks extremely dangerous for Black. }
9. Bc4
{ The best diagonal for this bishop, where it complicates Black's short casting. }
9... c6 10. Bg5 b5
{ Thanks to White's previous move, he can now meet the logical  10...d5  by  11.O-O-O  intending  11...dxc4  12.Qe5+   Black is also in trouble after  11...Be7  12.Rhe1  O-O  13.Qe5 }
11. Bb3 Be7 12. O-O-O Qd7 13. Rhe1
{ Carlsen's play in this game reminds me of Morphy's simple but effective treatment of the opening phase. In just 13 moves he has mobilized all his pieces and  13.Rhe1  now creates the concrete threat of  13...--  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Qxf6  . On his part, Dolmatov would be fine if his king and a8-rook changed places, but that will never prove possible. }
13... Kd8
{ An awkward place for the king.Throughout the book we will see many positions where a lead in development has to be exploited by concrete means; i.e. by tactical blows, sacrifices etc. Here is a first case.   But  13...O-O-O  was impossible due to  14.g4  Bxg4   @@StartBracket@@or  14...Bg6  15.Be6  @@EndBracket@@  15.Rxe7  Qxe7  16.Qxg4+  with material gains. }
14. Rxe7
{ Initiating a decisive combination to-wards the king on d8. In positions with unbalanced development we should get used to considering the relative value of the pieces. The bishop on e7 is Black's key defender, covering vital squares such as d6 and f6. Conversely, White has so many pieces in action that losing one of them, even one having a greater nominal value than the enemy piece being captured, isn't really a big deal. With such rooks on a8 on h8, how is Black supposed to save his king? }
14... Qxe7 { Or  14...Kxe7  15.Bxf6+  gxf6  16.Re1+  followed by  17. Qxf6+. }
15. Qf4 Bd7 16. Ne4
{ Intensifying the attack.   In contrast,  16.Rxd6  Kc8  lets Black hang on for a while. }
16... d5
{ Or  16...Rf8  17.Nxd6  with ideas like Qb4-a5+. With such an exposed king Black can hardly resist the attack. }
17. Nxf6 h6 18. Bh4 g5 19. Qd4
{ A nice final touch directed at the rook on h8.   Now if  19.Qd4  gxh4  20.Nxd5  , then  20...cxd5  21.Qxh8+  , while other 20th moves run into 21. Nf6, in both cases with an easy win for White, so Black resigned.   Not much better is  19...Rf8  20.Nxd7  Qxd7  21.Bg3  with an overwhelming advantage }
*

