{ An awkward place for the king.Throughout the book we will see many positions where a lead in development has to be exploited by concrete means; i.e. by tactical blows, sacrifices etc. Here is a first case.   But  13...O-O-O  was impossible due to  14.g4  Bxg4   @@StartBracket@@or  14...Bg6  15.Be6  @@EndBracket@@  15.Rxe7  Qxe7  16.Qxg4+  with material gains. }
14. Rxe7
{ Initiating a decisive combination to-wards the king on d8. In positions with unbalanced development we should get used to considering the relative value of the pieces. The bishop on e7 is Black's key defender, covering vital squares such as d6 and f6. Conversely, White has so many pieces in action that losing one of them, even one having a greater nominal value than the enemy piece being captured, isn't really a big deal. With such rooks on a8 on h8, how is Black supposed to save his king? }
14... Qxe7 { Or  14...Kxe7  15.Bxf6+  gxf6  16.Re1+  followed by  17. Qxf6+. }
