[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "Pawn advances "]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Pawn advances@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. --
{ Another key method for the better developed side is a pawn advance, if necessary in the shape of a sacrifice, that opens the position and clears new lines towards the enemy camp.   Actually Movsesian did just that with 18. c4! in the previous game. Here are a few more examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "V.Topalov-V.Ivanchuk Linares 1999 English Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6
{ In this variation of the English, White enjoys more space but Black is ready to create counterplay with his queen and king's bishop on the g1-a7 and e1-a5 diagonals. }
5. g3
{ More common is  5.Nc3  .   5.g3  keeps the option of meeting  5...Bb4+  with  6.Bd2  , although Topalov never makes use of this idea in the game. }
5... Bb4+ 6. Nc3 Qa5
{ As beginners we are taught not to bring out the queen too early, but here it helps Black in interfering with White's development. }
7. Nb5 d5 { Ruling out the knight check on d6 and fighting for the centre. } 8.
a3
{ Consistent with White's previous play, if rather slow. Stohl suggests  8.Bf4  e5   @@StartBracket@@or  8...d4  9.a3  @@EndBracket@@  9.Bd2  , when both  9...dxc4   @@StartBracket@@and  9...d4  10.Nd5  @@EndBracket@@  10.a3  Bxc3  11.Nd6+  Kf8  12.Bxc3  Qc5  13.Bg2  lead to an interesting battle. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3
{ In the event of  9.Nxc3  Black may choose between the simple  9...dxc4  , now that the knight check on  d6  is no longer possible.   And the riskier  9...d4  10.b4  Nxb4  11.axb4  Qxa1  12.Nb5  with unclear play. }
9... Nf6
{ Ivanchuk quickly brings out the pieces, unworried about  9...Nf6  10.Nd6+  Ke7  11.Nxc8+  Raxc8  , after which Black already enjoys a significant lead in development. }
10. Bg2 O-O 11. Qb3
{ Now White's dilemma is that  11.O-O  dxc4  loses a pawn while  11.cxd5  Nxd5  leaves his pieces hanging on  b5  and  c3  . Topalov finds a third option: safeguarding his queenside with the queen, at the cost of delaying development. }
11... dxc4 12. Qxc4 e5 { Simple and strong: now 13...Be6 is coming up. } 13.
Nd6 Be6 14. Qd3
{ By tactical means White has managed to stay above water.   Here  14.Qd3  Rad8   and  14...Rfd8  fail to  15.Nxb7  , but Ivanchuk has a much stronger move in reserve... }
14... e4
{ Another typical punishment method when the opponent has delayed his development: open the position. Now the e-file will be of great use in the attack towards White's king, and the annoying knight on d6 leaves the board. }
15. Nxe4
{ Queen moves all had their drawbacks:  15.Qc2  Nd4   - or  15.Qe3  Ng4   - or  15.Qd2  Rad8  .   As for  15.Bxe4  , Black can reply  15...Nxe4  16.Nxe4  Rad8  with a strong initiative just like in the game - Ivanchuk. }
15... Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Rad8 17. Qc2
{ After  17.Qe3  Rfe8  White is also in big trouble. } 17... Nd4 18. Qb2
{ Topalov has defended well and is just one move away from the desired O-O; however... }
18... Nxe2
{ One more sacrifice to force the white king to stay in the centre. Less promising was  18...Bc4  19.Qb4   or  18...Rfe8  19.O-O  Bh3  20.cxd4  Bxf1  21.Bf3  In both these short lines, White applies a common method when behind in development: return the material invested in order to bring out the pieces. }
19. Kxe2
{ If  19.Qb4  , trying to apply the method described in the previous note, then  19...Nxc3  with heavy material gains thanks to the mating threat on  d1  . }
19... Rfe8
{ A flexible move typical of many attacks. If we look at the two pieces on f8 and e6, it is obvious that the rook is heading for e8, whereas the bishop has so many possible destinies that it shouldn't be committed yet.   Less promising is  19...Bc4+  20.Kf3  f5  21.Bxb7  Bd5+  22.Ke2  Bxb7  23.Qxb7  Qxc3  24.Be3  Qc4+  25.Ke1  Qc3+  with a draw - Ivanchuk. }
20. Qb4
{ After  20.f3  f5  White is also in deep trouble;   while  20.Re1  is met by  20...Qh5+  21.Kf1  Bh3+  22.Kg1  Rxe4  - Ivanchuk. }
20... Qh5+ 21. f3 f5
{ Finally crashing through White's defence, who can only resort to desperate moves. }
22. g4 Qh3 { The threat 23...Qg2+ is added to the menu. } 23. gxf5 Bxf5
{ A typical pattern in games with unbalanced development: the attacker has less material but overwhelmingly more activity. With his king stranded on e2, there is no hope for White.   Another option was  23...Qg2+  24.Ke3  Qxh1  25.fxe6  Rd1  , but a direct attack on the white king is more tempting. }
24. Qc4+ Kh8 25. Re1 Rxe4+
{ The most elegant finish.   White resigned in view of  25...Rxe4+  26.fxe4  Bg4+  27.Kf2  Qxh2+  with mate on the next move. }
*

