14... e4
{ Another typical punishment method when the opponent has delayed his development: open the position. Now the e-file will be of great use in the attack towards White's king, and the annoying knight on d6 leaves the board. }
15. Nxe4
{ Queen moves all had their drawbacks:  15.Qc2  Nd4   - or  15.Qe3  Ng4   - or  15.Qd2  Rad8  .   As for  15.Bxe4  , Black can reply  15...Nxe4  16.Nxe4  Rad8  with a strong initiative just like in the game - Ivanchuk. }
15... Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Rad8 17. Qc2
{ After  17.Qe3  Rfe8  White is also in big trouble. } 17... Nd4 18. Qb2
{ Topalov has defended well and is just one move away from the desired O-O; however... }
18... Nxe2
{ One more sacrifice to force the white king to stay in the centre. Less promising was  18...Bc4  19.Qb4   or  18...Rfe8  19.O-O  Bh3  20.cxd4  Bxf1  21.Bf3  In both these short lines, White applies a common method when behind in development: return the material invested in order to bring out the pieces. }
