[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "R.Nezhmetdinov-A.Chistiakov Kharkov 1956 French Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 5. e5 h6 6. Bd2 Nfd7
{ Very passive.   Nowadays, adherents of the McCutcheon Variation play  6...Bxc3  and  6.--  7...Ne4  without much thinking. }
7. Qg4 Bf8
{ In closed positions like this, such retreats are usually justified. In contrast,  7...g6  8.Bd3  would have yielded White a target on  g6  , just as later occurs in the game. }
8. Nf3 c5
{ A standard advance in the French; but  8...a6  first was safer, in order to prevent White's next move in the game. }
9. Nb5
{ Apart from threatening Nd6+, this move comes with a more long-term idea - can you spot it? }
9... g6
{ Too slow.   9...Nc6  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.Qxg7  was very bad for Black;   - but  9...cxd4  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.Qxg7  White should probably try  11.exd6  instead, with some initiative  Bxe5  12.Nxe5  Qf6  looks quite okay for him. }
10. Bd3 { Development with tempo, as 11. Bxg6 is threatened. } 10... Rg8
{ Black managed to cover all the enemy threats but now suffers a serious delay in development. Thus White's next move suggests itself. }
11. c4
{ A key advance in order to open the position before Black closes it by ...c5-c4, making White's lead in development a less relevant factor. }
11... cxd4 12. cxd5 Nc5
{ Or  12...a6  13.dxe6  axb5  14.exf7+  Kxf7  15.e6+  with a fierce attack. }
13. Qxd4 exd5
{ Black omits the intermediate move  13...Nc6  , when  14.Qe3  Nxd3+  15.Qxd3  exd5  yields him a slightly superior version of the game. }
14. Nd6+
{ White had this option for several moves, but only uses it now when the centre has been cleared, which makes Black's dark-squared bishop a key defender. The pawn invested in this operation is irrelevant. }
14... Bxd6 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. O-O { White's position plays itself. } 16... Nxd3
17. Qxd3 Nc6 18. Rfe1+ Be6 19. Nd4
{ In chess strategy, exchanges can be carried out for a variety of reasons. One of them is facilitating an attack, as in this case, where White aims at eliminating one of the defenders on e6 and c6.   Note that after  19.Nd4  Nxd4  20.Qxd4  the presence of opposite-coloured bishops favours White, since the opponent will have a difficult task covering the dark squares. }
19... g5
{ After  19...O-O-O  20.Rac1  the black king is in big trouble. In the game he tries to hide it on  d7  , but White has enough material for a successful attack. }
20. Rac1 Kd7 21. Nf5
{ After mobilizing all his pieces, White initiates concrete actions. } 21...
Qf8 22. Qb5 Rc8 23. Qxb7+ Rc7 24. Qb5 a6
{ Obviously  24...Bxf5  runs into  25.Qxd5+  . } 25. Qd3 Qb8 26. Nxh6 Rg6 27.
Nxf7 { The final blow which destroys the black king's shelter. } 27... Bxf7 28.
Qf5+ Kd8 { Or  28...Kd6  29.Bxg5  with decisive threats. } 29. Rxc6 Rcxc6 30.
Ba5+ Qc7 31. Qxf7 Kc8 32. Bxc7 *

