[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "K.Miton-J.Sammour Hasbun Stratton Mountain 1999 Slav Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 a6
{ The Chebanenko Slav became very popular in the nineties, thanks to its flexibility and great room for creativity. One merit of this system is that Black can play 4...a6 against virtually any white move order. }
5. Bd3
{ Development and at the same time restriction of Black's ...Bf5.  Other options are:   -  5.Nf3   -  5.Qc2   -  5.a4  . }
5... Bg4
{ Perhaps  5...b5  6.b3  Bg4  is a more precise move order, avoiding White's queen sortie to b3. }
6. Qb3 Ra7
{ The safest way of dealing with the threat at b7. The rook is temporarily out of play but can later return to the eighth rank once the b-pawn has been protected by another piece, e.g. by ...Qc7. }
7. h3 Bh5 8. Nge2 Bg6
{ Black is anxious to exchange the opponent's 'good' bishop, but loses precious time.  8...e6  seems preferable, speeding up development; e.g.  9.Nf4  Bg6  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.O-O  Bd6  followed by ...O-O. }
9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. O-O e6
{ At this point it is not clear how to exploit the slight lead in development, but Miton finds a surprisingly simple solution. }
11. e4 dxc4
{ The safest reply.   White's idea was that both  11...Nxe4  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Be3  .   And  11...dxe4  12.Be3  would leave Black struggling to find a defence against d4-d5. }
12. Qxc4 b5 13. Qb3 b4
{ Having seen the rest of the game it is easy to suggest  13...Be7  14.Be3  Rd7  followed by ...O-O in order to conclude development. Sammour probably felt that 13...b4 was justified by the enemy queen's retreat to  b3  instead of  d3  , but this is not so. }
14. e5
{ By trading the knight on c3 for the one on f6 White manages to clear lines, in particular the b-file, towards Black's underdeveloped camp. }
14... bxc3 15. exf6 cxb2
{ Black grabs a pawn when it is ill-afforded.   The simple  15...gxf6  16.bxc3  Bd6  followed by ...O-O was called for. White's superior structure implies some advantage in the middlegame, but at least all Black's pieces get into play. }
16. Bxb2 gxf6
{ By now there is only one move that can justify White's previous play... } 17.
d5
{ The key move of the game, which clears several new lines towards the enemy king.   After  17.d5  , the strong threat of  17...--  18.Bxf6  Qxf6  19.Qxb8+  leaves Black with practically a single reply. }
17... e5 18. dxc6 Qc8
{ This is an early resignation, since the advanced c-pawn will just make White's attack even more powerful. For better or worse, the bold  18...Nxc6  had to be tried. Then  19.Qa4  is tempting - alas, after  19...Qd7  , both:   -  20.Rfd1  Nd4   - and  20.Rac1  Nd8  returning the pawn in order to swap queens, keep Black in the game.   A more critical try is  19.Rac1  Rc7  20.Qf3  , when  20...Qc8  21.Qxf6  Rh5  followed by ...Be7 seems survivable for Black. As will be seen more evidently in the final games of this chapter, difficult positions call for unusual solutions! }
19. Rac1 Rc7 20. Nf4
{ An aesthetic follow-up to the attack, creating the threat of 21. Nd5.   Perhaps  20.Nc3  was even more efficient, with the additional idea of  20...--  21.Ne4  . }
20... Bh6
{ 20...exf4  21.Bxf6  followed by Rfe1+ and Qb4 is terminal for Black;   While after  20...Rxc6  21.Nd5  he lacks a proper defence of the f6-pawn; e.g.  21...Nd7   or  21...Bg7  22.Ba3  preventing  ...O-O  and threatening a fork on e7.  22.Nxf6+  Nxf6  23.Qa4  Kd7  24.Rfd1+  Bd6  25.Bxe5  with a decisive attack. }
21. Nd5 Bxc1
{ How to continue the attack?   After  21...Bxc1  , none of  22.Nxc7+   @@StartBracket@@or  22.Nxf6+  Kf8  @@EndBracket@@   @@StartBracket@@or  22.Rxc1  Rxc6  23.Nxf6+  Kf8  @@EndBracket@@  Qxc7  23.Rxc1  O-O  is completely convincing. However, Miton has a much stronger move prepared... }
22. Qb4
{ While denying Black from castling, White sets up the devastating threat of 23. Qd6.   In the same spirit  22.Qa3  was also strong. }
22... Qd8
{ Giving back material in order to save the king.   22...Bg5  23.Qd6  Ra7  24.c7  wins easily;   while after  22...Bxb2  23.Qd6  Black can't cope with the double threat at  f6  and  c7  , e.g.  23...Rxc6  24.Qe7 }
23. Nxc7+ Qxc7 24. Rxc1 a5
{ In the event of  24...Nxc6  one of several winning lines is  25.Qc4  Kd7  26.Qxf7+  Kc8  27.Qxf6  etc. }
25. Qc5
{ Thanks to the strong passed pawn and Black's badly placed king, the rest is easy. }
25... g5 26. Ba3 Na6 27. Qb5 Nb4 28. Bxb4 axb4 29. Qxb4 Rh4 30. Qb7
{ The c-pawn finally takes its toll. } 30... Kd8 31. Rd1+ Rd4 32. Rxd4+ exd4
33. Kf1 { There follows Ke2-d3xd4 with an easy win, so Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "Exercise #1: Miton, K. vs. Sammour Hasbun, J."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1n1qkb1r/rp3pp1/p1p1pnp1/3p4/2PP4/1QN1P2P/PP2NPP1/R1B2RK1 w k - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ At this point it is not clear how to exploit the slight lead in development, but Miton finds a surprisingly simple solution. }
11. e4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "Exercise #2: Miton, K. vs. Sammour Hasbun, J."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1n1qkb1r/r4p2/p1p1ppp1/8/3P4/1Q5P/PB2NPP1/R4RK1 w k - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ By now there is only one move that can justify White's previous play... } 17.
d5
{ The key move of the game, which clears several new lines towards the enemy king.   After  17.d5  , the strong threat of  17...--  18.Bxf6  Qxf6  19.Qxb8+  leaves Black with practically a single reply. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2 Pawn Advances"]
[Black "Exercise #3: Miton, K. vs. Sammour Hasbun, J."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1nq1kb1r/2r2p2/p1P2pp1/4p3/8/1Q5P/PB2NPP1/2R2RK1 w k - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

20. Nf4
{ An aesthetic follow-up to the attack, creating the threat of 21. Nd5.   Perhaps  20.Nc3  was even more efficient, with the additional idea of  20...--  21.Ne4  . }
20... Bh6
{ 20...exf4  21.Bxf6  followed by Rfe1+ and Qb4 is terminal for Black;   While after  20...Rxc6  21.Nd5  he lacks a proper defence of the f6-pawn; e.g.  21...Nd7   or  21...Bg7  22.Ba3  preventing  ...O-O  and threatening a fork on e7.  22.Nxf6+  Nxf6  23.Qa4  Kd7  24.Rfd1+  Bd6  25.Bxe5  with a decisive attack. }
21. Nd5 Bxc1
{ How to continue the attack?   After  21...Bxc1  , none of  22.Nxc7+   @@StartBracket@@or  22.Nxf6+  Kf8  @@EndBracket@@   @@StartBracket@@or  22.Rxc1  Rxc6  23.Nxf6+  Kf8  @@EndBracket@@  Qxc7  23.Rxc1  O-O  is completely convincing. However, Miton has a much stronger move prepared... }
22. Qb4
{ While denying Black from castling, White sets up the devastating threat of 23. Qd6.   In the same spirit  22.Qa3  was also strong. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "Causes of delayed development"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Nobody likes to get behind in development, so why does this happen? Well, two typical causes can be identified:   ♟️One player grabs a pawn or two, thus slowing down his development.   ♟️ One player pursues strategical goals  @@StartBracket@@the bishop pair, gain of space etc@@EndBracket@@  at the cost of delaying his development.    These causes have a dual nature, in the sense that the side with a lead in development might also force his opponent to take a pawn  @@StartBracket@@ e.g. 14...e4! in Topalov-Ivanchuk @@EndBracket@@   or offer him the bishop pair, a doubling of pawns etc. In other words, the better-developed player could consider both material and strategic concessions when exploiting his lead in development.The following game neatly illustrates the first cause above, and it is one of my favourites on the topic of development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "M.Dvoretsky-Wl.Schmidt  Wijk aan Zee 1975  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ The Alapin Variation in a delayed version. Thanks to Black having already played e7-e6, White avoids some set-ups, such as the ones with ...Bg4. }
3... Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. a3
{ Preparing Bd3 without having to bother about ...Nb4. } 7... Nc6 8. Bd3 dxe5
9. dxe5 Qc7
{ Black initiates an attack on the e5-pawn at the cost of delaying development. A safer try is  9...g6  followed by ...Bg7 and ...O-O, which I have played myself in a few games. }
10. O-O
{ White doesn't worry about the pawn and just continues development. Of course  10.Qe2  Nd4  11.Nxd4  Qxc1+  had to be avoided. }
10... Nxe5
{ It wasn't yet too late for  10...g6  or  10...Be7  with a safe game. } 11.
Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Bb5+
{ A typical punishment method in positions with a lead in development: give a check in order to deprive the opponent of castling. }
12... Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7
{ When playing 10...Nxe5, Schmidt perhaps reckoned that his king would be quite safe on d7, thanks to the strong knight on d5 and the two previous piece exchanges. However, Dvoretsky's determined and logical play that follows will show us that this is not so. }
14. Re1
{ This natural rook move should be effected right away; since other moves like  14.Nc3  and 14. Qf3 permit  14...Bd6  when Black, thanks to the mating threat on  h2  , gains an important tempo for his development. }
14... Qd6 15. Qf3
{ Developing the queen with tempo, and vacating the d-file for the rooks. }
15... Ke8
{ In the event of  15...Be7  White should avoid  16.Qxf7  Raf8  with counterplay, and continue just as in the game. }
16. Nc3
{ An excellent move to eliminate the defender on d5. 'When your opponent is behind in development, exchange his developed pieces' goes another principle of opening play, which I think belongs to Yusupov. }
16... Rd8
{ After  16...Be7  17.Bd2  Rd8  18.Rad1  Black is definitely sad about having lost his castling rights. }
17. Bg5 { Such moves, developing the pieces with tempo, are rarely wrong. }
17... f6
{ Or  17...Be7  18.Bxe7  , followed by  Rad1  , with strong pressure. } 18.
Rad1
{ Another power move. The last piece enters the game with tempo thanks to the threat of Rxd5. Note that due to Black's unfortunate tenth move, not only is his king stranded in the centre, he also has one fewer rook in the battle than White. }
18... Kf7 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Bf4
{ After the timely swap on d5, when Black could no longer recapture with a piece, White identifies the weakest spot in the enemy camp: c7. }
20... Qb6 21. Rc1
{ Of course not  21.Rxd5  Bc5  and Black has more hope of salvation. } 21...
Rd7
{ Now  21...Bc5  is useless due to  22.b4  . Don't forget that activity is often worth more than material in positions with unbalanced development. }
22. Rc8
{ Such pins are of great use in restricting the opponent's development. } 22...
g6 23. Qe2
{ The final touch.   23.Ree8  might seem tempting, but after  23...Qxb2  the battle continues. }
23... Kg7
{ Black can't in any way prevent the queen's arrival at  e8  , since  23...Re7  fails to  24.Rxf8+  and 25 Qxe7. }
24. Qe8 Rf7 25. Bh6+ Kxh6 26. Qxf7 { The rest is easy. } 26... Bc5 27. Rxh8
Bxf2+ 28. Kh1 Bxe1 29. h4 Kh5 30. Qxd5+
{ In this utterly hopeless position, Black resigned. } *

