[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "L.Psakhis-L.Gofshtein  Israeli Team Championship 1996  English Opening "]
[Result "*"]

{ Now let's see an example of the second cause. White gives priority to certain positional aims such as space and a strong centre, at the cost of normal development, and duly pays for it. }
1. c4 d6 2. d4 e5 3. Nc3
{ he queenless middlegame arising after  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  Kxd8  , followed by ...c7-c6 and ...Kc7, is considered excellent for Black;   but  3.Nf3  makes quite some sense, in order to be able to recapture with the knight on  d4  . The pawn structure that arises after an exchange on  d4  implies a space advantage for White, so Black should get something in return for it. In the game, he wins a tempo by attacking the white queen. }
3... exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2
{ In this line White intends b2-b3 and Bb2, after which the queen will turn out to be well placed on d2. }
5... Nf6 6. g3
{ More consistent seems  6.b3  Be6  7.e4  followed by 8 Bb2;   but not  7.Bb2  d5  , when the move  ...Bb4  might soon become unpleasant for White. }
6... Be6
{ Development with tempo. We can now spot a slight drawback to 6. g3: the c4-pawn loses its natural defence. }
7. e4
{ White gains space but will soon have a vulnerable centre to worry about.   7.Nd5  followed by 8. b3 was preferable  again not   7.b3  d5  with similar play as in the note to White's sixth move. }
7... Be7 8. f3
{ This shows that something has already gone wrong for White in the opening.   Unfortunately, the natural  8.b3  was again risky due to  8...Nxe4  9.Nxe4  d5  and Black regains the material by a timely ...Bb4. }
8... O-O 9. Nd5
{ Seizing the centre, but losing more time.So Black has already a distinct lead in development, but how to make use of it?   9.b3  was better, when Black could just react as in the game. }
9... Nd7
{ A great move with various purposes. Gofshtein prepares the pawn break ...f7-f5, hitting the white centre and clearing lines towards the enemy camp. Moreover, an annoying ...Ne5 or ...Nc5 is added to the menu. }
10. Bg2 f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Ne3
{ The problem with moving this knight will soon be revealed. A lesser evil was  12.Ne2  Nde5  13.O-O  Nxc4  14.Qc3  followed by Nef4. White has lost a pawn but at least managed to bring his king into safety. }
12... Be6 13. f4
{ White has prevented ...Ne5, and 13...Nc5 no longer makes much sense. So how is Black supposed to punish the opponent for his slow development? }
13... d5
{ A strong pawn sacrifice that clears lines towards the white monarch. White's next move is forced, since it is the only capture that prevents 14...Bb4. }
14. Nxd5 Re8 15. Nf3
{ After  15.Nxe7+  Qxe7  ;   or  15.Ne2  Bg4  White is suffering heavily along the e-file. }
15... Bc5
{ Another typical method when enjoying a lead in development: prevent the opponent's castling. It can be effected by a check  @@StartBracket@@ see 12. Bb5+! in the previous game @@EndBracket@@ as well as by a bishop move to the a3-f8  @@StartBracket@@ f1-a6 @@EndBracket@@  or a2-g8  @@StartBracket@@ g1-a7 @@EndBracket@@  diagonal as in this case, while the deployment of a knight on e6  @@StartBracket@@ e3 @@EndBracket@@  is yet another variation on the theme. }
16. Kf1 Nb6 17. Ng5
{ Psakhis avoids  17.b3  Nxd5  18.cxd5  Bxd5  with a sad position to look at, and sets a little trap. }
17... Bf5
{ Gofshtein doesn't fall for  17...Nxc4  18.Qd3  with double threats at h7 and c4. }
18. b3
{ White must cover the c4-pawn, since  18.Nxb6  fails to  18...Bd3+  with mate. }
18... Nb4
{ To eliminate the defender on d5, just like Dvoretsky's 16. Nc3 in the previous game. }
19. Bf3
{ 19.Nxb4  Bxb4  20.Qxd8   or  20.Qxb4  Qd1+  21.Kf2  Re2+  with mate  Raxd8  is a simple but instructive line. White managed to swap a few pieces, including the queens, but even so his delay in development makes it impossible for him to cope with the multiple threats at c3, d3 and d1. }
19... N6xd5 20. Bxd5+
{ After  20.cxd5  Nc2  the knight doesn't just aim at  a1  , but also at  e3  . }
20... Nxd5 21. Qxd5+ { Or  21.cxd5  Qf6  22.Bb2  Qa6+  winning - Gofshtein. }
21... Qxd5 22. cxd5 Bd4 *

