[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "S.Conquest-A.Sokolov  Clichy 1991  Sicilian Defence,  Taimanov Variation"]
[Result "*"]

{ Obviously, keeping the king in the centre doesn't mean automatic defeat. In some openings, like the Open Sicilian, Black occasionally delays castling for a while, awaiting a safe moment or simply giving priority to other actions. Before continuing our investigation on the causes of a delayed development, let's see an example of a successful king in the centre. }
1. e4 c5 2. f4 Nc6 3. Nf3 e6 4. Nc3 a6
{ Thus Black prevents Bf1-b5, a move typical of White's Grand Prix Attack, and at the same time enables a future ...b7-b5. }
5. d4
{ White reverts to the Open Sicilian.   A different kind of play emerges after  5.g3  d5  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.e5  Nd7  followed by ...Be7, ...b7-b5, ...Bb7 etc. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Usually Black doesn't hurry to carry out this exchange, but here it helps him in achieving ...b7-b5 without having to worry about Nxc6. }
7. Qxd4 b5 8. Be2 Bb7
{ A great place for the bishop, where it puts pressure on the e4-pawn and might even assist in a future attack on the white king. }
9. O-O Rc8
{ Within the first nine moves, Black has just made one single movement on the kingside! When Taimanov introduced such a set-up into practice many years ago, the fact that the black queenside is developed before the kingside caused surprise and even suspicion.However, Black's play is perfectly logical. The queen's rook and bishop have rather obvious destinies on b7 and c8, so they are developed straight away. In contrast, the king's bishop has both c5 and e7 at its disposal, so it could wait a few moves, until White's set-up is more defined. Finally, the knight would like to settle at f6, but only if e4-e5 can be coped with, otherwise it will prefer the route ...Ne7-c6 @@StartBracket@@ g6 @@EndBracket@@ . }
10. Kh1
{ Parrying the threat 10...Bc5.   An earlier game of Sokolov's saw  10.Qd3  b4  11.Nd1  Nf6  12.e5  Nd5  13.f5  Qh4  14.Kh1  Bc5  15.Bf3  O-O  and Black had a more active position, A.Martin Gonzalez-A.Sokolov, Biel Interzonal 1985. }
10... Nf6
{ Now, on the other hand,  10...b4  11.Na4  Rxc2  12.Bd3  Rc8  13.Bd2  yields White a dangerous lead in development - Sokolov. }
11. e5 Nd5 12. Bf3
{ The desirable  12.Ne4  fails to  12...Rxc2  13.Bd3  Rc8  followed by ...Qb6. }
12... Rc4 13. Qf2 Qa8
{ Thanks to this and the previous move, Black stays in charge of the long diagonal. }
14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. b3 Rc7 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Bb2
{ Considering Black's slow development on the kingside,  17.f5  would seem like a logical choice. However, after  17...exf5   @@StartBracket@@The flexible  17...Bb4  doesn't seem bad either@@EndBracket@@  18.Qxf5  g6  Black can meet  19.Qf6  with  19...Rxc2  20.Rg1  Rxg2  21.Rxg2  Qd1+  securing a perpetual. }
17... Be7 18. Rad1
{ On this occasion,  18.f5  proves even less dangerous after  18...exf5  19.Qxf5  O-O  followed by ...Qe6. }
18... Qe4 19. Rd2 O-O
{ Ten moves later Black finally gets castled and has a minimal edge thanks to his superior pawn structure and more active bishop.   The game continued  19...O-O  20.Re1  Qf5  21.Red1  Bb4  22.c3  Bxc3  23.Bxc3  Rxc3  24.Rxd7  h5  25.h3  Rc2  26.R1d2  Rfc8  with a slight initiative, although it eventually ended in a draw. }
*

