[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "N.Firman-B.Itkis  Lvov 2003  Caro-Kann Defence "]
[Result "*"]

{ The following game shows the use of positional concessions, such as accepting weaknesses or exchanging 'good' pieces, in order to exploit a lead in development. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5
{ A modern alternative to the traditional 3...Bf5. Compared with the Advance Variation in the French @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  @@EndBracket@@ Black is a tempo down, but the h3-c8 diagonal remains open for the bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ The main line is  4.dxc5  , hanging on to the pawn, but the text is viable as well. }
4... Nc6 5. c4
{ A logical choice: White aims to open the centre, considering the tempo loss involved in ...c7-c6 and ...c6-c5.   In contrast, after  5.c3  Bg4  followed by ...e7-e6, Black obtains an excellent game. }
5... e6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. O-O
{ Speeding up development; whereas the greedy  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Qxd5  permits  9...Qb6  with a nasty double attack. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nc3
{ Again White prefers development to material.   After  11.Qxd5  Nge7  12.Qe4  O-O  , preparing ...Bf5, Black would enjoy quite a bit of activity for the pawn. }
11... Be6 12. Na4 Ne7
{ Black also gives priority to development. The attempt to keep the 'good' bishop by  12...Bc7  permits  13.Nac5  Ne7  14.Nd4  Qc8  15.Ncxe6  fxe6  16.Qg4  , when White has a clear advantage - Firman. }
13. Nxb6 Qxb6
{ Surprisingly enough, this natural move proves to be a serious mistake after White's strong follow-up.How to exploit the minimal lead in development?   Correct was  13...axb6  , followed by  ...O-O  , with just a slight disadvantage. }
14. Bxc6+
{ In the opening phase, time is money! Losing the 'good' bishop and indirectly the bishop pair is not a big deal if it can help us keep the enemy king in the centre. }
14... Nxc6
{ The following piece of analysis by Firman illustrates Black's problems if he recaptures with the pawn or the queen:   14...bxc6  15.Be3  Qc7  16.Bc5  Qxe5  @@StartBracket@@ otherwise the bishop settles on d6 @@EndBracket@@  17.Nd4  Qc7  18.Re1  O-O  19.Nxe6  fxe6  20.Rxe6  Rf7  21.Qa4  with a clear advantage  or:   14...Qxc6  15.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@ preventing ...O-O @@EndBracket@@  15...Ng6  16.Rc1  Qa4  17.f4  h6  18.f5  hxg5  19.fxg6  Qh4  20.gxf7+  Bxf7  21.h3  O-O  22.Nd4  Qg3  23.Re1  and the passed e-pawn spells trouble for Black. }
15. Be3 Qc7 16. Bc5
{ A key move to prevent the opponent's castling, just like Gofshtein's 15...Bc5! against Psakhis. }
16... Qxe5
{ Black isn't really happy about accepting this gift, since the absence of the e5-pawn will allow White to use the e-file for the attack, but the bishop would have become unbearable on d6. }
17. Re1 Qg5 { The greedy  17...Qxb2  is answered in the same way. } 18. Nd4
{ An aggressive exchange directed at the defenders on e6 and c6. We saw Nezhmetdinov carry out a similar idea against Chistiakov. }
18... Nxd4
{ The last chance was  18...Kd7  , although after  19.Qb3  Rab8  20.Rac1  White's pressure is overwhelming. }
19. Qxd4 a6
{ Defending against the threat of 20. Qa4+, but now White crashes through on the opposite flank. }
20. f4 Qf5 21. Re5
{ Renewing the threat of f4-f5.   At this moment Black resigned, a possible conclusion of the game being  21.Re5  Qg4  22.Qxd5   @@StartBracket@@of course  22.f5  is also fine@@EndBracket@@  Rd8  23.Qxb7  Rd1+  24.Re1  Rd7  25.Qa8+  Rd8  26.Qc6+  Rd7  27.Rad1  and the last piece enters the attack with devastating effect. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "Exercise #1: N.Firman-B.Itkis"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/2n5/1BppP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

8. O-O
{ Speeding up development; whereas the greedy  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Qxd5  permits  9...Qb6  with a nasty double attack. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nc3
{ Again White prefers development to material.   After  11.Qxd5  Nge7  12.Qe4  O-O  , preparing ...Bf5, Black would enjoy quite a bit of activity for the pawn. }
