14. Bxc6+
{ In the opening phase, time is money! Losing the 'good' bishop and indirectly the bishop pair is not a big deal if it can help us keep the enemy king in the centre. }
14... Nxc6
{ The following piece of analysis by Firman illustrates Black's problems if he recaptures with the pawn or the queen:   14...bxc6  15.Be3  Qc7  16.Bc5  Qxe5  @@StartBracket@@ otherwise the bishop settles on d6 @@EndBracket@@  17.Nd4  Qc7  18.Re1  O-O  19.Nxe6  fxe6  20.Rxe6  Rf7  21.Qa4  with a clear advantage  or:   14...Qxc6  15.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@ preventing ...O-O @@EndBracket@@  15...Ng6  16.Rc1  Qa4  17.f4  h6  18.f5  hxg5  19.fxg6  Qh4  20.gxf7+  Bxf7  21.h3  O-O  22.Nd4  Qg3  23.Re1  and the passed e-pawn spells trouble for Black. }
