[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "M.Tal-Z.Milev  Munich Olympiad 1958  Semi-Tarrasch Defence"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's see a few more games illustrating the risks of pursuing strategic goals at the expense of development. Mikhail Tal was a true maestro at exploiting a lead in development, as we already saw against Tringov. In the next example, his opponent is simply demolished after a few misguided positional considerations. }
1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. d4 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4
{ From a rather innocent English Opening, the game has transposed into a more delicate Semi-Tarrasch. }
7... Nb6
{ Such a knight retreat is typical of some openings like the Alekhine, but here it is not really necessary, and rather implies a loss of time.   Preferable was  7...cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  , followed by  9.--  9...O-O  , with a normal IQP battle. }
8. Bb5
{ Tal chooses the most active move. The threat of  8...--  9.Ne5  must already be taken into account.   Other reasonable options were  8.Bd3  and  8.Bb3  . }
8... a6
{ Anxious about releasing the pin, Milev keeps delaying his development.   8...Bd7  was better, bringing out the bishop and at the same time preventing 9. Ne5. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O
{ In exchange for the bishop pair, White enjoys a sounder pawn structure and a lead in development. }
10... Bb7
{ Yet one more unnecessary move. In view of the possible 11. Ne5 Milev protects the c6-pawn in advance;   but he should rather have accelerated the development on the opposite flank by  10...cxd4  11.exd4  Be7  12.Ne5  Bb7  , when Tal would probably have opted for something like  13.Qh5   @@StartBracket@@  13.Qf3  proves inoffensive after  13...O-O  14.Nxc6  Bf6  with decent compensation for the pawn; e.g.  15.Ne4  Bxc6  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  17.Qxc6  Nd5  followed by 18...Rfc8@@EndBracket@@  O-O  14.Rd1  , intending Rd3-h3, with attacking prospects. }
11. Ne4 { Provoking ...c5xd4 to clear both the c1-h6 diagonal and the e-file. }
11... Nd7
{ In order to prevent White's intentions, Black moves the knight for the fourth time.   Admittedly after  11...cxd4  12.exd4  Be7  13.Bg5  f6  14.Be3  Nd5   @@StartBracket@@not  14...O-O  15.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@  15.Rc1  , followed by 16. Nc5, White has the upper hand, yet Black's position is entirely fightable. }
12. Qc2 Qb6
{ Now how to step up the pressure?   12...cxd4  was the lesser evil, but Black is consistent. }
13. Ne5
{ A strong blow that either wins the battle for the c5-square or forces the black king to stay in the centre. }
13... cxd4
{ Black opts for the latter, since after  13...Nxe5  14.dxe5  , followed by b2-b3,  Ba3  , and  Rac1  , he would be strategically doomed. }
14. Nxd7 Kxd7 15. exd4
{ White's main priority is to clear the c1-h6 diagonal for the bishop.   Less promising is  15.Rd1  Rd8  16.Rxd4+  Kc8  and Black stays alive. }
15... Ke8
{ Intending ...f7-f6 and Kf7 to safeguard the king.   The attempt at artificial castling by  15...Rd8  is well met by  16.Be3  Qc7  17.Qd2  Kc8  18.Bf4  Qb6  19.Rfd1  , with ideas like Rc1-c3-b3 and  Bg3  followed by  Qf4  . }
16. Be3
{ Development with tempo. Due to the threat of  16...--  17.d5  , Black must waste a move on retreating his queen. }
16... Qc7 17. d5 { Anyway! Now the e-file is cleared with great effect. } 17...
exd5 18. Rfe1 Kd8
{ After  18...dxe4  19.Qxe4+  Be7   @@StartBracket@@and  19...Qe7  20.Qc4  followed by  Bc5+  is also fatal for him@@EndBracket@@  20.Bc5  Black is definitely missing his right to castling.   As for  18...Be7  , White breaks through by  19.Nd6+  Kf8   @@StartBracket@@or  19...Qxd6  20.Bc5  @@EndBracket@@  20.Nf5  Bf6  21.Bc5+  Kg8  22.Re7  and  22...--  23.Rae1  next. }
19. Qb3 c5
{ Losing on the spot, though the bishop's arrival on b6 spelled big trouble in any case;   e.g.  19...Kc8  20.Bb6  Qd7  21.Nc5  Bxc5  22.Bxc5  Re8  23.Rxe8+  Qxe8  24.Qc3  , followed by 25 Re1, when Black's lagging development finally takes its toll. }
20. Nxc5 Bxc5 21. Bxc5 Qxc5 22. Qxb7 { 22.Qxb7  Rc8  23.Rad1  is hopeless. } *

