{ Losing on the spot, though the bishop's arrival on b6 spelled big trouble in any case;   e.g.  19...Kc8  20.Bb6  Qd7  21.Nc5  Bxc5  22.Bxc5  Re8  23.Rxe8+  Qxe8  24.Qc3  , followed by 25 Re1, when Black's lagging development finally takes its toll. }
20. Nxc5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-N.G.Renman  Norrköping 1994  French Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qd3
{ This early queen sortie is hardly a critical test of the Winawer, but the unorthodox positions that often follow may not please every French player. Moreover, at the time of this game I was inspired by some White victories in this line by my countryman GM Jonny Hector. }
4... dxe4
{ One of several logical replies, aiming to gain a tempo by 5...Nf6 on the next move. }
5. Qxe4 Nf6 6. Qh4 c5 7. dxc5 Qa5
{ The correct move order is  7...Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Qa5  e.g.  9.Qb4  Qc7  10.Nf3  Nc6  11.Qh4  Qa5  12.Bd2  Qxc5  with mutual chances, J.Hellsten-L.Karlsson, Gothenburg @@StartBracket@@Rapid@@EndBracket@@-1996. }
8. Bd2
{ In contrast to 7...Bxc3+ above, here White keeps his pawn structure intact, thus making a future O-O-O possible. Besides which, a2-a3 might now prove unpleasant for Black at any moment. }
8... Nc6 9. Bd3 Ne5
{ Anxious about swapping White's 'good' bishop, Black moves the knight twice  @@StartBracket@@soon thrice@@EndBracket@@, which will cost him duly.   The simple  9...Qxc5  was called for; e.g.  10.a3  Bxc3  11.Bxc3  e5  , followed by ...O-O, with much better prospects than in the game. }
10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Qxc5
{ Perhaps  11...Nxd3+  12.cxd3  Qxc5  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Qxf6  Rg8  was a lesser evil, sacrificing a pawn in order to prevent White's 14th move in the game, although after  15.Nf3  Rxg2  16.Ne5  the latter keeps the initiative. }
12. O-O-O { Speeding up development. } 12... Bd7
{ Black can't do the same with  12...O-O  due to  13.Bb4 } 13. Nf3
{ Development with tempo.   13.Qg3  was interesting as well. } 13... Nxd3+
{ 13...Nxf3  14.gxf3  , followed by Rhg1, leads to unbearable pressure on the dark squares, whereas the doubled pawns are a less serious matter. }
14. Rxd3 Rc8
{ Since  14...O-O-O  fails to  15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Rc3  , Black opts for a useful move. }
15. Rhd1
{ A familiar picture in this chapter: one player has mobilized all his pieces, with an advantage in activity that leaves the opponent under a dark cloud. Note that Black's delayed castling doesn't just jeopardize his king, it also means that he is playing with a rook less. }
15... Qf5
{ This move doesn't achieve much, but what to do?   The desirable  15...O-O  fails to the simple  16.Rxd7  Nxd7  17.Rxd7   While  15...Nd5  16.Ne5  also has a bad aspect for Black; e.g.  16...Bb5   @@StartBracket@@ or  16...Nxc3  17.Rxc3  Qxe5  18.Rxc8+  Bxc8  19.Rd8  @@EndBracket@@  17.Rxd5  exd5  18.Qg3  with the double threat of 19. Qxg7 and 19. Re1. At this point,  18...O-O  fails to  19.Nd3 }
16. Qg3
{ Heading for d6 with tempo.   Less clear is  16.Bxf6  gxf6  , when  17.Rxd7  fails to mate. }
16... Nh5 { Or  16...O-O  17.Bxf6  Qxf6  18.Rxd7 } 17. Qd6 Bc6 18. Ne5
{ After  18.Ne5  , the threat of  18...--  19.Nxc6  bxc6  20.Qd7+  forces Black to enter a lost endgame. }
18... Qg5+ { Or  18...Nf6  19.Qd8+  with mate in two. } 19. Kb1 Qe7 20. Qxe7+
Kxe7 21. Nxc6+ bxc6 22. Rd7+ { The rest is easy: } 22... Ke8 23. Bb4 c5 24.
Bxc5 Rxc5 25. Rd8+ Ke7 26. Rxh8 h6 27. Rhd8 Rc7 28. g3 Nf6 29. R8d2 g5 30. h3
h5 31. Re1 Rc5 32. b3 *

