13. Nf3 { Development with tempo. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "C.Niklasson-J.Hellsten  Malmö 1994  Bird’s Opening "]
[Result "*"]

{ The following game was played just a few months after my battle with Renman, which confirms the fact that you learn more from your defeats than from your victories! }
1. g3 d5 2. f4
{ Adherents of Bird's Opening can use this move order to avoid From's Gambit  @@StartBracket@@1. f4 e5@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6
{ Launching a rather aggressive set-up. With  2...g6  , followed by  3.--  3...Bg7  , Black could have entered the Dutch Leningrad with reversed colours, where the minus tempo is no great issue. }
3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Bg2 Qd7 5. h3
{ While  5.O-O  Bh3  plays in Black's hands.   5.c4  might be a more critical test of his set-up. }
5... Bxf3 6. exf3
{ After  6.Bxf3  e5  followed by ...Nf6, ...Bd6 and ...O-O-O, Black obtains a great game.   Now, in contrast,  6.exf3  e5  can be met by  7.fxe5  Nxe5  8.d4  with a slight edge due to the bishop pair. }
6... Qe6+
{ Before playing ...e7-e6 Black aims to deploy the queen at g6 where it will hit the g3-pawn and seize the b1-h7 diagonal. The downside to this creative idea is the time loss involved.   A normal continuation was  6...e6  7.d4  Bd6  8.O-O  Nge7  , followed by ...O-O, with approximate equality. A later plan might be ...Nf5, ...Nce7 and ...c7-c5, hitting the enemy centre. }
7. Kf2
{ White of course avoids  7.Qe2  Qg6  with a double attack at  g3  and  c2  . }
7... Qg6 8. d4 { Fighting for the centre and ruling out any ideas of ...Bc5. }
8... Nb4
{ Black prepares ...c7-c5, striking at the enemy centre. Structurally speaking this is not a bad idea, and it is even utilized by White in a similar structure in the Trompowsky. Once ...c7-c5 is achieved, if White replies d4xc5 then Black obtains two pawns against none in the centre, whereas if he supports the d4-pawn by c2-c3, then the double pawn capture on d4 produces an isolated white pawn on the same square. The problem with 8...Nb4 is the same one as two moves ago: Black neglects development.   Again,  8...e6  was called for. }
9. Na3
{ Of course,  9.c3  Nd3+  had to be avoided, while a knight jump to  b5  might soon prove useful. }
9... c5
{ Now  9...e6  was, once more, Black's lesser evil, but I am consistent with my previous play. }
10. Bf1
{ The bishop was idle on g2 and now helps in pushing back the knight by c2-c3.   10.dxc5  e5  is less clear. }
10... Nc6
{ Or  10...cxd4  11.Nb5  Qxc2+  12.Bd2  Qxd1  13.Rxd1  Na6  14.Nxd4  , with ideas like Bb5+ and f4-f5, when White's lead in development more than compensates for the pawn. }
11. Nb5 { Well, how to defend against the fork on c7? } 11... Rc8
{ The decisive mistake, leaving the king stranded in the centre.   I discarded  11...O-O-O  due to  12.dxc5  e6  13.Be3  . However, after  13...d4  14.Nxd4  Bxc5  15.c3  Nge7  Black may claim some compensation for the pawn. The development he achieves in this line will remain an illusion for the rest of the game. }
12. dxc5 a6
{ Here  12...e6  fails to  13.Be3  , so Black has to spend more time to recover the c5-pawn. }
13. Nc3 Nb4 { After  13...e6  14.Na4  White hangs on to the pawn. } 14. Bd3
{ Niklasson has nothing against swapping his 'good' bishop for my only developed minor piece. }
14... Qc6
{ Black has to spend one more tempo on moving his queen; as after  14...Nxd3+  15.cxd3  Black's position is hopeless; e.g.  15...Rxc5   @@StartBracket@@ or  15...d4  16.Qa4+  with the same effect@@EndBracket@@  16.Be3  , winning the d-pawn. }
15. a3 Qxc5+ 16. Be3 { Development with tempo. } 16... Nxd3+
{ Now  16...d4  fails to  17.Bb5+  axb5  18.Bxd4  , recovering the piece with interest; e.g.  18...Qc4  19.axb4  Rd8   @@StartBracket@@or  19...Qxb4  20.Qd3  @@EndBracket@@  20.Bb6  Rxd1  21.Ra8+  Kd7  22.Rxd1+  , followed by 23. Rxf8. Remember, tactical complications usually favour the side with a lead in development. }
17. cxd3
{ Clearing the c-file for future operations. In contrast, after  17.Qxd3  Qc4  18.Rhd1  e6  Black has much better chances for resistance, since there is no open file where White can exploit his lead in development. }
17... Qd6
{ So, Black finally got what he wanted: a superior pawn structure. Unfortunately, this is irrelevant when most of his pieces are still in their initial positions. Note that White needs just one move to connect his rooks, while Black needs four - thus the latter won't have a chance in resisting on the open file.   Obviously  17...d4  fails to  18.Qa4+ }
18. Rc1 Rd8
{ Surrendering the c-file in order to avoid tactical surprises.   After  18...e6  19.Qa4+   @@StartBracket@@  19.Nb5  is also interesting@@EndBracket@@  Rc6  @@StartBracket@@both queen moves fail to the tactical shot 20. Nxd5!@@EndBracket@@  20.Ne2  , followed by  Nd4  , Black's queenside defence is soon destroyed.   18...Nf6  can be met in the same way. }
19. Bd4 e6 20. Na4
{ Exploiting the vulnerable squares c5 and b6, while clearing the c-file for the rook. }
20... Ne7
{ This tactical oversight loses the queen; but after  20...b5  21.Nc5  Ra8  @@StartBracket@@there was the threat of 22. Nb7@@EndBracket@@  22.a4  White breaks through anyway. }
21. Be5 Qd7 22. Rc7 Qb5 23. Rc5 f6 { Or  23...Qd7  24.Nb6 } 24. Bc7 Rc8 25.
Rxb5 axb5 26. Nc3 Rxc7 27. Nxb5 { White soon materialized his huge advantage. }
*

