[White "1.3 Causes of a Delayed Development"]
[Black "Exercise #2: C.Niklasson-J.Hellsten "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1kbnr/pp2pppp/2n3q1/1Npp4/3P1P2/5PPP/PPP2K2/R1BQ1B1R w k - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. dxc5 a6
{ Here  12...e6  fails to  13.Be3  , so Black has to spend more time to recover the c5-pawn. }
13. Nc3 Nb4 { After  13...e6  14.Na4  White hangs on to the pawn. } 14. Bd3
{ Niklasson has nothing against swapping his 'good' bishop for my only developed minor piece. }
14... Qc6
{ Black has to spend one more tempo on moving his queen; as after  14...Nxd3+  15.cxd3  Black's position is hopeless; e.g.  15...Rxc5   @@StartBracket@@ or  15...d4  16.Qa4+  with the same effect@@EndBracket@@  16.Be3  , winning the d-pawn. }
15. a3 Qxc5+ 16. Be3 { Development with tempo. } 16... Nxd3+
{ Now  16...d4  fails to  17.Bb5+  axb5  18.Bxd4  , recovering the piece with interest; e.g.  18...Qc4  19.axb4  Rd8   @@StartBracket@@or  19...Qxb4  20.Qd3  @@EndBracket@@  20.Bb6  Rxd1  21.Ra8+  Kd7  22.Rxd1+  , followed by 23. Rxf8. Remember, tactical complications usually favour the side with a lead in development. }
17. cxd3
{ Clearing the c-file for future operations. In contrast, after  17.Qxd3  Qc4  18.Rhd1  e6  Black has much better chances for resistance, since there is no open file where White can exploit his lead in development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.4 The Development Factor after Mutual Castling"]
[Black "The development factor after mutual castling"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@The development factor after mutual castling@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1.
--
{ So far in this chapter, leaving aside the 'atypical' game Conquest-Sokolov, the side lagging in development never managed to castle! The next two games will show us that the development factor remains relevant even after castling. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.4 The Development Factor after Mutual Castling"]
[Black "L.Van Wely-S.Guliev  European Championship,  Ohrid 2001  Dutch Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. b4
{ An interesting sideline against the Leningrad Dutch. White prepares Bb2, in order to neutralize the enemy bishop on g7, and grabs some space on the queenside. }
5... d6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Qe8 8. c4 h6 9. Nbd2 g5
{ A typical move in this defence; but the more restrained  9...Qf7  10.Qc2  c6  followed by ...Be6 and ...Nbd7 might have been preferable, completing development before taking further actions. }
10. e3
{ A sensible piece of prophylaxis as soon as ...f5-f4 appears on Black's agenda. }
10... f4
{ Black just can't wait to attack on the kingside, but this lets White open the position to the benefit of his better developed forces.   Again  10...Qf7  11.Qc2  c6  , followed by ...Be6, made sense. }
11. exf4
{ The virtue of 10. e3 becomes evident: White manages to open the e-file towards the backward pawn on e7, while his king remains completely safe. }
11... gxf4 12. Re1 fxg3 13. hxg3 Bg4
{ Black quickly brings out his remaining forces, but his position is already dubious. }
14. Qc2 Nc6
{ Other moves, such as  14...c6  and  14...Qf7  , are well met by  15.Nh4  just like in the game - Tyomkin. }
15. b5 Nd8 16. Nh4
{ Heading for the weak light squares on g6 and f5. By now Black's aspirations of a kingside attack are definitely outdated, and it is White who is thinking in such terms. }
16... Qd7 17. Nf1
{ The other knight joins the battle for the kingside.   Less flexible is  17.Ng6  Rf7  , when White has to look out for ...Bf5. }
17... Rf7 18. Ne3 Bh3 19. Qg6 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 e6 21. d5
{ White's game plays itself. This advance softens up the f5-square and includes the bishop in the attack,  since   21.d5  e5  22.Nef5  would be fatal for Black. }
21... Nh7
{ If  21...Kh8  White has the strong sacrifice  22.Nef5  exf5  23.Nxf5  with irresistible threats; e.g.  23...Nh5  24.Nxg7  Nxg7  25.Qxh6+  Kg8  26.Rh1  winning - Tyomkin. }
22. Ng4 Kf8
{ Black wasn't eager to enter the nice line  22...Kh8  23.Qxg7+  Rxg7  24.Ng6+  Kg8  25.Nxh6  - Tyomkin. }
23. Qxh7 Bxb2 24. Ng6+ { In view of  24.Ng6+  Ke8  25.Qg8+  , Black resigns. }
*

