[White "1.4 The Development Factor after Mutual Castling"]
[Black "Exercise #2:  L.Van Wely-S.Guliev"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3qrk1/ppp1p1b1/2np1n1p/8/1PPP2b1/5NP1/PBQN1PB1/R3R1K1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. b5 Nd8 16. Nh4
{ Heading for the weak light squares on g6 and f5. By now Black's aspirations of a kingside attack are definitely outdated, and it is White who is thinking in such terms. }
16... Qd7 17. Nf1
{ The other knight joins the battle for the kingside.   Less flexible is  17.Ng6  Rf7  , when White has to look out for ...Bf5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.4 The Development Factor after Mutual Castling"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-H.Lopez Silva  Pinamar 2004  Benoni Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 Nf6
{ In this type of accelerated Benoni, another direction is   2...e5  3.Nc3  d6  4.e4  Be7  , intending  5.Nf3  Bg4  followed by ...Bxf3 and ...Bg5 at the appropriate moment. }
3. Nc3
{ This is the downside to 1...c5 compared with the standard 1...Nf6 2 c4 c5. White skips c2-c4 in order to speed up development and enable a future Nf3-d2-c4. }
3... e5
{ I am no expert on this defence, but  3...d6  4.e4  g6  seems more promising to me, keeping the long diagonal open for the bishop. }
4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Nd2 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Qe7
{ Another idea is  8...a6  9.a4  Nbd7  10.Nc4  Nb6  , when White could try  11.Ne3   or  11.Na3  , preparing 12. a5 and the return of the knight to  c4  . }
9. a4 Nbd7 10. Nc4 Ne8 11. Ra3
{ A useful move, bringing the last piece into play while awaiting Black's next step.  In contrast, after   11.f4  exf4  12.Bxf4  Ne5  , followed by ...Bd7, the latter has nothing to complain about. }
11... f5
{ A natural advance in the present pawn structure; however, on this occasion White is soon able to open the position for his better developed pieces.   Black should have looked for play on the other flank with  11...Rb8  , preparing ...b7-b6, ...a7-a6 and ...b6-b5. }
12. exf5 gxf5 13. f4
{ A key move in order to put pressure on Black's centre before his pieces on a8 and c8 are able to join the battle. }
13... exf4
{ 13...e4  was preferable, keeping the position closed, although after  14.h3  , followed by g2-g4, White takes the initiative anyway. }
14. Bxf4 Ne5 15. Re1 Bd7
{ Now the pressure at e5 becomes intolerable;   but after  15...Ng6  16.Bh5  , followed by Bxg6 and Nb5   or  15...Nxc4  16.Bxc4  Qf6  17.Rb3  , preparing Ne2-g3, White is also much better. }
16. Bf1 Rf7 17. Nb5
{ Creating the threat of  17...--  18.Nbxd6  and clearing the third rank for the rook. The difference in activity between White's and Black's pieces is striking. }
17... Bxb5 18. axb5 a6 19. bxa6 bxa6 20. Bxe5
{ Initiating a winning sequence. The restrained  20.Rae3  was also strong. }
20... Bxe5 { Or  20...dxe5  21.d6  Qe6  22.Nb6  followed by  Bc4  . } 21. Nxe5
dxe5 22. d6 Nxd6 { Forced; in view of  22...Qxd6  23.Bc4 } 23. Qd5 Rd8
{ Or  23...Re8  24.Rxa6  Ne4  25.Bc4  etc. } 24. Rxe5
{ With his position in ruins, Black resigned. There could have followed  24.Rxe5  Qc7   @@StartBracket@@or  24...Qf6  25.Rxa6  with fatal pins@@EndBracket@@  25.Rxa6  Ne4  26.Ra8  Rxa8  27.Qxa8+  Kg7  28.Qd5  , when both  28...c4   @@StartBracket@@and  28...Qa7  29.c4  @@EndBracket@@  29.Qd4  should win easily for White. }
*

