[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.4 The Development Factor after Mutual Castling"]
[Black "E.Berg-P.Velicka  Stockholm 2006  Caro-Kann Defence"]
[Result "*"]

{ The next game is a good example on how to work on a lead in a development even after the opening phase has concluded. In clear contrast to the previous two games, when Black finally makes it to castling he is already beyond salvation. }
1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Ne5
{ A curious reply to the Caro-Kann, one that can claim a remote relation to the more familiar variation   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  In the latter case White has a slight problem with the development of his king's knight, in the sense that Nf3 might run into ...Bg4. With the early knight jump to e5 he avoids that pin, while he can speculate with the idea of Bb5 @@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@  at some moment. }
4... Nd7 5. d4 Nxe5 6. dxe5 e6
{ Considering that  6...Bf5  fails to  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.Qxd5  , Black applies a French-like set-up with that bishop at home. }
7. Bd3 Qc7
{ This attack on the e5-pawn loses its sense after White's reply.   7...Ne7  was preferable, followed by ...Nc6 or ...Ng6, speeding up development. }
8. O-O
{ Just like in Dvoretsky-Schmidt, White doesn't lose any time on defending the pawn. }
8... Ne7
{ 8...Qxe5  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Kxd7  11.Re1  , followed by 12 c4, would leave the black king in serious danger - Golubev. }
9. Nc3 Bd7
{ Black gets ready to swap off the white knight if it jumps to b5.   Again,  9...Qxe5  is too risky; e.g.  10.Re1  Qc7  11.Nb5  Qb8  12.Qf3  @@StartBracket@@ threatening 13. Bf4 @@EndBracket@@  12...e5  13.Nc3  d4  14.Bb5+  with huge compensation for the pawn.   On the other hand,  9...a6  made some sense, in order to prevent  Nb5  once and for all. }
10. f4
{ Finally White secures the e5-pawn and also adds the advance f4-f5 to his agenda, a fact that explains Black's next move. }
10... g6 11. Be3 h5
{ Prophylaxis against g2-g4.How can White exploit his clear lead in development?   But swift development by  11...Nf5  12.Bf2  Bc5  was more to the point. Black could then consider both castling options, depending on White's play. }
12. Nb5
{ Berg prepares the crucial c2-c4 break in order to open lines on the queenside. The fact that Black now manages to exchange his 'bad' bishop is less relevant. }
12... Bxb5 13. Bxb5+ Nc6 14. c4
{ The d- and c-files are cleared before Black manages to castle. } 14... a6
{ Forcing the trade of the active enemy bishop, but losing more time.   Also unsatisfactory was  14...dxc4  15.Qa4  , followed by  Rac1  and  Rxc4  .   Instead, the radical  14...O-O-O  deserved attention; e.g.  15.cxd5  Rxd5  16.Qa4  Bc5  with more resistance than in the game. }
15. Bxc6+ bxc6 16. cxd5 cxd5 { Or  16...exd5  17.f5  with a big initiative. }
17. Rc1 Qd7 18. Rf2
{ Another power move, which prepares Rfc2 with an invasion down the c-file. As Golubev observes, Black has a great pawn structure and the 'better' bishop, but his delay in development prevents these long-term factors from taking effect. }
18... Be7
{ A vulnerable square for the bishop.   18...Rc8  failed to  19.Rxc8+  Qxc8  20.Qa4+  @@StartBracket@@ Golubev @@EndBracket@@.   But  18...Bh6  was a more tenacious choice, intending  19.Bc5  Bf8  20.Bxf8  Kxf8  and ...Kg7.   @@StartBracket@@In turn White should prefer  20.Bb6  , followed by Rc7 and Rfc2, with a somewhat inferior version of the game@@EndBracket@@ }
19. Rfc2 O-O
{ The attempt to prevent the invasion at c7 by   19...Bd8  runs into  20.Bc5  , denying Black's castling. }
20. Rc7 Qd8 21. Qa4
{ With the simple idea of Rd7. Black can't do anything to stop this. } 21...
Re8 22. Rd7 Qb8 23. Rcc7 Qxb2
{ This desperate shot is easily refuted;  but after   23...Qb4  24.Qxb4  Bxb4  25.Rxf7  Bf8  26.Rf6  Black is done - Golubev. }
24. Rxe7 Rxe7 25. Rxe7 Qe2 26. Bf2 Qd2
{ Black's attack is already over, since  26...Rb8  fails to  27.Re8+  Velicka could have resigned at this point, but keeps on fighting until the bitter end. }
27. h3 Kg7 28. Bh4 g5 29. Bxg5 Qe1+ 30. Kh2 h4 31. Rxf7+
{ The most elegant finish. } 31... Kxf7 32. Qd7+ Kg8 33. Qxe6+ Kg7 34. Bf6+
{ Black lost on time when the mate was around the corner; e.g.  34.Bf6+  Kh6  35.Be7+  Kg7  36.Qf6+  Kh7  37.Qf7+  Kh6  38.Bg5 }
*

