[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.5 A Defender's Perspective"]
[Black "A defender’s perspective"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@A defender's perspective@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. --
{ Well, what to do when behind in development? Here are some simple recommendations:    ♟️ Consider giving  @@StartBracket@@back@@EndBracket@@  material, usually a pawn, in order to gain time for development.    ♟️ Look for exchanges, in particular of the queens.    ♟️Consider unusual ways of developing the pieces.    ♟️ Keep the tactical possibilities of both sides constantly supervised - under such circumstances, just one small error might be sufficient to lose the game.     The next two games will show these ideas in action. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.5 A Defender's Perspective"]
[Black "V.Anand-S.Tiviakov  Wijk aan Zee 2006  Scandinavian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
{ Over the last decade, this has become a popular alternative to the traditional 3...Qa5, with Tiviakov as its main protagonist. On d6 the queen seizes the h2-b8 diagonal, while keeping an eye on the white d-pawn. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ An alternate move order is  4...c6  5.Nf3  Bg4  , with the merit that White's sixth move in the game is avoided. }
5. Nf3 c6 6. Ne5
{ White immediately seizes the centre and prepares Bf4 in order to harass the black queen. }
6... Nbd7 7. Bf4 { Another direction is  7.Nc4  Qc7  8.Qf3  , preparing Bf4. }
7... Nd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Be2
{ White offers a pawn to speed up development and keep bothering the black queen. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Qxg2
{ Accepting the challenge is the best choice on this occasion. After  10...Bf5  11.O-O  e6  12.c4  Qd7  13.Qb3  , preparing Rad1 and d4-d5, White obtains a small advantage at no risk. }
11. Bf3 Qg6 12. d5
{ Logically enough, White tries to open the position for his better developed forces, but Black counts on a strong reply.   The preparatory  12.Qe2  was more flexible; e.g.  12...Qe6   or  12...Bf5  13.O-O-O  , intending d4-d5  13.d5  cxd5  14.O-O-O  f6  15.Bxd5  Qxe5  16.Qc4  e6  17.Rhe1  with strong pressure, J.M.Degraeve-I.Smirnov, Cappelle la Grande 2009. }
12... Bg4
{ By tactical means -  12...Bg4  13.Bxg4  Qe4+  - Black manages to exchange the dangerous bishop on  f3  . Moreover, he enables a quick ...Rd8 or even ...O-O-O, possibilities that Anand hurries to prevent with his next move. }
13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Qe2
{ Not  14.Rg1  Bxf3  15.Qxf3  Qxg1+  16.Ke2  Qg6  and Black wins. } 14... Bxf3
15. Qxf3 Rd8
{ Tiviakov first rules out the opponent's long castling, which obliges White to hide his king on the more exposed kingside. At first sight,  15...Qe6  , intending  16.Qe2   @@StartBracket@@However, White has the much stronger  16.O-O-O  , speeding up development, and the bishop is untouchable because of mate @@EndBracket@@  (f6 with simplifications, seems tempting.) }
16. Rd1 Qe6
{ After  16...Qxc2  17.Rxd8+  Kxd8  18.O-O  White has compensation for the two pawns - Anand.   Another idea is  16...Rxd1+  17.Kxd1  Qe6  18.Re1  Qd5+  , forcing the exchange of queens, although after  19.Qxd5  cxd5  20.Re3  , heading for  a3  or  b3  , White keeps the initiative even into the endgame. }
17. O-O Rxd1 18. Rxd1
{ Black is now left with a single defender and his last rank has become vulnerable. Fortunately, White doesn't have too many attacking pieces either - even so, the former should proceed with care. }
18... h5
{ A great idea. Since his remaining pieces can't be developed in a normal way, Tiviakov prepares to bring out the rook via h6. In contrast, after  18...f6  19.Bc3  Kf7  20.Rd4  followed by  Ra4  , White keeps the initiative. }
19. Qd3 Qc8 { Of course not  19...f6  20.Qg6+  Qf7  21.Rd8+ } 20. h4
{ By blocking the black h-pawn White prepares Kh2 and Bg3 with improved safety for his king. }
20... Rh6 21. Kh2 Rg6 22. Bg3 Rg4
{ Now that his rook has joined the battle, Black hardly has anything to worry about.   The game continued  22...Rg4  23.a3  a6  24.Re1  c5   according to Anand,  24...f5  produced a slight advantage  25.c3  Rg6  @@StartBracket@@ retreating the rook in order to swap its more active white counterpart, even at the cost of a pawn @@EndBracket@@  26.Re5  e6  27.Rxh5  Rh6  28.Rxh6  gxh6  29.Qf3  c4  and the roughly equal endgame later ended in a draw.If, by chance, you felt that Tiviakov's play was not that difficult, then in the following game Black faces a much more complex task. }
*

