[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.5 A Defender's Perspective"]
[Black "A.Naiditsch-V.Belov  Moscow 2007  Sicilian Defence, Najdorf Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. g4
{ With 6. Be3 White usually signals an English Attack by  7.f3, Qd2, O-O-O etc; in this game, he opts for a sharper line. }
7... e5
{ The most principled reply, which virtually forces White to sacrifice a piece in order to keep the balance.   A safer choice is  7...h6  with more standard Sicilian play. }
8. Nf5 g6 9. g5 gxf5 10. exf5
{ The meek  10.gxf6  f4  11.Bd2  Be6  would go against the spirit of the variation. }
10... d5
{ This pawn advance is Black's only promising choice.   After the materialistic  10...Nfd7  11.Qh5  , with ideas like O-O-O, Bc4, g5-g6 etc, his king gets under too much pressure   While the seemingly pragmatic  10...Bxf5  fails to  11.gxf6  , followed by Nd5 or Qf3, with a clear grip on the light squares. }
11. gxf6 d4
{ Black is ready to charge the piece, though it goes without saying that White's compensation will be enormous. }
12. Bc4 Qc7
{ White's previous clever move rendered both captures on  e3  and  c3  impossible due to the tactical blow  13.Bxf7   while  12...Qxf6  13.Nd5  Qc6  14.Bxd4  has yielded him excellent results in practice. After the text he will have to hand over the piece under less favourable circumstances. }
13. Qd3 dxe3
{ This is currently regarded as the best choice. Several older games saw the continuation  13...dxc3  14.O-O-O  cxb2+  15.Kb1  Nc6  16.f4  with a strong white initiative. }
14. f4
{ A rare try in this sharp position, with the obvious intention of clearing the e-file towards Black's king. The main line goes  14.O-O-O  exf2  15.Bxf7+  Kxf7  16.Qd5+  Kxf6  17.Ne4+  Ke7  with great complications. }
14... Bb4
{ Black hurries to swap the dangerous enemy knight on c3, exploiting the fact that, contrary to the main line with 14. O-O-O, White's king is still on e1. }
15. O-O-O Bxc3 16. bxc3
{ A chaotic position has occurred. White is a whole piece down and his pawn structure has been ruined. On the other hand, Black's development is minimal and his king is already being targeted by the active enemy pieces, in complicity with the strong f6-pawn. Needless to say, calculation abilities are essential to handle such a position with either colour. }
16... Nc6
{ Development first, and support of the crucial e5-pawn. The greedy  16...exf4  failed to  17.Qe4+  Kf8  18.Qxf4  with decisive threats. }
17. Rhg1
{ The last piece joins the battle, with focus on the g7-square. The attempts to clear the e-file were less convincing:  17.Qxe3  Bxf5   -  17.fxe5  Qxe5   -  17.Rhe1  exf4  18.Qe4+  Qe5  all help Black }
17... Rf8
{ Reinforcing the kingside defence. The earlier game E.Van Den Doel-L.Van Wely, Dieren 1999, saw  17...e2  18.Qxe2  Bxf5  19.Qh5  Be4  @@StartBracket@@or   19...Bg6  20.Rxg6  fxg6  21.f7+  Ke7  22.Qg5+  Kf8  23.Qf6  , winning@@EndBracket@@  20.fxe5  Na5  21.Be6  Rf8  22.Bd7+  Qxd7  23.Rxd7  Kxd7  24.Qg4+  and Black resigned. }
18. Qxe3
{ In the event of  18.fxe5  Qxe5  19.Rg3  Bxf5  20.Qe2  Black is saved by the opportune  20...Rd8  ; e.g.  21.Rxe3   @@StartBracket@@or  21.Rxd8+  Kxd8  , leaving the e-file@@EndBracket@@  Rxd1+  22.Kb2   @@StartBracket@@not  22.Kxd1  Bg4  23.Qxg4  Qxe3  24.Qc8+  Nd8  and Black wins.@@EndBracket@@  22...Qxe3  23.Qxe3+  Be6  24.Bxe6  fxe6  25.Qxe6+  Kd8  with a clear advantage - Naiditsch. }
18... Bxf5 19. Qc5
{ Restricting the knight on c6.   Naiditsch also indicates the curious line  19.fxe5  Nd8  20.Bxf7+  Rxf7   @@StartBracket@@both  20...Qxf7  21.Rg7  , and  20...Nxf7  21.e6  had to be avoided@@EndBracket@@  21.Rg8+  Rf8  22.Rg7  Rf7  with a perpetual. }
19... Rd8
{ The last piece is brought into the game.   After  19...b6  20.Qa3  White keeps the initiative; e.g.  20...Na5  21.Bb3  Nxb3+  22.axb3  Be6  23.Rg5  , intending  23...exf4  24.Qa4+  b5  25.Rxb5  axb5  26.Qxa8+  Qc8  27.Qa7  with a decisive attack. }
20. Bd5 Rxd5
{ Black returns some of the material in order to retain his valuable knight, whose departure would leave him very weak on the dark squares; e.g.  20...Be6  21.Bxc6+  bxc6  22.Rxd8+  Qxd8  23.Qxc6+  Bd7  24.Qxa6  e4  25.Re1  with a decisive attack - Naiditsch.   As for the attempt to castle artificially with  20...Kd7  , Naiditsch indicates  21.Be4+   @@StartBracket@@of course not  21.Bxc6+  Kc8  @@EndBracket@@  21...Ke6  22.Bxf5+  Kxf5  23.fxe5  Rxd1+  24.Rxd1  Rd8   @@StartBracket@@not  24...Qxe5  25.Rd5  @@EndBracket@@  25.Rf1+  Ke6  26.Qc4+  Kd7  27.Qg4+  Ke8  28.e6  with a clear advantage. }
21. Rxd5 Be6 22. Rd6 exf4 23. Rg7 Bd7
{ The only move, in view of the threat  23...--  24.Rxe6+  . } 24. Rd1
{ Redirecting the rook to a better destiny, such as e1 or g1. } 24... Be6 25.
Re1
{ The materialistic  25.Rxh7  was called for. Now the threat of 26. Qxf8+ forces Black to play  25...Rg8  , and after  26.Rg7   @@StartBracket@@  26.Qg5  Ne7  is less promising@@EndBracket@@  Rf8  27.Re1  Qc8  28.Qd6  Qd7  29.Qxf4  White has a clear edge - Naiditsch. The passed h-pawn makes a big difference compared with the position arising after White's 27th move in the game. }
25... Qc8 { The desirable  25...Qd8  failed to  26.Rxe6+  fxe6  27.Qh5+ } 26.
Qd6 Qd7 27. Qxf4 Qd8
{ Heading for a5, with some counterplay against the enemy king. } 28. Reg1
{ White should have settled for  28.Rxh7  Qa5  29.Rxe6+  fxe6  30.Qd6  Qg5+  31.Kb2  Qb5+  with a draw by perpetual - Naiditsch. }
28... Qb8 29. Qh6
{ This time,  29.Qxb8+  Nxb8  30.Rxh7  Nd7  31.Rf1  seems preferable, with an unclear endgame. }
29... Qd6 30. R1g2 Qa3+ 31. Kd1 Qxc3
{ In apparent time-trouble both players missed the strong  31...Kd7  , escaping with the king to  c7  , after which only Black would have real attacking prospects. }
32. R7g3 { Now Black has to look out for the threat of Qxf8+. } 32... Qa1+ 33.
Kd2 Qd4+ 34. Kc1 Qa1+ 35. Kd2 Qd4+ 36. Kc1 Qc5 37. Rd2
{ Preventing ...Kd7-c7. } 37... Qe5 38. c3 Qc5 39. Qf4 Qe5 40. Qf2 Qa5 41. Qf4
Qe5
{ It is difficult for either side to make progress, besides which both players must have been really tired at this point. }
