[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "M.Boguslavsky-A.Bazhin  USSR 1990  Benoni Defence "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/pp5p/2n2bp1/2pB4/8/5N2/PP4PP/R1B2RK1 w kq - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

19. Bg5
{ A powerful move, which helps to mobilize the queen's rook and invites the exchange of the active enemy bishop on f6. }
19... Bxb2
{ After  19...Bxg5  20.Nxg5  Black is also in trouble; e.g.  20...Bf5  21.g4  Bxg4  22.Nf7  Rf8  23.Bxc6+  bxc6  24.Rae1+  Kd7  25.Ne5+  , winning. }
20. Bxc6+
{ This and the 22nd move follow the same policy of swapping the opponent's active pieces, thus increasing one's advantage in activity. }
20... bxc6 21. Rae1+ Kd7 22. Ne5+
{ 22.Re7+  Kd6  23.Rd1+  Bd4+  is less precise - Yusupov. } 22... Bxe5 23. Rxe5
Kc7 24. Re7+ Bd7 25. Rd1 Rad8 26. Bf4+
{ White could have won the exchange with  26.Rg7  but prefers to keep up the attack. }
26... Kb6 27. Rb1+
{ Again activity above material - there is a mate coming up. } 27... Ka5 28.
Bd2+ Ka4 29. Re4+ c4 30. Rxc4+ Ka3 31. Bc1+ Kxa2 32. Rb2+ Ka3 33. Rb7+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "Y.Seirawan-P.Zarnicki  Buenos Aires 1993  Nimzo-Indian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3
{ Preparing to meet ...Bxc3+ at any moment with Qxc3, thus keeping the pawn structure intact. }
5... c5 6. a3 Ba5 7. Bg5 Nc6
{ Nowadays,  7...h6  8.Bh4  g5  , followed by  9.--  9...g4  or  9...Ne4  , enjoys more popularity. }
8. O-O-O Bxc3 9. d5 { A strong intermediate move. } 9... Be5 10. dxc6 Qc7
{ Losing time, since the bishop will have to retreat on the next move anyway.   10...Bc7  was preferable. }
11. g3
{ A move with various virtues: it avoids ...Bf4+, prepares Nxe5 followed by Bf4, and enables Bg2, seizing the long diagonal.   In contrast,  11.cxd7+  Bxd7  would just have helped Black with his development. }
11... Bd6 12. Bg2 dxc6
