[SetUp "1"]

13. Rxd6
{ A strong sacrifice that eliminates Black's main defender and facilitates an attack on his Achilles' heel on c6. }
13... Qxd6 14. Rd1 Qc7
{ 14...Nd5  was preferable, returning the material in order to secure the king, although after  15.e4  O-O  16.exd5  exd5  17.cxd5  cxd5  18.Rxd5  White keeps a clear edge - Ftacnik. }
15. Bf4 Qb7 16. Ne5 Bd7 17. Rxd7 Nxd7 18. Bxc6 Qa6 19. Nxd7 Qc8 20. Ba4
{ An even faster win was achieved by  20.Nb8+  Kf8  21.Bxa8 } 20... Ke7 21. Qd3
f6 22. Qd6+ Kf7 23. Ne5+ { Vacating the d7-square for the bishop. } 23... fxe5
24. Bd7 Qd8 25. Qxe6+ Kf8 26. Bxe5 g6 27. Bf6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "H.Nakamura-A.Goldin  Buenos Aires 2003  Scotch Game "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+
{ A sideline in the Scotch, by which Black provokes c2-c3 in order to avoid White's Nc3 later on. }
5. c3
{ After  5.Nc3  Nf6  the game transposes to an old variation which is currently considered as harmless,   5...Nge7  is possible too. }
5... Bc5 6. Be3 Bb6 7. Qg4
{ Exploiting the fact that ...Nf6 is not yet on the board, White launches an attack on the g7-pawn.   There are many other options here; for example,  7.Bc4   @@StartBracket@@and  7.Nf5  Bxe3  8.Nxe3  @@EndBracket@@ }
7... Qf6 8. Qg3 Qg6
{ Not  8...Nxd4  9.cxd4  Bxd4  10.Bxd4  Qxd4  11.Nc3  with dangerous compensation for the pawn. }
9. Nf5 d6 10. Bxb6
{ Black's point is that  10.Nxg7+  Kf8  just leads to trouble for White; e.g.  11.Nf5  Bxf5  12.exf5  Qxg3  13.hxg3  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Nf6  with excellent play for the pawn - Postny. }
10... axb6 11. Ne3 Nf6 12. f3
{ Weakening the dark squares, a fact that Black immediately exploits.   12.Nd2  was a better defence of the e4-pawn, developing a piece in the process. }
12... Qh6 13. Qf2
{ Black has slight lead in development.Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "H.Nakamura-A.Goldin  Buenos Aires 2003  Scotch Game "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1pp2ppp/1pnp1n1q/8/4P3/2P1NP2/PP3QPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13... d5
{ An excellent pawn break, exploiting the fact that any move with the knight on e3 runs into ...Qc1+. }
14. Na3
{ Finally White starts bringing out his pieces.  After   14.exd5  Nxd5  15.Nxd5  Qc1+  16.Ke2  O-O  he is indeed in deep trouble; e.g.  17.Nxc7  Qxb2+  18.Nd2  Qxa1  19.Nxa8  Re8+  20.Ne4  Qxa2+  , regaining the piece with a decisive advantage - Postny. }
14... dxe4 15. Nb5 O-O 16. Nxc7 Ra5
{ Possibly  16...exf3  17.Nxa8  Re8  was even stronger - Postny. } 17. b4
{ Creating new weaknesses.   17.f4  at once was better. } 17... Rh5 18. f4 Ng4
19. Qg3
{ After  19.Nxg4  Bxg4  it is far from clear where White's king should hide. In the game he sacrifices a pawn to castle long. }
19... Nxh2 20. O-O-O Nxf1 21. Rhxf1 Nxb4
{ By a simple trick Black wins another pawn. } 22. cxb4 Qc6+ 23. Kb2 Qxc7
{ Black later converted his strategic and material superiority into victory. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "A.Onischuk-A.Volokitin  German League 2010  Queen’s Indian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 c5
{ In this apparently quiet Queen's Indian line, Black usually continues  7...O-O  . The text aims at achieving a Hedgehog position by means of ...c5xd4 and ...d7-d6; however, White has a dangerous reply prepared. }
8. e4 Nxe4
{ A risky decision.   8...cxd4  9.e5  Ng4  was safer, when the knight can always retreat to h6 if necessary. }
9. Ne5 d5
{ Unfortunately for Black,  9...Nc3  fails to  10.Qh5  g6  11.Qh3  a trick familiar from the:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/8/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ba6  5  Nbd2  variation in the same opening. }
10. cxd5 exd5
{ Now Black is about to castle; however...   After  10...Nxd2  11.Nxf7  Kxf7  12.dxe6+  Kxe6  13.Bxb7  White wins - Golubev. }
11. Qa4+ Ke7 { Or  11...Nd7  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Bh3  with a decisive pin. } 12.
Nxe4 dxe4 13. Rd1
{ The apparently natural  13.dxc5  runs into  13...Qd5  , so White prepares it. }
13... Qd5 14. O-O f5
{ The attempt to castle artificially by  14...Rd8  fails to  15.Rfe1  f5  16.f3  , clearing too many lines towards the Black's camp.   His last chance was  14...cxd4  15.Rxd4  Qxe5  16.Bxe4  Nc6  , returning the piece in order to bring out the pieces. After  17.Bxc6  Bxc6  18.Qxc6  Rhc8  19.Rd7+  Kf8  20.Qf3  Qe6  21.Rfd1  White has a clear, though not yet decisive advantage - Golubev. }
15. --
{ Now, on the other hand, he manages to launch a decisive attack.Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

