1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Nf6 5. dxc5
{ Another main direction is  5.d5  with Benoni-like play. } 5... b6
{ Instead of recovering the pawn by  5...Qa5+  and 6...Qxc5, Black gambits. }
6. e4
{ White turns down the offer, giving priority to swift development. Less enterprising is  6.cxb6  Qxb6  7.Qc1  d5  , when the f2-f3 move does more harm than good. }
6... bxc5 7. e5 { The flexible  7.Nc3  is also reasonable. } 7... Ng8
{ Black's only developed piece returns home.  7...Qc7  seems more logical, as played in few games. Here White could try  8.Bc4   @@StartBracket@@or  8.Nc3  with a complex battle@@EndBracket@@   Instead,  8.Bg3  Nh5  proves useless for White. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Bb5 Nd4 10. Nge2
{ White keeps bringing out more pieces and invites the exchange of Black's only developed piece. In this context, the bishop pair is a much less relevant factor. }
10... Nxb5 11. Nxb5 Qa5+
{ This won't turn out well, but Black already had a difficult task, considering the abysmal difference in development. }
12. Nec3 a6
