1. c4 e5 2. e3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Bb4 5. Nd5
{ In this English variation, similar to a Rossolimo Sicilian with reversed colours,  5.Qc2  , preventing  ...e5-e4  , is White's main choice. }
5... e4 6. Ng1 O-O 7. Qc2 Re8 8. Ne2 b5
{ This pawn sacrifice became popular when Gelfand launched it one move later -  8...Bd6  9.a3  b5  - against Salov at Linares 1992. }
9. Ng3
{ Both  9.cxb5  Nxd5  10.bxc6  Bd6   @@StartBracket@@and  9.Nxf6+  Qxf6  10.cxb5  Ne5  11.Qxe4  Bb7  @@EndBracket@@ yield Black plenty of compensation for the pawn. }
9... Bb7
{ Insisting on the gambit.   In contrast, the unadventurous line  9...bxc4  10.Bxc4  would just help White with his development. }
10. a3 Bd6 11. b3 Ne5 12. Bb2 bxc4 13. bxc4
{ The attempt to speed up development by the continuation  13.Nxf6+  Qxf6  14.Bxc4  runs into  14...Nd3+  , when both  15.Bxd3   @@StartBracket@@and  15.Qxd3  Qxb2  @@EndBracket@@  15...exd3  favour Black. }
