15... Rb8
{ Black increases the pressure at the enemy camp, unworried about 16.Nxd6, depriving him of the bishop pair and damaging his pawn structure.   Either  15...Bxe4  16.Qxe4  Rb8  17.Bc3   @@StartBracket@@ or  15...Ng4  16.Nxd6  cxd6  17.Qf5  was less promising @@EndBracket@@   but  15...Bf8  also made sense, when  16.Bxe5  Rxe5  17.Bd3  , preparing  O-O  , might be White's best try. }
16. Nxd6 cxd6 17. Bc3 Qh4
{ The last piece enters the battle, creating the strong threat of 18...Ng4. }
18. h3 Ng4 19. Qf5
{ This runs into a strong sacrifice, but after 19.g3 Qh6  White was also suffering badly. }
19... Nxe3 20. dxe3 Rxe3+ 21. Kd2
{ Or if instead  21.Be2  Rxe2+  22.Kxe2  Qc4+  , when both  23.Kd2   @@StartBracket@@and  23.Qd3  Re8+  24.Kd2  Qf4+  25.Kc2  Be4  @@EndBracket@@  Be4  24.Qa5  Qd3+  25.Ke1  Re8  win for Black - De Dovitiis. }
21... Rxc3
{ A second sacrifice that eliminates the key defender of the dark squares in White's camp. }
22. Qxd5 { Or  22.Kxc3  Rb3+  23.Kc2  Qd4  with decisive threats. } 22... Rc5
23. Qd3 Rb2+ 24. Kd1 Qa4+
{ The same 'long' queen check that we witnessed in Onischuk-Volokitin, with colours and flanks reversed. }
