[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "G.Hertneck-H.Grooten  Salzburg 2004  Queen’s Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6
{ The Queen's Indian is one of the openings where the principle 'don't move the same piece twice' is most frequently infringed. Any defence of the c4-pawn now has its drawbacks, after which the bishop settles on its natural square b7, at least in a majority of cases. }
5. Nbd2 Bb7 6. Bg2 c5 7. e4 cxd4
{ Taking the pawn with  7...Nxe4  proves very risky after  8.Ne5  ; e.g.  8...Nc3  9.Qh5  g6  10.Qh3  , winning material. }
8. O-O d6 9. Nxd4 Nbd7
{ In the Hedgehog position that now emerges, the tempo loss caused by ...Ba6-b7 implies that Black is one move further away from castling, so he should choose the move order with some care.   Perhaps  9...Qc8  makes more sense; e.g.  10.Re1  Be7  11.a4  O-O  12.a5  Na6  13.N2b3  Nd7  14.Bf4  Ne5  with counterplay, P.Tregubov-V.Baklan, European Championship @@StartBracket@@ rapid playoff @@EndBracket@@, Plovdiv 2008. }
10. Re1 Qc7
{ Defending against the tactical shot e4-e5, but the queen gets exposed on this square.   Perhaps  10...Qb8   @@StartBracket@@ or  10...Qc8  was safer, although in either case  11.a4  , intending  11...--  12.a5  bxa5  13.N2b3  followed by Nxa5, yields White a certain initiative. }
11. Nb5 Qb8
{ Preparing a consolidation by ...a7-a6, ...Be7, ...O-O etc.Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
