14. Nc4
{ Unconcerned about the doubling of the f-pawns, White creates the threat of 15. Nb6 and clears the way for the queen's bishop. }
14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rb8
{ If  15...Bg7  , then  16.Nxd6+  exd6  17.Re1+  Kf7  18.Bc4+  d5  19.Bxd5+  Nxd5  20.Qxd5+  Kf8  21.Bf4  with a winning advantage - Mirkovic. }
16. Re1 Bg7
{ A misguided sacrifice of the d6-pawn.   Obviously  16...Rxb5  failed to  17.Nxd6   But the prophylactic  16...Kf7  made some sense, when  17.a4  keeps the advantage - Mirkovic. }
17. Nxd6+ Kf8 18. Bf4
{ The last piece joins the battle, securing the knight on d6. } 18... Ne8 19.
Qb4
{ The right square for the queen, where it supports both pieces on d6 and b5 without exposing herself to the black knights.   @@StartBracket@@  19.Bh6  Ndf6  is less clear @@EndBracket@@   while the game went  19.Qd3  Nc5  20.Qd5  Nxd6  21.Rxe7  Kxe7  22.Re1+  Nce4  23.fxe4  Nxb5  24.exf5+  Kf8  25.Qc5+  Kf7  and Black had a defendable position. }
19... Ne5
{ An unsuccessful try for complications, but the alternatives where no better;   e.g.  19...exd6  20.Bxd6+  with mate;   or  19...Nxd6  20.Bxd6  Bf6  21.Bxb8  Nxb8  22.a4  and the passed a-pawn soon decides. }
20. Nxe8 Nxf3+ 21. Kh1 Rxb5 22. Qxb5 Nxe1 23. Nc7
{ With decisive threats at e6 and e1.   But not  23.Nxg7  Qa8+  . } *

