1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3
{ An interesting line against the Caro-Kann, where White can hit the enemy pawn chain on both the queenside  @@StartBracket@@c2-c4 @@EndBracket@@  and the kingside  @@StartBracket@@f2-f4, g2-g4@@EndBracket@@  depending on Black's play. But in the first place, White aims at completing his kingside development. }
4... e6 5. Be2 Ne7 6. O-O Bg6 7. Nbd2 Nf5 8. g4
{ An advance that gains space and time, but slightly weakens the kingside structure.   8.Nb3  and  8.c3  are more flexible continuations. }
8... Ne7
{ After  8...Nh4  9.Nxh4  Qxh4  10.f4  f5  11.Nf3  Qxg4+  12.Kh1  White has compensation - Bologan. }
9. Nh4 h5
{ A risky choice. Black aims to liberate the f5-square for his knight, but delays development.   9...c5  is safer; e.g.  10.c3  Nec6  11.Nxg6  hxg6  12.Nf3  Nd7  13.Bf4  Be7  14.Qd2  a6  15.Kg2  Rc8  , preparing ...Na5-c4, with balanced chances in K.Lahno-B.Jobava, Wijk aan Zee 2006. }
10. gxh5 Bh7 11. Ndf3 Nf5 12. Ng2
{ Thus White leaves the black knight blocking the bishop on h7 and prepares a future Nf4. }
12... c5 13. Bg5 { Development with tempo. } 13... Qb6
{ Playing with fire: now the delay in development will make itself strongly felt.   13...Be7  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  , preparing  ...O-O  , was safer; e.g.  15.c4  dxc4  16.d5  exd5  17.Nf4  Nd4  when both  18.Nxd5   @@StartBracket@@and  18.Nxd4  Qg5+  @@EndBracket@@  Nxe2+  19.Qxe2  Bd3  seem okay for Black. }
14. --
