15. f5
{ Opening the position at all cost, considering Black's lack of development.   15.Kb1  O-O-O  is much less promising. }
15... Qxa2
{ After  15...Nxe5  16.Qe4  exf5  17.Qxf5  White's lead in development and strong bishop pair speak in his favour. }
16. fxe6 Qxe6
{ Or  16...Nxe5  17.exf7+  Qxf7  18.Qe4  , winning - Rozentalis. } 17. Qf4
{ A key move that enables Bh3 should Black castle long or capture the e5-pawn. }
17... Rd8
{ Both  17...Qxe5  18.Bh3   @@StartBracket@@and  17...Nxe5  18.Bh3  Qe7  19.Rhe1  f6  20.Qg3  @@EndBracket@@ preparing f2-f4, are fatal for Black. In the latter line, note that White's attack actually becomes much swifter once the e5-pawn leaves the board. }
18. Bc4 Qe7 19. Rhe1
{ By now White's lead in development is decisive; again we have the typical 'play against one goal' situation. }
19... h5 { Or  19...Nxe5  20.Bd4  Nxc4  21.Rxe7+  Bxe7  22.Re1  etc. } 20. Qg3
{ Preventing 20...Rh6;   and preparing to meet  20.Qg3  g6  by  21.e6   The immediate  20.e6  fxe6  21.Bxe6  was also strong. }
20... Nxe5 { Suicide, but there were no good alternatives anymore. } 21. Rxd8+
Kxd8 22. Bf4 { Avoiding the trap  22.Bg5  f6  23.Rxe5  Qd6 } 22... Nxc4 23.
Rxe7 Kxe7 24. Qd3
{ The queen enters on  d6  with devastating effect; and  24.Qd3  b5  25.b3  doesn't change much, so Black resigned. }
