[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "E.Bareev-V.Ivanchuk  Novgorod 1994  Nimzo-Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4
{ A topical line of the Classical Nimzo-Indian, where White counts on the bishop pair, but Black is ahead in development and will do everything possible to exploit it. }
7. Qc2 c5 8. dxc5 Nc6 9. Nf3
{ A natural choice; but practice has shown both  9.e3  , and  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Nf3  to be more promising. }
9... Qa5+ 10. Nd2
{ More ambitious than  10.Bd2  Qxc5  with equality.   Had @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2Pp4/2P1n3/P7/1PQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.cxd5  exd5  been inserted, then White could now swap the active black queen. }
10... Nd4 { Activity above material; the pawn can wait. } 11. Qd3 e5
{ Gaining space and preparing ...Bf5. } 12. b4
{ Now  12.cxd5  Nxc5  is bad for White. } 12... Qa4
{ Setting up the threat of  13.--  13...Nc2+  . } 13. Ra2 Nxd2
{ More promising than  13...Bf5  14.cxd5  Nxc5  15.Qc3  with e2-e3 or e2-e4 coming up. }
14. Rxd2
{ This recapture allows Black to develop his remaining pieces with great speed.   14.Bxd2  Bf5  is equally bad, with similar play as in the game.   Instead,  14.Qxd2  leaving the vulnerable b1-h7 diagonal at the price of a mere pawn, was called for. The old game D.Bronstein-I.Boleslavsky, Saltsj Baden Interzonal 1948, continued  14...dxc4   @@StartBracket@@now  14...Bf5  15.e3  Nc2+  16.Rxc2  , followed by  16...--  17.cxd5  , favours White@@EndBracket@@  15.e3  Nb3  16.Qc3  Be6  17.Bxc4  Bxc4  18.Qxc4  Nxc1  19.Qxc1  a5  and a draw was agreed. }
14... Bf5 15. Qe3 O-O-O
{ A move with various virtues: securing the king, mobilizing the rook, and defending the d5-pawn.   15...Nc2+  16.Rxc2  Qxc2  17.cxd5  is less clear. }
16. g4
{ Aware that both  16.cxd5  Rxd5  , followed by ...Nc2+   @@StartBracket@@and  16.Qxe5  Nc2+  17.Rxc2  Qxc2  @@EndBracket@@ leaves his king in big trouble, White employs radical measures to speed up development.   Now  16.g4  Bxg4  lets White escape by  17.cxd5  Rxd5  18.Bg2  , followed by O-O, but Black has a much stronger option at his disposal... }
16... --
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
