[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "E.Bareev-V.Ivanchuk  Novgorod 1994  Nimzo-Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr3r/pp3ppp/8/2Pppb2/qPPn2P1/P3Q3/3RPP1P/2B1KB1R b K - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

16... Qc2
{ A spectacular move, and the only one that does the job!   In contrast, after  16...Nc2+  17.Rxc2  Qxc2   @@StartBracket@@or  17...Bxc2  18.Bg2  @@EndBracket@@  18.gxf5  dxc4  19.Bd2  Qb1+  20.Bc1  , White is alive. }
17. Rxd4
{ Entering an inferior endgame, but the alternatives were no better;   e.g.  17.gxf5  Qxc1+  18.Rd1  Nc2   or  17.Rxc2  Nxc2+  18.Kd2  dxc4+  19.Kc3  Nxe3  20.gxf5  Nxf1  21.Rxf1  Rd4  with a clear advantage for Black. }
17... exd4 18. Qd2 Qxd2+ 19. Bxd2 Be4
{ Obstructing the enemy development;   19...Bxg4  would invite the white rook into the battle after  20.cxd5  Rxd5  21.Rg1 }
20. f3 Bg6 21. cxd5 Rxd5 22. Bg2 f6 23. Kf2 h5 24. Bf4 Bc2
{ Redirecting the bishop to a more promising diagonal, where it prevents Rd1. }
25. h4 Re8 26. Rc1 Ba4 27. gxh5 Rxh5 28. Bg3 Re3 29. Rc4 Rd5 30. Bd6
{ An oversight;   though after  30.Rxd4  Rxe2+  31.Kxe2  Rxd4  Black is much better. }
30... Rc3 31. f4 Rxd6
{ In view of  31...Rxd6  32.Rxc3  dxc3  33.cxd6  c2  , White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "S.Volkov-R.Kempinski  European Championship,  Dresden 2007  Semi-Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4
{ The variation that now arises has a huge body of theory;   so  4...Bb4  , followed by ...Nge7, makes sense for Slav players wishing to leave the 'book' at an early stage. }
5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+
{ The initial position of Marshall's Gambit. Black is a pawn up, but White enjoys the bishop pair and a lead in development, so a tense battle can be expected. }
8. Be2 Na6
{ After  8...Qxg2  9.Bf3  Qg5  10.Ne2  , followed by Rg1, White's compensation is duplicated. }
9. Ba5
{ By means of the threat 10. Qd8# White aims to provoke a minor weakness in Black's camp.   Another direction is  9.Bd6  . }
9... f6 10. Nf3
{ The straightforward  10.Qd8+  Kf7  11.O-O-O  is also possible, whereas the text keeps both castling options open. }
10... b6 11. Nd2 { Preparing Bf3 in order to attack the fresh weakness on c6. }
11... Qf4 12. Bh5+
{ Curiously, the provocation measure effected on move 9 is repeated on the opposite flank. }
12... g6 13. Bf3 Ne7 14. Bc3 Nc5
{ So far Black has played well, but now he starts delaying development.   This was a good moment for  14...O-O  - Krasenkow. }
15. g3 Qf5 16. O-O e5 { Again  16...O-O  was more to the point - Krasenkow. }
17. b4 Nb7
{ Perhaps Kempinski had planned  17...Ne6  and only now discovered the line  18.Ne4  O-O  19.g4  Qf4  20.Bd2  and White wins. }
18. b5
{ Finally White is able to create concrete threats.   Black should now have played  18.b5  Bd7  , preparing ...O-O, in order to complete development. Instead, he commits a new inaccuracy... }
18... c5
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
