[SetUp "1"]

19. Be4
{ Clearing the way for the f-pawn and enabling a future Qf3 with increased pressure on the long diagonal. }
19... Qe6 20. f4
{ A strong advance opening several lines towards Black's underdeveloped camp. }
20... Rb8
{ This leads to unsolvable problems on the queenside, but the alternatives weren't much better.   20...exf4  21.Qf3  fxg3  22.Rae1  wins for White  @@StartBracket@@Krasenkow@@EndBracket@@   While after  20...O-O  21.fxe5  Black is practically lost since  21...fxe5  fails to  22.Rxf8+  Kxf8  23.Qf3+  .   Now let's suppose that, instead of 18...c6-c5? Black had played the correct @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pn2n2p/1pp2pp1/1P2pq2/2P5/2B2BP1/P2N1P1P/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Bd7  . In that case, after the analogous continuation  19.Be4  Qe6  20.f4  O-O  21.fxe5  fxe5  he would be just fine, with the rooks connected and the long diagonal sufficiently defended. One tempo in development can indeed make an enormous difference. }
21. Qa4 Na5 22. Bxa5
{ In view of the horrible position arising after  22.Bxa5  bxa5  23.b6+  Bd7  24.bxa7  Rc8  25.Qxa5  Bc6  26.fxe5  Black resigned. }
