[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "A.Vovk-M.Kowara  Warsaw (rapid) 2009  Sicilian Defence, Kan Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 Nf6
{ In this branch of the Sicilian Kan,  6...b5  , followed by Bb7, is a safe option, delaying ...Nf6 until the right moment. We saw a similar case in Conquest-Sokolov. }
7. O-O b5
{ A well-known inaccuracy due to White's next move.   If Black wants to keep on delaying ...d7-d6, then  7...Nc6  7...Be7  or  7...Bb4  were better options. }
8. Bf3 { Suddenly 9. e5 is a strong threat. } 8... Bb7
{ If  8...Nc6  then White plays  9.e5  anyway.   While  8...e5  9.Nf5  also favours him. }
9. e5 Ng8 10. Bf4 Nc6
{ The queenside should be developed first.   After  10...Ne7  11.Ndxb5  axb5  12.Nxb5  the check on  d6  decides. }
11. Nxc6 dxc6 12. a4
{ White tries to open the position in order to exploit his lead in development.   The simple  12.Ne4  , heading for d6, looked strong as well. }
12... Ne7 13. axb5 cxb5
{ It seems that  13...Rd8  14.Qe2  cxb5  kept the material balance, whereas in the game White wins a pawn. }
14. Nxb5 axb5 15. Rxa8+ Bxa8 16. Bxa8 Ng6 17. Bg5
{ Correct was  17.Bg3  , hanging on to the pawn, but the fact that this was a rapid game perhaps made White choose a more active move. }
17... --
{ In this tense position, how do you continue with Black?  @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
