[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "M.Parligras-J.Melero Fidalgo  Seville 2005  Sicilian Defence, Kan Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5
{ Just as in Conquest-Sokolov, Black develops his queenside first.   A more classical approach in this branch of the Sicilian Kan is  5...Qc7  followed by ...Nf6. }
6. Bd3 Bb7 7. O-O Qb6 8. Be3 Bc5 9. Qg4
{ Instead of protecting his knight, White launches a counterattack at g7.   Perhaps  9.Nce2  is objectively stronger, preparing b2-b4, just like later on in the game. }
9... Ne7
{ Preparing ...Ng6;   but the simplifying  9...Bxd4  10.e5  Nh6  11.Qxd4  Qxd4  12.Bxd4  Nc6  was a safer choice - Parligras. }
10. Nce2 Ng6 11. b4
{ An excellent advance that helps clear the sensitive b-file towards Black's camp. }
11... Bxb4 12. Nxb5 Bc5 13. Nbd4
{ Having a lead in development White keeps as many pieces as possible on the board. For the same reason, the tension along the g1-a7 diagonal favours him. }
13... d6 14. Rab1 Qc7
{ Black is just about to castle; however...Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "M.Parligras-J.Melero Fidalgo  Seville 2005  Sicilian Defence, Kan Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2k2r/1bq2ppp/p2pp1n1/2b5/3NP1Q1/3BB3/P1P1NPPP/1R3RK1 w kq - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. e5
{ A strong blow that opens the position for White's forces and undermines the bishop on c5.  Less convincing was   15.Nxe6  fxe6  16.Qxe6+  Ne7  17.Bc4  Rf8  with unclear play - Parligras. }
15... Nd7
{ After  15...dxe5  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Bxg6+  hxg6  18.Qxg6+  White soon regains the piece with a huge advantage.   15...Nc6  might be a better try, although after  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Bxg6+  hxg6  18.Qxg6+  Kf8  19.Nf4  White keeps a strong initiative - 'Chess Today'. }
16. Nxe6 { A typical sacrifice to keep the enemy king in the centre. } 16...
fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kd8
{ Or  17...Ne7  18.Rxb7  Qxb7  19.exd6  Nf8  20.Qe5  Bxd6  21.Qxd6  with a clear edge - Parligras. }
18. exd6 Qc6 19. Rxb7 { Eliminating one of Black's most active pieces. } 19...
Qxb7 20. Be4 Qa7 21. Bxa8 Qxa8 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. Qc4
{ New threats with every move. } 23... Qc8
{ Now  23...Qc6  runs into  24.Nd4  Qxd6  25.Qxc5  simplifying to a won endgame. }
24. Nd4 Re8 { Black parries the threat of 25. Qxc5 and 26. Ne6+. } 25. d7
{ An ingenious move to expose the black king along the d-file. } 25... Kxd7
{ Or  25...Nxd7  26.Nc6+  Kc7  27.Ne7+  and wins - Parligras. } 26. Qd5+ Ke7
27. Nf5+ Kf8 28. Nd6
{ Finally White recovers the material, while Black's king remains exposed. }
28... Qc7 29. Nxe8 Kxe8 30. Re1+
{ In view of the continuation  30.Re1+  Ne7  31.Qg8+  Kd7  32.Qxg7  Qd6  33.Qxh7  , Black resigned. }
