[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "N.Kalesis-J.Hellsten  Corinth 1997  Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. a4 Bf5 6. Qb3 Ra7
{ We saw a similar pattern in Miton-Sammour: Qb3, attacking Black's Achilles' heel in the Slav, the b7-pawn, and the awkward, but safe reply ...Ra7. }
7. Nf3 e6 8. Be2 a5
{ Thus Black creates a stronghold on b4 and prevents a cramping a4-a5, which would have been an interesting option for White on the previous two moves. }
9. O-O Nbd7 10. Nh4
{ After a rather modest opening White starts fighting for the initiative. The exchange of the enemy bishop will facilitate the e3-e4 advance, a key idea in such positions. }
10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bf3 Ne4
{ Somehow I thought the tactical motif  12...Ne4  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bxe4  Qh4  justified this attempt to seize the centre, but it soon proves to be a loss of time.   A sounder choice was  12...Bb4  , complicating e3-e4, and preparing ...O-O in order to conclude development. }
13. g3 Ng5
{ 13...Ndf6  seems more natural, although after  14.Bg2  , followed by f2-f3, the knight will have to leave its prominent post anyway.   In contrast,  13...f5  is strongly met by  14.Nxe4  fxe4  15.Bg2  , followed by f2-f3. }
14. Bg2 Nh3+ 15. Bxh3
{ Probably there was nothing wrong with  15.Kh1  , but the text gains time and eliminates the only active enemy piece. }
15... Rxh3
{ 15...dxc4  16.Qxc4  Rxh3  was preferable, keeping the position somewhat more closed, but I still wasn't aware of the danger awaiting me. }
16. --
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
