[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "N.Kalesis-J.Hellsten  Corinth 1997  Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3qkb2/rp1n1pp1/2p1p1p1/p2p4/P1PP4/1QN1P1Pr/1P3P1P/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

16. cxd5
{ Before pushing the e-pawn White rules out ...d5xc4 as in the previous subvariation;   e.g.  16.e4  dxc4  17.Qxc4  Nb6  , followed by ...Bb4, with much more resistance than in the game. }
16... cxd5 17. e4
{ The key move of the game, which clears the position towards the uncastled black king. Note that both black rooks prove awkwardly placed once the game is opened. }
17... dxe4 18. Nb5
{ After  18.Nxe4  Nf6  19.Bg5  Be7  Black defends   Although  18.Be3  or even  18.d5  looked strong as well. }
18... Ra6 19. Bf4 Rc6 20. d5
{ In the same aggressive spirit, clearing more lines towards Black's king. }
20... exd5 { The tempting  20...Nc5  failed to  21.dxc6  Nxb3  22.cxb7 } 21.
Qxd5 Be7 22. Rad1 g5
{ After  22...Nf6  23.Qe5  Black is also in deep trouble. } 23. Nd6+ Bxd6 24.
Bxd6 Rh6 25. Ba3
{ The bishop is kept on its best diagonal.   Of course  25.Qxe4+  Re6  had to be avoided. }
25... Rhe6 26. Rfe1 Qc7 27. Rxe4
{ A good alternative was  27.Qxg5  Qe5   @@StartBracket@@or  27...Ne5  28.Qxg7  Nf3+  29.Kh1  with irresistible threats@@EndBracket@@  28.Qh4  Rh6  29.Qxe4  , transposing to a endgame with a decisive extra pawn. }
27... Ne5 28. --
{ At this point the game continued  28.Kg2  Nc4  29.Rxc4   @@StartBracket@@  29.Rde1  was correct, keeping up the pressure@@EndBracket@@  Rxc4  30.Qxg5  Qc6+  31.Kg1  Rd4  and Black later saved a draw.   In contrast, the simple  28.Red4  would have left him defenceless against the mating threat; e.g.  28...f6  29.f4  gxf4  30.gxf4  Nf7  31.Re4  Qc8  32.Rde1  Nd8  33.f5  and White wins. }
