[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "S.Palatnik-S.Lputian  Irkutsk 1983  English Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. g3 Be6 7. e4 a5
{ We are already familiar with this line from the game Psakhis-Gofshtein, where the latter preferred  7...Be7  , speeding up his development. As for the text, Black enables an annoying ...a5-a4 whenever White plays b2-b3. In conclusion, this line seems rather demanding for the first player, who should probably prefer  7.Nd5  instead. }
8. b3 a4
{ The temporary sacrifice  8...Nxe4  9.Nxe4  d5  was even stronger, followed by an opportune ...Bb4. }
9. Rb1 axb3 10. axb3 Nxe4
{ On the second occasion Black takes his chance, although this time the piece can't be recovered immediately. }
11. Nxe4 d5 12. cxd5
{ In the event of  12.Nc3  --  Black can transpose to the game by  12...Bb4  13.cxd5  Bxd5   Although  12...d4  seems even stronger; e.g.  13.Na2  Bf5  14.Rb2  Rxa2  15.Qe2+   @@StartBracket@@but not  15.Rxa2  Bb4  @@EndBracket@@  Kd7  16.Rxa2  Bb4+  with 17...Re8 next. }
12... Bb4 13. Nc3 Bxd5
{ In return for his material deficit Black enjoys excellent piece activity, and the enemy king is stranded in the centre. }
14. f3 O-O
{ This natural move seems inaccurate due to White's strong reply.   Later the improvement  14...Qe7+  preparing ...Qc5, was discovered; e.g.  15.Be2  Qc5  16.Bb2  O-O-O  17.Kf1  Bxf3  18.Qxd8+  Rxd8  19.Nxf3  , as in the game P.Poobalasingam-C.McNab, Uxbridge 2009, where  19...Nd4  would have yielded Black a crushing advantage. }
15. Kf2
{ Suddenly the pin on the d-file has become more serious than the one on the e1-a5 diagonal. }
15... Ra5 16. Bc4 Nd4
{ After  16...Bxc4  17.bxc4  , both  17...Qf6   @@StartBracket@@and  17...Qe7  18.Nge2  @@EndBracket@@  18.Rxb4  Nxb4  19.Nd5  Nxd5  20.Qxa5  are dubious for Black. }
17. --
{ In this tense position, how do you continue with White?Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
