1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2 e5 7. Nb3
{ In this Catalan line, White usually prefers  7.Nf3  these days, with immediate pressure on Black's centre. }
7... d4 8. e3 Bg4
{ Practice has mostly seen the continuation  8...a5  9.exd4  a4  , but the text has its logic: Black provokes f2-f3 in order to weaken the opponent's dark squares and limit the bishop on g2. }
9. f3 Be6 10. exd4 Bxc4
{ At the cost of a pawn, Black manages to keep the enemy king in the centre.  10...exd4  11.Nxd4  Bxc4  was probably fine as well, since  12.Qa4+  b5  13.Nxb5  fails to  13...Qe7+  followed by a deadly check on e2. }
11. dxe5 Nd5 12. Nc3 Bb4 13. Bd2 Bxc3
{ Keeping the active knight. After  13...Nxc3  14.bxc3  Be7  15.f4  White is slightly better - Ftacnik. }
14. Bxc3 Nc6 15. Qd2 Qb6
{ A natural move, in order to prevent O-O and enable ...Ne3, but White possesses a strong reply.   Preferable was  15...Bxb3  16.axb3  Nxc3  17.Qxc3  and only now  17...Qb6  , with sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
16. Na5 Ne3
{ Or  16...Nxa5  17.Bxa5  Qc5  18.f4  O-O  19.Rc1  , with the strong threat of Rxc4. }
17. Nxc4 Nxc4 18. Qf2 Ne3
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
