[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "G.Rechlis-B.Avrukh  Israeli Team Championship 2005  Sicilian Defence,  Rossolimo Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. Bxc6+
{ Nowadays, the early Bxc6+  capture is seen rather often in different lines of the Rossolimo Sicilian.   The old main line is  4.O-O  followed by 5. Re1 or 5. c3. }
4... bxc6 5. O-O e5 6. c3
{ White immediately prepares the d2-d4 break, even at the cost of a pawn, as we will see next. }
6... Bg4 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 exd4 10. Re1
{ Preparing e4-e5.   The immediate  10.e5  is less promising due to  10...d5  11.Rd1  Ne7  , followed by ...Ng6 - Avrukh. }
10... Be7
{ Another, perhaps safer option was  10...Nf6  11.e5  dxe5  12.Qxc6+  Nd7  13.Rxe5+  Be7  , followed by ...Rc8 and ...O-O - Avrukh. }
11. e5 dxe5
{ Black agrees to do without castling, since  11...d5  12.Qg4  would just make things worse for him with the knight deprived of its natural destiny on f6. }
12. Qxc6+ Kf8 13. Nd2
{ Time to resume development, as  13.Rxe5  runs into  13...Rc8  . } 13... Rc8
14. Qf3
{ 14.Qa6  was stronger, so that the queen keeps on interfering with Black's play; e.g.  14...f6   @@StartBracket@@or  14...Qc7  15.Rxe5  @@EndBracket@@  15.Qxa7  Qd5  16.Ne4  f5  17.Ng5  with the initiative - Avrukh. }
14... Qc7 15. b3
{ Now that the f3-square is occupied, preparing the move 16. Nc4 makes good sense for White. }
15... Nf6
{ At first sight,  15...Qc3  , swapping the queens, seems logical; however, White is better after  16.Qxc3  dxc3  17.Nc4  f6  18.Be3  a6  19.Rec1  - Avrukh. }
16. Nc4 e4 17. Qf5
{ Preparing 18. Bf4, with increased pressure at the enemy camp. In this tense position, how do you continue with Black?Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 1"]
[Black "G.Rechlis-B.Avrukh  Israeli Team Championship 2005  Sicilian Defence,  Rossolimo Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2k1r/p1q1bppp/5n2/5Q2/2Npp3/1P6/P4PPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17... h5
{ A key move, which prepares ...g7-g6 without having to bother about Bh6+ and lets Black develop his last piece by ...h5-h4 and ...Rh5 later on.   In contrast,  17...g6  was risky because of  18.Bh6+  Kg8  19.Qg5  Rd8  20.Rac1  , intending Ne5-c6 - Avrukh. }
18. Bf4 g6 19. Qg5
{ After  19.Qh3  Qxf4  20.Qxc8+  Kg7  21.Qh3  Rd8  Black enjoys excellent compensation for the exchange;   While  19.Qxf6  Bxf6  20.Bxc7  Rxc7  21.Rxe4  Kg7  leads to an equal endgame - Avrukh. }
19... Qd8 20. Be5 h4
{ Black is just in time to bring the rook into play before his centre crumbles. }
21. Rad1 Rh5 22. Qf4 Nd5 23. Qg4
{ Of course not  23.Qxe4  which is met by  23...Nc3  . } 23... Rg5
{ Avrukh is not satisfied with the equality arising after  23...Rxc4  24.bxc4  Rxe5  25.cxd5  Qxd5  26.f3  exf3  27.Qxf3  Rxe1+  28.Rxe1  Qd7  and goes for more. But also White has his trumps, as we will see next. }
24. Qxe4 Nc3 25. Qxd4 Nxd1 26. Bd6
{ Now that the black king's rook is no longer preventing the mate on h8, this counterblow becomes possible. }
26... Kg8 27. Rxe7 Nc3 { An ingenious defence that keeps Black in the game. }
28. Qxc3 Qxd6 29. Re8+ Rxe8 30. Nxd6 Rd5 31. h3 Rxd6
{ An approximately equal endgame has arisen, and the game later ended in a draw. }
