1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+
8. Be2 c5
{ Returning the pawn so as to enable ...Nd7 with tempo in the complications that now follow.   We already came across this line in Volkov-Kempinski,  where Black preferred the modern  8...Na6  . }
9. Bxc5 Qxg2 10. Qd2
{ A dubious choice, since White will have difficulties in recovering the material sacrificed.   Either  10.Bf3  or  10.Qd6  Nd7  11.O-O-O  is preferred nowadays. }
10... Qxh1 11. O-O-O Nd7 12. Nf3
{ White brings more pieces into the battle, but objectively his compensation is insufficient.   In contrast, with his queen on d6 cf. 10. Qd6 above at this point  12.Bf3  would have been decisive, while here it fails simply to  12...Qxh2  . }
12... Qg2
{ Not  12...Qxd1+  13.Qxd1  Nxc5  14.Qd4  and White recovers the material with some initiative. }
13. Ba3
{ The tempting  13.Ne5  Ngf6  14.Qd6  is refuted by  14...Qg5+  15.f4  Qxf4+  16.Kb1  Ng8  - Vera. }
13... Ne7
{ Black speeds up development, but he had more efficient possibilities at hand, as Vera himself indicates.   After  13...Qxf2  14.Ne5  Qxh2  15.Nxd7  Qh6  White is lost;   While  13...a5  preparing ...Ra6, would also have refuted the enemy attack. }
14. Ne5
{ Obviously this knight is untouchable because of mate. In this tense position, how do you continue with Black?Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
