[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1 Early Pawn-Grabbing"]
[Black "P.H.Nielsen-J.Timman  Malmö 2002  Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5
{ 6.e3  is another direction in this Slav main line. } 6... Nbd7
{ Black, for his part, could opt for the sharp  6...e6  7.f3  Bb4  8.e4  Bxe4  9.fxe4  Nxe4  . }
7. Nxc4 Nb6
{ Black used to play  7...Qc7  exclusively here, preparing ...e7-e5, but nowadays the text is equally popular. }
8. Ne5 a5 9. g3 Nfd7
{ Again challenging the active enemy knight.   Another option is  9...e6  10.Bg2  Bb4  , speeding up development and complicating the e2-e4 thrust. }
10. Nxd7 { With this capture White gains a tempo for development. } 10... Qxd7
11. e4 Bg4
{ Black somehow wants to provoke f2-f3 but, as the remainder of the game will show us, it is rather White who is helped by that move.   11...Bh3  at once was correct; e.g.  12.Bxh3  Qxh3  13.Qb3  Ra6  14.Be3  e6  , when both  15.d5   @@StartBracket@@and  15.O-O-O  @@EndBracket@@  can be met by  15...Bb4  . }
12. f3 Bh3 13. Bxh3 Qxh3 14. Qb3
{ Attacking Black's vulnerable queenside and preparing O-O-O. } 14... Ra6
{ Or  14...Qg2  15.Rf1  Ra6  16.d5  with a clear advantage - I.Sokolov. It is indeed difficult to see how Black can cope with the threat 17. Be3, whereas  16...Qxh2  17.Bf4  , followed by O-O-O, also looks grim for him. }
15. Be3 Qg2
{ When behind in development, don't hunt pawns! The fact that a player of Timman's calibre infringes this principle tells us something about its relevance.   The last chance was  15...e6  , when I.Sokolov advocates  16.Kf2   @@StartBracket@@instead of  16.d5  Bb4  @@EndBracket@@  Bb4  17.Ne2  with a clear initiative now that Black's queen proves dangerously exposed to 18. Nf4 on the next move. In retrospective, that powerful king move would not have been available after the immediate 11...Bh3. }
16. O-O-O Qxf3 17. Rhe1
{ White brings his last piece into the battle, setting up the irresistible threat of 18. d5. }
17... g6
{ This practically loses a piece;   though after  17...Qf6  18.d5  cxd5  19.exd5  , followed by Nb5   @@StartBracket@@or  17...e6  18.d5  Bb4  19.dxe6  @@EndBracket@@ Black is also done; e.g.  19...O-O  20.Bxb6  Rxb6  21.e7  Re8  22.Rd8  , winning - Hübner. }
18. d5 Bg7 19. Bxb6 O-O 20. Bd4 { With an extra piece the rest is easy. } 20...
Bxd4 21. Rxd4 Qf2 22. Red1 Qxh2 23. Qxb7 *

