[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1 Early Pawn-Grabbing"]
[Black "A.Vaisser-M.Illescas Cordoba  Spanish Team  Championship 1996  Tarrasch Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3
{ 4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nf3  is a more popular reaction to the Tarrasch Defence, followed by g2-g3 and Bg2, eyeing the potential isolated pawn on d5. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. Ne5
{ We will soon see the drawbacks of this early attack on c6.   A normal continuation was  8.O-O  O-O  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.b3  and Bb2 in order to complete development, although I suspect that the king's bishop would be better off at e2. }
8... Qc7
{ Here and on the next move, Black doesn't hand over the bishop pair by  8...Bd7  9.Nxd7  , but keeps the tension. }
9. Qa4
{ With hindsight,  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Be2  , followed by 12. O-O, was preferable. }
9... O-O
{ A key decision. Black sacrifices a pawn in order to speed up development. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 cxd4
{ Illescas immediately clears the centre;   aware that  11...cxd4  12.Bxa8  now fails to  12...dxc3  13.Bc6  Be5  14.Rb1  Bf5  . }
12. Nxd5
{ Here  12.exd4  Rb8  13.Bb5  a6  14.Be2  , preparing O-O, was preferable - Illescas, even though Black keeps the pressure after  14...Re8  . At this point, White should probably just bite the apple by  15.O-O   @@StartBracket@@since the materialistic  15.h3  runs into  15...Bb4  with strong threats@@EndBracket@@  Bxh2+  16.Kh1  . Indeed, when ahead in material but behind in development, giving back a pawn tends to be a sensible idea. }
12... Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rb8 14. Qxd4
{ Taking a second pawn is far too greedy.   After  14.O-O  Bxh2+  15.Kh1  Bd6  , with ...Rb4 coming up, Black has a great position with certain attacking prospects, but at least White has managed to castle. }
14... Ba6
{ Of course. Now White is denied castling, and his two extra pawns hardly help the defence. On the contrary, the absence of black pawns on the b- and e-files lets Black use his heavy artillery more efficiently in the attack. }
15. Bd2 Be5 { Parrying the threat of 16. Bc3. } 16. Qa4 Qd6
{ Stepping up the pressure.   In contrast,  16...Bxb2  would be a strategic error in view of  17.Qxa6  Bxa1  18.O-O  Be5  19.g3  , followed by e3-e4. White is the exchange down but Black's attack has disappeared completely and the bishop is a giant on d5. }
17. e4 Rxb2 18. Rd1
{ After  18.Qc6  Rxd2  19.Kxd2   @@StartBracket@@or  19.Qxd6  Re2+  @@EndBracket@@  Bf4+  20.Kd1  Qb4  , the white king succumbs. }
18... Rc8
{ The last piece joins the battle, adding new tactical themes to the menu. }
19. g3
{ White's position was already beyond salvation. The text prevents 19...Bf4, but Black is now able to land another tactical blow. }
19... Rxd2 20. Rxd2
{ Or  20.Kxd2  Qh6+  21.f4  Bxf4+  with a quick mate on e3. } 20... Rc1+
{ 20...Rc1+  has the idea  21.Rd1  Bc3  . White is completely lost, though he keeps on fighting until the bitter end. }
21. Qd1 Qa3 22. Bc4 Rxd1+ 23. Kxd1 Qf3+ 24. Kc2 Qc3+ 25. Kd1 Qa1+ *

