[Round "?"]
[White "2.1 Early Pawn-Grabbing"]
[Black "Exercise #2: A.Vaisser-M.Illescas"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rb2rk1/p1q2ppp/3b4/3B4/3Q4/4P3/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... Ba6
{ Of course. Now White is denied castling, and his two extra pawns hardly help the defence. On the contrary, the absence of black pawns on the b- and e-files lets Black use his heavy artillery more efficiently in the attack. }
15. Bd2 Be5 { Parrying the threat of 16. Bc3. } 16. Qa4 Qd6
{ Stepping up the pressure.   In contrast,  16...Bxb2  would be a strategic error in view of  17.Qxa6  Bxa1  18.O-O  Be5  19.g3  , followed by e3-e4. White is the exchange down but Black's attack has disappeared completely and the bishop is a giant on d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1 Early Pawn-Grabbing"]
[Black "A.Moiseenko-S.Dvoirys  European Cup, Fügen 2006  Grünfeld Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ This line against the Grünfeld became increasingly popular during the new century, with fresh ideas for White being discovered, particularly by Georgian players. }
4... Ne4 5. Bh4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 dxc4
{ The most principled reply.   6...c5  and  6...Bg7  are other options. } 7. e3
Qd5
{ This defence of the c4-pawn has the evident drawback of exposing the queen.   7...Be6  is the main line here. }
8. Be2
{ By developing the bishop first, White enables Bf3 on some occasions, e.g. if Black launches a set-up with ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7.   Obviously  8.Be2  Qxg2  now fails to  9.Bf3  . }
8... Qa5
{ Black goes for a second pawn when his development is almost zero.   8...Nd7  9.Nf3  Nb6  10.O-O  Bg7  seems much sounder, bringing out the pieces and preparing ...O-O. B.Jobava-P.Svidler, Dortmund 2006, continued  11.a4  a5  12.Nd2  Qc6  , and here Svidler recommends  13.Bf3  Qd7  14.Qe2  , eventually leading to a white advantage. A key factor in the whole 4. Bg5 variation is the bishop on h4 which exerts annoying pressure at e7. }
9. Nf3 { White ignores the threat at c3 and just continues development. } 9...
Qxc3+ 10. Nd2 c6
{ Clearing a retreat route for the queen via a5-d8.   Hanging on to the pawn with  10...b5  proves disastrous after  11.a4  Bb7  12.O-O  a6  13.Bf3  - Moiseenko.   The developing  10...Bg7  seems more reasonable, although after  11.O-O  Qa5  12.Nxc4  Qd5  13.Qb3  Nc6  14.Bf3  Qf5  15.Rac1  O-O  16.Rfd1  , preparing d4-d5, White had a distinct initiative in Z.Izoria-V.Mikhalevski, Minneapolis 2005. }
11. O-O Qa5 12. Nxc4 Qd8
{ In the event of  12...Qc7  White could choose between the game continuation and  13.Bg3  followed by  13...--  14.Be5 }
13. Qb3 { Moiseenko has observed a great square for his queen on a3. } 13...
Bg7 14. Qa3
{ From a3 the queen increases the pressure at the e7-pawn, just before Black is able to castle. Moreover, a tactical shot with Nb6 is enabled on some occasions. }
14... Bf8
{ Returning the pieces to their initial positions is rarely correct in the opening, but Dvoirys probably didn't expect White's next move.   A better choice was  14...f6  15.Rab1  Nd7  @@StartBracket@@parrying the threat of 16. Nb6@@EndBracket@@ , although by  16.Bg4  White keeps the pressure. At this point, after  16...O-O  17.Bxd7  , both  17...Bxd7   @@StartBracket@@and  17...Qxd7  18.Nb6  @@EndBracket@@  18.Rxb7  lose material for Black - Moiseenko;   He also analyzed  14...b5  15.Na5   @@StartBracket@@not  15.Nb6  b4  @@EndBracket@@  Qd6  16.Qxd6  exd6  17.Rac1  , followed by Bf3 and Bg3, with strong pressure. Nevertheless, either of these lines was preferable to the text, as we will see next. }
15. d5
{ A well-calculated pawn break that clears several new lines towards Black's camp. }
15... cxd5
{ 15...Qxd5  obviously failed to  16.Nb6   While after  15...b5  16.Qc3  f6  17.Na5  cxd5  18.Bxb5+  Kf7  19.Rfd1  White keeps a strong initiative - Moiseenko. }
16. Qc3 f6
{ The apparently clever  16...d4  17.exd4  Bg7  , giving back a pawn to bring out the pieces, fails to  18.Nd6+   16...Rg8  has the same flaw. By the text Black prepares ...Bg7 on the next move, but runs into a new tactical problem. Let's remember the fact that tactical complications tend to favour the side with better development. }
17. Nd6+ Qxd6
{ Black has to accept the enemy intrusion, since  17...exd6  18.Bxf6  would make things even worse. }
18. Qxc8+ Kf7 19. Bb5
{ Enabling a check on e8, while limiting both the black queen and knight.   19.Qxb7  Qc6  20.Ba6  was another good option. }
19... Bg7
{ Now White recovers the material with heavy interest;   but  19...Qb6  20.Be8+  Kg7  21.Rab1  was also terminal. }
20. Qxb7 Rd8 21. Qxa8 Qb4 22. Rab1 Qxh4 23. Be2 f5 24. g3 *

