[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.2 Early Queen Raids"]
[Black "Early queen raids "]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Early queen raids@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. --
{ One of the first things taught to beginners is to be careful with the queen, bringing her out only when the rest of the pieces have been developed. Although the validity of this 'rule' obviously varies from case to case, we just witnessed an affirmative one in Moiseenko-Dvoirys. Here are two more games where early queen sorties led to big difficulties for the involved side. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.2 Early Queen Raids"]
[Black "T.Hillarp Persson-K.Nygren  Sweden 2004  Owen’s Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 3. a3
{ A sensible reply to Owen's Defence, in which Black often tries to get rid of his king's bishop on b4. }
3... Bb7 4. Nc3 Qh4
{ This early sortie with the queen doesn't fulfil any particular function and rather exposes her to the enemy pieces.   Normal continuations are  4...f5  and  4...Nf6  , taking control of the key square e4. }
5. Nf3
{ The most natural reply;   though  5.e4  was possible too, since  5...Bxe4  loses the bishop after  6.g3  . }
5... Qh5
{ Or  5...Bxf3  6.exf3  , followed by g2-g3 and Bg2, when the location of the queen on h4 just helps White. }
6. e4 { Gaining space and preparing the tempting Be2. } 6... f5
{ Despite the lack of development Black opens the game, as this was probably the only way to justify his previous play. }
7. Be2
{ Relying on some simple tactics White ignores the threat to e4 and just speeds up development.   Other continuations were less promising; e.g.  7.d5  fxe4  8.Nxe4  exd5   Or  7.e5  Bxf3  8.gxf3  Nc6  and the queen is no longer that badly placed on the h-file. }
7... Qf7
{ A sad necessity;   as after  7...fxe4  8.Ng5  Black can't defend his queen properly; e.g.  8...Qh4  9.g3  Qh6  10.Ngxe4  Qh3  11.Bg4  Qg2  12.Bf3  Qh3  13.Ng5  etc. }
8. Ne5
{ 8.Ng5  seems even stronger:  8...Qe7   @@StartBracket@@or  8...Qg6  9.Bh5  @@EndBracket@@  9.exf5  exf5  10.O-O  , followed by Re1+, with a devastating lead in development. }
8... Qf6 9. h4
{ In order to bring the last minor piece into play via g5.   At this point there are several tempting continuations such as  9.Bf3  and  9.exf5  Qxf5  10.Bd3  , but Hillarp finds an even more enterprising one. }
9... Be7
{ Black can't stop White's idea by  9...h6  due to  10.Bh5+   While  9...fxe4  fails fatally to  10.Bg5  Qf5  11.Bg4  . }
10. Bg5 Qf8
{ Hardly the square that the queen was dreaming of when she left the camp on move 4. }
11. exf5
{ Simple but strong - in order to exploit the great lead in development White should open the position. The fact that the bishop on b7 wakes up becomes irrelevant after the next move. }
11... exf5
{ Unfortunately for Black,  11...Qxf5  fails tactically to  12.Bd3  Qf8  13.Qh5+   Whereas  11...Bxg5  12.hxg5  would just activate the rook on  h1  . }
12. Bf3 { Another logical move, in order to swap the only active enemy piece. }
12... Nc6 13. Nb5
{ Stepping up the pressure, now that Black no longer can protect the c7-pawn by ...Na6. }
13... O-O-O
{ This won't end well, but what else?   For example,  13...Bd8  allows the nice blow  14.Bh5+  g6  15.Nxg6  . }
14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Nxa7+ Kb7 16. d5 { The most forceful follow-up. } 16... Bxg5
{ Obviously  16...Kxa7  runs into  17.dxc6  dxc6  18.Qa4+  . } 17. dxc6+ dxc6
18. Qa4
{ More precise than  18.Bxc6+  Kb8  . Now Black has to give a piece in order to repel the attack. }
18... Qe8+ 19. Kf1 Ne7 20. hxg5 Ra8 21. Re1 Rxa7 22. Qb4
{ Finally White wins material. } 22... Ng6 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Bxc6+
{ In view of  24.Bxc6+  Kxc6  25.Qb5+  . } *

