[Round "?"]
[White "2.2 Early Queen Raids"]
[Black "Exercise #1: T.Hillarp Persson-K.Nygren"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kbnr/pbpp2pp/1p2p3/5p1q/2PPP3/P1N2N2/1P3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

7. Be2
{ Relying on some simple tactics White ignores the threat to e4 and just speeds up development.   Other continuations were less promising; e.g.  7.d5  fxe4  8.Nxe4  exd5   Or  7.e5  Bxf3  8.gxf3  Nc6  and the queen is no longer that badly placed on the h-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.2 Early Queen Raids"]
[Black "Exercise #2: T.Hillarp Persson-K.Nygren"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kbnr/pbpp2pp/1p2pq2/4Np2/2PPP3/P1N5/1P2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

9. h4
{ In order to bring the last minor piece into play via g5.   At this point there are several tempting continuations such as  9.Bf3  and  9.exf5  Qxf5  10.Bd3  , but Hillarp finds an even more enterprising one. }
9... Be7
{ Black can't stop White's idea by  9...h6  due to  10.Bh5+   While  9...fxe4  fails fatally to  10.Bg5  Qf5  11.Bg4  . }
10. Bg5 Qf8
{ Hardly the square that the queen was dreaming of when she left the camp on move 4. }
11. exf5
{ Simple but strong - in order to exploit the great lead in development White should open the position. The fact that the bishop on b7 wakes up becomes irrelevant after the next move. }
11... exf5
{ Unfortunately for Black,  11...Qxf5  fails tactically to  12.Bd3  Qf8  13.Qh5+   Whereas  11...Bxg5  12.hxg5  would just activate the rook on  h1  . }
12. Bf3 { Another logical move, in order to swap the only active enemy piece. }
12... Nc6 13. Nb5
{ Stepping up the pressure, now that Black no longer can protect the c7-pawn by ...Na6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.2 Early Queen Raids"]
[Black "E.Postny-T.Abergel  European Championship,  Warsaw 2005  Benko Gambit "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5
{ By this advance Black stays in the waters of the Benko and Blumenfeld Gambits.   3...e6  , heading for the Benoni, is a main alternative. }
4. Bg5
{ At first sight, a surprising move - is White about to exchange his 'good' bishop and surrender the bishop pair? The answer is yes, mainly since the knight on f6 exerts unpleasant pressure on his centre  @@StartBracket@@ i.e. 4...Bb7, hitting the d5-pawn, is coming up @@EndBracket@@ , but also because in this system Black often needs considerable time to develop his remaining minor pieces, thus the absence of that knight might be strongly felt. }
4... Ne4
{ Black also frequently plays  4...Qb6  and  4...d6  , not opposing the exchange on f6. }
5. Bf4
{ Even the odd  5.Qd3  has been tried here, insisting on the bishop vs. knight exchange. }
5... Bb7 6. a4
{ A typical idea: before carrying on with his development White softens up the light squares on the queenside. }
6... Qb6
{ An unfortunate decision. Black assigns the defence of the b5-pawn to the queen, but now she becomes dangerously exposed to the enemy pieces, just like 4...Qh4 in the previous game.   6...Qa5+  is a more justified queen sortie to disrupt White's development, although after  7.Nbd2  Bxd5  8.axb5  Qb6   @@StartBracket@@not  8...Qxb5  9.c4  @@EndBracket@@  9.Nxe4  Bxe4  10.Nd2  , followed by e2-e4 and Nc4, White has had excellent results in practice.   Perhaps the modest  6...b4  is Black's best choice here; e.g.  7.c4  e6  8.Qd3  Nf6  9.e4  exd5  10.exd5  d6  with just a slight disadvantage in D.Komarov-J.M.Degraeve, French Team Championship 2002. }
7. axb5 Qxb5 8. Nbd2
{ Speeding up development and swapping the opponent's most active piece for an undeveloped one. We saw a similar case with 13. Nf3! in Hellsten-Renman. }
8... Nxd2
{ 8...Bxd5  loses a piece to  9.c4   While the provocative  8...Qb4  is well met by  9.c4  Nxd2  @@StartBracket@@the threat was 10.Ra4@@EndBracket@@  10.Nxd2  , with ideas like Ra3-b3. }
9. Nxd2 d6
{ Black resumes development, noticing that both pawns are immune.   9...Bxd5  this time runs into  10.e4   Whereas  9...Qxb2  fails to  10.Rb1  Qf6  11.e3  - Postny. }
10. e4 Qd7
{ The queen takes the square intended for the knight, since  10...Qb6  would just give White another extra tempo with  11.Nc4  . }
11. Nc4 g6
{ Now if Black manages to play ...Bg7 and ...O-O the worst would be over for him; however... }
12. e5
{ Just in time, hitting the opponent's pawn chain before he is fully developed. }
12... Bg7
{ Abergel sacrifices a pawn, after seeing that  12...dxe5  13.Nxe5  Qxd5  fails fatally to  14.Bb5+  . }
13. exd6 O-O 14. Be2 exd6 15. O-O
{ The straightforward  15.Nxd6  permits  15...Bxb2  16.Rb1  Bc3+  17.Kf1  Ba6  with some counterplay - Postny. The text lets Black save the pawn, but only by making a serious positional concession. }
15... Ba6
{ Or  15...Be5  16.Nxe5  dxe5  17.Bh6  , followed by c2-c4 and f2-f4, with a huge positional plus. }
16. Nxd6
{ Postny is happy to trade the d6- and b2-pawns, anticipating a great future for his queen's rook. }
16... Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Bxb2 18. Rab1 Bg7 19. Rb7
{ Material is even, but White's active pieces spell big trouble for Black. }
19... Qa4 20. Be5
{ White exchanges the main defender of the enemy king, exploiting the fact that ...Re8 isn't available. }
20... Qh4
{ Instead,  20...Nd7  runs into  21.Ra1   While after  20...Bxe5  21.Qxe5  both  21...Qd4   @@StartBracket@@and  21...Nd7  22.Qe7  Rad8  23.Nxf7  @@EndBracket@@  22.Nxf7  Qxe5  23.Nxe5  win for White. }
21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. Qe5+ Kg8 23. Ne8
{ In view of the multiple threats at g7, f6 and c7, Black resigned. } *

