[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.3 Multiple Moves with the Same Piece"]
[Black "R.Vera Gonzalez - A.Romero Holmes  Leon 1996  Colle’s Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 Nf6 4. e3
{ White sets up the Colle, an apparently modest opening but with great attacking potential, as in this game! }
4... b6 5. Nbd2 Bb7 6. Bd3 cxd4
{ A logical capture now that White can no longer play Nc3, but Black had many other options;   e.g.  6...d5  , gaining space.   Or  6...Nc6  , preparing to meet  7.e4  at any moment with  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nb4 }
7. cxd4
{ 7.exd4  is more popular, clearing the c1-h6 diagonal for the bishop, whereas the text has the merit of enabling e3-e4 later. }
7... Nd5
{ With bishops on g5 and e7 this is a common feature in openings like the Queen's Gambit Declined and Torre's Opening, in order to release the tension by exchanges. Here, on the other hand, Black's intention is rather to meet e3-e4 by ...Nb4 or ...Nf4, but we will soon see that this idea doesn't justify a second move with the knight.   Preferable was  7...d5   -Or  7...Be7  8.O-O  d6  9.e4  Nbd7  in Hedgehog style. }
8. O-O f5
{ Directed against e3-e4, but now the black king is dangerously exposed.   8...Be7  , bringing out the pieces, was more prudent, although after  9.e4  Nb4   @@StartBracket@@  9...Nf4  10.Bc2  Ba6  11.Re1  Nd3  comes to the same thing@@EndBracket@@  10.Bb1  Ba6  11.Re1  Nd3  12.Bxd3  Bxd3  13.d5  with the threat of 14. Nb3 and 15. d6, Black still has some difficulties to resolve. }
9. e4
{ The same old story: the side with a lead in development opens the position. }
9... fxe4
{ Black could now delay ...fxe4 for one move by 9...Nb4 or 9...Nf4, yet after  9...Nb4  10.Bb1  or  9...Nf4  10.Bc2  , it is not clear what he has achieved. }
10. Nxe4 g6
{ Romero takes precautions against the emerging threats on the b1-h7 and h5-e8 diagonals, but also delays development for the third time in ten moves.In GM Baburin's words: 'Black has been ignoring the principles of development and the punishment is swift!'   Instead,  10...Be7  11.Neg5  with ideas like  11...Nf6   @@StartBracket@@  11...g6  12.Nxh7  @@EndBracket@@  12.Ne5  O-O  13.Qc2  looks extremely dangerous for him;   So the radical  10...Nc6  , preparing ...Qc7 and ...O-O-O, seems like his last chance; e.g.  11.Neg5  Qc7  12.Nxh7  O-O-O  with some slight compensation for the pawn. Remember, difficult situations call for unusual solutions! }
11. Bg5 { Development with tempo. } 11... Qc7
{ Now  11...Be7  runs into  12.Nd6+  , so Black has to move his queen, thus giving the opponent another extra tempo. }
12. Rc1 Nc6
{ With the bishop already on g7 Black would be quite fine here, but now White is able to launch a deadly strike. Indeed, one tempo plays a gigantic role in the opening battle. A similar 'cheating' experiment in Postny-Abergel, placing the bishop on g7 just before White's 12th move, would have a similar effect. }
13. Nf6+ Nxf6 14. Bxf6 Rg8 15. d5
{ Exploiting the pin along the c-file, Vera manages to clear the e-file towards the black monarch. }
15... exd5 16. Re1+ { The white pieces are cooperating beautifully. } 16... Kf7
17. Be5 Qd8 18. Ng5+
{ An elegant way of including the last piece in the attack.   In view of  18.Ng5+  Qxg5  19.Qf3+  Ke6  20.Bf4+  Qe5  21.Rxc6+  dxc6  22.Rxe5+  Black resigned. }
*

