[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.3 Multiple Moves with the Same Piece"]
[Black "Mi.Adams-M.Gurevich  FIDE World Cup,  Khanty-Mansiysk 2007  French Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ A flexible move, by which White postpones e4xd5 until the moment seems right.   4.exd5  is the main option in this French Tarrasch. }
4... cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd8
{ Black deviates from the main line  6...Qd6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.Nb3  Nc6  9.Nbxd4  with a heavy theoretical battle. The text permits a more flexible development, since ...Nf6, preventing White's Ne4 harassing the queen, is no longer mandatory. }
7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 a6 9. Qe2
{ Before taking the pawn White wants to play Rd1 in order to control the d-file.   After  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  11.Qe2  Bd6  , followed by ...Ne7, Black has less to worry about. }
9... b5
{ Thus Black delays White's recapture on d4 and provides the bishop with the great b7-square. On the downside, his queenside pawns become vulnerable to a future a2-a4.   A safer choice was  9...Bd6  10.Rd1  Nge7  11.Nbxd4  Nxd4  12.Rxd4  with just a slight edge for White - Grivas. }
10. Bd3 Nf6
{ By now, the set-up with ...Nf6 makes sense, in order to prevent Be4 or Qe4. }
11. Rd1 Be7 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qc7 14. c3
{ The immediate  14.a4  permits the cramping  14...b4  , so White prepares it. }
14... Bc5
{ Black gets ready to meet  14...Bc5  15.a4  by  15...b4  . Unfortunately, moving the bishop again also implies the loss of a vital tempo for development.   Gurevich obviously rejected  14...O-O  due to  15.a4  , when both  15...b4   @@StartBracket@@and  15...bxa4  16.Rxa4  , hitting the a6-pawn@@EndBracket@@  16.cxb4  Bxb4  17.Bg5  , followed by Rac1, yield White the upper hand.   However, a simple solution was  14...Bd7  , complicating a2-a4 while getting on with development. Admittedly this bishop was heading for b7, but in demanding situations you need to be flexible. After  15.Nf3  O-O   @@StartBracket@@and he could even consider  15...Bc6  16.Ne5  Bd5  17.Bf4  Qb7  with unclear play@@EndBracket@@  16.Ne5  Rfd8  - Adams, followed by ...Be8, Black is okay. }
15. Bg5
{ White immediately changes his focus to the kingside, exploiting the absence of the bishop on e7. }
15... Bb7
{ Underestimating the danger.  15...Bxd4  16.cxd4  Nd5  was essential, with some kind of blockade, although after  17.Rac1  Qd6   @@StartBracket@@or  17...Qd7  18.Qh5  @@EndBracket@@  18.Qg4  , intending  18...O-O  19.Bh6  , Black has definite problems in completing his development. }
16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Be4
{ After destroying the black king's shelter, White proceeds with the exchange of the active bishop on b7. }
17... Bxe4
{ 17...Rd8  fails to  18.Bxb7  Qxb7  19.Nxe6  fxe6  20.Qh5+   While after  17...O-O-O  18.b4  Bxd4  19.cxd4  Qd7  20.a4  White has a clear initiative - Adams. }
18. Qxe4 O-O 19. Qh4 { Hitting the vulnerable f6-pawn. } 19... Rfd8
{ Black just hands over the pawn, seeing that both  19...Be7  and  19...Qe5  run into  20.Rd3  , heading for h3 or g3   While  19...f5  20.Qg5+  Kh8  21.Qf6+  Kg8  22.Rd3  is also dangerous for him. }
20. Qxf6 Bf8 21. Rd3
{ The rook gets ready for action along the third rank, while its colleague reaches the d1- and e1-squares. For a player of Adams' calibre, the rest is a matter of technique. }
21... Bg7 22. Qg5 { Of course not  22.Rg3  Qxg3  . } 22... Qe5
{ Conversely, Black should avoid  22...Rd5  23.Nxe6  . } 23. Qg4 Rd6 24. Rg3
Rc8 25. Qh4 Kh8 26. Qe7 Qc5
{ Or  26...Qd5  27.Qxf7  Bxd4  28.cxd4  Qxd4  29.h3  Qxb2  30.Re1  Rdc6  31.Kh2  etc - Adams. }
27. Re1 Rf8 28. Nxe6 { 28.Rxg7  Kxg7  29.Re3  was even stronger - Adams. }
28... Qe5 29. Rge3 *

