[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.4 Exposure of the King"]
[Black "Exposure of the king"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Another recommendation to beginners is to castle quickly in order to secure the king and activate one of the rooks. However, in practice things are far from being that simple, and sometimes one side delays castling for one or another reason - to avoid an enemy attack, develop other pieces, fight for the centre, etc.Next, let's see two games where Black's decision to delay castling was less justified, and cost him dearly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.4 Exposure of the King"]
[Black "U.Andersson-L.Portisch  Skopje Olympiad 1972  Sicilian Defence,  Rossolimo Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+
{ You might think of the Rossolimo Sicilian as a quiet, solid, opening line, yet it often produces miniatures, perhaps due to White's typically rapid development. }
3... Nc6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3
{ A main idea of the Rossolimo is to build a pawn centre by c2-c3 and d2-d4. }
6... a6 7. Bf1 e5
{ Nowadays, the disruptive   7...Bg4  is much more popular; e.g.  8.d3  e6  9.Nbd2  Be7  10.h3  Bh5  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nh4  Nd7  with a complex game. }
8. h3
{ A useful piece of restriction: before launching d2-d4, White prevents ...Bg4. }
8... h6
{ In contrast, Black's corresponding pawn move makes little, if no sense at all.  He should have preferred   8...Be7  9.d4  O-O  in order to speed up development. }
9. d4 Qc7 10. a4
{ Typical preparation for the Na3 @@StartBracket@@ d2 @@EndBracket@@ -c4 manoeuvre. }
10... g6
{ Portisch must have decided that this bishop belongs on g7; unfortunately, he now loses one more tempo for his development.   After  10...Be7  11.Na3  O-O  12.dxc5  dxc5  13.Nc4  , with ideas like a4-a5 and Ne3-d5, White is a bit better, but at least Black has managed to castle. }
11. Na3 Bg7 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Nc4
{ Simple and strong, spotting the fresh weakness at d6. } 13... Rb8
{ A fatal misevaluation.   Portisch probably didn't like the look of  13...O-O  14.Qd6  Qxd6  15.Nxd6  Rfb8   Both:  15...b6  16.Nc4   @@StartBracket@@and  15...Rab8  16.Be3  @@EndBracket@@ shed a pawn  16.Bc4  Be8  with a passive position for Black. However, worse things will happen to him in the game.   After  13...Rb8  there is of course  14.Nd6+  , depriving Black of castling - yet after  14...Ke7  , followed by ...Rhd8, things aren't that clear. Andersson finds a much stronger solution. Remember, when ahead in development, open the position! }
14. b4
{ An ingenious sacrifice that aims to exploit the a3-f8 diagonal with the bishop. }
14... cxb4 15. cxb4 Be6
{ With the text Portisch prepares ...Bxc4 as well as ...Rd8, but Andersson is just in time to complete the punishment.  Unfortunately for Black, the desired   15...O-O  now loses material after  16.b5  , followed by Ba3 @@StartBracket@@ -d6 @@EndBracket@@ .  Even worse is   15...Nxb4  16.Bb2  with overwhelming pressure; e.g.  16...Nc6  17.Ba3  followed by Nd6+. }
16. Nd6+ Ke7 17. Ba3
{ The move order matters - after   17.b5  Nb4  18.Ba3  a5  Black can put up a better defence. }
17... Ne8
{ After  17...Qxd6  18.b5  Nb4  19.Qxd6+  Kxd6  20.Bxb4+  Kc7  21.Rac1+  the location of the black king decides. }
18. Nxb7
{ The most effective follow-up, which helps to clear the c-file for the attack. }
18... Qxb7
{ After   18...Rxb7  19.b5+  Nd6  20.bxc6  Qxc6  21.Rc1  Qd7  22.Bxa6  Black is also helpless. }
19. b5+ Kf6 20. bxc6 Qc7
{ Or   20...Qxc6  21.Nxe5  , inviting the king to a fatal walk. } 21. Nxe5
{ In view of   21.Nxe5  Kxe5  or   21...Qxe5  22.Qf3+  22.f4+  Kxf4  23.e5  , followed by mate, Black resigned. }
*

