[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.4 Exposure of the King"]
[Black "R.Ovetchkin-N.Efanov  Nizhnij Tagil 2007  Semi-Slav Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Qb3
{ A flexible sideline against the Slav. By defending the c4-pawn with his queen, White keeps any other development issues open. }
4... e6
{ 4...dxc4  5.Qxc4  Bf5  , followed by ...e7-e6, is one of many alternatives. }
5. Nc3
{ White opts for a classical set-up.   5.g3  with Catalan-like play is also possible. }
5... Nbd7
{ Black finally reverts to some kind of Queen's Gambit Declined.   A more active choice was a Meran set-up with  5...dxc4  6.Qxc4  b5  , followed by ...Nbd7, ...a7-a6 and ...c6-c5. }
6. Bf4 Be7 7. e3 Nh5
{ This was a natural moment to castle, but Black prefers to challenge the bishop on f4. }
8. Be5 Nxe5
{ White's previous move forced Black to make some minor concession in order to swap the bishop. After the text his knight becomes temporarily misplaced on h5; whereas  8...f6  9.Bg3  Nxg3  10.hxg3  f5  11.Bd3  leaves him with a somewhat passive position. }
9. dxe5 g6 { Parrying the threat of 10. g4. } 10. Be2 Qb6 11. Qc2
{ White correctly estimates that his space advantage and slight lead in development will be more efficiently exploited with the queens still on the board. }
11... Ng7 12. O-O f5
{ Black somehow wants to prevent e3-e4 but, as we will see next, the effect of his move is quite the opposite.   This was another good moment for  12...O-O  . }
13. exf6 { Opening the position is usually correct when ahead in development. }
13... Bxf6 14. e4
{ A key move that creates new threats before Black manages to castle. } 14...
Qa5
{ Moving the queen again does very little to resist White's initiative; and neither does  14...d4  15.e5  Be7  16.Ne4   @@StartBracket@@nor  14...dxe4  15.Nxe4  Qxb2  16.Qd3  .@@EndBracket@@   So Black should have tried  14...O-O  15.cxd5  exd5  16.exd5  Bf5  with some compensation for the pawn thanks to the bishop pair. As we will see next, it was definitely worth a pawn to get castled. }
15. exd5 exd5 16. cxd5 Bxc3
{ Practically forced; in view of  16...cxd5  17.Bb5+  displacing Black's king. }
17. bxc3 { The intermediate  17.Qe4+  was interesting as well. } 17... cxd5 18.
c4
{ Just like four moves ago, White hurries to install new threats before Black castles away. }
18... Be6
{ Now after  18...O-O  19.cxd5  Bf5   @@StartBracket@@  19...Qxd5  obviously fails to  20.Bc4  @@EndBracket@@  20.Qb3  Black's compensation for the pawn is much less convincing than in the 14...O-O subvariation above.   On the other hand,  18...dxc4  19.Bxc4  would leave his king fatally exposed in the centre, so he decides to reinforce that diagonal with the bishop. }
19. Rab1
{ An accurate move, bringing a new piece to the battle with tempo. In contrast,  19.Ng5  lets Black escape by  19...O-O  20.Nxe6  Nxe6  21.cxd5  Nd4   While  19.cxd5  Bxd5  also moves him a bit closer to castling. }
19... Qc7
{ The only defence of the b7-pawn; since  19...Rb8  loses after  20.cxd5  Bxd5  21.Rb5  or  21.Bb5+  . }
20. Qa4+
{ Again Black is just one move from getting castled, but this ingenious manoeuvre puts an end to any illusions. }
20... Qc6 { 20...Bd7  is met with the same reply. } 21. Qa3
{ Now Black can definitely forget about castling, and the rest is play against one goal. }
21... dxc4 22. Nd4 Qd7 23. Nxe6 Nxe6 24. Bxc4 Kf7
{ At the same time, Black resigned.   24...Kf7  25.Qf3+  , followed by Rxb7, is one of several winning options. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.4 Exposure of the King"]
[Black "Exercise #1: R.Ovetchkin-N.Efanov "]
[Result "*"]
