*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.4 Exposure of the King"]
[Black "A.Sokolov-L.Sandler  USSR 1991  Sicilian Defence, Najdorf Variation"]
[Result "*"]

{ The next game shows another unfortunate decision regarding the king: castling to the 'wrong' side. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. f4
{ Twenty years ago set-ups with f2-f4 were quite popular in the Sicilian, whereas nowadays, the English Attack starting with  7.f3  is far more common in practice. }
7... Nbd7 8. Qf3 Qc7 9. Bd3 b5 10. O-O Bb7 11. Nd1
{ A curious idea. White spends two tempi on transferring the knight to f2, where it can't be bothered by ...b5-b4. }
11... Nc5
{ Another sensible option is  11...g6  12.Nf2  Bg7  ; e.g.  13.Rac1  e5  14.Nb3  d5  with counterplay in Wang Zili-Xu Jun, Shenzhen 1992. }
12. Nf2 Be7 13. Rae1 g6
{ Black prepares ...e6-e5 without having to worry about Nf5, but also weakens his kingside.   The simple  13...O-O  , followed by ...Re8 and ...Bf8, was perfectly possible; e. g.  14.a3  Rfe8  15.b4  Nxd3  16.cxd3  Bf8  with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 next. }
14. a3 { Preparing b2-b4, or just a clever waiting move... } 14... O-O-O
{ A fatal decision. Sandler must have thought that with most enemy pieces located on the kingside, his king would be safe on the opposite flank, but this is far from being the case.   Again there was nothing wrong with  14...O-O  ; e.g.  15.g4  e5  16.fxe5   @@StartBracket@@or  16.Ne2  d5  @@EndBracket@@  16...dxe5  with a solid game. At this point  17.Ne2  Ne6  18.g5  backfires after  18...Nh5  19.h4  f5  with a strong initiative.   Black could also delay castling for a while, a typical feature of some open Sicilians in order to frustrate White's attack. One idea in this sense is  14...d5  15.e5  Nfe4  ; e.g.  16.b4  Nxf2  17.Qxf2  Ne4  with balanced play. }
15. b4
{ It makes sense to start the attack right away, before Black consolidates with ...Kb8 and ...Rc8. }
15... Nxd3 { After  15...Na4  16.c4  White also manages to clear the c-file. }
16. cxd3 Kb8 17. a4 { Opening more lines towards the black monarch. } 17... e5
{ Black tries a counterstrike, aware that  17...bxa4  would just play in White's hands after  18.b5  e5  19.Rc1  Qa5  20.Nc6+  etc - Sokolov. }
18. Rc1 Qd7 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Nb3
{ The knight has found a great destiny on c5. Apart from the clouds gathering around his king, Black has a serious problem with the unstable knight on f6. }
20... bxa4 21. Nc5 Bxc5
{ Or  21...Qb5  22.Bg5  Rd6  23.d4  with a clear edge - Sokolov. } 22. bxc5
{ The right recapture, to clear the b-file and create a dangerous passed pawn. }
22... Ne8 23. Qg3 Ka8
{ Black just hands over the pawn since  23...f6  24.d4  followed by 25 d5 is terminal. }
24. Qxe5 f6 25. Qc3 { By now White's game plays itself. } 25... Bc6 26. Rb1 Bb5
27. Rfc1 Qc6 28. d4 Nc7 29. Qa5
{ After  29.d5  Nxd5  30.exd5  Rxd5  things might get a little more complicated. In fact there is no hurry with d4-d5, since Black is short of active plans. Thus Sokolov just improves his pieces until the position becomes ripe for a tactical shot. }
29... Rhe8 30. Bf4 Kb7 31. Bxc7 Qxc7 32. c6+ Kc8 33. Rxb5 axb5 34. Qa6+ Kb8 35.
Qxb5+ Ka8 36. Rc4 *

