[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5 Premature Attacks"]
[Black "Premature attacks"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ 'Don't be rushed into a premature, unprepared attack' says one of Yusupov's rules in Opening Preparation. The following two games illustrate rather well the risks involved in such action. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5 Premature Attacks"]
[Black "I.Csom-V.Korchnoi  Gyula 1965  King’s Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. d5
{ This move is usually effected only after Black's ...c7-c5 or ...e7-e5. By playing it at this early stage White sidesteps the Grünfeld  @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3 d5@@EndBracket@@  but also loses a tempo and weakens the dark squares, in particular c5. }
3... Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 c6
{ The opponent's third move made Black's planning a bit easier, and he now starts actions on the queenside. }
7. Be3 a6 8. a4 { 8.Nf3  b5  9.Nd2  , preparing O-O was quite reasonable. }
8... a5
{ The conclusion of a typical trick in openings like the King's Indian. First, Black sets up the 'threat' ...b7-b5 in order to provoke White's a2-a4, then he plays ...a6-a5, fixing the dark squares on c5 and b4 as future outposts. }
9. g4
{ The beginning of an absurd plan. Ignoring factors such as the tense centre and a certain delay in development, White initiates an attack on the black king.   The modest  9.Nf3  , followed by O-O, was called for. }
9... Na6 10. f4 { On  10.h4  Black could just react as in the game. } 10... Nd7
{ Simple but strong. Black redirects the knight to c5 and clears the long diagonal for the bishop. }
11. h4 Ndc5 12. Bf3
{ Fatally diverting the bishop from the defence of d3 and c4.   White had to be consistent and continue  12.h5  , when  12...Bxc3+  13.bxc3  Nxe4  14.Bf3  yields him some compensation for the pawn. In turn Black should avoid this line and continue as in the game. }
12... Qb6
{ A severe punishment that practically decides the game. The method of attacking the weakest spot in the enemy camp, in this case b2 and its neighbouring squares, is familiar to us from Tal-Tringov and Movsesian-Tibensky. }
13. Qd2
{ This fails to a simple trick; but after  13.Rb1  Qb4  14.Ne2  Qxc4  White is suffering anyway. }
13... Qxb2 14. Qxb2 Nd3+ 15. Kd2 Nxb2 16. Be2
{ Trying to trap the knight; however... } 16... Bxg4
{ A second blow directed at the overloaded bishop on e2. White resigned, since both  16...Bxg4  17.Bxg4   @@StartBracket@@and  17.Bf1  cxd5  18.cxd5  Rac8  @@EndBracket@@  17...Nxc4+  18.Kd3  Nxe3  are hopeless for him - Neishtadt. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5 Premature Attacks"]
[Black "Exercise #1: I.Csom-V.Korchnoi "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/1p2ppbp/p1pp1np1/3P4/P1P1P3/2N1B3/1P2BPPP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

8... a5
{ The conclusion of a typical trick in openings like the King's Indian. First, Black sets up the 'threat' ...b7-b5 in order to provoke White's a2-a4, then he plays ...a6-a5, fixing the dark squares on c5 and b4 as future outposts. }
9. g4
{ The beginning of an absurd plan. Ignoring factors such as the tense centre and a certain delay in development, White initiates an attack on the black king.   The modest  9.Nf3  , followed by O-O, was called for. }
9... Na6 10. f4 { On  10.h4  Black could just react as in the game. } 10... Nd7
{ Simple but strong. Black redirects the knight to c5 and clears the long diagonal for the bishop. }
