[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5 Premature Attacks"]
[Black "Exercise #2: I.Csom-V.Korchnoi "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1p2ppbp/n1pp2p1/p1nP4/P1P1PPPP/2N1BB2/1P6/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... Qb6
{ A severe punishment that practically decides the game. The method of attacking the weakest spot in the enemy camp, in this case b2 and its neighbouring squares, is familiar to us from Tal-Tringov and Movsesian-Tibensky. }
13. Qd2
{ This fails to a simple trick; but after  13.Rb1  Qb4  14.Ne2  Qxc4  White is suffering anyway. }
13... Qxb2 14. Qxb2 Nd3+ 15. Kd2 Nxb2 16. Be2
{ Trying to trap the knight; however... } 16... Bxg4
{ A second blow directed at the overloaded bishop on e2. White resigned, since both  16...Bxg4  17.Bxg4   @@StartBracket@@and  17.Bf1  cxd5  18.cxd5  Rac8  @@EndBracket@@  17...Nxc4+  18.Kd3  Nxe3  are hopeless for him - Neishtadt. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5 Premature Attacks"]
[Black "R.Milu-I.Zaitsev  Bucharest 1994  Modern Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6
{ One of the main protagonists in the Modern Defence with 4...a6 is my countryman GM Tiger Hillarp Persson. The present game is referenced in Tiger's Modern, his entertaining work on this opening system. }
4. Bg5
{ 4.Be3  is far more popular, followed by Qd2 and O-O-O. With the text White tries to provoke ...h7-h6, but if Black refrains from that move, then the bishop might prove somewhat misplaced on g5.  Note that, in a similar position to the game, after  4...a6  5.Qd2  b5  6.O-O-O  Nd7  7.h4  , the analogous  7...c5  would fail to  8.dxc5  dxc5  9.Bxc5  . }
4... a6 5. Qd2 b5 6. f3 Nd7
{ One merit of the Modern is its flexible development.   By delaying  6...Nf6  Black avoids an annoying  7.Bh6  ; neither has he to worry about e4-e5. }
7. h4
{ Such an early kingside expansion is not uncommon in this system, but here White doesn't have sufficient central control for it to work properly.   A more sustained approach was  7.a4  b4  8.Nd1  a5  9.c3  with a queenside focus. }
7... c5
{ In accordance with classical principles, Black responds to the flank attack with actions in the centre. }
8. dxc5
{ If  8.d5  , trying to keep the centre closed, then Black could react by  8...h6  9.Be3  Ngf6  ; e.g.  10.g4  b4  11.Nd1  Ne5  12.Nf2  e6  in Benoni-style, with excellent counterplay in the centre. }
8... Nxc5 9. h5 Be6
{ Black simply gets on with his development;   avoiding double-edged lines like  9...b4  10.Nd5  Bxb2  11.Rb1  . From now on, with the bishop on e6, it is sometimes possible to swap a knight on d5. }
10. h6
{ This advance only makes sense when the reply ...Bf8 is forced.   Preferable was  10.Nge2  b4  11.Nd1  , keeping the tension on the h-file. }
10... Be5
{ The bishop is of course happy to stay on the long diagonal. By now it is hard to find a justification for the time spent on the h4-h5-h6 advance. }
11. Nge2
{ Or  11.f4  Bxc3  12.Qxc3  Nf6  , followed by ...O-O, with a clear lead in development. }
11... Nf6
{ Black brings his last minor piece into the battle and prepares to meet  11...Nf6  12.f4  by  12...Nfxe4  . }
12. Bf4
{ The following bishop exchange will just open the d-file for Black's better developed forces.  12.Nf4  , followed by  Be2  and  O-O  , was probably a lesser evil. }
12... Qc7 13. Bxe5 dxe5 14. Nc1 O-O
{ Of course. With the h-file closed forever, Black's king is completely safe on g8. }
15. Nd3 Rfd8 16. Qg5 Rd4
{ Simple and strong, in order to double rooks on the open file. } 17. Be2
{ Or  17.Nxe5  Nfxe4  18.fxe4  f6  , recovering the pawn with a huge positional plus. }
17... Bc4 18. Nxe5 { White makes a tactical slip in a difficult position. }
18... Ne6 19. Qg3 b4 { Finally Black breaks through on the queenside. } 20.
Bxc4 Rxc4 21. Ne2 Rxc2 { Unable to castle, White is rendered helpless. } 22.
Kf1 Rd8
{ Short of a proper defence against the threatened 23...Rdd2, White resigned. }
*

