[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.6 Extravagance"]
[Black "Extravagance"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Some opening lines challenge the logic of opening play, usually by neglecting development or the fight for the centre. Often they are associated with play on the flanks, as in the next three examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.6 Extravagance"]
[Black "G.Kaidanov-D.Gurevich  US Championship, Chandler 1997  Irregular defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 a6
{ With this offbeat move Black tries to obtain an improved version of the Benko. This game will give us a hint about why his idea is not seen more often in practice.  We should compare the game position with the one arising after   2...c5  . In this case, White usually continues  3.d5  ,  aware that   3.dxc5  Na6  or   3...e6  yields Black an easy road to equality. As we will see next, the inclusion of Nb1-c3 and ...a7-a6 changes things a great deal. }
3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5
{ Here the natural   4.d5  permits  4...b5  5.cxb5  axb5  6.Nxb5  Qa5+   6...Ba6  7.Nc3  transposes to the Benko  7.Nc3  Bb7  8.Bd2  Qb6  9.e4  e6  with interesting compensation for the pawn. The text is much stronger - White gains an important tempo that will help him seize the centre by e2-e4 on the next move. }
4... e6
{ After  4...Qa5  5.e4  Qxc5   or  5...Nxe4  6.Qa4  Qxa4  7.Nxa4  Nc6  8.Bd3  with a firm grip on the queenside  6.Be3  Qa5  7.Bd3  Black's opening hardly impresses, but in the game he will actually face more serious problems. }
5. e4 Qc7 { The immediate  5...Bxc5  runs into  6.e5  , so Black prepares it. }
6. b4
{ There was nothing wrong with  6.f4  Bxc5  7.e5  and 8 Ne4 next, but the text is more ambitious. }
6... Nxe4
{ Kaidanov also indicates that  6...a5  7.Nb5  Qe5  8.Be3   or  6...b6  7.cxb6  Qe5  8.Bd2  Bxb4  9.Nf3  Qc5  10.Rb1  leads Black into big difficulties. The text lets him regain the pawn, at the cost of a serious delay in development. }
7. Nxe4 Qe5 8. Be3 Qxe4 9. Nf3 b6
{ Trying somehow to release White's queenside bind, and providing the queen with a retreat square on b7.   9...Nc6  failed fatally to  10.Bd3  Qg4  11.h3  , trapping the queen after  11...Qxg2   or  11...Qh5  12.g4  12.Rh2  . }
10. Bd3 Qb7
{ The opening experiment has turned into a nightmare for Black - the open centre suggests a tactical battle, in which his bad development will be severely felt. }
11. Ng5
{ Exploiting the absence of a knight on f6, Kaidanov takes the first step to an attack on the black king;   And  11.Ng5  creates the threat of  11...--  12.Be4  Nc6  13.b5  . }
11... bxc5 12. bxc5 f5
{ Or  12...Qb4+  13.Kf1  Nc6  14.Qf3  f5  15.Nxe6  etc - Kaidanov. The text parries most of White's threats but creates new weaknesses on the kingside. }
13. O-O Qc6
{ After  13...Nc6  14.Re1  Be7  15.Rb1  Qc7  16.Bxf5  exf5  17.Qd5  Rf8  18.Nxh7  , followed by Bg5, Black is also in big trouble. }
14. Bd4
{ 14.Bd4  doesn't just prepare to meet  14...Bxc5  by  15.Bxg7  , it also installs the irresistible threat of Qh5+. Black is already beyond salvation. }
14... Bb7 15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qh3 Rg8 17. Be4 { A nice piece of obstruction. }
17... fxe4 18. Qxh7 Rg7 19. Bxg7 Qxc5 20. Bf6
{ In view of the imminent mate, Black resigned. } *

