20. Bf6 { In view of the imminent mate, Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.6 Extravagance"]
[Black "I.Cheparinov-L.Salgado Lopez  Moscow 2011  Blumenfeld Gambit "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 b5
{ In contrast to Black's nameless defence in the previous game, the Blumenfeld Gambit is a fully respectable opening, which has been used by many strong players over the years. On the other hand, its treatment in the present game could be regarded as truly extravagant. How often do you make four of your first eleven moves with a rook? }
5. Bg5
{ As we already discussed in Postny-Abergel, in such lines White is generally happy to swap his 'good' bishop for the active knight on f6. }
5... Qa5+
{ The sharpest reply, unpinning the knight in order to increase the pressure on White's centre.   The Benoni-style  5...exd5  6.cxd5  d6  is also playable. }
6. Nbd2
{ White temporarily gives up a pawn to speed up development.   Curiously, this natural move is nowhere near as popular as  6.Qd2  or  6.Nc3  . }
6... bxc4
{ The tempting  6...Ne4  runs into  7.b4  Qxb4  8.Rb1  , a trick familiar from a similar Benko line   @@StartBracket@@i.e. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  4.Nd2  Qa5  5.e4  Nxe4?!  6.b4!  @@EndBracket@@.  There can follow  8...Qc3  9.Rb3  Qa5  10.Rxb5  Qc3  11.Rb3  Qa5  12.Bf4  , and  12...--  13.Qb1  next, with a clear initiative. }
7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. e4 Rg8
{ Exploiting the semi-open file to complicate the recapture Bxc4.   Capitalizing on the pawn with  8...c3  yields White a dangerous initiative after  9.bxc3  Qxc3  10.Rc1  Qa5  11.Bc4  , followed by O-O. }
9. g3 Rg4
{ A fancy rook raid, though move 9 is a bit too early for it!   Much sounder was  9...Ba6  , starting to bring out the minor pieces; e.g.  10.Qc2  Bh6  11.Bxc4  Bxc4  12.Qxc4  Na6  as tried in a few earlier games, with rather unclear play. }
10. Be2
{ Simple and strong. White just hands over the e4-pawn in order to castle, after which his lead in development will be overwhelming.   In contrast, after  10.Qc2  f5  11.Bxc4  Rxe4+  12.Kf1  Rg4  , followed by ...Bb7, Black gets the kind of play he was looking for. }
10... Rxe4 11. O-O Rxe2
{ This exchange sacrifice doesn't really ease Black's defence - rather, it helps White to seize the central files with his major pieces.   After  11...Rg4  12.Nxc4  Qc7  13.Re1  ,   or even  13.Qa4  intending Nd6+, White has a huge initiative for the pawn, but the battle goes on. }
12. Nxc4 Qa6 13. Qxe2
{ An amusing picture - of Black's pieces, everyone except the queen is still in its initial position! With several open files at White's disposal, the black king is practically doomed. }
13... Bb7 14. Rad1 Qxa2 15. Rfe1 Qa4
{ Unfortunately for Black,  15...Na6  loses a piece after  16.Ra1  Qb3  17.Na5  . }
16. b3
{ White gives his knight some extra protection, thus liberating the queen;   exploiting the trick  16.b3  Qxb3  17.Rb1  . }
16... Qb4 17. Qd3 a6
{ 17...Na6  fails to  18.dxe6  , threatening mate. The text prepares ...Ra7 reinforcing the defence, though it is already too late. }
18. dxe6
{ Having placed his pieces in ideal positions, Cheparinov is ready for a decisive combination.  Here   18.Qxh7  , intending  18...--  19.Nfe5  fxe5  20.Nxe5  , was another strong option. }
18... fxe6 19. Rxe6+ { Opening the gates to Black's king. } 19... dxe6 20. Qd8+
Kf7 21. Ng5+ Kg6
{ Or  21...fxg5  22.Ne5+  Kg8  23.Qxg5+  with mate - Golubev. } 22. Nxe6 Qxb3
{ If  22...Nc6  , White wins by  23.Nxf8+  Kf7  24.Nd6+  Kg8  25.Qd7  Rxf8  26.Nf5  Rf7  27.Nh6+  - Golubev. }
23. Nxf8+ Kh5 24. Ne5
{ Avoiding any tricks with ...Qf3 and creating the threat 25. g4+. Obviously the knight is immune because of mate. }
24... Bf3 25. Nxf3 Qxf3 26. Rd5+ Kh6 27. Qe7
{ In view of  27.Qe7  Qxd5  28.Qxh7+  Kg5  29.Qg6  , Black resigned. } *

