[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.6 Extravagance"]
[Black "K.Hulak-I.Saric  Croatian Team  Championship 2007  Benoni Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 g6
{ In this initial position of the Czech Benoni, Black usually continues   5...Be7  , followed by ...0-0, with ...Ne8, ...g7-g6 and ...Ng7 as a future idea. Saric's move looks like a transposition to the King's Indian, but we will soon see that he has other intentions. }
6. Be2 h5
{ Thus Black prepares ...Bh6 in order to swap the 'bad' bishop. This might seem like a clever strategic idea; unfortunately, it implies a certain time loss and also rules out short castling. Moreover, as Watson pointed out several times in 'Secrets of Modern Chess Strategy', such 'bad' bishops can actually be missed once the position is opened.  The simple   6...Bg7  was preferable here. }
7. f4
{ Anticipating the absence of dark-squared bishops, Hulak clears lines towards the vulnerable points at d6 and f6. }
7... exf4 8. Bxf4 Qe7
{ Preventing e4-e5 and preparing ...Nbd7-e5.  After   8...Bh6  9.Bxh6  Rxh6  10.Qd2  Rh8  11.Qf4  a6  @@StartBracket@@ the threat was 12 Nb5 @@EndBracket@@  12.Nf3  , followed by 13 e5, White develops a strong initiative. }
9. Qa4+ { A clever restrictive move. } 9... Bd7
{ Now the desired   9...Nbd7  runs into  10.Nb5  ; e.g.  10...Qxe4  11.Nh3  Qxg2  12.O-O-O  with a dangerous initiative. Thus Saric prefers to parry the check with the bishop. }
10. Qc2 Bh6
{ The pragmatic   10...Bg7  11.Nf3  Ng4  might have been worth a shot, but Black gets on with his plan. }
11. Bxh6 Rxh6 12. Nf3 Ng4
{ With the queen's knight deprived of the intended route d7-e5, Saric uses the other knight to control the crucial e5-square. }
13. O-O f6
{ Strategically well-founded but too slow in this position.   13...Ne3  obviously failed to  14.Qd2  so the developing   13...Na6  was called for. There can follow  14.Qd2  Rh8  15.h3  Ne5  16.Qf4  Nxf3+  17.Rxf3  g5  18.Qf6  and Black is under pressure, but the text leads to worse sufferings for him. }
14. Qd2 g5
{ Black's dark square blockade looks impressive, but Hulak's next move puts an end to any illusions. }
15. e5
{ A timely blow, clearing the centre before Black gets castled. Now it is White who will enjoy a great blockading square on e4. }
15... dxe5
{ This implies a knight sacrifice on g4, but alternatives were even worse.   15...fxe5  16.Nxg5  leaves Black's king exposed to ideas like Rf7 and Nce4  while after   15...Nxe5  16.Nxe5  --  , both   16...dxe5  17.d6  , and   16...Qxe5  17.Bd3  , preparing 18 Rae1+, is terminal for him  , while   16...fxe5  is no improvement in view of  17.Ne4  with the irresistible threats of  17...--  18.Nxg5  and   18.Bxh5+  Rxh5  19.Nf6+  . In these lines the 'missing' tempo in Black's queenside development is strongly felt, preventing him from a relieving ...0-0-0. }
16. Ne4
{ The tempting   16.d6  permits  16...Qe6  17.h3  Nc6  with similar play to the game, but with Black's queen's knight more actively placed on c6. }
16... Na6 17. h3 O-O-O 18. hxg4
{ White correctly estimates that he can cope with the enemy attack on the h-file.   Otherwise  18.b4  was a different idea, when both  18...Nxb4  and   18...cxb4  19.c5  19.d6  Qg7  20.Nxc5  lead to interesting attacking prospects. }
18... hxg4 19. Nh2 f5
{ Or   19...Rxh2  20.Kxh2  Qh7+  21.Kg1  Qxe4  22.Rxf6  g3  23.Rh6  , repelling the attack with a clear advantage. }
20. Nxg4
{ A practical choice, giving back the piece in exchange for positional superiority. }
20... fxg4 21. Qxg5 Qh7
{ After   21...Qxg5  22.Nxg5  the endgame favours White, but the text lets him launch a decisive counterattack. }
22. Nf6 Rh1+ 23. Kf2 Rxf1+ 24. Rxf1 Qc2 25. Qxe5 g3+ 26. Kg1 Rf8 27. Qe7 *

