[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "Ignorance and indifference"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ A common reason for opening failures is insufficient attention to details in the position; for example, when a player doesn't pay attention to a tactical or positional threat that was just created by his opponent. Another, related situation is when a player goes against the logic of the particular opening or opening position; for example, by a pawn advance that doesn't form part of his set-up, or by developing the 'wrong' piece. Finally, a third cause of early defeats or difficulties is simply when a player doesn't know or remember a vital move, move order or idea in the particular opening. Let's see some examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "L.Aronin-Kantorovich  USSR Team Championship 1960  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. c3
{ White steers the game into the Alapin, now that Black's second move has ruled out some of his more popular set-ups against that system, such as 2...Nf6. }
3... b6
{ Generally speaking, in the opening phase it makes sense to conclude a fianchetto right away; i.e.  3...Bg7  in this case, when  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  d5  leads to a well-known theoretical position. In the game Black initiates a second fianchetto, which is not that bad an idea in itself - the problem is that he never finishes the first one with ...Bg7. }
4. d4 Bb7 5. Bc4
{ After  5.Bd3  Bg7  6.O-O  White also has an easier game, but the text is more ambitious.   In fact, after just five moves, Black's extravagant opening already exposes him to some danger; e.g.  5.Bc4   @@StartBracket@@  5...Bxe4  6.Ng5  d5  7.Bb5+  Nd7  8.dxc5  bxc5  9.f3  Bxb1  10.Qxd5  with decisive threats@@EndBracket@@   @@StartBracket@@or  5...Bg7  6.dxc5  , when  6...bxc5  fails to  7.Qb3  .@@EndBracket@@   Learning from the last line,  5...cxd4  6.cxd4  Bg7  could be suggested   While  5...e6  , preparing ...Bg7, is another option, tried in the game J.Timman-L.Ljubojevic, Wijk aan Zee 1972. Instead, Kantorovich found a 'simpler' solution to White's threats. }
5... d5
{ This counter-logical move, opening the position when behind in development, proves to have fatal consequences. }
6. exd5 Bxd5
{ The automatic recapture implies that Black hasn't yet sensed the danger.   The last chance was  6...Nf6  7.Bb5+  Nbd7  8.c4  Bg7  with a rather suspicious gambit. }
7. Qa4+
{ Punishing the opponent on his most vulnerable spot: the a4-e8 diagonal. }
7... Bc6
{ This loses outright; though after  7...Nc6  8.Ne5   @@StartBracket@@or  8.Bb5  followed by 9. c4@@EndBracket@@  Rc8  9.Bb5  Qc7  10.O-O  , preparing 11. c4, Black is also in enormous trouble. }
8. Ne5
{ Black resigned, in view of  8.Ne5  Qc7   @@StartBracket@@or  8...Bxa4  9.Bxf7  @@EndBracket@@  9.Nxc6  Nxc6  10.d5  - Neishtadt. }
*

