[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-J.Calderon  Riobamba 2008  Tarrasch Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 e6 2. d4 d5 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. g3
{ Reaching an initial position of the Tarrasch. } 6... Be6
{ Somewhat premature - in this defence the queen's bishop tends to be the last minor piece to leave the house, simply because its colleagues have more or less predefined squares.   The main line goes  6...Nf6  7.Bg2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  , when White is at a major junction between  9.Bg5  and  9.dxc5  . }
7. Bg2 a6
{ This move, preventing Nb5, is a common feature in the Tarrasch - but not this early!   Black could still get a normal game with  7...Nf6  . }
8. O-O Bd6
{ This third inaccuracy leads to fatal consequences.   8...Nf6  was again vital, although after  9.Bg5  Be7  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Bxf6   @@StartBracket@@ Black can't play  11...Qxf6  @@EndBracket@@  So he is forced into the horrible  11...gxf6  12.Nxd5  Qxb2  due to 13.Nc7+.  @@StartBracket@@ Interestingly, if we replace ...a7-a6 by ...O-O in this line, then 11...Qxf6 12 Nxd5 Qxb2 is indeed possible, and has actually been tried hundreds of times in practice! @@EndBracket@@   As for the alternative  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  Be7  , White could try something like  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Rc1  O-O  13.Na4  with a stable advantage, now that ...a7-a6 doesn't contribute to Black's game at all. However, much worse things will happen to him after the careless move played in the game. }
9. e4
{ Of course - hitting Black in the centre before he is fully developed. Evidently this blow would not have worked after 8...Nf6 instead of 8...Bd6. In conclusion, not every development move comes to the same thing. }
9... Nge7
{ After  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  or  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  Black is also in deep trouble. }
10. exd5
{ As usual, opening the position makes sense when ahead in development.   10.e5  Bc7  would be a relief for Black. }
10... Nxd5 11. Ng5 { With irresistible pressure on the light squares. } 11...
Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bc4 13. Re1+ Be7
{ This loses material; though after  13...Kf8  14.Rb1  Black can't defend properly either; e.g.  14...Rb8  15.dxc5  Bxc5  16.Bf4  . }
14. d5 O-O 15. dxc6 Bxg5 16. Qxd8
{ In view of  16.Qxd8  Bxd8  17.cxb7  Rb8  18.Bf4  , Black resigned. } *

