[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "R.J.Fischer-M.Tal  Bled 1961  Sicilian Defence,  Taimanov Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3
{ This fianchetto line is one of the main replies to the Sicilian Taimanov.   Play usually continues  6.g3  a6  7.Bg2  Nf6  8.O-O  , when Black has several choices such as  8...d6  8...Bc5  and  8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Bc5  . Instead, with his next move Tal 'modifies' the move order and is severely punished for the rest of the game. }
6... Nf6
{ 'Probably the losing move!' - Fischer. Interestingly, against 6. Be3 or 6. Be2 there is nothing wrong with playing 6...Nf6 before ...a7-a6, but here it proves to be a serious inaccuracy, as we will see next. }
7. Ndb5 Qb8
{ From now on Fischer will never let his opponent rest, creating new threats on every move, with a particular focus on the d6-square. }
8. Bf4 Ne5
{ Later it was discovered that the ugly  8...e5  offers more resistance. There can follow  9.Bg5  a6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Na3  Bxa3  12.bxa3  Ne7  13.Qf3  Qc7  14.Bg2  d6  15.O-O  , intending Nd1-e3, with a more comfortable game for White in Alexa. Ivanov-I.V.Ivanov, US Championship, Long Beach 1989.  But if Black is aiming at such kind of play, I guess he should rather go for the Sveshnikov @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ straight away! }
9. Be2
{ From here the bishop covers the f3-square, thus creating the threat of 10. Qd4. }
9... Bc5
{ On most other moves 10. Qd4 is troublesome for Black; e.g.  9...a6  10.Qd4  d6  11.Rd1  axb5  12.Bxe5  with a huge edge, now that the bishop is untouchable due to mate. }
10. Bxe5
{ This exchange isn't favourable by itself but, together with the following two pawn moves, it lets White take a firm grip on the centre. }
10... Qxe5 11. f4 Qb8 12. e5
{ Right on time, before Black consolidates with ...d7-d6. } 12... a6
{ Aware that  12...Ng8  13.Ne4  , followed by Nbd6+, would be terrible for him, Tal opts to complicate the game. }
13. exf6 axb5 14. fxg7
{ 14.Ne4  Bf8  15.Qd4  was another good option - Keres. } 14... Rg8 15. Ne4 Be7
16. Qd4
{ A move with several virtues: it protects the important g7-pawn, speeds up development and enables a future check on f6. The b5-pawn can of course wait. }
16... Ra4
{ This inventive move won't solve Black's problems, but he was already short of a good defence.   On  16...Qc7  White could consider  17.O-O-O  Rxa2  18.Kb1  with similar play to later on in the game. }
17. Nf6+ Bxf6 18. Qxf6 Qc7 19. O-O-O
{ Fischer has observed that his king will be safe on b1, irrespective of the capture on a2.   In contrast,  19.Bxb5  failed to  19...Qa5+   While both  19.Bh5  d5  and  19.Bd3  Qc5  give Black more hope of survival. }
19... Rxa2 20. Kb1 Ra6
{ Or  20...Qa5  21.b3  with the strong threat of 22 Bh5. } 21. Bxb5
{ Another good option was  21.Bh5  d6   @@StartBracket@@or  21...d5  22.Rxd5  @@EndBracket@@  22.Rhe1  Qe7  23.Qh6  Kd7  24.Qxh7  with a quick win - Fischer. }
21... Rb6 22. Bd3 e5
{ Tal tries to reach an inferior endgame after  22...e5  23.Qxe5+  Qxe5  24.fxe5  Rxg7  , but in vain... }
23. fxe5 Rxf6 24. exf6 { Now the threat of 25. Bxh7 proves irresistible. }
24... Qc5 { 24...Qb6  , then  25.Rhf1  - Fischer. } 25. Bxh7 Qg5 26. Bxg8 Qxf6
27. Rhf1 Qxg7 28. Bxf7+ { With such a material advantage, the rest is easy. }
28... Kd8 29. Be6 Qh6 30. Bxd7 Bxd7 31. Rf7 Qxh2 32. Rdxd7+ { White soon won. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "Exercise #1: R.J.Fischer-M.Tal"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/ppqp1ppp/2n1pn2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ 'Probably the losing move!' - Fischer. } 7. Ndb5 Qb8
{ From now on Fischer will never let his opponent rest, creating new threats on every move, with a particular focus on the d6-square. }
8. Bf4 Ne5
{ Later it was discovered that the ugly  8...e5  offers more resistance. There can follow  9.Bg5  a6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Na3  Bxa3  12.bxa3  Ne7  13.Qf3  Qc7  14.Bg2  d6  15.O-O  , intending Nd1-e3, with a more comfortable game for White in Alexa. Ivanov-I.V.Ivanov, US Championship, Long Beach 1989.  But if Black is aiming at such kind of play, I guess he should rather go for the Sveshnikov @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ straight away! }
9. Be2
{ From here the bishop covers the f3-square, thus creating the threat of 10. Qd4. }
9... Bc5
{ On most other moves 10.Qd4 is troublesome for Black; e.g  9...a6  10.Qd4  d6  11.Rd1  axb5  12.Bxe5  with a huge edge, now that the bishop is untouchable due to mate. }
10. Bxe5
{ This exchange isn't favourable by itself but, together with the following two pawn moves, it lets White take a firm grip on the centre. }
10... Qxe5 11. f4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
