[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "Exercise #2: R.J.Fischer-M.Tal"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rqb1k1r1/1p1pbpPp/4p3/1p6/4NP2/6P1/PPP1B2P/R2QK2R w KQq - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

16. Qd4
{ A move with several virtues: it protects the important g7-pawn, speeds up development and enables a future check on f6. The b5-pawn can of course wait. }
16... Ra4
{ This inventive move won't solve Black's problems, but he was already short of a good defence.   On  16...Qc7  White could consider  17.O-O-O  Rxa2  18.Kb1  with similar play to later on in the game. }
17. Nf6+ Bxf6 18. Qxf6 Qc7 19. O-O-O
{ Fischer has observed that his king will be safe on b1, irrespective of the capture on a2.   In contrast,  19.Bxb5  failed to  19...Qa5+   While both  19.Bh5  d5  and  19.Bd3  Qc5  give Black more hope of survival. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "G.Ravinsky-E.Bebchuk  Moscow 1964  Scandinavian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 g6
{ An interesting way of treating the Scandinavian. From g7 the bishop will exert pressure on the d4-pawn, possibly joined by the knight via h6-f5. }
5. Bf4
{ A move popularized by Fischer after his instructive win against Robatsch at the 1962 Varna Olympiad. }
5... Bg7 6. Nf3
{ How should Black continue his development?   Fischer played  6.Qd2  , speeding up the plan of O-O-O and Bh6, though the text is equally reasonable. }
6... Bg4
{ Difficult to believe, but after this natural move White is close to winning!   Either  6...Nh6  , heading for f5   or the simple  6...Nf6  , followed by ...O-O, should have been tried - Neishtadt. Having browsed through many short games lately, I have observed that one cause of opening disasters is the development of low-priority pieces; e.g. bringing out the queenside pieces when you are going to castle kingside, as in this case. }
7. Bc4 e6
{ Parrying the threat of 8. Bxf7+.   Instead,  7...Nf6  obviously failed to  8.Bxf7+  Kxf7  9.Ne5+   while the prophylactic  7...Qc8  is strongly met by  8.Nd5  . }
8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nc6
{ This is like sending an invitation card to White's d4-d5.   Unfortunately, the desirable  9...c6  failed to  10.Ne4  , heading for d6, when Black is definitely regretting the fact that his king's knight is still on g8.   As for the brave  9...Qxd4  , after  10.Qxb7  Qxc4  11.Qxa8  Black's slow kingside development again speaks against him; e.g.  11...Bxc3+  12.bxc3  Qxc3+  13.Ke2  Qxc2+  14.Kf3  Qd3+  15.Be3  and the checks are soon over. }
10. O-O-O
{ The quickest way to conclude development and enhance the punishing d4-d5 advance.   In contrast, after  10.d5  Nd4  things might get more complicated. }
10... Nge7
{ Both  10...Nxd4  11.Qxb7  and  10...Bxd4  11.Nb5  were fatal for Black - Neishtadt. }
11. d5
{ Right on time, clearing both central files before Black castles away. } 11...
exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Rhe1+
{ More efficient than  13.Bxd5  O-O  14.Bxf7+   @@StartBracket@@not  14.Bxc6  Qf6  @@EndBracket@@  Rxf7  15.Rxd8+  Rxd8  , when Black could play on for a while in the lost endgame. }
13... Kf8 { Or  13...Nce7  14.Bxd5  O-O  15.Bxb7  with heavy material gains. }
14. Rxd5 Qf6 15. Qa3+
{ A final accuracy, defending the b2-pawn with tempo and liberating the bishop on f4. }
15... Kg8 16. Bg5 Qxf2 17. Rf1
{ In view of  17.Rf1  Qxg2   or  17...Qb6  18.Rb5  18.Rd2  Qxg5  19.Bxf7  , Black resigned. }
*

