[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "E.Gufeld-T.V.Petrosian  USSR Championship,  Moscow 1969  Three Knights Game "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6
{ This variation has quite an old record, with several World Champions taking on Black's position. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5
{ The sharpest choice; though  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  , followed by Qd2 and O-O-O, is probably a more critical test of Black's opening. }
5... Bg7 6. Bg5 Nce7
{ With that knight; since  6...Nge7  runs into the trap  7.Nxd4  Bxd4  8.Qxd4  Nxd4  9.Nf6+  Kf8  10.Bh6  . }
7. Nxd4 c6 8. Nc3
{ After  8.Nxe7  Nxe7  9.Qd2  h6  10.Be3   @@StartBracket@@or  10.Bh4  d5  @@EndBracket@@  10...d5  Black has had few problems in practice. }
8... h6 9. Be3 { 9.Bh4  , maintaining the pin, seems more logical. } 9... Nf6
10. Bc4 O-O
{ The immediate  10...d5  looks strong as well.   After  10...O-O  Black already enjoys a slight lead in development and ...d7-d5 is in the air, so White should proceed with care.  11.--   . Here  11.O-O  d5  12.exd5  Nfxd5  is hardly in his favour   , but by  11.e5  Ne8  12.O-O  he could obtain a decent game; e.g.  12...d5   or  12...Bxe5  13.Bxh6  13.Be2  c5  14.Nb3  d4  15.Bf4  , followed by Ne4. Instead, the game took a completely different turn... }
11. Qf3
{ A seemingly active move, which, however, leads to huge difficulties due to the exposed position of the queen. I suspect that Gufeld simply didn't foresee Black's 12th move, or else miscalculated something. }
11... d5 12. exd5 c5
{ Cramping the enemy pieces and gaining the f5-square for the knight.   In contrast, after  12...Bg4  13.Qg3  Nexd5  14.Bxd5  cxd5  15.O-O  White is okay. }
13. Ndb5
{ After  13.Nb3  Bg4  14.Qf4  g5  15.Qe5  Nf5  , preparing ...Re8, Black obtains a strong attack; e.g.  16.h3  Re8  17.Qh2  Nxe3  18.fxe3  Rxe3+  19.Kd2  Rxc3  20.bxc3  Bd7  with ideas like 21...Ne4+ and 21...b5.   Even worse is  13.Nde2  Bg4  14.Qf4  g5  15.Qe5  Nh5  16.Qe4  Bf5  17.Qf3  g4  and the queen is trapped at last. }
13... a6
{ 13...Bg4  14.Qg3  Nf5  permits  15.Qc7  , so Petrosian eliminates that possibility, leaving White with a single reply. }
14. d6 Nf5 15. Nc7 Nxd6 { A final finesse. } 16. O-O-O
{ Now after  16.Nxa8  Nxc4  , followed by ...Bd7, Black recovers the material with a huge positional plus, so White starts fishing in muddy waters. }
16... Qxc7 17. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most practical choice, in order to simplify the game. } 18. Qd3
{ 18.Bxd6  Bxf3  19.Bxc7  Bxd1  20.Rxd1  was marginally better, when White is an exchange down. After the text, Black's pressure soon becomes unbearable. }
18... b5 19. Bd5 Rad8 20. f3 b4 21. Qxg6 { Desperation in a lost position. }
21... bxc3 22. fxg4 Qb6 23. b3 Qb4 *

