[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.7 Ignorance and Indifference"]
[Black "T.Nabaty-I.Khairullin  European Championship,  Rijeka 2010  Caro-Kann Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3
{ One of the most aggressive replies to the Caro-Kann, which has become quite popular in recent years. }
3... g6
{ Other main options are  3...e6  with French-like play and  3...dxe4  4.fxe4  e5  5.Nf3  Be6  , preventing the dangerous 6. Bc4. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Be3 Qb6
{ Thus Black interferes with the opponent's plan of Qd2 and O-O-O, but also exposes his queen and delays development.   Perhaps  5...dxe4  6.fxe4  e5  or  6...Nf6  offers better chances for equality. }
6. a3
{ A tricky defence of the b2-pawn; both here and later,  6.a3  Qxb2  fails to  7.Na4 }
6... dxe4
{ The immediate  6...e5  is well met by  7.Nge2  Qxb2  8.dxe5  Bxe5  9.Kf2  , intending  9...Bxc3  10.Nxc3  Qxc3  11.Bd4  - Postny. }
7. fxe4 e5
{ This counterblow leads to a favourable pawn structure, but slows down Black's development even further;   the simple  7...Nf6  might have been preferable. }
8. Nf3 exd4 9. Nxd4
{ A tense position has emerged. If Black manages to castle he will have a great game thanks to the weak points on e4 and e5, but White does make everything possible to prevent that, even by means of sacrifices. To start with, Black has to cope with the threat of 10. Nf5. }
9... Bh6
{ In my opinion, this move is completely opposed to the nature of the position. Black moves his only developed minor piece away from its natural place on g7, where it was controlling the crucial e5-square, among other things. I guess Khairullin simply wanted to prevent O-O-O but, as we will see next, he pays too high a price for that.   A sounder option was  9...Qc7  , on which Postny analyses  10.Ndb5  cxb5  11.Nxb5  Qe5  12.Nd6+  Kf8  13.Nxc8  Nc6  14.Qd6+  Qxd6  15.Nxd6  Bxb2  16.Rd1  with just a slight advantage for White.   Even the paradoxical  9...Qd8  intending ...Nf6 and ...O-O, seems much better than the text. }
10. Bf2
{ Nabaty surrenders the plan of long castling to maintain dark square pressure. }
10... Qd8
{ If  10...Qc7  , White has  11.Ndb5  cxb5  12.Nxb5  followed by  13. Nd6+, with a strong attack - Da Costa Junior;   And  12.Qd4  f6  13.Nxb5  , followed by Rd1, is another idea in the same spirit. With the text Black avoids any such sacrifices but soon runs into new problems. }
11. e5
{ A key move that exploits the absence of the bishop on g7 in order to seize the centre. Now 12. Ne4 is coming up. }
11... Qe7
{ This direct attack on the e5-pawn won't work out well.   11...Ne7  , preparing ...O-O, seems more reasonable, although after  12.Bc4  O-O  13.O-O  , intending e5-e6, White keeps a strong initiative. }
12. Ne4 Nd7
{ Or  12...Qxe5  13.Qe2  with devastating threats; e.g.  13...Ne7  14.Nf3  Qe6  15.Rd1  O-O  16.Rd6  , followed by 17. Nf6+ and 18. Qxe7 - Postny. }
13. Nf3
{ Seeing that  13.Nd6+  Kf8  leads nowhere, White prepares the knight check. }
13... Ngf6
{ Both  13...Nxe5  14.Bc5  ;   and  13...Bg7  14.Bc4  Bxe5  15.O-O  are fatal for Black - Da Costa Junior.   With  13...Ngf6  he again prepares to meet  14.Nd6+  by  14...Kf8  , but Nabaty has a strong intermediate move prepared. }
14. Bh4
{ By provoking ...g6-g5 White creates a weakness on f5 and limits the bishop on h6. }
14... g5 15. Nd6+ Kf8 16. Bg3
{ Reinforcing the e5-pawn while creating the threat 17 Nf5. Black's game is by now very difficult due to his exposed king.   16.Nf5  Qe6  was less clear. }
16... Nb6 17. Be2 Nfd5 18. O-O
{ A nice decision in these computer days. White doesn't mind losing the exchange, his main priority being the swift exploitation of the f-file towards Black's king. }
18... Ne3 19. Qd3 Nxf1 20. Rxf1 Nd5
{ The only move, in order to keep White's rook from f4. } 21. Nd4 Nf4 22. Bxf4
gxf4 23. Nxc8 Qxe5
{ Black finally has to give up material, since  23...Rxc8  fails to  24.Qh3  . }
24. Nf5 Rxc8 25. Nxh6 Re8 26. Qc4 { A new sacrifice to intensify the attack. }
26... Re6 27. Ng4 Qxe2 28. Qxf4 Re7
{ This lets White recover the material at once; though after  28...f5  29.Qxf5+  Ke7  30.Qg5+  Kd6  31.Qf4+  Kd7  32.Qd4+  Kc7  33.Qxh8  Qxg4  34.Qxh7+  Black is also lost - Postny. }
29. Qh6+ Ke8 30. Qg7 Kd7
{ Seeing that  30...Rf8  fails to  31.Nf6+  , Black prepares a final counterattack, but Nabaty has everything under control. }
31. Nf6+ Kc7 32. Qxh8 Qe3+ 33. Kh1 Qf2 34. Nd5+
{ 34.Nd5+  has the idea  34...cxd5  35.Qc3+  and the queen covers e1. By his next move Black avoids this, but runs into a new intermediate check. }
34... Kd7 35. Qc8+ { 35.Qc8+  Kxc8  36.Nxe7+  Kd7  37.Rxf2  wins. } *

