1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 a6
{ A sensible move, ruling out Bb5, which is a typical feature in White's set-up. }
4. Nf3 b5 5. g3
{ The game has now transposed from a Grand Prix Attack to the Closed Sicilian variation. }
5... Bb7 6. d3 Qc7
{ Another approach is  6...b4  7.Ne2  d5  , hitting the light squares. } 7. Bg2
d6 8. O-O Nd7 9. f5
{ The most straightforward choice; though the flexible  9.Qe2  might be more promising; e.g.  9...Ngf6  10.e5  . }
9... Ngf6
{ Complete indifference.  9...e5  was correct, keeping the position closed; e.g.  10.g4  h6  11.h4  Ngf6  12.Nh2  b4  13.Ne2  c4  with counterplay, P. Dankert-B.Kurajica, Hamburg 1977. }
10. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
