1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nf6
{ This loses an important tempo.   Better is  5...Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  with an initial position of the Semi-Tarrasch. }
6. Bg5
{ Another good set-up is  6.Nf3  , followed by Bd3, O-O, Qe2, Rd1 etc, as we will see in the next chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Nf3 c5
{ A risky counterstrike, in view of White's superior development.   First  7...O-O  was preferable. }
8. e5
{ 8.dxc5  Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Bxc5  10.e5  was even stronger; e.g.  10...Nfd7  11.Nb5  Na6  12.Nd6+  Bxd6  13.Rxd6  with a clear edge in the endgame. }
8... Nfd7
{ Here  8...cxd4  was preferable; e.g.  9.Nb5   @@StartBracket@@or  9.exf6  gxf6  @@EndBracket@@  a6  10.Nbxd4  Nd5  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  with just a slight disadvantage. }
9. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
