9. Bxe7 Qxe7 { Or  9...Kxe7  10.d5  with a clear initiative. } 10. Nb5
{ With a nasty double threat at  c7  and  d6  . This idea is also seen in some lines of the French; e.g. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bg5  Be7  5.e5  Nfd7  6.Bxe7  Qxe7  7.f4  c5?!  8.Nb5!  .   In contrast, the game continued  10.Bb5  a6  11.Bxd7+  Bxd7  12.Ne4  cxd4  13.Nd6+  Kf8  14.O-O  Nc6  with rather unclear play. }
10... Na6
{ Or  10...O-O  11.Nc7  Nxe5  12.Nxa8  Nxf3+  13.Qxf3  cxd4  14.Qa3  neutralizing Black's counterplay. }
11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. dxc5 { With a huge advantage; } 13... --
{ Now that  13...Nxc5  fails to  14.Rc1  . } *

