[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 g6
{ This is not the same thing as 2. c3 g6, and we will soon see why. } 4. d4
cxd4 5. cxd4 d5 6. Nc3
{ The obvious punishment for Black's suspicious opening was  6.exd5  Qxd5  7.Nc3  , followed by d4-d5; e.g.  7...Qd8  8.d5  Nb8  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.O-O  and Re1 next with a clear plus. }
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Bg4
{ It made more sense to develop the kingside first; i.e.  7...Nf6  8.Nxf6+  exf6  , followed by ...Bb4+ and ...O-O. }
8. d5 { On the second occasion, White finds the correct plan. } 8... Bxf3
{ This ruins White's pawn structure but, more importantly, decreases Black's light square control.   Obviously  8...Ne5  failed to  9.Nxe5  Bxd1  10.Bb5+   So  8...Qa5+  9.Nc3  O-O-O  was more in the spirit of the position. }
9. gxf3 Ne5 10. Qa4+ Nd7
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
