13... Qb6
{ Hitting the vulnerable b2-pawn, while preparing ...Bc5 with strong pressure on the g1-a7 diagonal. Now the absence of White's queen's knight in the battle is strongly felt. }
14. Nf5
{ A fatal error.   14.Nxc6  was essential, although after  14...bxc6  15.Nc3  Bc5  Black keeps a clear advantage. }
14... Bc5 { With decisive threats at f2 and b2. Black soon won the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "A.Llamuca-K.Tigrero  Riobamba 2010  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 g6
{ A rather relaxed approach against the Alapin. } 5. h3
{ A good restrictive move, leaving the bishop on c8 short of a good destiny. }
5... Bg7 6. Nf3 Bd7
{ Here the bishop does not contribute to Black's position in any way, and rather obstructs the other pieces. Not without reason, we are taught to bring out the knights before the bishops, for example with  6...Nf6  in this case. }
7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Be2 e6
{ Seeing that  8...Nf6  permits the annoying  9.e5  Black prepares ...Nge7. We will soon see the flaw to this idea. }
9. O-O Nge7
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
