13. e5 { A strong advance that hits Black on the dark squares. } 13... dxe5 14.
dxe5 Nd7 15. e6
{ 15.Nd5  was another good option, when both  15...Re8   @@StartBracket@@and  15...f6  16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.exf6  @@EndBracket@@  16.e6  fxe6  17.Nxe7+  Rxe7  18.Rxe6  Bf8  19.Qd6  win for White. }
15... fxe6 16. Rxe6 Bf6
{ After  16...Nf6  17.Qxd8  Rxd8  18.Rxe7  Black is a pawn down, but the text leaves his king severely exposed. }
17. Bc4 Kh8 18. --
{ At this point White played  18.Bh6  , permitting the salvaging  18...Ne5  .   In contrast, after  18.Ne4  his attack would have been irresistible; e.g.  18...Bxg5  19.Nxg5  Qc7  20.Rxe7  Qxc4  21.Rxh7+  Kg8  22.Rc1  , followed by a decisive check on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
