[SetUp "1"]

8. d4
{ Hitting Black on the e-file just before he castles away.   8.Ng5  also made sense   Whereas the game went  8.c3  O-O  9.Nbd2  , when  9...Nf4  10.Bxe6  Nxe6  11.Nc4  Qf6  would have led to rather equal play. }
8... O-O
{ There is nothing better; e.g.  8...exd4  9.Bxd5   Or  8...f6  9.Bb3  with the strong threat of c2-c4. }
9. dxe5 { White is a healthy pawn up; } 9... --
{ e.g.  9...Bc5  10.Bg5  Qd7  11.Nbd2  Na5  12.Bf1  Be7  13.Nc4  , J.Breukelman-J.De Groote, Hengelo 2004. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "E.Perez-L.Paredes  Riobamba 2010  English Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 { Offering a transposition into the Chigorin variation. } 2. g3 d6
3. c4 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be6
{ A peculiar idea, aiming to swap the light-squared bishops as soon as possible.   Instead, by  4...e5  followed by ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, he could have steered the game into a standard English. }
5. d3 Qc8 6. O-O
{ Both here and on the next move, the interfering  6.Bg5  was interesting as well.   While  6.h3  would also cast some doubts on Black's idea. }
6... Bh3 7. Nc3 Bxg2 8. Kxg2 h6 9. Rb1 e5 10. b4 Nd4
{ Without any obvious need, Black moves the knight again.   10...Be7  , followed by ...O-O, was much better, waiting with the knight move until White goes b4-b5. }
11. --
{ Well, how to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "E.Perez-L.Paredes  Riobamba 2010  English Opening "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1q1kb1r/ppp2pp1/3p1n1p/4p3/1PPn4/2NP1NP1/P3PPKP/1RBQ1R2 w kq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nb5
{ Gaining a vital tempo by attacking the weak d4-pawn.   In contrast, the game went  12.Ne4  Nxe4   @@StartBracket@@Black is not attentive either; keeping the position closed by  12...Be7  was essential for him@@EndBracket@@  13.dxe4  c5  14.bxc5  dxc5  15.Qa4+  @@StartBracket@@at last, a punishment@@EndBracket@@  15...Qc6  16.Qxc6+  bxc6  17.Rd1  Rd8  18.Rb7  Rd7  and at this point the simple  19.Rxd7  Kxd7  20.e3  would have produced an endgame with an extra pawn. }
12... c5 13. bxc5 dxc5 14. Bf4
{ Just in time, creating the threat Nc7+ before Black consolidates with ...Be7 and ...O-O. }
14... Qc6+ 15. Kg1 Kd7 { The only way of avoiding material losses. } 16. e3
{ Clearing new lines with a strong initiative. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "J.Calderon-A.Chang  Tena 2008  Scandinavian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3
{ An interesting sideline against the Scandinavian, which leaves the bishop rather well placed on g2. }
4... Nf6 5. Bg2 Bg4 6. Nf3 Nc6 { 6...c6  is a more solid choice. } 7. h3
{ The immediate  7.O-O  would permit the annoying  7...Qh5  . } 7... Bh5 8. O-O
e6 9. d3 Bxf3
{ An incomprehensive exchange; the simple  9...Be7  , followed by ...O-O, was much better. }
10. Qxf3 Be7 11. Bd2 Qc5
{ Of course there was nothing wrong with  11...O-O  . Chang somehow forgets about castling in this game. }
12. Be3 Qd6 13. a3 a5 14. Rad1 e5
{ Black doesn't sense the danger.   14...O-O  was called for. } 15. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "J.Calderon-A.Chang  Tena 2008  Scandinavian Defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1pp1bppp/2nq1n2/p3p3/8/P1NPBQPP/1PP2PB1/3R1RK1 w kq - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. Nb5
{ Preparing a central break with d3-d4 before the opponent castles away.   Another good option was  15.d4  exd4  16.Nb5  Qd7  17.Nxd4  with irresistible threats. }
15... Qd7 16. d4 e4 17. Qe2 Bd8
{ This over-careful move lets White's d-pawn reach the sixth rank.   Again,  17...O-O  was preferable. }
18. d5 Nb8 19. d6 c6 20. Nc3
{ With a decisive advantage thanks to the powerful passed pawn.   The game concluded  20.Nc3  O-O  21.Nxe4  Nxe4  22.Bxe4  Qxh3  23.Qd3  g6  24.d7  Bc7  25.Bg5  f6  26.Bxf6  Rxf6  27.d8=Q+  Bxd8  28.Qxd8+  Rf8  29.Qe7  Qc8  30.Rfe1  Ra6  31.Rd6  and Black resigned in view of the inevitable and overwhelming Bxg6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "J.Sanaguano-A.Vallejo  Riobamba 2010  Caro-Kann Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3
{ In this, Fischer's old pet line against the Caro,  6.Bf4  is considered the most accurate move, in order to avoid Black's next. }
6... e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5
{ In exchange for the IQP, Black has quite an easy development for his minor pieces. }
8. Bc2
{ A more critical try is  8.Qe2  Qe7  9.Bb5+  in order to swap pieces. In the game White applies this idea one move later, which will make a big difference. }
8... Be6 9. Qe2
{ Better was  9.Nf3  , speeding up development, but White is on a material hunt. }
9... Bd6 10. f4 { Consistent with his plan. Again,  10.Nf3  was called for. }
10... --
{ How to punish White? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
