[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Bf5 3. c4 c6
{ Later,  3...e6  was discovered to be the right move; e.g.  4.Qb3  Nc6  5.Bd2   @@StartBracket@@or  5.Qxb7  Nb4  @@EndBracket@@  5...Rb8  with complex play. }
4. Qb3
{ 4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  was a more precise move order for White, when  5...Qb6  simply drops a pawn to  6.Qxd5  . }
4... Qc8
{ Correct was  4...Qb6  5.cxd5  Bxb1  6.Rxb1  Qxb3  7.axb3  cxd5  with equality - Neishtadt. }
5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nc3 e6 7. Bf4 a6
{ Both: -  7...Nf6  8.Nb5   -  7...Na6  8.e4  followed by  8...--  9.Bb5+  , were disastrous for Black - Neishtadt.   Instead,  7...Nc6  8.Nb5  Bb4+  9.Kd1  Kf8  would perhaps offer more resistance, although  10.Rc1  keeps a clear initiative for White. }
8. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
