[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "W.Lombardy-V.Smyslov  Teesside 1975  Vienna Game"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n5/3nP3/1b1p1N2/3P1N2/PPP1BKPP/R1BQ3R b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10... Ne3
{ At the cost of a mere pawn Black breaks through on the dark squares.   10...Re8  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Bf4  was somewhat less promising. }
11. Bxe3 dxe3+ 12. Kxe3 { Or  12.Kg1  Nxe5  13.Nxe5  Qd4  - Smyslov. } 12...
Bc5+ 13. d4
{ On  13.Kd2  the sacrifice  13...Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Qd4  again works fine. } 13...
Nxd4 { An elegant sacrifice directed at White's unsafe king. } 14. Nxd4 Qg5 15.
c3 Qxe5+ 16. Kf3 Rd8 17. g3
{ 17.Qd2  is met by  17...g5  18.Rad1  Qf6  19.g3  Bd6  , getting on with the attack - Smyslov. }
17... Bxd4 18. Kg2
{ After  18.cxd4  Rxd4  19.Qb3  g5  Black also regains the material. } 18...
Bf5 19. cxd4 Rxd4 20. Qe1 g5 21. Bf3
{ Holding on to the piece by  21.Nh5  fails to the crushing pin  21...Re4  22.Kf2  Re8  - Smyslov. }
21... Qxe1 22. Rhxe1 gxf4 23. gxf4 Rxf4
{ Black later converted his extra pawns into victory. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "W.Lange-E.J.Diemer  Weidenau 1937  Dutch Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. c4 e6 3. e3
{ A rather passive set-up against the Dutch.   More popular is  3.g3  and 4. Bg2, taking command of the long diagonal, while the c1-h6 diagonal remains open for the other bishop. }
3... d5
{ Setting up the Stonewall.   Another good option was  3...Nf6  , followed by ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, exploiting the fact that with his third move White practically discarded a kingside fianchetto. }
4. Bd3 c6 5. Nf3 Bd6 6. O-O Qf6
{ 6...Nf6  seems more natural, enabling a future...Ne4, which is a key idea in the present structure. }
7. Nc3 Ne7
{ Not every developing move is of equal value.   7...Nh6  was preferable. } 8.
--
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
