[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "G.Sax-L.Hazai  Hungarian Championship,  Budapest 1974  Alekhine’s Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Be2 e6
{ Quite a solid branch of the Alekhine. } 6. O-O Be7 7. h3 Bh5 8. c4 Nb6 9. Nc3
dxe5
{ At this point Black must already have been thinking about snatching a pawn on move 11; otherwise he would have no reason to refrain from the natural  9...O-O  . }
10. Nxe5 Bxe2 11. Qxe2
{ White has seen that the d4-pawn is poisoned.   11.Nxe2  was less inspiring. }
11... Qxd4
{ Consistent, but... losing.   Black should have settled for  11...O-O  , followed by ...N8d7, with a cramped but solid position. }
12. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "G.Sax-L.Hazai  Hungarian Championship,  Budapest 1974  Alekhine’s Defence "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2k2r/ppp1bppp/1n2p3/4N3/2Pq4/2N4P/PP2QPP1/R1B2RK1 w kq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. Rd1
{ More precise than  12.Nb5  Qd8  13.Qf3  Bf6  14.Rd1  Qc8  and Black is alive. }
12... Qc5
{ Now White wins on the spot; though after  12...Qh4  13.Nb5  Bd8   @@StartBracket@@or  13...Na6  14.Rd4  Qf6  15.Rf4  - the bishop move vacates e7 for the queen@@EndBracket@@  14.Qf3  O-O  15.Qxb7  Black's game is also difficult. }
13. b4
{ A key move that wins a tempo by diverting the queen from the defence of the c7-pawn, and clears the a3-f8 diagonal for the bishop. }
13... Qxb4 14. Nb5 Na6 { Obviously  14...Qc5  failed to  15.Ba3  . } 15. Qf3
Rf8 { Unfortunately for Black,  15...O-O  drops the bishop after  16.Ba3  . }
16. Qxb7 { In view of  16.Qxb7  Qc5  17.Be3  Qxe5  18.Qc6+  , Black resigned. }
