[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "I.Boleslavsky-G.Stoltz  Saltsjöbaden Interzonal 1948  Spanish Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 { We have reached an initial position of the Open Spanish. } 9. Qe2
{ A somewhat outdated line.   Nowadays White usually continues either  9.Nbd2  or  9.c3   After  9.Qe2  ,  9...Be7  or  9...Bc5  , with 10...O-O next, yields Black a solid game, but Stoltz finds a more 'active' idea... }
9... g5
{ Gaining space and preparing ...g5-g4 with a fight for the centre, but the king is irreparably weakened by this flank advance.How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "I.Boleslavsky-G.Stoltz  Saltsjöbaden Interzonal 1948  Spanish Opening"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/2p2p1p/p1n1b3/1p1pP1p1/4n3/1B3N2/PPP1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10. c4
{ Meeting the flank aggression with a strong counterstrike in the centre.   In contrast, after  10.Nbd2  g4   Or  10.Rd1  g4  11.Ne1  Rg8  , Black's ninth move would prove more justified. }
10... bxc4
{ Or  10...g4  11.cxd5  , when both  11...Bxd5   @@StartBracket@@and  11...gxf3  12.Qxe4  @@EndBracket@@  12.Rd1  gxf3  13.Qxf3  Nxe5  14.Qe2  c6  15.Nc3  leave White on top. }
11. Ba4 Bd7 12. e6
{ Another ingenious advance that clears the e5-square and h5-e8 diagonal for an attack on Black's king.   Otherwise,  12.Nc3  , challenging the active knight on  e4  , also made sense. }
12... fxe6 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Ne5 Qd6
{ Saving the bishop but fatally exposing the king.   By the sacrifice  14...Qf6  15.Nxc6  Kd7  , followed by ...Bc5, Black could have complicated the opponent's task in practice. }
15. Qh5+ Ke7 16. Bxg5+ Nxg5 17. Qxg5+ Ke8 18. Qh5+ Ke7 19. Qf7+ Kd8 20. Qf6+
Kc8 21. Qxh8 { White later won. } *

