[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "P.Ricardi-H.Lopez Silva  Pinamar 2004  English Opening"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/p2p1ppp/1p2pn2/8/2PN4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

6. Ndb5
{ Immediately fighting for the d6-square, in similar fashion to Fischer-Tal. }
6... Bc5
{ The lesser of evils; since  6...d6  7.Bf4  just makes things worse for Black; e.g.  7...e5  8.Bg5  a6  9.Bxf6  gxf6  10.Qd5  and White wins material. }
7. Bf4 { 7.Nd6+  Ke7  8.Bf4  , followed by 9. e3, was more precise. } 7... Na6
{ This lets White take a firm grip on the d6-square.   Preferable was  7...O-O  8.Bc7   @@StartBracket@@not  8.Nc7  e5  9.Bxe5  Ng4  @@EndBracket@@  Qe7  9.Bd6  Bxd6  10.Qxd6  Nc6  with just a slight disadvantage in the endgame. }
8. Bd6 Bxd6 9. Nxd6+ Ke7 10. Qd2 { To reinforce the strong knight on d6. }
10... Qc7 11. Rd1 Qc5
{ After  11...Nc5  12.e4  Bb7  13.f3  Black also has a difficult time. One of his problems is that  13...a6  , denying either Nb5, runs into  14.b4  . }
12. a3 Nc7 13. b4 Qc6 14. e4
{ Seizing the centre with a big edge.   There followed  14.e4  Nce8  15.Nxe8  Rxe8  16.Bd3  d6  17.f4  e5  18.O-O  Be6  19.Nd5+  Bxd5  20.exd5  Qc7  21.fxe5  dxe5  22.Qg5  and White soon converted his advantage into a full point, now that  22...Kf8  fails to  23.Rxf6  gxf6  24.Qxf6  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "E.Sutovsky-A.Bykhovsky  Tel Aviv 1995  Caro-Kann Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Bc4 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ A somewhat less aggressive continuation than the usual  6.Ng5  e6  7.Qe2  , when both knights are kept on the board for a future attack. }
6... Nxf6 7. c3 e6
{ With this move, the game takes upon a French-like character.   While  7...Bf5   @@StartBracket@@or  7...Bg4  failed to  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@   The elastic  7...Qc7  is a more popular choice, delaying ...e7-e6 or ...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@ g4 @@EndBracket@@  in accordance with White's next move. }
8. Nf3 c5 9. O-O a6
{ A useful move on many occasions. For example, after a later ...c5xd4, Nxd4, Black can play ...Qc7 without worrying about Nb5. }
10. Bg5 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5
{ This apparently active move turns out to have a serious flaw.   11...Be7  12.Qe2  O-O  13.Rad1  Qc7  was preferable, although White seems to be a tempo up compared with analogous positions in the French Tarrasch with 3...c5 4 exd5 Qxd5. }
12. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "E.Sutovsky-A.Bykhovsky  Tel Aviv 1995  Caro-Kann Defence "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2b3B1/2BN4/2P5/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Unfortunately for Black, the desirable  12...Qxf6  drops a pawn after  13.Nxe6  Bxe6  14.Bxe6  fxe6   @@StartBracket@@or  14...Qxe6  15.Re1  @@EndBracket@@  15.Qh5+  . }
13. Qg4
{ A move with several virtues: it prevents 13...O-O, prepares 14. Rad1, and installs the threat of 14. Qg7. }
13... Bxd4 14. cxd4 h5
{ After  14...b5  15.Bb3  Bb7  16.d5  Bxd5  17.Rad1  Black also has a difficult game. }
15. Qg7 Ke7 16. d5 Qg8
{ Both:  16...e5  17.d6+   16...exd5  17.Bxd5  Qxd5  18.Qxh8  Bh3  19.Qg7  win for White - Blatny. }
17. d6+ Kxd6 18. Qxf6 { Black's king has become fatally exposed. } 18... Bd7
19. Rfd1+ Kc7 20. Be2
{ A quiet but powerful move.   In view of  20.Be2  Bc6  21.Bf3  Bxf3  22.Qxf3  , with threats like Rac1+ and Qf4+, Black resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "V.Ivanchuk-A.Shirov  Wijk aan Zee 2001  Sicilian Defence, Najdorf Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Ng4
{ A very popular way of interfering with White's English Attack. } 7. Bg5 h6 8.
Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Bg7
{ In exchange for his exposed kingside structure Black enjoys decent dark-square control. }
10. h3 Nf6
{ 10...Ne5  is a popular alternative, preventing White's next move in the game. }
11. Bc4 Qb6 12. O-O Nxe4
{ This pawn soon turns out to be poisoned.   Ivanchuk analyses  12...O-O  13.Nf5  Bxf5  14.exf5  Qxb2  15.Nd5  Nxd5  16.Qxd5  with compensation for the pawn, but this certainly looks like a better deal for Black than the game continuation.   As for snatching the other pawn by  12...Qxb2  , after  13.Qd3  Qa3  14.Rad1  Bd7  15.e5  dxe5  16.Bxe5  Nc6  17.Nxc6  Bxc6  18.Rfe1  White counts on a clear initiative - Pikula. }
13. Nxe4 Qxd4 { Or  13...Bxd4  14.Qh5  winning - Ivanchuk. } 14. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "V.Ivanchuk-A.Shirov  Wijk aan Zee 2001  Sicilian Defence, Najdorf Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1k2r/1p2ppb1/p2p3p/6p1/2BqN3/6BP/PPP2PP1/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Nxd6+
{ A strong sacrifice with the aim of keeping Black's king in the centre. }
14... exd6 15. Qe2+ Be6
{ Both:  15...Be5  16.Rad1  , followed by Rxd6   15...Kd7  16.Rad1  Qf6  17.Rxd6+  Qxd6  18.Rd1  win for White - Ivanchuk. }
16. Bxe6 fxe6
{ The game went  16...O-O  17.Rad1  Qf6  18.Bd5  Nc6  19.c3  with a huge positional plus for White. }
17. Qxe6+ Kd8 18. Rad1 Re8 19. Qg6
{ Black is doomed; e.g.  19.Qg6  Qxb2  20.Qxd6+  with mate on the next move. }
