[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "Oratovsky, M. vs. Sulava, N."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. d4
{ White finally agrees to an Open Sicilian. } 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 a6 7. Be2 Qc7
8. f4
{ Quite an aggressive choice.   With  8.Be3  Nf6  9.f3  White could have set up a standard Maroczy Bind. }
8... Bb4
{ 8...Nf6  9.e5  Ne4  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  , followed by ...Nc6, was safer, not yet defining the destiny of the other bishop. }
9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 d6
{ This indifferent move will be violently refuted in the game.   10...Bxe4  11.Ba3  also looks promising for White   Whereas by  10...Nf6  11.e5  Ne4  , followed by ...Nc6, Black could have obtained some counterplay on the light squares. }
11. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
