[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "Oratovsky, M. vs. Sulava, N."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2k1nr/1bq2ppp/pp1pp3/8/2PNPP2/2P5/P3B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Bh5
{ A surprising attack on the black king, exploiting the absence of a knight on f6.   Both  11.f5  e5  and  11.e5  dxe5  12.fxe5  Nd7  were less promising. }
11... g6
{ 11...Nf6  obviously failed to  12.Nxe6   While after  11...Qe7  12.f5  e5  13.f6  Nxf6  14.Nf5  White develops a deadly attack. }
12. f5 { Intensifying the attack before Black gets his pieces into the game. }
12... exf5
{ 12...gxh5  13.fxe6  is even worse, with the queen heading for h5. } 13. Nxf5
gxf5 14. Rxf5 Kd8 15. Qd4
{ With a tremendous initiative for the piece. Rather curiously for a Sicilian, on move 15 Black has not yet developed either of his knights! }
15... f6 16. Rxf6 { Transposing to a superior endgame. } 16... Nxf6 17. Qxf6+
Qe7 18. Bg5 Qxf6 19. Bxf6+ Kc7 20. Bxh8 Nd7 21. Bd4 Bxe4 22. Re1 Bc6 23. Re7
{ White soon won. } *

