[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "St.Schneider-C.Olsson  Swedish Team  Championship 2006  Benoni Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3
{ After  4.c4  the game would have transposed to the Benoni, but White prefers a set-up based on swift development. }
4... Qa5
{ This and Black's following move make a strange impression.   4...exd5  5.Nxd5  Nxd5  6.Qxd5  Be7  , followed by ...O-O and d7-d6, would have been a normal continuation. }
5. Bd2 b5 6. Ne4
{ White parries the threat of 6...b4 in advance and prepares the exchange of Black's only active minor piece. }
6... Qb6 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 8. e4
{ Reinforcing the centre and enabling further kingside development. } 8... Rg8
9. c4 bxc4
{ Or  9...b4  10.g3  , followed by Bg2 and O-O, with a comfortable game for White. }
10. Bc3
{ An excellent post for the bishop now that ...b5-b4 is no longer possible. }
10... Ba6
{ This deprives the knight of its supposed destiny; but after  10...Bb7  11.g3  Na6  12.Bxc4  Nc7  13.O-O  White also has the upper hand. }
11. g3 f5
{ Suicide - despite a lagging development and the king in the centre, Black opens the position.How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
