[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "B.Spassky-Avtonomov  Leningrad 1949  Queen’s Gambit Accepted"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6
{ A standard position of the Queen's Gambit Accepted has been reached. } 7. Qe2
Nc6
{ Nowadays,  7...b5  8.Bb3  Bb7  is more popular, with the queen's knight heading for d7. }
8. Nc3 b5 9. Bb3 cxd4
{ This capture facilitates White's plans, now that both the e-file and the c1-h6 diagonal are opened for his pieces.   More flexible continuations are  9...Be7  10.Rd1  Qc7   And  9...Na5  10.Bc2  Bb7  . }
10. Rd1 Bb7
{ A natural move, but one that soon leads Black into huge difficulties.   10...d3  11.Rxd3  Qc7  12.e4  Be7  13.Nd5  is known to favour White   so  10...Na5  was a safer choice, harassing the dangerous bishop on  b3  . }
11. exd4 Nb4
{ An attempt to overprotect the vital d5-square.   11...Be7  runs into  12.d5   while after  11...Na5  12.d5  Nxb3  13.dxe6  Qxd1+  14.Nxd1  Nxa1  15.exf7+  Kxf7  16.Ng5+  White's attack was decisive in P.H.Nielsen-E.Bentzen, Danish Team Championship 2001. }
12. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "B.Spassky-Avtonomov  Leningrad 1949  Queen’s Gambit Accepted"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/1b3ppp/p3pn2/1p6/1n1P4/1BN2N2/PP2QPPP/R1BR2K1 w kq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. d5
{ Anyway!   In the same spirit,  12.Bg5  Be7  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.d5  is also strong. In fact, the d4-d5 break tends to work well in a wide range of IQP positions. }
12... Nbxd5 { 12...Nfxd5  13.a3   or  12...Bxd5  13.Bg5  is even worse. } 13.
Bg5 Be7
{ Black manages to keep the d5-square under control, but now his pawn structure is ruined. }
14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Nd4 Kf8
{ 17...O-O  obviously failed to  18.Nc6   While after  17...Qd7  18.Re1  Ra7  19.Rac1  the threat of 20 Nc6 decides. }
18. Nf5 h5
{ This loses at once, though Black was already short of a good defence. } 19.
Rxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxe7+ Kg8 21. Qxf6 *

