[SetUp "1"]

12... Nxe4
{ Exchanging a pair of knights in order to avoid any tactical shots at e6 or f7.   Instead,  12...O-O  again failed to  13.Nxe6   @@StartBracket@@While the game continued  12...Bc7  13.Nxf7  Kxf7  14.Ng5+  Kg6   a lesser evil was  14...Ke8  15.Nxe6  Bxg2  16.Nxd8  Rxd8  17.Rg1  Bd5  18.Qc2  with just a clear advantage for White - Lalic@@EndBracket@@  15.Bxb7  Rxb7  16.d4  e5  @@StartBracket@@ 17. Qd3+ was threatened @@EndBracket@@  17.Qf7+  Kf5  18.e4+  and Black resigned in view of mate on the next move. }
13. Nxe4 O-O
{ Exploiting the pin on the h1-a8 diagonal, Black finally manages to castle.   The alternative  13...Be5  at once should be fine as well. }
14. O-O Be5 { Black has no problems. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "E.Mnatsakanian-V.Simagin  Kiev 1965  Caro-Kann Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. Bc4 Be7
{ 6...Bd6  is more active. } 7. Qh5
{ Quite a straightforward approach.   7.Ne2  is more flexible. } 7... O-O 8.
Ne2 g6 9. Qh6 Bf5 { Development with tempo. } 10. Bb3
{ After  10.c3  Re8  11.Be3  Bf8  12.Qh4  b5  13.Bb3  Nd7  , followed by ... Nb6-d5, Black is also fine. }
10... c5
{ Being slightly ahead in development, Black is happy to open up the game. }
11. Be3
{ Now  11.dxc5  Na6  , followed by ...Nxc5, just helps his case, so White prefers to bring one more piece into the battle. }
11... Nc6
{ Evaluate  12.O-O-O  . @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
