[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp2bp1p/2n2ppQ/2p2b2/3P4/1B2B3/PPP1NPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. O-O-O
{ On this flank the king becomes severely exposed to Black's forces.   12.d5  Nb4  is just as bad   While  12.Rd1  runs into the same reply as in the game.   In contrast, the simple  12.dxc5  held the balance; e.g.  12...Bxc5  13.Bxc5  Qa5+  14.c3  Qxc5  15.O-O  . }
12... c4 { This strong sacrifice was perhaps overlooked by White. } 13. Bxc4
Nb4 14. Bb3 Rc8
{ Neishtadt also suggests  14...a5  when  15.a4  is strongly met by  15...b5  . }
15. Nc3 Qa5 16. Kb1
{ This loses at once.   16.Bd2  was essential, when Black could try  16...Rxc3  anyway; e.g.  17.Bxc3  Nxa2+  18.Bxa2  Qxa2  with interesting compensation for the exchange. }
16... Rxc3 17. bxc3 Bxc2+
{ In view of  17...Bxc2+  18.Bxc2   @@StartBracket@@or  18.Kc1  Bxb3  19.axb3  Qa2  @@EndBracket@@  Qxa2+  19.Kc1  Qxc2  , White resigned. }
