[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "E.Postny-J.Shahade  Budapest 2003  King’s Indian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ White avoids the mainline Grünfeld arising after  3.Nc3  d5  and invites a Sämisch King's Indian. }
3... Bg7
{ Black accepts the proposal.   By  3...d5  he could have stayed in Grünfeld waters.   While the gambit  3...e5  4.dxe5  Nh5  has its supporters too. }
4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 Nbd7 6. Be3 c6 7. Qd2 h5
{ A double-edged advance - Black rules out Be3-h6 but also weakens his kingside structure.   7...e5  is more common or 7...a6  , preparing ...b7-b5. }
8. O-O-O Qa5 9. Kb1 a6 10. Nh3 b5 11. Nf2 Bb7
{ 11...Nb6  was more active - Postny. } 12. f4
{ The time is right for central expansion, now that Black's reply 12...Ng4 has been neutralized. }
12... b4 13. Ne2 c5 14. d5 { 14.e5  Ne4  and Black is fine - Postny. } 14...
Qc7 15. Ng1
{ A nice regrouping. The knight is heading for f3 in order to support the e4-e5 advance, while the bishop reaches d3. }
15... Nb6 16. Bd3 Nfd7 17. Qe2
{ The immediate  17.Nf3  permits  17...Na4  , so White first enables the prophylactic retreat Bc1. }
17... --
{ Which do you prefer,  17...O-O-O  or  17...O-O  , and for what reason? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

