[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "N.Mikkelsen-A.Mohammadi  Lund 2005  Sicilian Defence,  Scheveningen Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4 h6 7. h4 Nc6 8. Rg1
d5
{ A logical reply to the Keres Attack - Black responds to the flank aggression with action in the centre. }
9. Bb5 Bd7 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Be3 Bb4+
{ It is not really clear what Black gains by provoking c2-c3, but it worked well for him in the game!   12...Be7  is the main option in this rather well-researched position. }
13. c3 Be7 14. Nf3
{ Retreating the knight from its great post in the centre.   More logical was  14.g5  , getting on with the kingside expansion or  14.Qd2  preparing O-O-O, without bothering about the h4-pawn. }
14... a6 15. Ba4 Qa5 { Protecting the d5-pawn and enabling a future ...O-O-O. }
16. b4
{ When White starts pushing his pawns on both flanks in the Sicilian, he often ends up being punished in the centre.   Preferable was  16.Bb3  Be6  17.Qc2  , followed by O-O-O, in order to conclude development - Eriksson. }
16... Qc7 17. Rb1
{ After  17.Qxd5  O-O-O  , followed by ...Rhe8, Black has great compensation for the pawn. }
17... --
{ How do you continue with Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "N.Mikkelsen-A.Mohammadi  Lund 2005  Sicilian Defence,  Scheveningen Variation "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1pqbbpp1/p1n4p/3p4/BP4PP/2P1BN2/P4P2/1R1QK1R1 b kq - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17... O-O
{ Black has noticed that his king will be quite safe on this flank.   In contrast,  17...O-O-O  permits  18.b5  with some attacking prospects though the flexible  17...Be6  was reasonable too. }
18. g5
{ After  18.h5  Bf6  19.Rc1  Rfe8  White's king is in more danger than Black's; e.g.  20.g5  hxg5  21.Nxg5  Rxe3+  22.fxe3  Qe5  , recovering the material with interest. }
18... h5 19. Bc2
{ Or  19.Qxd5  Rad8  20.Qe4  g6  21.Bf4  Bd6  , preparing ...Rfe8 with a strong initiative. }
19... g6
{ By now Black is strategically winning thanks to White's unsafe king.   There followed  19...g6  20.Kf1  @@StartBracket@@ ? @@EndBracket@@  20...Bh3+  21.Ke1  Rfe8  22.Rg3  Bd7  23.Bb3  Bd6  24.Rg1  Ne5  25.Bxd5  Qxc3+  26.Nd2  Nd3+  27.Kf1  Bb5  28.Kg2  Qe5  , heading for h2, and Black's attack soon took its toll. }
