[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 2"]
[Black "S.Ernst-R.Miedema  Dutch Championship,  Haaksbergen 2009  Ragozin Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Bb4
{ Reaching an initial position of the Ragozin Defence. } 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6
{ Immediately challenging the enemy bishop.   Another way to play the Ragozin is  6...Nbd7  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  Qa5  9.Qc2  c4  10.Bf5  O-O  11.O-O  Re8  , intending ...Bxc3 and ...Ne4. }
7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. Nd2
{ Sacrificing a pawn in order to challenge the knight on e4.   In contrast, after  9.Rc1  h5  Black is even playing for an advantage. }
9... Nxg3
{ Black turns down the offer.   After  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Rc1  a sharp position arises, which has been heavily debated in recent games. }
10. hxg3 Be6 11. Qc2 c6 12. a3 Bf8
{ The idea of regrouping the bishop to g7 is rather slow.   12...Be7  might have been better. }
13. e4 dxe4
{ Being behind in development Black shouldn't open the position.   Either  13...Nd7  or  13...Bg7  was preferable - Baburin. }
14. O-O-O Nd7 15. Bc4
{ Instead of recovering the pawn at once, White looks for a bishop exchange that will strengthen his control of the light squares. }
15... e3
{ An unfortunate intermediate move.   15...Qe7  , preparing ...O-O-O, was Black's last chance - Baburin. }
16. --
{ How to punish Black? @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
