[Black "Exercise #1:  Z.Andriasian-M.Litwiniec"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/ppp1qpp1/2np1n1p/8/2BPP3/1QP2N2/P4PPP/R1B2RK1 w kq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. e5
{ A key method for the side possessing a pawn centre: its advance. The possible benefits are several: gain of space, creation of a passed pawn, or clearance of lines for the fellow pieces, as in this case.   11.Re1  , preparing e4-e5, was also strong. }
11... dxe5 12. Ba3 Qd7 13. Nxe5
{ By now Black's exposed king makes her game hopeless.  13.dxe5  and  13.Rfe1  were good as well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-M.Howe  Gothenburg 1989  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3
{ At that time I was 13 years old and my team-mate, GM  @@StartBracket@@back then, IM@@EndBracket@@  Stellan Brynell, had just taught me this sideline against the Sicilian. Similarly to the previous game, White aims to set up a pawn centre with d2-d4. }
3... Nf6 4. Be2 Nc6
{ The most straightforward reaction, eliminating the queen check on a4; i.e.  4...Nxe4  5.Qa4+  .   Another common option is  4...g6  5.O-O  Bg7  , when White can choose between  6.Re1  , followed by Bf1, and  6.Bb5+  , followed by Re1 or Qe2, with the desired d2-d4 next. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4
{ Just like 4...d6 in the previous game, Black does little to challenge the enemy pawn centre.   The main line goes  6...Nxe4  7.d5  Qa5+  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Ne5  10.Nxe5  Qxc3+  11.Bd2  Qxe5  12.O-O  with a sharp battle. }
7. O-O g6 8. Be3
{ Interestingly, rather few opening systems for Black tend to tolerate such a pawn structure. In contrast, with the c-pawns still on the board it is a main feature of the King's Indian and the Pirc, among others. }
8... Bg7 9. h3
{ Possibly  9.Nc3  O-O  10.Nd2  Bxe2  11.Qxe2  was more promising, speeding up development. }
9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 O-O 11. Nc3 Qa5
{ Hitting thin air.   Black could have fought for the centre by  11...e5  when  12.d5   @@StartBracket@@White should rather react by  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Be2  Nd4  14.Bc4  Rc8  15.b3  with a slight advantage@@EndBracket@@  12...Nd4  13.Bxd4  exd4  14.Qxd4  Nd7  yields him good compensation for the pawn. }
12. a3 Rac8 13. b4 Qd8 14. Qb3
{ Overprotecting the knight and ceding d1 to the rooks. } 14... b6
{ An unnecessary weakening of the light squares.   14...a6  15.Rfd1  e6  was preferable, followed by 16...Qe7 and 17...Rfd8, with a passive but safe position.   In contrast,  14...e5  was no longer feasible due to  15.dxe5  dxe5  16.Nb5  with ideas like Rfd1 and Bc5. }
15. Rac1 Nd7 16. Rfd1
{ White's development is complete. With the centre firmly in his control, he can now start looking for possibilities on the whole board, in particular on the queenside where Black's unfortunate 14th move left targets on c6 and a6. }
16... Kh8
{ My opponent perhaps dreamed about a kingside attack, or simply didn't know what to do.   The lesser evil was  16...a6  17.Qa4  Ncb8  , resisting on the queenside. }
17. Qa4
{ With ideas like 18. Nb5 and Be2-a6. Moreover, Black has to look out for the e4-e5 advance. }
17... e5 18. dxe5
{ Of course not  18.d5  Nd4  with counterplay. In contrast, the text clears the d-file for the rooks and establishes a new weakness on d6. }
18... Ndxe5
{ Both  18...dxe5  19.Rd6  and  18...Ncxe5  19.Be2  Nc4  20.Bxc4  Rxc4  21.Rxd6  were equally bad for Black. }
19. Be2
{ Setting up the strong threat of 20. f4. Black's next move leads to instant defeat, but his problems were unsolvable anyway. }
19... Qe7 20. Nd5 Qd7 21. Ba6
{ Avoiding the trap  21.f4  Nd4  22.Qxd7  Nxe2+  23.Kf2  Nxd7  24.Kxe2  Bb2  and the battle goes on   Whereas now, Black can't avoid heavy material losses; e.g.  21.Ba6  Rcd8  22.f4  , so he resigned. }
*

