[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "R.Ortega-V.Korchnoi  Havana 1963  Sicilian Defence,  Taimanov Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Be2
{ 5.Nc3  is more flexible and  5.Nb5  , preparing a Maroczy Bind with c2-c4, is also possible. }
5... Nf6 6. Nxc6
{ Strengthening the enemy centre without any obvious reason.   Again,  6.Nc3  is preferable, when Black can stay in Taimanov waters with  6...Qc7  ;   Switch to the Scheveningen by  6...d6  ;   or enter the gambit line  6...Bb4  7.O-O  Bxc3  8.bxc3  Nxe4  9.Qd3  , followed by Ba3. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3
{ Of course  7.Nd2  or  7.Nc3  was more logical, avoiding a second bishop move. }
7... d5 { Black starts fighting for the centre. } 8. exd5
{ White commits a new inaccuracy, one that will leave the centre in the opponent's hands.   Instead, either  8.e5  or  8.Nd2  was a reasonable reply. }
8... cxd5
{ The correct recapture, which leaves Black with two pawns against none in the centre. }
9. O-O Bd6
{ Development first. The tempting  9...e5  would be premature in view of  10.Bg5  Be7  11.Bb5+  intending  11...Bd7  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.Qxd5  . }
10. Nd2
{ With hindsight,  10.c4  , fighting against the enemy centre seems like a lesser evil; e.g.  10...dxc4  11.Qa4+   @@StartBracket@@not  11.Bxc4  Bxh2+  @@EndBracket@@  Bd7  12.Qxc4  Rc8  13.Qh4  , followed by Nc3 and Bg5. }
10... O-O 11. Re1 e5
{ Of course. The central pawns start rolling, with great effect. } 12. Nf1 e4
13. Be2 d4
{ Thanks to the tactical trick  13...d4  14.Qxd4  Bxh2+  , both pawns reach the fourth rank. Before advancing  ...e5-e4  Black had to assure this follow-up, as otherwise White could now have blocked the central pawns by 14. Be3 and Bd4. }
14. Ng3 Qa5
{ This time minor tactics help Black bring his queen to a great post on d5, where she will support the central pawns and, at the same time, use them as a shield. }
15. Bd2 Qd5 16. Qc1 Bb7 17. Bf4
{ A tactical oversight.   After  17.Bf1  Rac8  Black keeps a clear advantage, but at least the g2-pawn becomes safe. }
17... d3
{ A carefully calculated blow.   The preparatory  17...Bc5  looked strong as well, whereas the obvious  17...e3  proves less powerful after  18.Bf3  . }
18. cxd3 e3 19. Bf3 exf2+
{ Thanks to the intermediate 17...d3, Black managed to clear the g1-a7 diagonal towards the enemy king. }
20. Kxf2 Ng4+
{ One more accuracy.   In contrast, after  20...Bc5+  21.Be3  Ng4+  22.Kg1  White defends. }
21. Kg1
{ Or  21.Bxg4  Qxg2+  22.Ke3  Bxf4+  23.Kxf4  Qf2+  with mate to come. } 21...
Qd4+ 22. Be3 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Rxe3 Bc5
{ Finally Black wins the exchange and transposes to a clearly superior endgame.   There followed  24...Bc5  25.Bxb7  Bxe3+  26.Kh1  Rab8  27.Bf3  Rxb2  and Korchnoi went on to win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "Exercise #1: R.Ortega-V.Korchnoi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/3P4/8/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

8... cxd5
{ The correct recapture, which leaves Black with two pawns against none in the centre. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "Exercise #2: R.Ortega-V.Korchnoi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p4ppp/3bpn2/3p4/8/3B4/PPPN1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... e5 { Of course. The central pawns start rolling, with great effect. } 12.
Nf1 e4 13. Be2 d4
{ Thanks to the tactical trick  13...d4  14.Qxd4  Bxh2+  , both pawns reach the fourth rank. Before advancing  ...e5-e4  Black had to assure this follow-up, as otherwise White could now have blocked the central pawns by 14. Be3 and Bd4. }
14. Ng3 Qa5
{ This time minor tactics help Black bring his queen to a great post on d5, where she will support the central pawns and, at the same time, use them as a shield. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "Exercise #3: R.Ortega-V.Korchnoi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb3ppp/3b1n2/3q4/3ppB2/6N1/PPP1BPPP/R1Q1R1K1 b - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17... d3
{ A carefully calculated blow.   The preparatory  17...Bc5  looked strong as well, whereas the obvious  17...e3  proves less powerful after  18.Bf3  . }
18. cxd3 e3 19. Bf3 exf2+
{ Thanks to the intermediate 17...d3, Black managed to clear the g1-a7 diagonal towards the enemy king. }
20. Kxf2 Ng4+
{ One more accuracy.   In contrast, after  20...Bc5+  21.Be3  Ng4+  22.Kg1  White defends. }
21. Kg1
{ Or  21.Bxg4  Qxg2+  22.Ke3  Bxf4+  23.Kxf4  Qf2+  with mate to come. } 21...
Qd4+ 22. Be3 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Rxe3 Bc5
{ Finally Black wins the exchange and transposes to a clearly superior endgame.   There followed  24...Bc5  25.Bxb7  Bxe3+  26.Kh1  Rab8  27.Bf3  Rxb2  and Korchnoi went on to win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "M.Grabarczyk-P.Podlesny  Karvina 1994  Queen’s Gambit Declined"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ A well-known inaccuracy that leaves the centre in White's hands. If Black is aiming for the Queen's Gambit Declined, he should play  2...e6  first. }
3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. e4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ This leads to a rather cramped game.   After  5...e5  6.Nf3  exd4  7.Qxd4  Qxd4  8.Nxd4  Bb4  9.f3  White has also had good results in practice, but Black enjoys more activity than with the text. Anyway, by playing 4.Nf3 first White could have sidestepped that line. }
6. Nf3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O a6
{ Unfortunately for Black,  8...c5  runs into  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.e5  Nd5  11.Bxh7+  Kxh7  12.Ng5+  with the Greek gift working perfectly.   The text prepares ...b7-b5, but the modest  8...b6  , followed by ...Bb7, was probably more to the point, speeding up development and exerting some pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
9. Qe2 Nbd7 10. Rd1
{ Such a set-up is often used in similar positions in the Queen's Gambit Accepted. On e2 the queen avoids exposure to the black pieces and enables the attacking idea e4-e5, followed by Qe4, while the rook on d1 discourages Black's ...c7-c5. }
10... c6
{ Again very passive; but the desired  10...b5  ran into  11.e5  Nd5  12.Qe4  f5  13.exf6  N7xf6  14.Qh4  with a huge edge. }
11. Bg5 Re8 12. Rac1 h6 13. Bh4 Nf8
{ Time for White to convert his central control into something more tangible. }
14. e5
{ A typical idea. In exchange for weakening the d5-square, Grabarczyk manages to swap Black's 'good' bishop, something that will yield him a grip on the dark squares and, indirectly, attacking prospects on the kingside. }
14... Nd5 15. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ Or  15...Nxc3  16.Rxc3  Qxe7  17.Nd2  with similar play. } 16. Ne4 Nf4
{ This exchange doesn't help Black's case in any way, but it was already difficult to give him good advice. }
17. Qe3 Nxd3 18. Rxd3 Rd8 19. Nfd2
{ White doesn't even want to allow  19.Nd6  Rxd6  20.exd6  Qxd6  , so directs the other knight to  d6  as well. }
19... Ng6 20. Nc4 Qc7 21. Ncd6
{ In strategic terms, the game is already over - Black will never be able to get rid of that knight, which deprives him of any counterplay and makes White's kingside attack child's play. }
21... Ne7 22. Qf4 Nd5 23. Qg4 Qe7 24. Rf3 Rf8 25. Nf6+
{ Enhancing the attack and eliminating any attempts at ...f7-f5. } 25... Kh8
26. Qh5 Rb8 27. Re1 { The last piece joins the party with devastating effect. }
27... Bd7 28. Re4 Nxf6 29. Rxf6 Kh7 30. Rh4 Qxf6 31. exf6 Rh8 32. Qxf7 *

