[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "L.Polugaevsky-J.Dorfman  USSR Championship, Tbilisi 1978  Grünfeld Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 g6
{ This leads to an inferior version of the Grünfeld.  3...c6  ,  3...e6  , and  3...dxc4  are normal continuations. }
4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4
{ White sets up the pawn centre, and forces Black to spend a tempo on withdrawing his knight, in similar fashion to the previous game. Note that this doesn't happen in the mainstream Grünfeld arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4  , where Black has  5...Nxc3  at his disposal. }
5... Nb6 6. h3
{ A simple measure of restriction directed at 6...Bg4, which would leave the d4-pawn somewhat exposed. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 Be6
{ After White's annoying sixth move, Dorfman decides to get rid of his problem bishop via c4.   The drawback to Black's idea is that it doesn't put any pressure on the enemy centre, something that he could have achieved by  8...Nc6  9.Be3  f5  Probably White is a bit better after  10.exf5  Bxf5  11.Qb3+  Kh8  12.Rd1  , but Black has much more counterplay than in the game. }
9. O-O Bc4 10. Bxc4 Nxc4 11. Qe2
{ Development with tempo. From e2 the queen supports the e4-pawn and cedes d1 to the rooks. }
11... Nb6 12. Rd1 N8d7 13. Bg5 { The most active square for the bishop. } 13...
c6 { 13...h6  14.Bh4  doesn't help Black too much. } 14. a4
{ By the threat a4-a5 White tries to provoke the weakening 14...a5.   There was nothing wrong with  14.Rac1  , but Polugaevsky's move is stronger. }
14... Qe8
{ This lets White effect a strong advance in the centre.   14...a5  was a lesser evil; e.g.  15.d5  cxd5  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.Rxd5  Qe8  18.Rb5  b6  with better defensive chances than in the game. }
15. a5 Nc8 16. d5
{ Just at the right moment; when  16.d5  cxd5  17.Nxd5  creates the annoying threat of 18. Nc7. }
16... a6
{ Practically the only move, in order to prevent 17. a6 demolishing the black queenside. }
17. e5
{ In strategic terms, White is already winning - the centre is totally in his control, while Black's pieces are getting short of space. }
17... h6 18. Bh4 e6
{ This leads to a powerful passed pawn on d6, but it was difficult to see any other liberating attempt. }
19. d6 g5 20. Bg3 f5 21. exf6 Rxf6 22. Ra4
{ A nice way of integrating the rook into the coming kingside attack. } 22...
Na7 23. h4 gxh4 24. Rxh4 Nb5 25. Be5
{ Black is forced to swap one of two important pieces - either the blocker of the passed pawn or the main defender of his king. }
25... Rg6
{ After  25...Nxe5  26.Nxe5  , followed by d6-d7, the passed pawn will be decisive. }
26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Ne5
{ The clouds are starting to gather around the black king. } 27... Nxc3 28.
bxc3 Rg5
{ In the event of  28...Nxe5  29.Qxe5+  Kh7  White wins by  30.d7  Qe7  31.Rb4  . }
29. f4 Rf5 30. Qg4+ Kh7 31. Qh3 Rf6 32. Ng4
{ Polugaevsky finally converts his positional advantage into material gains. }
32... Qf8
{ An early surrender; but after  32...Rg6  33.Nxh6  Kg7  34.f5  Black is also helpless. }
33. Nxf6+ Qxf6 34. Re1 Nf8 35. Re5 Kg7 36. Reh5 *

