[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "Zsu.Polgar-U.Bönsch  Dortmund 1990  Queen’s Gambit Declined "]
[Result "*"]

{ The next three games show a more concerned approach from the side playing against the pawn centre. Even so, its possessor triumphs in the end, after effecting a central advance to support the attack on the enemy king. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5
{ By transposition we have reached an initial position of the Queen's Gambit Declined. With her next move Polgar initiates the venomous Exchange Variation with Nge2, which was popularized by Botvinnik in the middle of the 20th century. }
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Qc2 Bg4
{ Black prepares the exchange of his 'bad' bishop, but also wastes time.   The main line goes  7...O-O  8.Bd3  Nbd7  9.Nge2  Re8  10.O-O  Nf8  , when White usually continues  11.f3  , preparing an opportune e3-e4, just as in the game. }
8. Nge2 Bxe2 9. Bxe2 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bd3 Re8 12. f3
{ White prevents the simplifying ...Ne4 and prepares e3-e4, setting up a pawn centre. This is the reason why the king's knight is deployed at e2 instead of f3 in this system. }
12... Nf8
{ 12...c5  was dubious due to  13.dxc5  Nxc5  14.Bb5  , followed by Rad1, with pressure on the weak d5-pawn. }
13. Bh4
{ Black's last move enabled another simplifier with ...Nh5, which can now be met by Bf2. }
13... a6
{ Seeing that  13...c5  runs into the annoying  14.Bb5  , Black prepares it. }
14. Rad1
{ A 'mysterious' rook move that gives extra support to the d4-pawn and discourages Black from ...c6-c5;   e.g.  14.Rad1  c5  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.dxc5  Rxe3  17.Nxd5  , winning a pawn. }
14... Ng6 15. Bf2 Bd6
{ Again the counterstrike  15...c5  is tactically flawed, this time due to  16.Bxg6  hxg6  17.dxc5  Bxc5  18.Nxd5  - Polgar. }
16. e4
{ White finally pursues her plan of creating a pawn centre. In contrast to the previous two games, here she also achieves a semi-open f-file, which will come handy in a future attack on the black king. }
16... dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 18. e5 Bc7
{ Unfortunately for Black, after  18...Nxf2  19.Qxf2  the f7-pawn falls. } 19.
Bc4
{ Increasing the pressure on f7. At this point Black is probably missing his 'bad' bishop, which would have been doing a good defensive job at e6. }
19... Re7 20. Kh1 Nxf2+ { Reacting to White's intention of Bg1 and h2-h3. } 21.
Qxf2 Qd7 22. Ne4
{ The knight is heading for g5 or c5, increasing the pressure on Black's camp. By now White's central control is remarkable - practically all the four central squares are dominated by her, a fact that facilitates her kingside attack to great extent. }
22... Rf8 23. Qf3
{ Seeing that the f7-pawn is rather well-protected, Polgar switches her focus to the one on h7. }
23... Qe8 24. Qh5 Kh8
{ In view of the line  24...h6  25.Qxg6  , Bönsch unpins the f-pawn. } 25. Rd3
{ Keeping up the attack.   After  25.Ng5  h6  26.Nxf7+  Rexf7  27.Rxf7  Rxf7  28.Qxg6  Rf8  Black could pin some hopes on the opposite-coloured bishops. }
25... h6
{ Or  25...f5  26.Rh3  h6  27.Nf6  with the mortal threat of 28 Qxh6+ - Polgar. }
26. Rdf3 Nxe5 { Desperation, but the threat 27. Qxg6 was irresistible. } 27.
dxe5 Rxe5 28. Rxf7 Rxf7 29. Qxf7
{ In view of  29.Qxf7  Qxf7   @@StartBracket@@or  29...Rxe4  30.Qf8+  with similar consequences@@EndBracket@@  30.Rxf7  Rxe4  31.Rf8+  Kh7  32.Bd3  , Black resigned. }
*

