[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "W.Browne-E.Martz  Philadelphia 1980  Grünfeld Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3
{ One of the starting positions of the Exchange Grünfeld has been reached. White enjoys a pawn centre, whereas Black is ready to undermine it by ...c7-c5, ...Nc6 etc, exploiting the strong bishop on g7. Interestingly, at the time of its invention in the 1920s, the Grünfeld was regarded with suspicion due to the temporary surrender of the central squares. Nowadays, in contrast, it is definitely one of the hardest nuts for the 1. d4 players to crack. }
7... O-O
{ These days Black usually plays  7...c5  straight away, one explanation being that after  8.Be2  Nc6  9.Be3  Bg4  White can't safeguard his centre properly.   As a result, the approaches with  8.Rb1  and  8.Be3  are more popular in practice. }
8. Be2 c5 9. O-O b6
{ In contrast to the previous note, after  9...Nc6  10.Be3  cxd4   @@StartBracket@@or  10...Bg4  11.d5  @@EndBracket@@  11.cxd4  Bg4  12.d5  White can still hope for an advantage; e.g.  12...Bxa1  13.Qxa1  Na5  14.Bh6  , recovering the exchange with a promising central grip. }
10. Bg5
{ The most active post for the bishop, where it puts some pressure on the e7-pawn and complicates ...e7-e6. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Bb7 12. Qd3 Qd7
{ Black enables ...e7-e6 again, but the queen will soon have to move again in order to vacate d7 for the knight.   12...Nd7  13.Rad1  Nf6  14.d5  should also be a bit better for White.   So Black should prefer  12...Nc6  13.Rad1   @@StartBracket@@and  13...h6  14.Be3  @@EndBracket@@   Instead, O.Gladyszev-Z.J.Szabo, Gyongyos 1995, took an instructive course:  13...Qd7  14.d5  Ne5  15.Nxe5  Bxe5  16.f4  Bg7  17.Bh4   @@StartBracket@@the immediate  17.e5  allows  17...f6  @@EndBracket@@  17...Rfc8  18.e5  Rc5  19.Bf3  Re8  20.Rfe1  f6  21.exf6  Bxf6  22.Bxf6  exf6  23.Rxe8+  Qxe8  24.d6  Bxf3  25.d7  Qd8  26.Qxf3  a5  27.Qb3+  Kf8  28.Qe6  and Black resigned in view of 29. Re1 next. Quite an impressive march by the white central pawns! }
13. Rad1 e6 14. Qe3
{ Using the central pawns as a shield for his queen, White prepares Bh6, swapping the Grünfeld bishop.   In contrast, the apparently natural  14.d5  runs into  14...Na6  , followed by ...Nc5 with counterplay. }
14... Qa4 15. Bh6 Nd7
{ In the event of  15...Qxa2  one tempting option is  16.h4  , followed by Bxg7 and h5-h6, a plan that Black is now ready to counter by ...Nf6. }
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. d5
{ The key move of the game. White isn't really trying to create a passed pawn, he is rather launching a positional pawn sacrifice, whose benefits will become evident two moves later. }
17... exd5 18. Rd4
{ An important intermediate move.   After  18.e5  Qe4  Black manages to interfere with the enemy attack   While:  18.exd5  Rfe8   -or  18.Qc3+  Nf6  isn't convincing. }
18... Qxa2 19. e5
{ Now we can clearly appreciate Browne's idea. At the cost of one pawn the bishop on b7 has been severely restricted, a great blockading square has emerged on d4 for White's pieces, and the black kingside has become exposed. By the way, a similar pawn sacrifice also appears in the Benoni  @@StartBracket@@ e4-e5, ...d6xe5, f4-f5 @@EndBracket@@ , and by Black in the King's Indian  @@StartBracket@@ ...e5-e4, f3xe4, ...f5-f4 @@EndBracket@@ . }
19... Rae8
{ After  19...h6  20.Rh4  Rh8  21.e6  Rae8  22.Nd4  White also enjoys a strong initiative. }
20. Rh4 Rh8
{ On  20...h5  there follows  21.Rxh5  gxh5  22.Qg5+  Kh8  23.Qxh5+  Kg7  24.Qg5+  Kh8  25.Bd3  f5  26.Bxf5  with a decisive attack. }
21. Bb5 { The check on h6 can wait until the optimum moment. } 21... Re7 22. e6
Nf6
{ Or  22...fxe6  23.Bxd7  Rxd7  24.Qe5+  Kg8  25.Qxe6+  , winning - Browne. }
23. Qh6+ Kg8 24. exf7+ Rxf7 25. Ne5 Qb2
{ Desperation;   but  25...Re7  26.Qg5   @@StartBracket@@or  25...Rg7  26.Qg5  was equally fatal.@@EndBracket@@ }
26. Nxf7 Kxf7 27. Bd3 Re8
{ There was the threat of 28.Bxg6+;   and  27...Ne4  failed to  28.Rxe4  dxe4  29.Bc4+  Ke8  30.Qf4  - Browne. }
28. Rf4 Rf8
{ Ignoring the enemy threat;   though  28...Ke6  29.Re1+   @@StartBracket@@and  28...Kg8  29.Bxg6  were losing as well.@@EndBracket@@ }
29. Qxh7+ *

