[SetUp "1"]

16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. d5
{ The key move of the game. White isn't really trying to create a passed pawn, he is rather launching a positional pawn sacrifice, whose benefits will become evident two moves later. }
17... exd5 18. Rd4
{ An important intermediate move.   After  18.e5  Qe4  Black manages to interfere with the enemy attack   While:  18.exd5  Rfe8   -or  18.Qc3+  Nf6  isn't convincing. }
18... Qxa2 19. e5
{ Now we can clearly appreciate Browne's idea. At the cost of one pawn the bishop on b7 has been severely restricted, a great blockading square has emerged on d4 for White's pieces, and the black kingside has become exposed. By the way, a similar pawn sacrifice also appears in the Benoni  @@StartBracket@@ e4-e5, ...d6xe5, f4-f5 @@EndBracket@@ , and by Black in the King's Indian  @@StartBracket@@ ...e5-e4, f3xe4, ...f5-f4 @@EndBracket@@ . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.1 Pawn Centre"]
[Black "P.Tregubov-P.Van der Sterren  Amsterdam 2000  Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Nh4
{ We shouldn't move our pieces twice in the opening - unless there is a good reason, of course.   Here  6.Nh4  immediately challenges the Slav bishop, one benefit being that after the lazy  6...Bg6  7.Nxg6  hxg6  , he could go  8.e4  in one single move.   Other main options are  6.e3  and  6.Ne5  . }
6... e6
{ Black doesn't care about the doubled pawns and simply continues development. The pawn structure that now arises might seem dubious at first sight, but practice has shown Black's position to be perfectly playable, with the f5-pawn being useful in obstructing White's e2-e4 advance. }
7. Nxf5 exf5 8. e3 Bd6
{ 8...Bb4  is more popular, further complicating the e3-e4 plan; e.g.  9.Bxc4  O-O  10.Qc2  g6  11.O-O  Nbd7  , preparing ...Rc8 and ...c6-c5. }
9. Bxc4 g6
{ A useful move, though not really a priority at this early stage.   Van der Sterren perhaps refrained from the natural  9...O-O  in view of  10.h3  followed by g2-g4, a dangerous plan that has been launched several times in practice. Even so, Black's position is not without resources; e.g.  10...Nbd7  11.g4  Ne4  12.gxf5  Qa5  13.Qc2  Ndf6  14.Bd3  Rfe8  with counterplay in V.Filippov-I.Ibragimov, New York Open 1998. }
10. f3
{ Tregubov immediately starts building a pawn centre, before Black gets in ...O-O and ...Re8. }
10... Qc7
{ A flawed attempt at restricting White's plan.   Again,  10...O-O  was called for; e.g.  11.e4  fxe4  12.fxe4  c5  , immediately striking at the enemy centre. Tregubov indicates the sharp line  13.e5  cxd4  14.exd6   @@StartBracket@@not  14.Qxd4  Bxe5  @@EndBracket@@  dxc3  15.O-O  Qb6+  16.Kh1  cxb2  17.Bh6  Nbd7  18.Rb1  Rfe8  19.Qd2  with a clear advantage. However, by  19...Re4  20.Rxb2  Qd4  Black seems to hold his own. }
11. e4
{ Anyway! White doesn't bother about the h2-pawn and just continues the battle for the centre. }
11... Bxh2
{ After  11...fxe4  12.fxe4  Bxh2  13.e5  Bg3+  14.Kf1  Nh5  15.Qf3  Black has no defence against Rxh5 and Qxg3. }
12. e5 Bg3+ 13. Kf1 Nh5
{ Or  13...Nfd7  14.f4  with the strong threat of 15. Ne2. } 14. Rxh5
{ A second sacrifice, one that will leave Black's kingside structure in ruins and let White establish a strong grip on the centre.  14.Ne2  f4  was less convincing. }
14... gxh5 15. f4 h4
{ In the event of  15...Nd7  , Tregubov indicates  16.Qxh5  O-O-O  17.Ne2  Rhg8  18.Ra3  and White wins. }
16. Qh5 Na6
{ Since  16...Qd7  runs into  17.e6   Or even  17.d5  , Black surrenders the f5-pawn and gives priority to development. }
17. Qxf5 Rd8 18. Be3 Nb4 19. Ne4
{ By now White's central control is really impressive, with the double threat of 20. Nd6+ and 20. Nf6+ spelling the end for Black. }
19... Nd5 20. Bxd5 cxd5 21. Rc1 Qxc1+
{ There is nothing better; e.g.  21...Qe7  22.Nf6+  Kf8  23.Qh5  h6  24.f5  Kg7  25.Qg4+  Kf8  26.Bxh6+   Or  21...Qb6  22.Nd6+  Rxd6  23.exd6  O-O  24.d7  , followed by Rc8 - Tregubov. }
22. Bxc1 dxe4 23. e6
{ The quickest way to victory, opening the gates to the black monarch. } 23...
Rf8 { 23...fxe6  drops a rook after the reply  24.Qxe6+  Kf8  25.Qf6+  . } 24.
Bd2 { In view of the devastating 25. Bb4, Black resigned. } *

