[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "Centre controlled by a piece "]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Another key method when fighting for the centre is the occupation of a central square with a piece, usually a knight. Such a piece can become a real headache for the opponent, as we will see in the following games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "J.Fries Nielsen-J.Hellsten  Copenhagen 1996  Colle’s Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3
{ The Colle, a venomous opening despite its modest appearance, as we already saw in Vera-Romero. }
4... d5 5. O-O Nc6 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Quite a sensible set-up - both bishops enjoy good perspectives and a future knight jump to e5 is enabled. }
8... Qe7
{ Black wants to push ...e6-e5;   but  8...Re8  was a better way of preparing this idea; e.g.  9.Ne5  Qc7  10.f4   @@StartBracket@@or  10.Ndf3  cxd4  11.exd4  Nb4  with similar play@@EndBracket@@  cxd4  11.exd4  Nb4  12.Bb5  Bd7  with a favourable minor piece exchange and approximately even chances. }
9. Ne5
{ White installs the knight on a great post in the centre, exploiting the fact that 9...Nxe5? isn't tactically possible. This method, once popularized by Pillsbury, is frequent in many opening systems, particularly in the queen's pawn openings. On e5 the knight will have a huge impact on the battle, cramping Black's ...e6-e5 advance and supporting a future kingside attack. }
9... Rd8
{ Indifference.   I could have given some justice to my previous move by  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Ba3  , swapping the attacker on  b2  . There can follow  11.Qc1  Bxb2  12.Qxb2  Bd7  13.a3  Rac8  14.f4  Qd8  15.c4  with a distinct initiative for White, J.Nogueiras Santiago-J.Gonzalez Zamora, Cuban Championship, Holguin 1991, but even so Black is better off than in the game. }
10. a3 { Preventing both ...Ba3 and ...Nb4. } 10... Nd7 11. f4
{ Backing up the knight, in good old Pillsbury style.   11.Ndf3  f6  was less promising. }
11... Nf8
{ During the game I thought that things were going well - by ...Nd7-f8 I reinforced the sensitive h7-pawn, and now I would be ready for ...f7-f6, pushing the knight away from e5. Then, by ...e6-e5 I would take control of the centre, with my queen and rook ideally located. But my opponent played with worrying speed and I soon woke up from my illusions.   As for the immediate  11...f6  , after  12.Qh5  g6   @@StartBracket@@  12...Nf8  13.Rf3  leads to the game@@EndBracket@@  13.Nxg6  hxg6  14.Bxg6  Qg7  15.Rf3  White obtains a strong attack. }
12. Qh5 f6 13. Rf3
{ A key decision of the game. Nielsen doesn't move the knight away but just gets on with the attack. }
13... Qe8
{ Vacating the e7-square for the knight or the bishop.   At this moment  13...fxe5  14.fxe5  Bc7  is refuted immediately by  15.Rxf8+  Kxf8  16.Rf1+  with mate. }
14. Qh4 cxd4 15. exd4 h5
{ Eliminating the tactical idea of Rxf8+ and Qxh7, so that the piece on e5 can finally be captured. However, after White's reply Black will just have weakened his kingside.   Had I been a bit more pragmatic, I would have played  15...f5  , surrendering the e5-square but, more importantly, hampering White's attack. There can follow  16.Nxc6  bxc6  17.Re1  with a clear positional advantage, but at least Black has saved his king. }
16. Raf1
{ White ignores the threat at his knight again and brings the last piece to the attack. }
16... fxe5
{ Rather foolhardily, Black accepts the challenge.   Instead,  16...Ne7  was correct, sending the knight to the defence; e.g.  17.g4  hxg4  18.Nxg4  Nfg6  19.Qh5  Nf5  20.Rh3  Qf7  and despite a promising white attack, Black is alive. }
17. fxe5 Be7 18. Qg3 Bd7 19. Rf4
{ Nielsen takes his time, aware that Black can't coordinate his forces properly. The text prepares Nf3-g5  @@StartBracket@@ or Nh4 @@EndBracket@@ , enhancing the attack. }
19... Rdc8 20. Nf3 Qd8 21. Ng5 Qb6
{ Losing at once; though after  21...Bxg5  22.Rxf8+  Qxf8  23.Rxf8+  Rxf8  24.Qxg5  White is also winning. }
22. Rf7 g6 23. Nxe6 { Finally Black's kingside crumbles. } 23... Nxe5
{ Or  23...Bxe6  24.Rxf8+  with mate. } 24. Qxe5 Nxe6 25. Bxg6 Nf4 26. Qg7# *

