[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-R.Akesson  Sweden 1996  Queen’s Indian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ A perfectly playable line; even if  4.g3  and  4.a3  are considered as more critical tests of the Queen's Indian. }
4... Bb7 5. Bd3 d5 6. b3 Bd6
{ Launching a similar set-up to White's in the previous game. } 7. O-O O-O 8.
Nc3 Nbd7 9. Bb2 Ne4 { This time it is Black who applies Pillsbury's method. }
10. Rc1
{ A rather mechanical move.   10.Qc2  was more ambitious, fighting for the e4-square; e.g.  10...Nxc3   @@StartBracket@@or  10...f5  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Nb5  , swapping the dangerous bishop on d6@@EndBracket@@  11.Bxc3  dxc4  12.Bxh7+  avoiding the perpetual after   12.bxc4  Bxf3  13.gxf3  Bxh2+  Kh8  13.Be4  cxb3  14.axb3  with a slight edge, J.Fries Nielsen-J.Stanke, German League 2003. }
10... a6
{ An essential move in Black's set-up, so as to rule out the same Nb5 that we saw in the previous note. }
11. cxd5 exd5 12. Ne2 Qe7 13. Ng3 f5
{ Black reinforces his central knight and at the same time prevents 14. Nf5. With the centre more or less secured, he is now ready for a kingside attack. }
14. Rc2 c6
{ Akesson is well aware of the enemy intentions and takes prophylactic measures. Both   14...Rf6  and 14...g5 would have run into  15.Qa1  followed by Ne5;   e.g.  14...Rf6  15.Qa1  Re8  16.Ne5  , and after multiple captures on  e5  , White snatches the c7-pawn in the end.   As for the impulsive  14...f4  , after  15.exf4  Bxf4  16.Re1  the e-file is opened to White's benefit. }
15. Qe2 a5
{ A useful move that secures the a-pawn and enables the ...a5-a4 pinprick, a fact that explains my next move. }
16. a4 Rf6 { Time to get on with the kingside attack. } 17. Rfc1 Raf8 18. Ba6
Ba8 19. Qd1
{ A useless retreat, which leaves White in a very passive position.   Much better was  19.Nf1  , followed by Ne1 and f2-f3, with chances for a successful defence. }
19... Rh6 20. Nf1 g5
{ With such a firm grip on the centre, nothing speaks against a full-scale advance on the kingside.   Less precise was  20...Ndf6  21.Ne5  with some interference. }
21. g3 f4 22. exf4 gxf4 23. Be2 Ndf6
{ Finally Black permits Ne5, when he has created sufficient threats on the kingside.   Otherwise,  23...fxg3  24.fxg3  Qg7  25.Bd3  Rhf6  also looked strong. }
24. Ne5 Nxf2
{ The position was begging for this sacrifice, which opens the gates to the white king. }
25. Kxf2 fxg3+ 26. hxg3
{ After  26.Kg1  gxh2+  27.Nxh2  Bxe5  28.dxe5  Rg6+  29.Kh1  Ne4  Black's attack is also irresistible. }
26... Ne4+ 27. Kg1
{ In heavy time-trouble I just chose the most obvious retreat; but  27.Kg2  was worth considering, since  27...Rf2+   @@StartBracket@@Black should rather continue  27...Bxe5  28.dxe5  c5  29.Bf3  Qd7  with strong pressure; e.g.  30.Bg4  d4  31.Bxd7  Nd2+  , regaining the queen with heavy interest@@EndBracket@@  28.Kg1  actually helps White more than Black. }
27... Bxe5 28. dxe5 Nf2
{ With the simple plan of ...c6-c5 and ...d5-d4, including the last piece in the assault. }
29. Qd2 Qe6
{ 29...Qe6  defends the rook and creates the threat of  30.--  Rh1+   @@StartBracket@@or simply  30...Qh3  @@EndBracket@@  31.Kg2  Qh3  at the same time. }
30. Qg5+ Kh8
{ Since  30...Kh8  31.Bf3  saves the king but not the queen, White resigned. }
