[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-C.Vizama  Linares, Chile 2003  Slav Defence "]
[Result "*"]

{ It is no wonder that after such painful defeats, I became interested in applying the same idea myself. Here is one example. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3
{ In comparison with the more common  4.Nf3  , White rules out  4...dxc4  at this early stage, at the cost of restricting his bishop on  c1  . }
4... Bf5
{ A natural move in the Slav, but slightly inappropriate on this occasion, which White will show with his next two moves.   More usual are  4...e6  4...a6  and  4...g6  . }
5. cxd5 { In contrast,  5.Qb3  at once was less accurate due to  5...Qb6  . }
5... cxd5 6. Qb3
{ A typical idea in this opening - after the bishop's departure from c8, White hurries to attack the vulnerable b7-pawn. }
6... Bc8
{ The least of evils; now that  6...Qb6  runs into  7.Nxd5  Nxd5  8.Qxd5  Qb4+  9.Bd2  Qxb2  10.Rc1  with a clear advantage   While  6...b6  drops a pawn after  7.Bb5+  and 8. Nxd5. }
7. f4
{ An interesting way of seizing the centre - the ensuing weakness on e4 hardly makes itself felt here.   Otherwise, White could consider the simple  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.Bd3  e6  9.O-O  , followed by Bd2, Rfc1 and Qd1, or even e3-e4!?, transposing to an IQP structure. }
7... e6 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Bd3 a6 10. O-O Bd7
{ After  10...Be7  11.Ne5  O-O  12.Bd2  Nxe5  13.fxe5  Nd7  14.e4  White also keeps the initiative. }
11. Ne5
{ By now this idea is well familiar to us.   Incidentally,  11.Qxb7  Na5  obviously had to be avoided. }
11... b5 12. Qd1 Bd6
{ 12...Be7  was better, enabling a future ...Nxe5. Admittedly the other knight could no longer retreat to d7 as in the note with 10...Be7 above, but in the game Black will suffer worse problems. }
13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Be1
{ Such a bishop transfer is well known from the Stonewall Dutch. } 14... h5
{ A pseudo-active move, which just makes it more difficult for Black to castle.   It was not yet too late for  14...Be7  , admitting the mistake on move  12. }
15. Bh4 Be7 16. Rc1
{ The fact that Black can't connect his rooks will play heavily against him in the dispute for the open c-file. }
16... g6 { Or  16...Rc8  17.Qf3  Qb8  18.Qg3  intending  18...g6  19.Nxf7  . }
17. Qf3 Ng4
{ This counterstrike won't work out well; though after  17...Rc8  18.Qg3  Rg8  19.a3  with the simple plan of Rc2 and Rfc1, Black is also in trouble. }
18. Nxd7
{ The proud knight finally leaves the board in order to keep Black's king in the centre, thus enhancing the following sacrifice. }
18... Kxd7 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Qxd5+
{ Black's position falls apart completely and the rest is relatively easy. }
20... Bd6 21. Qxf7+ Ne7 22. f5 Rhf8
{ Or  22...Bxh2+  23.Kh1  Rae8  24.fxg6  with irresistible threats. } 23. Qe6+
Ke8 24. Kh1
{ Prophylaxis in the attack. Now both 25. Bxe7 and 25. f6 are threatened, neither of which worked at this moment due to 24...Bxh2+. }
24... Qd8 25. f6 Nxf6 26. Bxg6+ *

