[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "L.Van Wely-S.Karjakin  Spanish Team  Championship 2005  Slav Defence "]
[Result "*"]

{ From the previous three games, one could get the impression that once a knight is installed on e5 or e4, the other player is doomed to defeat. Of course this is not the case, and here is an example on how to fight against a 'Pillsbury' knight. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 a6
{ The Chebanenko system, which we already saw in Miton-Sammour. } 5. a4
{ One of the most critical replies, ruling out any attempt at ...b7-b5, at the cost of slightly weakening the b4-square. }
5... e6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Qc2
{ White could also play  7.e3  at once, though the text tends to be a useful move in such positions. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 Qa5
{ An ambitious choice in the spirit of the Cambridge Springs variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Bg5  Nbd7  6.e3  Qa5  etc @@EndBracket@@ .   The simple  8...Be7  was possible as well; e.g.  9.e3  O-O  10.a5  c5  11.dxc5  Nxc5  12.cxd5  Nxd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Be2  Bg4  16.O-O  Rac8  with counterplay in L.Van Wely-V.Ivanchuk, Monte Carlo  @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@  2006. }
9. e3 Ne4
{ Karjakin hurries to install a knight on e4 at the cost of delaying development.   9...Bb4  , followed by ...O-O, was a safer choice. }
10. Bd3 f5
{ Reinforcing the knight in Pillsbury style.   Less appealing is  10...Bb4  11.Bxe4  dxe4  12.Nd2  f5  13.c5  followed by Nc4, when Black faces severe problems on the dark squares. }
11. O-O Bd6
{ At first sight Black's position seems rather promising. He just needs a few tempi to get castled and activate his queenside pieces, after which his central grip would motivate a kingside attack, just as in the previous games. However, Van Wely has a strong antidote prepared. }
12. c5
{ Before taking charge of the knight on e4, Van Wely fixes the queenside pawn structure, in order to rule out a possible ...c6-c5 break, and enables a future Nd2-c4 manoeuvre.   In effect, after  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.Nd2  c5  Black wouldn't have anything to complain about. }
12... Bb8 13. Bxe4
{ Swapping the least active minor piece for the strong enemy knight. } 13...
fxe4
{ By now,  13...dxe4  14.Nd2  , followed by Nc4 and Bg3, would yield White a clear grip on the dark squares. }
14. Nd2 O-O 15. f3
{ A key move to break the enemy pawn chain and clear the f-file before Black's queenside pieces join the battle. }
15... exf3 16. Nxf3 Rf7
{ Preparing ...Nf8 to reinforce the kingside defence.   In contrast, the active  16...e5  permits  17.Qg6  exd4   @@StartBracket@@or  17...e4  18.Nd2  with the strong threat 19.Be7@@EndBracket@@  18.exd4  Nf6  19.Rae1  with a colossal lead in development. }
17. Rf2
{ The most logical choice, in order to include the queen's rook in the battle. }
17... Nf8
{ This time  17...e5  is strongly met by  18.Raf1  e4  19.Nxe4  dxe4  20.Qb3  ; e.g.  20...Nf6  21.Bxf6  gxf6  22.Ng5  hxg5  23.Rxf6  and White wins. }
18. b4
{ Exploiting the tactical twist  18.b4  Qxb4  19.a5  , followed by Ra4, Van Wely lures the black queen to c7, thus enabling Ne5 on the next move.   The simple  18.Raf1  Bd7  19.Bg3  preparing Ne5 after the exchange of bishops, looked strong too. }
18... Qc7 19. Ne5 Rxf2 20. Qxf2 g5
{ Practically the only move, so as to get some breathing space. } 21. Bg3 Qg7
22. Rf1
{ The triumph of White's strategy. The knight on e5 is a giant, and Black can hardly save his king with the rook and queen's bishop still out of play. }
22... Bc7
{ Seeing that  22...Bd7  runs into  23.Qxf8+  Karjakin prepares the bishop move. }
23. Ng4 { Hitting the vulnerable dark squares on f6 and h6. } 23... e5
{ This loses outright, though Black was short of a defence anyway; e.g.  23...Bxg3  24.Qxg3  Bd7  25.Nf6+  Kh8  26.Nh5  , followed by  26...--  27.Qe5+  . }
24. Nf6+
{ In view of the material losses after  24.Nf6+  Kh8  25.Ne8  , Black resigned. }
*

