[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "K.Haznedaroglu-M.Gurevich  Izmir 2002  Pirc Defence"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now let's see some examples of other central squares being subject to the same idea. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3
{ These days, the Austrian Attack,  4.f4  and the flexible  4.Be3  are probably more demanding lines for Black. }
4... Nf6 5. Be2 { A quiet approach against the Pirc. } 5... O-O 6. O-O Bg4
{ Black surrenders the bishop pair in order to start working on the dark squares, in particular d4.   He has many other options here, such as  6...c6  , preparing ...Nbd7 and ...e7-e5. }
7. h3
{ Another direction is  7.Be3  Nc6  8.d5  Bxf3  9.Bxf3  Ne5  10.Be2  c6  11.f4  Ned7  with a complex strategical battle. }
7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nc6 9. Be3
{ Considering the dark square problems faced by White later on,  9.Ne2  e5  10.c3  might be a more promising approach, safeguarding the d4-pawn.   He could also contemplate  9.Bg5  in order to provoke ...h7-h6, so that a later Qd2 gains a tempo by attacking h6. }
9... Re8
{ An odd move at first sight;   why doesn't Black just play  9...e5  straight away; e.g.  10.d5  Ne7  , followed by ...Nd7 and ...f7-f5 -  ? Well, Gurevich has quite a different idea in mind, one that will become evident on the next move. }
10. Qd2
{ On moves like 10.Re1 or 10.Ne2 Black could react in similar fashion; e.g.  10.Ne2  e5  11.d5  Nd4  12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Qxd4   @@StartBracket@@or  13.Bxd4  Nxe4  14.Re1  Ng5  @@EndBracket@@  13...Ng4  14.Qd2  Nxe3  15.Qxe3  Bxb2  16.Rab1  Qf6  17.Qb3  Be5  18.Qxb7  Qf4  with clear compensation for the pawn, N.Guliev-M.Gurevich, French Team Championship 2004. }
10... e5 11. d5 Nd4 { By now Black's strategy is easily appreciated. } 12. Bd1
{ The knight on d4 is very annoying for the opponent, and removing it by  12.Bxd4  exd4  13.Qxd4  fails to  13...Nxe4  , crediting the prophylactic 9...Re8. }
12... c6
{ Such a knight supports action on the whole board, and here Gurevich has estimated that the queenside is his best battlefield. }
13. dxc6
{ The active  13.f4  runs into  13...cxd5  14.exd5  Nf5  , followed by ...e5-e4 or ...Bh6, with strong pressure on the dark squares. }
13... bxc6 14. Be2
{ But here,  14.f4  , followed by Qf2, seems like a better shot, creating some counterplay on the f-file. The text prepares the bishop transfer Bc4-b3 but, as we will see next, it won't work tactically. }
14... Rb8 15. Bc4 { 15.Rab1  was a lesser evil, keeping the material balance. }
15... d5
{ Black sets up a pawn centre, exploiting the fact that  15...d5  16.Bb3  now fails to  16...Nxb3  17.axb3  d4  .   In contrast,  15...Rxb2  16.Bb3  would make things unnecessarily complicated. }
16. Bd3 Ne6
{ Probably there was nothing wrong with  16...Rxb2  , but the text has the merit of installing the additional threat 17...d4. }
17. Nd1 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Qxd8 Rexd8 20. Bxa7
{ Despite the material balance, White is seriously worse in this endgame due to Black's active pieces and central control. }
20... Rb7 21. Be3 f5 22. b3 Nd4
{ The knight returns to its preferred position, increasing the pressure on White's camp. In the same spirit,  22...f4  23.Bc1  Nd4  was interesting too. }
23. Bxd4
{ This just helps Black in creating a passed pawn; though after  23.c3  Ne2+  24.Kh1  Ra8  White is suffering anyway. }
23... exd4 24. Rb1 Ra8 25. Rb2 c5
{ One more pawn starts rolling, while White remains badly coordinated. } 26. c3
Rba7 27. cxd4 Bxd4
{ There was nothing wrong with  27...cxd4  , but Gurevich prefers to take a pawn. }
28. Rb1 Rxa2 29. Ne3 Re2
{ In view of the double threat of 30...Bxe3 and 30...Raa2, White resigned. } *

