[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "Y.Nikolaevsky-V.Mikhalevski  Kiev 1995  English Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 { Black responds to the English in Grünfeld style. } 3.
cxd5 Nxd5 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Nb6 6. d3
{ Another option was  6.d4  Bg7  7.Nf3  , transposing to the Fianchetto variation of the Grünfeld. }
6... Bg7 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ A typical English structure has emerged, similar to the Sicilian Dragon with reversed colours. White has an extra pawn in the centre and also possesses a semi-open c-file. On the other hand, Black enjoys more space and easy development. }
8. Bd2
{ White prepares Qc1 and Bh6 in order to exchange the bishop on g7, aware that the absence of pawns on the central squares makes both fianchettoed bishops rather valuable.   If Black tries to prevent this by  8.Bd2  h6  , then after  9.Qc1  he can't easily castle, which is why Mikhalevski prefers just to continue development. }
8... O-O 9. Qc1 Rb8
{ An interesting piece of prophylaxis. Black overprotects the b7-pawn, so that his knight can move away from c6 later on.   In contrast, after  9...Re8  10.Bh6  Bh8  11.h4  followed by 12. h5, White develops an initiative on the kingside. }
10. Bh6 Bg4 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. h3
{ Perhaps Nikolaevsky wanted to avoid  12.O-O  Qd7  , followed by ...Bh3, but the text just accelerates Black's plan. }
12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nd4
{ Thanks to the  9...Rb8  move, Black can centralize his knight straight away. From now on, whenever White plays e2-e3, he will be left with a slight weakness on d3. }
14. Bg2 e5
{ Just in time, before White achieves an ideal pawn structure by 15. e3 and 16. d4. }
15. O-O Qe7 16. Kh2
{ This and White's following moves are rather passive.   16.e3  Ne6  17.Qc2  seems preferable, intending Rb1 and b2-b4 with some queenside play. The slight weakness on d3 can be lived with. }
16... c6 17. Qd2 Rbd8 18. Rac1
{ Again White refrains from e2-e3 and Qc2, preferring a rather cryptic rook move. By now he even has to watch out for ...Nc4. }
18... f5
{ With the centre more or less controlled, Mikhalevski starts active operations on the kingside.   Less useful was  18...Nc4  19.Qe1  , when  19...Nxb2  20.Rb1  Qa3  21.Qc1  leaves the knight trapped. }
19. f4
{ A serious oversight that lets Black establish a firm grip on the dark squares by tactical means.   19.e3  no longer worked due to  19...Nc4  20.Qe1  Nxb2  21.exd4  Nxd3  22.Qe3  Nxc1  23.Rxc1  Rxd4  - Ribli   So  19.b3  was more cautious and only then 20. e3. Perhaps Black could react by  19...h5  intending ...h5-h4; e.g.  20.h4  e4  21.Qe3  f4  22.Qxe4  Qd6  with attacking prospects. }
19... Nc4
{ Exploiting the tactical twist  19...Nc4  20.dxc4  Nf3+  , Black sends his knight to a great destiny on e3. }
20. Qe1 Ne3 21. Rf2 exf4 22. gxf4
{ Or if  22.Rxf4  , Black replies  22...g5  23.Rf2  Qe5  intending ...h5-h4 with a strong attack - Ribli. }
22... Qh4
{ With the centre completely in his hands, Black intensifies his attack and now threatens 23...Ng4+. }
23. Kh1 Rfe8
{ With  23...Rfe8  the last piece joins the battle, creating the unpleasant threat of  24.--  Nxg2  25.Kxg2  Re3  . }
24. Rf1 Qh6 25. Qg3
{ White offers the exchange in order to relieve his defence, but Mikhalevski just ignores it and keeps on attacking. }
25... Nxg2 26. Qxg2 Re3 27. Kh2 Ne6
{ The concrete idea behind 25... Nxg2 - the f4-pawn now falls. } 28. Rf3 Nxf4
29. Qg3
{ At the same time White resigned, without waiting for the reply  29.Qg3  Rxf3  30.Qxf3  Nxh3  , discovering an attack on the rook on c1. }
