[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "R.Slobodjan-V.Epishin  German Team Cup 2002  Sicilian Defence, Closed Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3
{ Obviously Black also had to be ready for  3.Nf3  and 4.d4, transposing to the Open Sicilian. }
3... d5 { A solid reply to the Closed Sicilian. } 4. d3 Be7
{ By bringing out the bishop first, Black avoids  4...Nf6  5.e5 } 5. Bg2 dxe4
{ The simplest. } 6. dxe4
{ Now  6.Nxe4  Nf6  leaves White without any trace of an advantage, but neither does the queenless middlegame that arises after the text, so he should probably have preferred e4xd5, followed by Bg2, either on the fourth or fifth move. }
6... Qxd1+ 7. Nxd1 Bd7
{ Heading for c6 to neutralize the bishop on g2 and put some initial pressure on the e4-pawn. }
8. Ne3 Bc6 9. Ne2 Nd7 10. Bd2 Ngf6 11. f3 O-O 12. Nc4
{ With the dual intention of 13. Na5 and 13. e5.   Slower moves like  12.Kf2  permit  12...b5  gaining space and taking the c4-square from White's pieces. Actually Black could already have considered  11...b5  on the previous move. }
12... Bb5
{ Immediately preventing both enemy ideas.   12...b5  13.Na5   Or  12...b6  13.e5  Nd5  14.f4  was less promising - Bangiev. }
13. Na3 Bc6 14. Nc4 Bb5 15. Ne3 Bc6
{ At this point White could have taken a three-fold repetition by 16. Nc4, but he decides to play for a win.   Black, on his part, could have avoided the repetition by  15...Rfd8  at this moment, or by 13... Ba6 earlier on. }
16. a4 Rfd8 { Black is finally ready to start fighting for the open file. } 17.
Nc3
{ The immediate  17.Nc4  would have run into  17...Bxa4  18.Rxa4  b5  - Bangiev, so White prepares it. }
17... Ne5
{ The key move of this game, by which Black seizes the centre and, at the same time, prevents 18. Nc4. }
18. Ke2
{ As the remainder of the game will show us, White shouldn't have let the knight stay on e5.   Preferable was  18.f4  Neg4  19.Nxg4  Nxg4  20.h3  Nf6  21.Rh2  preparing e4-e5; e.g.  21...c4  22.e5  Nd5  23.Nxd5  Bxd5  24.Be3  with just a slight disadvantage. When you are defending, a key task is to choose between different inferiorities, find the least of evils, so to speak. In the position after 24. Be3 White has slightly exposed his pawn structure and his dark-squared bishop might not be such a great piece, whereas in the game he will face more serious problems. }
18... g5
{ A strong move that reinforces the central knight and enables a future pinprick by ...g5-g4. }
19. Rhd1
{ Now if  19.f4  , then  19...gxf4  20.gxf4  Ng6  , with the knight eyeing both f4 and h4. }
19... Rd4 { One more central field is occupied by the black forces. } 20. b3
{ Unfortunately for White, the desirable  20.Nb5  fails to  20...Rxa4  so he prepares it, though his idea is easily prevented by Black's next move. }
20... a6 21. Be1 h5 22. Nf1 g4
{ A timely undermining of the e4-pawn, before White pushes away the rook by 22. Bf2. }
23. fxg4
{ Or  23.f4  Nf3  24.Bxf3  gxf3+  25.Kxf3  Nxe4  with a clear advantage - Bangiev. }
23... hxg4
{ A triumph of Black's strategy - the powerful knight on e5 can no longer be expelled, and the e4-pawn has become a long-term weakness. }
24. Nd2
{ After  24.Bf2  Rxd1  25.Rxd1  b5  with the threat 26...b4, Black keeps his grip. }
24... Kg7
{ Epishin now directs his attention to the h2-pawn and will even be ready to give up the exchange for it. }
25. Bf2 Rh8 26. Bg1
{ After  26.Bxd4  cxd4  27.Na2  Rxh2  28.Kf1  Rh6  followed by ...Nh5, White is in deep trouble;   but not  28...Nh5  29.Kg1  . }
26... Rh5
{ The tempting  26...b5  allows  27.axb5  axb5  28.Ra7  with some counterplay, so Epishin first makes a useful move safeguarding the fifth rank. }
27. Nf1
{ If  27.a5  , preventing ...b7-b5, then  27...Rd8  , preparing ...c5-c4 and ...Bb4, looks interesting for Black. }
27... Rxd1 28. Rxd1 b5
{ Right on time. Now White again has to take care of the e4-pawn, considering the threat of ... b5-b4. }
29. axb5 axb5 30. Nd2 b4 31. Ncb1 Nfd7
{ Preparing ...f7-f5, with a final stroke against the e4-pawn. } 32. Kf2 f5 33.
Re1
{ Since  33.exf5  drops a piece after  33...Rxf5+  , White is doomed to passivity. }
33... Nf6 34. Ke3 Kf7
{ This is not the only winning option, but the most elegant, preparing ...Bf8-h6+. }
35. Rf1 Bf8 36. Rd1 fxe4 37. Nc4
{ 37.Nc4  Bh6+  38.Ke2  Nxc4  39.bxc4  Ba4  is just one possible winning path. As for the knight on e5, it never actually moved again after getting there. Still, its presence in the battle was quite strongly felt. }
*

