[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "Exercise #2: R.Slobodjan-V.Epishin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2r2k1/pp1nbppp/2b1pn2/2p5/P3P3/2N1NPP1/1PPB2BP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17... Ne5
{ The key move of this game, by which Black seizes the centre and, at the same time, prevents 18. Nc4. }
18. Ke2
{ As the remainder of the game will show us, White shouldn't have let the knight stay on e5.   Preferable was  18.f4  Neg4  19.Nxg4  Nxg4  20.h3  Nf6  21.Rh2  preparing e4-e5; e.g.  21...c4  22.e5  Nd5  23.Nxd5  Bxd5  24.Be3  with just a slight disadvantage. When you are defending, a key task is to choose between different inferiorities, find the least of evils, so to speak. In the position after 24. Be3 White has slightly exposed his pawn structure and his dark-squared bishop might not be such a great piece, whereas in the game he will face more serious problems. }
18... g5
{ A strong move that reinforces the central knight and enables a future pinprick by ...g5-g4. }
19. Rhd1
{ Now if  19.f4  , then  19...gxf4  20.gxf4  Ng6  , with the knight eyeing both f4 and h4. }
19... Rd4 { One more central field is occupied by the black forces. } 20. b3
{ Unfortunately for White, the desirable  20.Nb5  fails to  20...Rxa4  so he prepares it, though his idea is easily prevented by Black's next move. }
20... a6 21. Be1 h5 22. Nf1 g4
{ A timely undermining of the e4-pawn, before White pushes away the rook by 22. Bf2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2 Centre Controlled by a Piece"]
[Black "Joe.Benjamin-A.Wagener  US Championship, Seattle 2002  Sicilian Defence,  Rossolimo Variation "]
[Result "*"]

{ When we talk about seizing the centre with a piece, we usually refer to knights. The following game will show us that, occasionally, the job can be carried out by bishops too. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6
{ A popular reply to the Rossolimo, by which Black prepares ...Nge7 and ...a7-a6 in similar fashion to White's play in some lines of the Rubinstein Nimzo-Indian @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.e3  @@EndBracket@@ }
4. O-O Nge7 5. Re1
{ Reinforcing the e4-pawn and providing a shelter for the bishop on f1.   Another direction  5.c3  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  , followed by an opportune d2-d4. }
5... a6 6. Bf1 d5
{ Black immediately strikes at the centre, before White achieves the standard plan of c2-c3 and d2-d4, building a pawn centre. }
7. exd5 Qxd5
{ After  7...exd5  8.d4  Black has a problem with her development   But  7...Nxd5  was fully possible; e.g.  8.d4  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@replying to c2-c4 in advance@@EndBracket@@  9.Be3  Be7  10.c4  O-O  11.Nc3  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Bd7  with roughly equal play, L.Totsky-V.Golod, Cappelle la Grande 2007. }
8. Bd3
{ Quite an unnatural move, but rather strong. White aims to install the bishop on e4, where it can't be easily chased away by the black knights.   Less promising was  8.Nc3  Qd8  , followed by ...Nf5, ...Be7 and ...0-0. }
8... Ng6
{ 8...Nf5  drops a piece after  9.Be4   But  8...g6  was another way of resolving the kingside development. M.Ulibin-A.Galliamova, Russian Team Championship 1996, continued in curious fashion:  9.b4  cxb4   @@StartBracket@@or  9...Bg7  10.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@  10.Bb2  Rg8  11.a3  Bg7   @@StartBracket@@or  11...bxa3  12.Nxa3  heading for c4@@EndBracket@@  12.Bxg7  Rxg7  13.axb4  Nxb4  14.Be4  Qd6  15.d4  with interesting compensation for the pawn. }
9. Be4 Qd6 10. c3
{ Benjamin aims at an IQP structure with d2-d4, where the black king's knight would have been much better off on f6. }
10... Be7 11. d4 O-O 12. Be3 cxd4 13. cxd4
{ From now on White's plan is rather simple: bring out the remaining pieces and launch the d4-d5 break. }
13... Bd7
{ 13...Nb4  seems more active, fighting for the crucial d5-square; e.g.  14.Nc3  Nd5  15.Qb3  Rd8   Or  15...Nf6  . }
14. Nc3 Rad8 15. Rc1 f5
{ Black pushes away the powerful bishop and complicates the d4-d5 plan, at the cost of long-term weaknesses on e5 and e6.   Perhaps the modest  15...Bc8  , intending  16.d5  Nb4  was a lesser evil. }
16. Bc2 { Heading for b3 to attack the fresh weakness on e6. } 16... f4
{ The ensuing complications hardly favour Black;   So the restrained  16...Nb4  17.Bb3  Bc6  would have been a better choice, even if by  18.Bg5  White keeps the advantage. }
17. Ne4 Qd5
{ After  17...Qb4  18.Bd2  Qxb2  19.Rb1  Black is also in big trouble; e.g.  19...Qa3   @@StartBracket@@or  19...Qxa2  20.Bb3  Qa3  21.Ra1  Qb2  22.Bc3  , trapping the queen@@EndBracket@@  20.Rxb7  Bc8  21.Rc7  Nxd4  22.Nxd4  Rxd4  23.Qa1  with the strong threat of  23...--  24.Rc3  Qa5  25.Rxc8  - Gershon. }
18. Bd2 Nb4
{ Or  18...Nxd4  19.Nxd4  Qxd4  20.Ba5  recovering the pawn with interest. }
19. Bb3 Qh5 20. Neg5
{ White intensifies the attack at the e6-pawn, exploiting the fact that the bishop on e7 is overloaded.   20.Rc7  was also strong. }
20... Bxg5 21. Bxb4 Be7 22. Bxe7 Nxe7 23. Rc7
{ Benjamin refrains from the obvious  23.Bxe6+  Bxe6  24.Rxe6  , aware that the e6-pawn won't disappear from the board, and instead seizes the seventh rank. }
23... Nd5 24. Rxb7 Bc8 25. Ra7
{ On top of all his positional advantages White now has an extra pawn, and the rest is easy. }
25... Kh8 26. Re5 Qe8 27. h3 Nf6 28. Qe2 Rd6 29. Rc5
{ Heading for c7, while vacating e5 for the fellow pieces. } 29... Qg6 30. Bc2
Qe8 31. Qe5 Rb6 { A blunder in a completely hopeless position. } 32. Qc7 *

