[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "Centre controlled at distance"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Returning to the subject of the pawn centre, most openings actually don't permit its creation.   For example, the two main reactions to  1.d4  @@StartBracket@@  1...Nf6  and  1...d5  @@EndBracket@@ both prevent 2.e4   While the Sicilian Alapin  1.e4  c5  2.c3  @@EndBracket@@is usually met by either  2...d5  or  2...Nf6  3.d4  in both cases.   Nevertheless, there are a number of openings, such as the Pirc, the Modern, the King's Indian, and the Grünfeld, where White is indeed allowed to create a pawn centre. However, in these defences Black will sooner or later try to undermine the enemy centre by means of pawn breaks  @@StartBracket@@e.g. ...c7-c5 or ...e7-e5 in the first three@@EndBracket@@ , or by piece pressure on the central pawns  @@StartBracket@@e.g. ...Bg4, ...Nc6, ...Qa5 etc in the Grünfeld@@EndBracket@@. From White's perspective, openings such as the Réti and the English permit similar ideas with reversed colours.Such an approach, with the centre being controlled 'at distance', was championed by Réti and Nimzowitsch, among others, and maintains a fundamental role within opening strategy. Let's see some examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "J.Van der Wiel-R.Vaganian  Ter Apel 1993  Alekhine’s Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ The fearsome Four Pawns Attack, one of White's main weapons against the Alekhine. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3
{ The seemingly natural  7.Nf3  is imprecise due to  7...Bg4  8.Be3  e6  and Black has won a tempo on the game continuation. }
7... Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Bg4
{ An established exception from the rule that the same piece shouldn't move twice in the opening. Here it serves the purpose of putting pressure on White's pawn centre.   Another direction is  9...Be7  10.d5  exd5  11.cxd5  Nb4  12.Nd4  with sharp play. }
10. Be2 Bxf3 11. gxf3
{ By swapping on f3 at this very moment, Black exploits the fact that  11.Bxf3  fails to  11...Nxc4  . }
11... Qd7
{ Preparing ...Rd8 or ...O-O-O with increased pressure on d4.   The alternative is  11...Qh4+  12.Bf2  Qf4  13.c5  Nd7  with double-edged play. }
12. f4
{ A logical move at first sight, but now the d4-pawn becomes rather exposed.   The restrained  12.Qd2  , followed by O-O-O, is considered a better option. }
12... Rd8 13. d5
{ After  13.c5  Nd5  14.Nxd5  Qxd5  15.Bf3  Qd7  the problem with the d4-pawn still persists.   At this point White was probably hoping for  13.d5  exd5  14.Bg4  with some initiative, but Black has a much stronger move at his disposal, which will leave the enemy pawn centre in a rather shaky state. }
13... Bb4
{ Exploiting the tactical twist  13...Bb4  14.dxc6  Qxc6  with a double attack at d1 and h1, Black speeds up development and increases the pressure on the d-file. }
14. Bxb6 axb6 15. Bf3
{ By surrendering the bishop pair White managed to keep his pawn centre intact; unfortunately, his king will now be subject to a strong counterattack. }
15... exd5 16. cxd5 Qh3 17. Ke2
{ An awkward move; but the desirable  17.Qe2  failed to  17...Nd4  . } 17...
O-O { By now White's unsafe king makes his game very difficult. } 18. Qd3
{ Both  18.Ne4  Bc5  intending ...Nd4+   And  18.Nb5  Rfe8  preparing ...Nxe5, keep up the attack - Ftacnik. }
18... Ne7 19. Qc4 Bxc3 20. bxc3 b5
{ An ingenious way of clearing new lines towards the white monarch. Now  20...b5  21.Qc5  , or  21.Qb3  is strongly met by  21...Ng6  so Van der Wiel accepts the offer. }
21. Qxb5 c6 22. dxc6 { Or  22.Qxb7  Nxd5  with multiple threats. } 22... bxc6
23. Qc4 { After  23.Bxc6  Qxc3  White collapses. } 23... Ng6 24. Rag1 Qf5
{ A final detail, by which Black installs the double threat of ...Nxf4+ and ...Qc2+. }
25. Rg4 Qc2+ 26. Ke3 { Or  26.Kf1  Rd1+  winning a piece. } 26... Qd2+ 27. Ke4
Rd5
{ After  27...Rd5  , unable to parry the threat of  28.--  f5+  29.exf6  Re8  , White resigned. }
*

