[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "D.Rosandic-A.Delchev  Zadar 2001  Modern Defence"]
[Result "*"]

{ In the previous game, Black's pressure on the enemy centre was basically conducted via the semi-open d-file. However, the most typical way of 'long distance' central control is by means of a fianchetto, or even two of them, as in the following games. }
1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3
{ One of the most dangerous set-ups against the Modern, by which White prepares either Qd2 and O-O-O, followed by a kingside attack, or f2-f4, supporting future expansion in the centre. }
4... a6 5. f4 b5 6. Be2
{ Preparing Bf3 to reinforce the light squares.   6.Bd3  is also frequently seen in practice. }
6... b4 7. Nb1
{ 7.Na4  is more critical - Hillarp Persson, who also suggests the flexible 6...Nd7 on the previous move. }
7... Bb7
{ As beginners we are taught to bring the knights out before the bishops, since the destiny of the former tends to be a bit more evident. However, in this defence it is the other way around - the bishops are rather predestined for g7 and b7, while the knights, in particular the one on g8, have more squares to consider. }
8. Bf3 Nf6 9. Qd3
{ Neither  9.e5  Nd5  nor  9.Nd2  Nbd7  10.c3  a5  11.Ne2  O-O  12.O-O  c5  promises White any advantage - Hillarp. }
9... Nbd7 10. Ne2
{ Black is also fine after  10.Nd2  O-O  11.c4  bxc3  12.bxc3  c5  ; e.g.  13.Ne2  cxd4  14.cxd4  e5  15.Rb1   @@StartBracket@@note that the tempting  15.fxe5  dxe5  16.d5  would have backfired after  16...Bxd5  17.exd5  e4  , when the bishop on g7 makes itself remembered@@EndBracket@@  16...Bc6  , followed by ...Bb5, with counterplay in A.Galkin-R.Ponomariov, Lausanne 2000. }
10... O-O 11. O-O e5
{ Supported by his powerful fianchettoed bishops, Delchev begins striking at the white pawn centre.   11...c5  , in the same spirit, was also possible. }
12. Ng3
{ Reinforcing the e4-pawn.   In the event of  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.d5  Black could consider  13...a5  , just as in the game; e.g.  14.Nd2  Ba6  15.Nc4  Qe7  , followed by ...Nc5 with counterplay. }
12... a5 { Preparing a pinprick by ...Ba6. } 13. Re1 Nb6 14. c4
{ By advancing one more pawn to the fourth rank White takes precautions against ...Ba6, but also further weakens the dark squares, in particular d4.   Instead,  14.Nd2  was preferable - Hillarp, when Black could try  14...Ba6  15.c4  exf4  16.Bxf4  d5  with some initiative; e.g.  17.b3  dxc4  18.bxc4  Nh5  19.Be3  Nxg3  20.hxg3  c5  , exploiting the double pin. }
14... Nfd7
{ A key move of the game, by which the knight takes prophylactic control of the dark squares on c5 and e5, while clearing the long diagonal for the bishop on g7. }
15. fxe5
{ After  15.dxe5  dxe5  16.f5  Qe7  , preparing ...Nc5   Or  15.Nd2  exf4  16.Bxf4  c5  , Black also enjoys a clear positional plus; e.g.  17.Bxd6  Bxd4+  18.Kh1  Ne5  with a terrible game for White. }
15... c5
{ An impressive pawn break which demolishes the enemy centre.   The modest  15...dxe5  16.d5  Qe7  and ...Nc5 was also possible, but the text promises more. }
16. e6
{ Rather pointless; but after  16.dxc5  Nxe5  , followed by 17...Nbxc4   Or  16.exd6  cxd4  17.Bxd4  Ne5  18.Bxe5  Bxe5  19.c5  Nd7  , Black also has a huge advantage - Hillarp. At this point, hanging on to the c5-pawn with  20.Qe3  is refuted by  20...Rc8  21.Rc1  Qf6  with multiple threats. }
16... cxd4 17. Bxd4 Ne5 18. exf7+ Rxf7 19. Bxe5
{ A strategic capitulation; though  19.Qd1  Nbxc4  , preparing ...d6-d5, was equally troublesome for White, who by now is regretting his slow queenside development. }
19... Bxe5 20. Qc2 a4
{ Just in time; enabling ...a4-a3 before the rook leaves a1. } 21. Nd2 a3 22.
Rab1 axb2 23. Rxb2 Bxb2 24. Qxb2 Nd7
{ Even after winning the exchange, Delchev keeps his grip on the dark squares. }
25. Bg4 Nc5 26. Qd4 Qg5 27. Bh3 Rxa2 28. Nf3 Qf4
{ In this desperate position, White resigned. } *

