[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "J.G.Gallagher-R.Ponomariov  Biel 2000  Modern Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6 5. Qd2
{ White opts for the first of the set-ups outlined in the previous game. } 5...
Nd7 6. a4
{ Preventing ...b7-b5, but the advance with the a-pawn also means that long castling becomes unadvisable.   6.O-O-O  b5  7.h4  is a more critical option. }
6... b6
{ On his part, Black prevents the cramping a4-a5 and enables ...Bb7, thus giving rise to an opening system that is known as the Hippopotamus. }
7. Nf3 e6
{ The immediate  7...Bb7  would yield White the additional option of  8.d5  , preparing Nd4.   After  7...e6  , on the other hand,  8.d5  can be confidently met by  8...e5  . }
8. Bc4
{ On other moves Black can react in similar fashion as in the game; e.g.  8.Be2  Bb7  9.h3  h6  10.O-O  Ne7  11.Rad1  g5  12.Nh2  Ng6  13.Bh5  Nf6  14.Bxg6  fxg6  , followed by ...O-O with balanced chances in M.Rogovoi-N.Nikolaev, St Petersburg 2000. }
8... h6
{ Seeing that the immediate  8...Ne7  permits  9.Bh6  , swapping the valuable king's bishop, Black prepares it. }
9. h3 Ne7 10. O-O Bb7
{ The Hippopotamus is complete. White has more space but it is not easy for him to improve his position; e.g.  10...Bb7  11.d5  leads nowhere after  11...e5  , when Black can even grab the initiative by a later ...f7-f5. In similar fashion, e4-e5 often runs into ...d6-d5, followed by ...c7-c5. Black, on his part, is mainly awaiting the right moment for a pawn break, in which virtually any of his pawns from the c- to the g-file can participate. }
11. Rfe1 { Now Black can't castle due to 12. Bxh6, so what to do? } 11... g5
{ A typical 'Hippo' move that enables ...Ng6 with a grip on the dark squares. }
12. Nh2 Ng6 { Just in time, before White strikes with f2-f4. } 13. Nf1
{ At this point  13.d5  e5   @@StartBracket@@so the flexible  13...Nde5  14.Bb3  Qf6  @@EndBracket@@  , followed by ...O-O, is probably a better choice.  14.Nf1  , preparing Ng3-f5, favours White. }
13... Nf6 14. Ng3 O-O
{ Despite the slightly weakening ... g6-g5, the king is quite safe here. } 15.
Bd3
{ On  15.f3  Black is ready for  15...d5  16.exd5  Nxd5  17.Nxd5  Bxd5  with rough equality.   15.Bd3  makes  15...d5  unfeasible due to  16.e5  , but invites another pawn break. }
15... c5
{ An excellent advance, which softens up the a1-h8 diagonal for the bishop on g7, and also disputes the e5-square for the knight on g6. }
16. dxc5
{ A passive reaction that hands over the initiative to Black.   16.d5  Ne5  17.Bf1  , followed by Rad1 and f2-f4, was preferable - Finkel. }
16... bxc5
{ Now White's pawn centre is gone and Black enjoys an extra central pawn, a fact that he soon exploits.   16...dxc5  17.a5  was less advisable. }
17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Qe2 d5 19. exd5 exd5 20. Bc1
{ A necessary retreat in view of the threatened 20...d4. } 20... Rae8 21. Qd2
Nh4
{ Before advancing the c- or d-pawns Black eliminates the possibilities of Bxg6 and Nf5, while eyeing the g2-pawn.   21...Nf4  22.Bf1  d4  looked strong as well. }
22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Re1
{ Exchanges often favour the defender, but here Black keeps all his trumps even after the rooks' departure. }
23... Rxe1+ 24. Qxe1 c4
{ Move order matters:  24...d4  25.Nce4  was less clear. } 25. Bf1 d4
{ A dream position for Black. All his pieces, in particular the bishops, upstage their white counterparts, and a passed pawn can quickly emerge on the d-file. }
26. Nce2 { Or  26.Nce4  Nxe4  27.Nxe4  Qe5  , preparing ...f7-f5 - Finkel. }
26... Qc5
{ Again there is no hurry with advancing the pawns - after  26...d3  27.cxd3  cxd3  28.Nc3  , the d3-pawn becomes a bit exposed. }
27. Qd1 Ne4 28. Nxe4 Bxe4 29. Ng3 Bg6
{ A timely diagonal shift, which makes 30...d3 inevitable. White's next move accelerates the end, though it was not easy to give him good advice. }
30. Qe2 d3 31. cxd3 cxd3 32. Qe8+ Kh7 33. Be3 Qd5
{ Installing the queen in the centre tends to be an excellent idea in the endgame, and here it forces White to shed a pawn in order to stop ...d3-d2. }
34. Bd2 Bxb2 35. f3 Be5
{ Ponomariov avoids the 'strategical trap'  35...Qe5  36.Qxe5  Bxe5  37.Ne4  , when White unexpectedly stays in the game. }
36. Ne4 Bxe4 37. fxe4 Qd4+ 38. Kh1 Qf2
{ Attack and defence at the same time. Faced with multiple threats, White resigned. }
