[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "A.Beliavsky-V.Anand  Munich 1991  Pirc Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O
{ The traditional way of meeting White's Austrian Attack.   The sharp  5...c5  is also popular. }
6. Be3
{ The main direction here is  6.Bd3  , followed by O-O, after which White often starts a kingside attack with moves like Qe1-h4, f4-f5 etc. The text prepares quite a different set-up with Qd2 and O-O-O; moreover, it enhances the central e4-e5 advance now that after ...d6xe5, d4xe5, White is ready to recapture on d1 with the rook. }
6... b6
{ A move with two functions: enabling ...Bb7 and facilitating the c7-c5 thrust. }
7. e5
{ White gains space in the centre, but also exposes his central pawns at quite an early stage of the game.   Nowadays,  7.Qd2  , followed by O-O-O, is more frequently played. }
7... Ng4 8. Bg1 c5 9. h3
{ The greedy  9.dxc5  bxc5  10.Qd5  backfires after  10...Qb6  intending  11.Qxa8  Bb7  12.Nd5  Qxb2  with decisive threats - Anand. }
9... Nh6 10. d5
{ Thus White maintains his pawn centre, and now enjoys a considerable space advantage. On the other hand, he is rather behind in development, a fact that Anand will exploit vigorously during the rest of the game. }
10... Bb7 11. Qd2
{ Preparing O-O-O.   If  11.Qe2  , in the same spirit, Black could react by  11...Ba6  12.Qf2  Bxf1  13.Qxf1  Nf5  with counterplay; e.g.  14.Bf2  dxe5  15.fxe5  Nd7  16.g4  Nd4  , destroying the enemy centre.   As for  11.g4  , preventing ...Nf5, after  11...dxe5  12.fxe5  e6  , followed by 13. ..Nd7, White's centre again comes under strong pressure. }
11... Nf5 12. Bh2
{ Anand also indicates  12.Bf2  dxe5  13.fxe5  e6  when  14.O-O-O  fails to  14...Bh6  . With the text White enables Bf4 at the end of this line. }
12... dxe5 13. fxe5 e6
{ A key move in order to challenge White's pawn centre before he is comfortably developed. }
14. O-O-O
{ At this point both  14.g4  Nh4   @@StartBracket@@and  14.d6  Nd7  leave the e5-pawn doomed@@EndBracket@@   While  14.Bc4  b5  also favours Black. As a consequence, Beliavsky just gets on with development. }
14... exd5 15. Nxd5 Nc6 16. c3
{ Now if White just manages to play Bc4 and Rhe1 he would be considerably better - Anand. But he has no time for that; e.g.  16.Bc4  Ncd4  17.Nxd4  cxd4  , with ...Ne3 coming up. The text aims at preventing an annoying ...Ncd4, but in vain. }
16... Ncd4 17. Nf6+
{ The best try; since  17.cxd4  Qxd5  18.Kb1  Rad8  would leave White under unbearable pressure. }
17... Bxf6 18. cxd4 Bg7 19. d5
{ By a precise sequence of moves Beliavsky has managed to rebuild his pawn centre, and now intends to reinforce it by 20. Bc4. Anand finds a great reply. }
19... c4
{ Exploiting some simple tactics -  19...c4  20.Bxc4  Rc8  - Black prevents the enemy plan and enables a future ...c4-c3 as well.   19...Bh6  20.Bf4  Bxf4  21.Qxf4  Bxd5  22.Bc4  was less convincing. }
20. Be2
{ Practically dropping a pawn.   The prophylactic  20.Kb1  was called for, when  20...Rc8  can be met by  21.d6  Bh6   @@StartBracket@@Black should rather try  21...b5  , followed by ...a7-a5 and ...b5-b4 with some initiative@@EndBracket@@  22.Bf4  , without losing the d-pawn as in the game. }
20... Rc8 21. Kb1
{ Or  21.g4  Ne7  22.d6  Nd5  , when 23...c3 next proves inevitable. } 21...
Bh6 22. Bf4 Bxf4 23. Qxf4 Bxd5
{ After some calculating Anand accepts the gift, convinced that White can't exploit the ensuing pin. }
24. h4
{ In a difficult position, Beliavsky goes for a desperate attack.   A key variation was  24.g4  Ng7  25.Qh6  Ne6  26.h4  c3  , when after  27.bxc3   @@StartBracket@@while  27.Ng5  fails to  27...c2+  28.Ka1  Nxg5  29.hxg5  Bxh1  30.Rxh1  c1=Q+  @@EndBracket@@  Be4+  28.Kb2  Qc7  , Black's attack is the more convincing one - Anand.   As for  24.Nd4  , trying to exploit the pin, then  24...Qh4  . }
24... c3
{ As the remainder of the game will show us, Black's attack is faster. } 25.
bxc3 Rxc3 26. h5 Ne3
{ The knight joins the attack and at the same time liberates the queen from the defence of the bishop. }
27. Ng5
{ 27.hxg6  fxg6  28.Qh6  Qc7  leaves only Black's attack intact   While  27.Qh6  is refuted by  27...Nxd1  28.hxg6  Be4+  29.Ka1  Bxg6  30.Rxd1  Qe7  - Anand. }
27... Qc7 28. Nxh7 Rb3+
{ An elegant finish.   In view of  28...Rb3+  29.axb3  Qc2+  30.Ka1  Qc3+  31.Kb1  Qxb3+  32.Ka1  Nc2  , White resigned. }
