[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "M.Taimanov-V.Hort  Tallinn 1975  English Opening "]
[Result "*"]

{ As I mentioned in the introduction to this section, controlling the centre at long distance is also possible with the white pieces. Here are two examples. }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bc5
{ Another option is  4...Bb4  , although in that case the reply  5.Nd5  gains in strength. }
5. e3
{ White chooses a set-up with e2-e3 and Nge2 in order to restrict the bishop on c5. }
5... d6 6. a3 Be6
{ 6...a5  or  6...a6  was more precise, providing the bishop with a shelter on a7. }
7. b4 Bb6 8. d3
{ Aware that after  8.d3  , the desirable  8...d5  fails to  9.c5  , White just continues development. In contrast, with the black bishop on a7 he would probably have preferred  8.Nd5  at this point. }
8... Qd7 9. h3
{ Before playing Nge2 Taimanov prevents ...Bh3, in identical fashion to Ponomariov's 8...h6 against Gallagher. In fact, White's treatment of the English in this game has great similarities to the Hippopotamus. }
9... O-O 10. Nge2 Nd8
{ Hort prepares ...c7-c6 and ...Bc7, but this plan is easily refuted by White's next move.   Perhaps  10...a5  was more to the point; e.g.  11.b5  Ne7  12.Bxb7  Rab8  13.Bg2  d5  , followed by ...Rfd8, with quite some counterplay for the pawn.   Even the simple  10...Rab8  , preparing ...Ne7-g6 to improve the knight, seems like a better choice - in the game, that piece becomes a problem child on d8. }
11. Na4 c6 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. Bb2
{ An excellent deployment of the bishop, and renewed restriction of Black's ... d6-d5. }
13... Ne8
{ Preparing ...f7-f6 and ...Nf7, after which the ...d6-d5 thrust would at last become possible, but White has a strong reply prepared. }
14. f4
{ A key move, striking at the enemy centre and softening up the long diagonal for the bishop on b2. }
14... f6 15. g4
{ With the centre under control, nothing speaks against this flank advance,  15.g4  , which enables castling and also prevents  15...Nf7  on account of  16.f5  . }
15... Kh8
{ Preparing ...Bg8, but Black has overlooked the pin that soon emerges on the f-file.   15...Nc7  was better, intending ...b6-b5 - Taimanov. }
16. O-O Qe7
{ Since  16...Bg8  runs into  17.fxe5  dxe5  18.Bxe5  Black has to adjust his plans. }
17. Qe1 Bf7 18. Ng3 { Step by step White brings more pieces to the kingside. }
18... Bg6 19. Rd1 Nc7 20. Qf2 b5
{ This facilitates White's further task, though it was already difficult to suggest a constructive plan for Black. }
21. c5 { A new pawn thrust in order to soften up the enemy centre. } 21... exf4
{ Now neither  21...Nf7  22.f5   Nor  21...d5  22.fxe5  works for Black, so he has finally to swap the proud e5-pawn. }
22. exf4 h6
{ On  22...dxc5  Taimanov had prepared  23.Rfe1  Qd7  24.f5  Bf7  25.g5  with a strong attack; e.g.  25...fxg5  26.f6  g6  27.Re7  . }
23. Be4 { Exchanging the defender of the light squares in the enemy camp. }
23... Bxe4 24. cxd6 Qxd6 25. dxe4 Qe6 26. e5
{ For the third time in the game White softens up the long diagonal for his bishop, on this occasion with decisive effect. }
26... fxe5 27. Bxe5 Nd5 28. Qb2
{ Taimanov once mentioned that the fianchettoed queen's bishop was his favourite piece, both with White and Black. It definitely didn't let him down in this game, and you can find many other games of his where this piece plays the main role. }
28... Qf7 29. Nh5
{ More exact than  29.Nf5  Ne6  30.Nxh6  Qg6  with complications. } 29... Rg8
{ Now, on the other hand,  29...Ne6  fails to  30.f5  . } 30. f5 b6
{ Obviously  30...Ne3  runs into  31.Qc1  x-raying the h6-pawn. } 31. Rfe1 Nb7
{ This loses material, though Black was beyond salvation anyway. } 32. Qc1 Kh7
33. Qxc6 { In this terrible position, Black resigned. } *

