[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "A.Kundin-Kostanovich  Israeli Team Championship 1998  French Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ We are already familiar with this line from Adams-Gurevich. } 4... cxd4 5.
Nxd4
{ That game went  5.exd5  Qxd5  6.Bc4  , transposing to one of the main lines of the French Tarrasch. With the text White keeps the central tension, and takes the game into less explored terrain. }
5... Nc6
{ After  5...e5  6.N4f3  Nc6   @@StartBracket@@or  6...dxe4  7.Nxe5  @@EndBracket@@  7.exd5  Qxd5  8.Bc4  , White obtains a clear lead in development   But  5...Nf6  was a valid alternative. }
6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Another direction is  7...Bxc6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.c4  preparing Qa4. } 8. Bd3
e5
{ A very ambitious move. Black achieves a pawn centre, but the delay in development will make it difficult for him to support it adequately.   8...Bd6  was safer, followed by ...Ne7. }
9. O-O Nf6
{ After  9...Bd6  10.Re1  Ne7  11.exd5  cxd5  12.c4  Black's centre is successfully undermined; e.g.  12...O-O   @@StartBracket@@or  12...d4  13.c5  , preparing 14. Nc4@@EndBracket@@  13.cxd5  Nxd5  14.Nc4  Be6  15.Bd2  with a slight edge - Kundin. }
10. Re1 Bd6
{ Aware that  10...d4  invites  11.Nc4  , Black accepts the clearance of the e-file. }
11. exd5 cxd5 12. Nf3
{ Supported by his lead in development, White starts concrete actions against Black's pawn centre.   12.c4  was also possible; e.g.  12...O-O  13.cxd5  Nxd5  14.Nc4  , transposing to the 9...Bd6 subvariation given above. }
12... Qe7
{ After other moves White prevails tactically;   e.g.  12...e4  13.Bxe4  Nxe4  14.Qxd5  , recovering the piece with interest   @@StartBracket@@or  12...Bg4  13.Nxe5  Bxd1  14.Nc6+  Kd7  15.Nxd8  Bxc2  16.Bxc2  Rhxd8  17.Bd2  with Ba4+ next - Kundin@@EndBracket@@   Finally,  12...Qc7  runs into  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.Bf4  Ne4  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.Rxe4  f6  17.Bxe5  fxe5  18.Qd5  with twin threats at a8 and e5. }
13. Bf4
{ The correct follow-up; now that  13.Nxe5  no longer works due to  13...Bxe5  14.Bf4  Bxf4  15.Rxe7+  Kxe7  . }
13... Bg4
{ The only viable defence; unfortunately, Black will be left without castling after the opponent's next move. }
14. Bb5+ Kf8 15. Bg5
{ White now directs his attention to the d5-pawn.   15.Bc6  Rd8   Or  15.c4  Qc7  16.Bg5  a6  was less convincing - Kundin. }
15... Qb7 16. Bc4
{ Increasing the pressure.   16.h3  Bxf3  17.Qxf3  Ne4  would be much less clear. }
16... d4
{ After the alternative  16...Bxf3  17.Qxf3  e4  18.Qf5   Or  18.Qb3  , White also remains on top - Kundin. }
17. Be2
{ An ingenious retreat which creates new threats, such as the captures  17...--  18.Nxe5  and  18.Nxd4  . }
17... Ne4 18. Bh4 Be6
{ A logical defensive try, but it will lead to the collapse of Black's centre.   18...Bf5  19.Bd3  , preparing Qe2, is equally bad for him   So the active  18...h5  , reinforcing the bishop, was probably the last chance to stay alive - Kundin, whose sample line  19.h3  Re8  20.hxg4  hxg4  21.Ng5  Rxh4  22.Nxe4  Qxe4  23.Bb5  Qh7  illustrates Black's idea. White should rather prefer Bd3 either on the 20th or 21st move, keeping the pressure. }
19. Bd3 Bd5
{ Or  19...f5  20.c3  , exploiting the loose bishop on d6, just like White's next move in the game. }
20. c4 Bc6
{ Black can't reply  20...dxc3  21.Bxe4  Bxe4  , due to   @@StartBracket@@while  21...cxb2  22.Rb1  doesn't change much@@EndBracket@@  22.Qxd6+  . }
21. Nxd4
{ By tactical means White finally liquidates the enemy centre. In fact this sacrifice was already available on the previous move. }
21... Nc5
{ An early resignation; though  21...exd4  22.Bxe4  Bxe4  23.Qxd4  was equally bad for Black; e.g.  23...Bxh2+  24.Kxh2  Bxg2  25.Rg1  winning - Kundin. }
22. Nf5 Qc7
{ Now the e5-pawn falls as well; but  22...Bc7  was impossible due to  23.Be7+ }
23. Bf1 Nb7 24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25. Qxd6+ Nxd6 26. Rxe5
{ White is completely winning and the rest is easy. } 26... Re8 27. Rae1 f6 28.
Rxe8+ Nxe8 29. Bg3 Kf7 30. c5 Bd5 31. Rd1 { In view of  31.Rd1  Bxa2  32.c6 } *

