[White "3.3 Centre Controlled at a Distance"]
[Black "Exercise #2: A.Kundin-Kostanovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4k1r/pq3ppp/3b4/3bp3/3pn2B/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

20. c4 Bc6
{ Black can't reply  20...dxc3  21.Bxe4  Bxe4  , due to   @@StartBracket@@while  21...cxb2  22.Rb1  doesn't change much@@EndBracket@@  22.Qxd6+  . }
21. Nxd4
{ By tactical means White finally liquidates the enemy centre. In fact this sacrifice was already available on the previous move. }
21... Nc5
{ An early resignation; though  21...exd4  22.Bxe4  Bxe4  23.Qxd4  was equally bad for Black; e.g.  23...Bxh2+  24.Kxh2  Bxg2  25.Rg1  winning - Kundin. }
22. Nf5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.4 Pawn Breaks"]
[Black "Pawn breaks"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ By the term 'pawn break' I refer to the advance of a pawn that puts it in contact with an enemy pawn. This is an important strategic idea in the middlegame as well, for example in the context of pawn chains.In the opening battle, a pawn break often proves useful in order to put pressure on the enemy centre, apart from its inherent function of opening a file. We already saw several pawn breaks in the previous section; e.g. 11...e5 and 15...c5 in Rosandic-Delchev, 15...c5 in Gallagher-Ponomariov, 13...e6 in Beliavsky-Anand, as well as 14. f4 and 21. c5 in Taimanov-Hort. Here are some more examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.4 Pawn Breaks"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-M.Morales  Riobamba 2010  Queen’s Gambit Declined "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A topical line against the Queen's Gambit Declined, which we already came across in Polgar-Bönsch. }
5... Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Qc2 h6
{ In the present structure, this move often makes Black's kingside a bit more vulnerable.   8...Nbd7  , followed by ...Re8 and ...Nf8, is the main continuation here. }
9. Bh4 Re8 10. Nge2
{ Just like in Polgar-Bönsch, the knight goes to e2 in order to enable the future plan of f2-f3 and e3-e4. }
10... Ne4
{ A typical idea to seize the centre, but here it is somewhat premature as Black will lack the support of a knight on f6 later on.   For this reason,  10...Nbd7  11.O-O   @@StartBracket@@although White could consider inserting  11.f3  before castling@@EndBracket@@  11...Ne4  was a better move order. }
11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Bxe4
{ Creating a target on e4.   An alternative approach is  12.O-O  Nd7  13.Rae1  , preparing f2-f3 and e3-e4. }
12... dxe4 13. Ng3 f5
{ With the rook on e8 this move looks a bit odd, but there was no other defence of the e4-pawn available. }
14. O-O Na6
{ In the event of  14...Be6  , preparing ...Nd7, then  15.f3  looks just as strong as in the game. }
15. a3
{ Quite a lazy move.   The immediate  15.f3  was called for; e.g.  15...Nb4  16.Qd2  Nd5  17.fxe4  Nxc3  18.Qxc3  fxe4  19.Rf4  winning a pawn, as occurred in M.Kantorik-J.Veselsky, Czech League 2007. }
15... Kh7
{ Black perhaps regarded this as a piece of prophylaxis, but he is in fact putting his king right into the line of fire.   15...Nc7  16.f3  Nd5  was correct, with just a slight initiative for White after  17.Rae1  . }
16. f3
{ A key strike, in order to soften up Black's grip on the centre and enable a future kingside attack. We saw a similar idea in Van Wely-Karjakin. }
16... exf3
{ Or  16...Qg5  17.fxe4  Qxe3+  18.Kh1  and the black king remains exposed along the b1-h7 diagonal, just as in the game. }
17. Rxf3 g6 18. e4
{ One more pawn break to clear more lines towards the enemy king.   18.Raf1  , followed by e3-e4, looked strong as well. }
18... fxe4 19. Ncxe4 Bf5 20. Nxf5 Qxe4
{ Black seems to be defending quite well; however, when deciding upon 18. e4 I had already calculated the following sacrifice that exploits the weak seventh rank in the enemy camp. }
21. Qb3 gxf5 22. Qf7+
{ Of course  22.Qxb7+  Kh8  23.Qxa6  Rab8  was not White's idea. } 22... Kh8
23. Qf6+ Kh7 24. Rh3
{ The point. Black's queen is now forced to f4, which lets White's second rook join the battle with tempo.   In contrast,  24.Rg3  Rg8  leads nowhere. }
24... Qf4 25. Rf1 Qd2 26. Qxf5+ Kh8
{ At this point, for White's attack to prosper he must activate the other rook, and this is achieved by the following sequence. }
27. Qf6+ Kh7 28. Rg3
{ Diverting Black's rook from the e-file so that the queen can give check on e7. }
28... Rg8 29. Qe7+ Kh8 30. Qe5+
{ In view of  30.Qe5+  Kh7  31.Rf7+  , Black resigned. } *

