[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.4 Pawn Breaks"]
[Black "M.Illescas Cordoba-J.Moreno Carnero  Spanish Championship,  Seville 2004  Benoni Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 exd5 4. cxd5 d6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Here, and on the following two moves, with  5...Nf6  Black could have entered standard Benoni waters. }
6. e4 Bg7 7. Nf3 Ne7
{ The point of Black's unusual move order. On e7 the knight doesn't block the fianchettoed bishop, while the ...f7-f5 advance can be achieved much earlier than in a usual Benoni. On the other hand, White does not have to worry about the customary pressure on his e4-pawn from a knight on f6 and a subsequent ...Re8.   In fact, Black could have considered ...a7-a6 even earlier; e.g.  7...a6  8.a4  Ne7  , thus avoiding the check on b5. }
8. Bb5+
{ This check, in conjunction with White's next move, aims at disorganizing Black's minor pieces.   Another idea was  8.Bf4  ; e.g.  8...O-O  9.Be2  a6   @@StartBracket@@By now,  9...f5  at any moment runs into  10.e5  @@EndBracket@@  10.a4  , followed by O-O. }
8... Nd7
{ This natural reply soon proves to have its flaws.   8...Bd7  was preferable; e.g.  9.a4  a6  10.Be2  Bg4  , with ...Nd7 next, and all Black's minor pieces are satisfactorily developed. }
9. Bf4 a6
{ No simple defence of the d6-pawn was available; e.g.  9...Qc7  10.e5  , when  10...dxe5  11.d6  is fatal for Black   Or  9...Qb6  10.Qb3  , renewing the threat. With the text Moreno secures the pawn once and for all, at the cost of temporarily misplacing his queen. }
10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. O-O O-O 12. e5
{ This pawn break is a main idea for White in the Benoni, and he rarely has the luck of achieving it at such an early point. Its benefits are several: increased central control, the creation of a passed pawn on the d-file, and a possible exchange of the strong bishop on g7. }
12... dxe5 13. Bxe5
{ Of course not  13.Nxe5  Qf5  . In any case, the text is also preferable from a strategical perspective, since it facilitates the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. }
13... b5
{ A useful move that enables both ...Bb7 and ...b5-b4.   After other moves White also keeps the initiative; e.g.  13...Rd8  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.Qb3  , followed by Rad1   Or  13...f6  14.Bg3  Nf5  15.d6  , preparing Nd5 or Qd5 - Postny. }
14. d6 Nf5 15. Ne4
{ White reinforces the d6-pawn and increases his central grip at the same time. }
15... Qc6 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Re1 Bb7
{ Or  17...Re8  18.Qc2  , with the unpleasant threat of 19. Qc3+. } 18. Rc1
{ The last piece joins the battle, making Black's position critical. } 18...
Rad8
{ Either by desperation or miscalculation, Black gives up material.   The cold-blooded  18...c4  was called for, when White seems unable to exploit the opponent's dark square weaknesses in any decisive way; e.g.  19.Nd4   @@StartBracket@@or  19.g4  Rae8  @@EndBracket@@  Qd5  20.Nxf5+  gxf5  21.Qxd5  Bxd5  22.Nc5  Rfd8   @@StartBracket@@but not  22...Rac8  23.d7  Rxc5  24.Re8  etc@@EndBracket@@  23.d7  Bc6  24.Rcd1  Ra7  25.Rd6  Rc7  26.Red1  Kf8  with an inferior but holdable endgame for Black - Postny. Obviously, for humans it is not easy to decide upon such lines over the board, and we often prefer 'active' defence like Moreno's choice in the game. }
19. Nxc5
{ But not  19.Rxc5  Qb6  , soon recovering the material with counterplay. }
19... Rxd6
{ There is nothing better; e.g.  19...Qxd6  20.Nxb7   Or  19...Qb6  20.d7  . }
20. Ne6+ fxe6
{ Or  20...Rxe6  21.Rxc6  Rxc6  22.Nd4  with a technical win - Postny. } 21.
Rxc6 Rxd1 22. Rc7+
{ Perhaps Black had overlooked this intermediate check, which secures an extra exchange for White. }
22... Kh6 23. Rxd1 Bxf3
{ After  23...Bd5  24.Ne5  White's task is also very trivial. } 24. gxf3 Nh4
25. Rdd7 Nxf3+ 26. Kg2 Kg5 27. Rf7 *

