[SetUp "1"]

12. e5
{ This pawn break is a main idea for White in the Benoni, and he rarely has the luck of achieving it at such an early point. Its benefits are several: increased central control, the creation of a passed pawn on the d-file, and a possible exchange of the strong bishop on g7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.4 Pawn Breaks"]
[Black "L.Ljubojevic-S.Gligoric  Belgrade (3rd matchgame) 1979  English Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Qb3
{ Thus White avoids doubled c-pawns, but also misplaces his queen.   More promising is  6.Nb5  , preparing a2-a3   Or  6.g3  , transposing to the Nimzo-Indian with g2-g3. }
6... Bc5
{ Exploiting the fact that the knight on d4 is now undefended, Black forces a minor concession from the opponent. }
7. Be3
{ Setting up the threat of 8. Nxe6, but Gligoric finds a clever antidote.   Perhaps the modest  7.e3  was a better choice. }
7... b6 8. Nc2
{ This retreat leaves the queen in a really awkward position, and complicates further development.   By  8.f3  O-O  9.Bf2  White could still hope for a normal game. }
8... Na6
{ Just as on the previous move, Black combines development with tactical considerations. Now White is discouraged from taking on c5. }
9. Rd1 O-O 10. Bd4 Bb7 11. e3 Be7
{ With the threat of ...Nc5, punishing White for his dubious eighth move. } 12.
a3 Nc5 13. Qa2 a5 14. f3
{ A slightly weakening move, but essential for White's further development. }
14... Qb8
{ The standard break  14...d5  would have yielded Black at least equality, but by now Gligoric is looking for more. With the text he seizes the h2-b8 diagonal and enhances future kingside aggression. }
15. e4
{ Ljubojevic finally achieves some kind of Maroczy structure and also parries the threat of 15...e5; however, Gligoric has a strong reply prepared. }
15... Nh5
{ With the dual idea of ...Nf4 and ... f7-f5, punishing White for his slow development. }
16. Be2
{ Correctly speeding up development.   16.g3  f5  would be horrible for White. }
16... Nf4 17. O-O f5
{ This pawn break puts some pressure on the enemy centre, and helps clearing the h1-a8 diagonal and the f-file for Black's forces. The exchange on e2 can wait until a more optimal moment. }
18. e5 { After  18.exf5  Rxf5  Black also has a strong initiative. } 18... d6
{ Another pawn break, which clears the h2-b8 diagonal towards White's king, and creates a pawn majority in the centre. }
19. exd6 Bxd6 20. Kh1 e5
{ Of course not  20...Nxe2  21.Nxe2  Bxh2  22.f4  etc - Gligoric. With the text, he instead prepares one more pawn break with ...e5-e4 to soften up the long diagonal for the bishop on b7. }
21. Bg1 e4 22. fxe4 Nxe2
{ Just at the right moment, in order to exploit the long diagonal to the maximum.   Both  22...fxe4  23.Ne3   and  22...Nxe4  23.Bf3  were somewhat less promising. }
23. Nxe2 Bxe4 24. Ncd4 Rf6
{ More pieces to the attack. Meanwhile, White has considerable difficulties in organizing counterplay, partly due to his badly placed queen. }
25. Nf3 { Or  25.Nc3  Rh6  26.Nxe4  Bxh2  27.Nxf5  Rh5  with a strong attack. }
25... Rh6 26. h3 Qb7 27. Ned4 g5
{ From now on, the threat of ...g5-g4 hangs like the sword of Damocles over White. }
28. Be3 f4 29. Nb5 Bf8
{ 29...fxe3  30.Nxd6  Rxd6  31.Rxd6  e2  32.Re1  Bxf3  33.gxf3  Qxf3+  etc was another winning line. }
30. Bxc5 Bxc5 31. b4 g4
{ Consequent and strong.   In contrast, after  31...axb4  32.Nxg5  White stays alive. }
32. bxc5 gxf3 33. Kh2 Qg7
{ Instead of  33...fxg2  34.Rxf4  with rather unclear play, Gligoric, by means of the threat of ...Qg3+, forces White to obstruct his rook with his queen. }
34. Qf2 fxg2 35. Rfe1 Qg4 { An elegant finishing move. White resigned. } *

