7... b6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.4 Pawn Breaks"]
[Black "G.Mateuta-J.Hellsten  Kavala 2003  Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. e3 a6 5. Nbd2
{ A rather passive choice.   5.Nc3  and  5.Bd3  are the main continuations in this Slav line. }
5... Bf5
{ Black refrains from the standard  5...b5  , as after  6.cxd5  cxd5  , White could try to exploit the early weakening of c5 by Nb3-c5 at some moment. }
6. Nh4
{ The most ambitious choice.   In the event of  6.Qb3  Black could simply reply  6...Qc7  , exploiting the fact that White has no knight on c3 attacking the d5-pawn. }
6... Be4
{ Before accepting the exchange of his bishop, Black provokes f2-f3 so that White's remaining knight can't move to f3. }
7. f3
{ Black is also fine after  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.g3  e6   Or  7.Qb3  Ra7  8.a4  e6  9.a5  c5  10.f3  Bg6  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Nxg6  hxg6  , preparing ...Nc6, as in Bu Xiangzhi-A.Morozevich, Bled Olympiad 2002. }
7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. f4
{ Vacating f3 for the knight, at the cost of a weakened e4-square. } 9... e6
10. Qb3
{ The attempt to restrict Black by  10.c5  backfires after  10...b6  11.b4  a5  ; e.g.  12.Qa4  b5  13.Qb3  Nh5  with ideas like ...Qh4+ and ...Ng3. }
10... Qc7 11. Nf3
{ Or  11.c5  Nbd7  12.Qc3  a5  13.a3  a4  , followed by ... b7-b6, breaking the enemy pawn chain and enabling a future counterstrike with ...c6-c5. }
11... c5
{ Instead of standard Slav development with  11...Nbd7  , Black immediately strikes at the enemy centre, and provides the knight with a more active destiny on c6. The fact that mutual pawn captures on d5 and c5 would leave him with an isolated pawn on d5 is less relevant now that White has weakened his own structure by f2-f4. }
12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bd2
{ 13.Be2  seems more natural, though after  13...Nc6  Black has an excellent game anyway. }
13... Nc6 14. Be2
{ Or  14.Rc1  c4  15.Qd1  Ne4  with a clear initiative. After the text 14...c4 is entirely possible too; however, I don't want to take off the tension on White's pawn centre yet, preferring a tempting pawn sacrifice. }
14... Ne4 15. Qxd5
{ Seeing that  15.O-O  drops a pawn after  15...cxd4  , Mateuta accepts the challenge. }
15... Nxd2 16. Nxd2 cxd4 17. Qe4+ Be7 18. exd4
{ Too greedy.   After  18.O-O  O-O  Black has a pleasant edge thanks to the dark square weaknesses in White's camp, who probably would have liked to have his f-pawn back on f2. But the text has the clear drawback of leaving the king stranded in the centre. }
18... O-O-O 19. d5
{ After  19.O-O  Nxd4  20.Rac1  Bc5  Black enjoys a strong initiative. } 19...
Rhe8
{ The last piece joins the party, creating the threat of ...Bh4+.   19...Rhe8  also prevents  20.O-O  on account of  20...Bc5+  . }
20. Qc4 Nb4
{ Even after the exchange of queens Black's attack will be quite strong.   20...Bb4  was interesting as well. }
21. Rc1 { 21.Qxc7+  Kxc7  22.Rc1+  Kb8  is similar. } 21... Qxc4 22. Rxc4+
{ A fatal mistake, which leaves both the rook and the knight tactically exposed.   22.Nxc4  was essential, when both  22...Kb8   @@StartBracket@@And  22...Nxa2  23.Rd1  @@EndBracket@@  23.Rd1  Nxd5  24.g3  offer White some hope of salvation. }
22... Kb8 23. Re4 Nxd5 24. Kd1
{ An early surrender; but  24.O-O  was impossible due to  24...Nf6  . } 24...
f5 25. Re5 Nxf4 26. Bc4 Rxd2+
{ In view of  26...Rxd2+  27.Kxd2  Bb4+  28.Ke3  Rxe5+  29.Kxf4  Re4+  , White resigned. }
