[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.5 Flank Advances"]
[Black "Flank advances "]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ The flank advance is a modern addition to the methods in the fight for the centre. By moving a pawn forward on the flank, we can indirectly undermine the opponent's centre, as shown in the following examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.5 Flank Advances"]
[Black "V.Salov-R.Hübner  Barcelona 1989  English Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ 1.d4  c5  2.d5  Nf6  3.Nc3  d6  4.e4  g6  5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Be2  O-O  is the position in the game with reversed colours. Here simply  7.O-O  is possible.  The idea of advancing the b-pawn  @@StartBracket@@see 7. b4! below@@EndBracket@@  is seen in several other opening lines, such as the Four Pawns Attack in the King's Indian:  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.f4  O-O  6.Nf3  c5  7.d5  e6  8.Bd3  exd5  9.cxd5  b5   And the Sicilian Dragon:  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  6.Be2  Bg7  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  O-O  9.f4  b5  . }
1... d5 2. c4 d4
{ A principled reply. Black enters some kind of Benoni with reversed colours, albeit with one tempo less, something that can be strongly felt in this opening.  2...e6  and  2...c6  are other frequent options. }
3. g3 Nc6
{ Aware of his minus tempo, Black saves on  3...c5  for the sake of development. }
4. Bg2 e5 5. d3 Be7 6. O-O Nf6
{ A well-known inaccuracy.   6...a5  first was correct, for reasons that soon become evident. Interestingly, with reversed colours  @@StartBracket@@see 1. d4 c5 above@@EndBracket@@  White would just have castled at this point, thus avoiding the trick that now follows. }
7. b4
{ A strong flank advance, by which White puts unpleasant pressure on the enemy centre. You can find this idea in several other opening lines, such as the Four Pawns Attack in the King's Indian and the Sicilian Dragon  @@StartBracket@@see above@@EndBracket@@ . It displays a kind of relation between the b4 and e5  @@StartBracket@@ or b5 and e4 from Black's perspective@@EndBracket@@  squares, regarding which the knight on c6 proves overloaded. }
7... e4
{ Hübner replies with a pawn break similar to 12. e5 in Illescas-Moreno, but on this occasion it lacks support from fellow pieces.   Instead,  7...Nxb4  8.Nxe5  favours White thanks to the extra central pawn and semi-open b-file   While  7...Bxb4  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Qa4+  Nc6  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Qxb4  , preparing Ba3, would be even worse.   Black's best option is rather  7...Nd7  , trying to keep the pawn centre intact, even though after  8.a3  O-O  9.e3  White enjoys some initiative. Having achieved b2-b4 so early on is quite a success - in similar Benoni positions with reversed colours, White usually does anything he can to prevent Black's ...b7-b5. }
8. dxe4 Bxb4
{ Obviously  8...Nxe4  9.b5  , followed by 10. Nxd4, was not in Black's favour. }
9. Bb2 { Simple and strong - White focuses on the fresh weakness at d4. } 9...
Bc5 10. Nbd2 Qe7
{ This leads to unfavourable simplifications, though it is hard to suggest anything better. }
11. Nb3 Nxe4 12. Nfxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxc5
{ Securing the bishop pair, which will play a huge role now that there are no pawns left in the centre. }
13... Nxc5 14. Qxd4 Ne6 15. Qe3 O-O 16. Rfd1
{ White has emerged with a dream position - his bishops control the whole board, and Black can't easily conclude his queenside development. }
16... Re8 17. Rab1 c6
{ The simplifying  17...Qc5  drops a pawn after  18.Qxc5  Nxc5  19.Ba3  - Salov. }
18. Ba3
{ The bishop leaves the long diagonal in order to exploit the fresh weakness at d6. }
18... Qc7 19. Bd6 Qa5 20. Rb2
{ More energetic was  20.f4  - Salov, with f4-f5 coming up. } 20... Qa4 21. Qb3
{ It is not easy to suggest a plan for Black after  21.Rc1  , but Salov, being a renowned endgame expert, prefers a more technical approach. }
21... Qxb3 22. Rxb3 f6
{ Hübner prepares a clever regrouping of his pieces by ...Nd8, ...Be6 and ...Nf7. }
23. f4 Nd8 24. Bc7 Ne6 25. Bd6 Nd8 26. Kf2 Be6 27. Rd4 Rc8
{ After  27...Nf7  28.Rxb7  Nxd6  29.Rxd6  Bxc4  30.Bf3  Black is also suffering - Salov. }
28. Ra3 c5
{ This leads to tactical problems on the light squares.   28...a6  was called for. }
29. Re4 f5
{ White also breaks through after  29...Rc6  30.Bb8   Or  29...Nf7  30.Rae3  Nxd6  31.Rxe6  Rxe6  32.Rxe6  Rd8  33.Re7  . }
30. Rxe6 Rxe6
{ Or  30...Nxe6  31.Bxb7  Rcd8  32.Bc6  , regaining the material with interest. }
31. Bd5 a6 { If  31...Rc6  then  32.Be7  - Salov. } 32. Rb3 Kf7 33. e4
{ Just when it seemed that Black has managed to consolidate, White brings more pieces into the battle. }
33... Kg6
{ Seeing that  33...g6  34.e5  would leave him terribly restricted, Hübner goes for active defence. }
34. Bxe6 Nxe6 35. g4 { Very nice. } 35... fxe4
{ Now  35...Nd8  36.gxf5+  is just depressing for Black, so Hübner gives up his knight. }
36. f5+ Kf6 37. fxe6 b5
{ Or  37...Kxe6  38.Rb6  with an easy win, just as in the game. } 38. cxb5 Kxe6
39. Bf4 c4 40. Rb1 axb5 41. Rxb5 Ra8 42. Re5+ Kf6 43. Rc5 Rxa2+ 44. Ke3 Rg2 45.
Bg3 *

