[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.5 Flank Advances"]
[Black "B.Predojevic-A.Morozevich  Sarajevo 2008  French Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ An initial position of the Classical French has been reached. White enjoys more space but Black has many dynamic resources at his disposal, some of which we will see in this game. }
7... a6
{ Preparing queenside expansion with ...b7-b5.   Other common options are: -  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5   -  7...Be7   -  7...Qb6  . }
8. Ne2
{ White enables c2-c3 to strengthen his centre. On the other hand, his queenside is now left somewhat unattended, a fact that Black immediately exploits.   The flexible  8.Qd2  is much more popular in practice. }
8... Qb6
{ A key move in many variations of the French, and rather natural here as White can no longer reply 9. Na4. }
9. Qc1
{ After  9.Qc1  , at this point  9...cxd4  10.Nexd4  Bc5  11.c3  might yield White a slight advantage; however, Morozevich has a much more challenging idea in mind. }
9... g5
{ An energetic pawn advance, which exists in several French lines and related structures. Black tries to soften up the enemy centre, exploiting the fact that any capture on g5 would weaken the d4-pawn and, indirectly, its colleague on e5. }
10. c3
{ The most solid reply.   Both:  10.Nxg5  cxd4  11.Bf2  Bc5   @@StartBracket@@and  10.fxg5  cxd4  11.Nexd4  Ncxe5  look promising for Black@@EndBracket@@   While the greedy  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Bxc5  Nxc5  12.Nxg5  is well met by  12...h6  , preparing 13...Ne4, with great compensation for the pawn. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4
{ After  11.Nexd4  gxf4  12.Bxf4  Bg7  Black has some pressure on the e5-pawn. Even so, this might be White's lesser evil, in view of what follows in the game. }
11... Bb4+ 12. Kf2
{ White's king is forced to a more dangerous location; since both  12.Nc3  and  12.Bd2  drop the d4-pawn after  12...g4  . }
12... f6
{ Another typical French pawn advance, which further destabilizes White's centre and lets Black open the f-file towards the enemy king. }
13. g3
{ Predojevic tries to keep his pawn chain intact, aware that  13.exf6  Nxf6  would just help Black in activating his knight. }
13... g4
{ An improvement on the earlier game V.Topalov-A.Morozevich, Morelia/Linares 2007, which continued  13...Rf8  14.Kg2  g4  15.Nh4  and White managed to consolidate. }
14. Nh4 fxe5 15. fxe5
{ Forced; since  15.dxe5  fails to  15...Bc5   @@StartBracket@@but not  15...d4  16.Nxd4  Nxd4  17.Qc4  @@EndBracket@@  16.Bxc5  @@StartBracket@@otherwise 16...d4 follows@@EndBracket@@  16...Nxc5  , with ...Nd3+ next - Erenburg. }
15... Ndxe5
{ A strong positional sacrifice that blows up the enemy centre and clears new lines towards the white monarch.   In contrast, both  15...Rf8+  and  15...O-O+  would just help White to secure his king by  16.Kg2  . }
16. dxe5 d4 17. Bf4 Rf8
{ With this and his next move, Black brings more pieces to the battle, whereas White has considerable difficulties in doing the same thing due to the poor coordination of his forces.   Of course  17...d3+  18.Be3  was less to the point. }
18. Kg2 Bd7 19. h3
{ Clearing some space for the king.  19.Qc2  was impossible due to  19...Nxe5  20.Bxe5  Bc6+  21.Kg1  d3+  22.Bd4  Qxd4+  23.Nxd4  dxc2  , with ...Bc5 next - Erenburg. }
19... d3 20. hxg4
{ White gives the piece back in order to relieve his defence to some extent.   Instead,  20.Nc3  was strongly met by  20...Nxe5  preparing ...Bc6+   While after  20.Be3  Qa5  21.Nf4  Nxe5  22.Kh2  Rc8  Black's initiative is overwhelming; e.g.  23.Qd1  Rc2+  24.Bg2  Rxf4  25.Bxf4  Nf3+  26.Nxf3  gxf3  27.Rg1  Qd5  with a clear advantage - Erenburg. }
20... dxe2 21. Bxe2 Nd4
{ Black has emerged with a pleasant advantage - his pieces are more active and the white king remains exposed. }
22. Qe3
{ A bad place for the queen, as Black's next move will show.   More resilient was  22.Bf3  not shying away from the exchange of the 'good' bishop; e.g.  22...Nxf3   @@StartBracket@@Erenburg suggests  22...Rc8  , followed by ...Rc2+, as a better choice. @@EndBracket@@  23.Nxf3  Bc6  24.Rh6  with counterplay - Erenburg. }
22... Bc5 23. b4
{ The only defence against the multiple threats: 23...Qxb2, 23...Bc6+ and 23...Nc2. }
23... Qxb4 24. Rhb1
{ This leaves the other rook badly placed on a1.   After  24.Rab1  Bc6+  25.Kh3  Nxe2  26.Qxe2  Qe4  Black will end up with a clearly better endgame - Erenburg, but the text lets him go for more. }
24... Qa5 25. Kh3
{ Or  25.Rd1  O-O-O  26.Rac1  Ba4  , when  27.Rxd4  Rxd4  28.Qxd4  fails to  28...Bc6+  . The text avoids any such checks but, unfortunately, also lets Black win material. }
25... Nxe2 26. Qxe2 Bd4 { The drawback of White's 24th move becomes evident. }
27. Bh6 Rf2 28. Qe4 Bxa1 29. Rxa1 O-O-O
{ With the black king secured and ...Bc6 coming up, the game is practically over. }
30. Bg5 Bc6 31. Rc1 Qd5 { Obstructing any attempts with Rxc6+. } 32. Qxh7 Qxa2
{ Installing a decisive mating threat. } 33. Rxc6+ bxc6 34. Nf3 Rxf3 35. Bxd8
Kxd8
{ Seeing that the black king easily escapes from the checks via c7-b6, White resigned. }
