[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.5 Flank Advances"]
[Black "Ru.Sadykov-E.Sveshnikov  Cheliabinsk 2004  Semi-Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In the Open Sicilian there are many lines with an early g2-g4, as we already witnessed in Naiditsch-Belov and Hracek-Bönsch. Even in the Open Games there are cases of this advance; e.g.   1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.g4  , as introduced by Shirov.   You can also find it in the English -  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.g4  - and in several Indian Defences. }
1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The idea carried out by White on the seventh move in this game can be found in various openings, such as the Queen's Gambit:  3...Be7  4.cxd5   @@StartBracket@@or  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.g4  as in S.Mamedyarov-R.Ponomariov, Dortmund 2010@@EndBracket@@  exd5  5.Bf4  Nf6  6.e3  Bf5  7.Qb3  Nc6  8.g4  as played in L.Aronian-V.Kramnik, Monte Carlo @@StartBracket@@blindfold rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2011 }
4. Nf3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2
{ In this standard position of the Semi-Slav,  6.Bd3  is another direction, when Black usually replies  6...dxc4  7.Bxc4  b5  , followed by ...a7-a6 and ...c6-c5, giving rise to the Meran System. In contrast,  6.Qc2  can be regarded as a useful move while awaiting Black's next step. }
6... Bd6 7. g4
{ Just as in the previous games, White launches a flank advance at quite an early stage of the battle. This move caused astonishment at the time of its invention by Shirov and Shabalov in the early nineties, but twenty years later it has an established place in opening theory. Although White seems, at first sight, to be intending a quick kingside attack, the main idea behind 7. g4 is quite another: to dislodge the knight on f6 by ...g4-g5, and then exploit its absence with a timely e3-e4 break.   By the way, the immediate  7.e4  has proved less promising after  7...dxe4  8.Nxe4  Nxe4  9.Qxe4  Bb4+   Or  9...c5  . We will soon see that things are a bit different when e3-e4 is effected without a black knight on f6. }
7... Nxg4
{ A principled reaction.   Other common replies are:  7...h6  , preventing g4-g5   7...Bb4  , preparing to meet g4-g5 by ...Ne4   And  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  e5  , striking back in the centre. In the last case, play often continues  9.g5  Nd5  10.Bd2  , followed by 11. Ne4. Or even the immediate  10.Ne4  , with a fierce battle for the central squares. }
8. Rg1
{ One key circumstance which makes the 7. g4 line work is that 6...Bd6 has left the g7-pawn undefended.   Here,  8.Rg1  Nxh2  and  8...f5  are Black's main choices, but Sveshnikov's next move is fully playable as well. }
8... Qf6 9. Rxg4 Qxf3 10. Rxg7 Nf8
{ The natural  10...Nf6  permits  11.Rg5  , with the threat 12. Bg2,   While the simple  11.h3  has also had good results in practice. Now, on the other hand, the threat of 11...Ng6 makes White withdraw his rook on less voluntary terms. }
11. Rg1 Bxh2
{ Black grabs a pawn, at the cost of delaying development.   Safer was  11...Ng6  12.Be2  Qf6  13.Bd2  Bd7  with complex play. }
12. Be2 Qf6 13. Rh1 Bd6 14. e4
{ An energetic pawn advance that hands the initiative to White. As seen in the following subvariations, his choice is tactically well-founded. }
14... Bb4
{ After  14...Qxd4  15.Be3  Qf6  16.O-O-O  Black is already under strong pressure; e.g.  16...d4  17.e5  Bxe5  18.Ne4  Qd8  19.f4  Bg7  20.c5  , preparing Nd6+  @@StartBracket@@ Sadykov @@EndBracket@@ .   And  14...dxe4  15.Nxe4  Qd8   @@StartBracket@@Or  15...Qxd4  16.Bd2  - Sadykov@@EndBracket@@  16.Nxd6+  Qxd6  17.Be3  , followed by O-O-O, also gives White plenty of compensation for the pawn. }
15. Be3
{ The most appealing solution. White just keeps on bringing his pieces out, aware that Black's king has no safe destiny anywhere on the board. }
15... dxe4 16. O-O-O Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Rg8
{ Activating the rook and avoiding any skewers on the a1-h8 diagonal.   In the event of  17...Bd7  White could consider  18.Rdg1  , enabling a future Bg5. }
18. Qb3 { White prevents ...Bd7 and prepares d4-d5 at the same time. } 18... b6
19. d5
{ The position was begging for this move, which clears new lines for White's pieces towards the enemy king. }
19... Bd7
{ After  19...c5  20.Qc2  White also keeps up the pressure; e.g.  20...exd5  21.cxd5  Qe5  22.Rh4  f5  23.d6  with compensation - Sadykov. }
20. dxc6 Bxc6 21. c5
{ White just keeps on attacking, not caring about the possible exposure of his king on the c-file. }
21... Nd7 22. Rd6 Rc8 23. Bb5 Bxb5 24. Qxb5 Rc7 25. Rhd1 Rg5
{ After this pseudo-active move, Black's position falls apart immediately.   25...Qe7  was critical, on which Sadykov's main line goes  26.b4  Rg6  27.Rc6  Qd8  28.cxb6  Rxc6+  29.Qxc6  axb6  30.Qxe4  Qc7+  31.Kb1  h5  32.b5  Rg4  33.f4  with compensation for the pawn, but nothing more. }
26. Kb1
{ Now the double threat at d7 and g5 proves irresistible and Black is just left with desperate moves. }
26... a6 27. Qxa6 Rgxc5 28. Bxc5 bxc5 29. Qb5 Qd8 30. a4
{ A new player enters the field, exhausting the enemy defences. } 30... Qc8 31.
a5 Ke7 32. a6 Nf6 33. Rd8 *

