[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "The role of the centre"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ By now we are well aware of the fact that the centre is not an element of the opening phase exclusively, but keeps its relevance in the middlegame battle as well. Here I would like to repeat a few strategic principles with relation to the centre:   1.--  The side that controls the centre has a greater freedom of actions on the whole board.   1.--  An attack on the flank is often well met by a counterstrike in the centre.   1.--  Without sufficient control of the centre, an attack on the flank is less likely to succeed.   1.--  Note that these are not absolute truths, but just principles, which nevertheless have kept their validity over the years. In the next five games we will see them in action again. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "V.Bologan-H.Westerinen  Gausdal 1991  Italian Game "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3
{ Nowadays, this is the most popular way of treating the Italian.   Adherents of open positions can consider  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  instead. }
4... Bc5 5. c3 a6 6. Bb3
{ A typical prophylactic measure in this line, and Black actually makes a similar one three moves later. }
6... d6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. h3 Ba7 9. Nf1
{ One key feature in this opening system, designed by Moldavian trainer Chebanenko and frequently used by his students such as Bologan, is that the knight manoeuvre Nbd2-f1-g3 is executed before castling. Thus White saves on the Re1 move, compared with similar positions in the Spanish. }
9... Ne7
{ Black 'copies' the opponent's idea.   Another option is  9...d5  , when White usually replies  10.Qe2  , keeping the light square control while avoiding the exchange of queens. }
10. Ng3 Ng6 11. O-O h6 12. d4
{ With the knight on g6 hindering the standard attacking plan of Nh4, Ngf5, Qf3 etc, White prefers to set up a pawn centre. }
12... exd4
{ This capture leaves White with an extra pawn in the centre, a common situation in defences characterized by a strong fianchetto bishop such as the Grünfeld and Benoni, but less advisable in the current structure.   12...Re8  and  12...Bd7  were reasonable options, keeping the tension while getting on with development. }
13. cxd4 d5 14. e5 Ne4
{ This was probably Black's point when deciding upon 12...exd4. Unfortunately, the centralized knight will have to depart at once after White's next move. }
15. Bc2 Nh4
{ 15...f5  obviously drops a pawn after  16.exf6   But  15...Nxg3  16.fxg3  c5  was a lesser evil, putting some pressure on White's centre, even if the latter keeps the advantage after  17.Be3  . The text has the drawback of leaving the centre completely in White's hands. }
16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 Qxd4 19. Bf4
{ Bologan gets on with development and, at the same time, reinforces his central grip. After Rad1 on the next move he will in fact be controlling all four central squares, which leaves him ready to take action on the whole board.   Of course  19.Bxb7  Bxb7  20.Qxb7  Qxe5  was less to the point. }
19... c6
{ In the event of  19...Qxb2  , White has  20.Rfb1  Qd4  21.Rd1  Qa4  22.Bxh6  gxh6  23.Qg3+  Kh8  24.Qf4  Kg7  25.Rd3  with a decisive attack, just like later on in the game. }
20. Rad1 Qb4
{ This time  20...Qxb2  is strongly met by  21.Qg3  Kh8  22.e6  , intending Be5. }
21. Bxh6
{ With the centre completely under his control, White launches a strong attack on Black's king, in which the pawn on e5 plays a crucial role by shielding its fellow pieces and controlling the key square on f6. }
21... gxh6 22. Qg3+ Kh8 23. Qf4 Kg7 24. Rd3 Re8
{ Or  24...f5  25.exf6+  Rxf6  26.Rg3+  Kf7  27.Bg6+  , winning the queen. }
25. Rg3+ Kf8 26. Qxh6+ Ke7 27. Qh4+
{ A clever check that obliges the retreat of Black's king; now that  27.Qh4+  Kd7  fails to  28.Bf5+  . }
27... Kf8 28. a3
{ One more intermediate move to force Black's queen to a rather less favourable square. }
28... Qd4
{ The only move; since  28...Qxb2  runs into  29.Qh6+  Ke7  30.Qd6   While  28...Qc5  is met by  29.Bh7  - Cu.Hansen. }
29. Qh6+ Ke7 30. Qf6+ Kd7
{ This loses the queen; but  30...Kf8  31.Bh7  was terminal anyway. } 31. Rd3
Qxd3 32. Bxd3 { In this hopeless position, Black resigned. } *

