[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "P.Eljanov-V.Akopian  European Cup, Ohrid 2009  Catalan Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3
{ Instead of entering a Semi-Slav battle with  5.Bg5  or  5.e3  , White takes the game into Catalan waters. }
5... dxc4
{ A principled reaction, exploiting the fact that with Nc3 already on the board White can't easily recover the pawn.   The flexible  5...Nbd7  is popular as well. }
6. Bg2 b5 7. Ne5 Nd5
{ Black can also consider  7...a6  , when  8.Nxc6  Qb6  is quite inoffensive for him. }
8. a4
{ Immediately attacking the enemy pawn phalanx, before Black consolidates by ...Bb7 and ...a7-a6. }
8... Bb4 9. O-O
{ More energetic than the obvious  9.Bd2  . In Eljanov's own words, 'a real Catalan player should be ready to prefer to sac a second pawn to win a few tempi!'. }
9... O-O
{ Eljanov analyses  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Ra3  when both  11...Bb4   @@StartBracket@@and  11...b4  12.Rxc3  bxc3  13.Ba3  @@EndBracket@@  12.axb5  Bxa3  13.Bxa3  lead to an overwhelming initiative for White   As does  9...Bxc3  10.e4  Bxb2  11.Bxb2  Ne7  12.d5  .   On the other hand,  9...f6  10.e4  Ne7  was quite a reasonable choice; e.g.  11.Nf3  O-O  12.axb5  Bxc3  13.bxc3  cxb5  14.Ba3  Rf7  with unclear play in M.Ulibin-I.Salgado Lopez, Cappelle la Grande 2009. In effect, positions of a double-edged nature often require non-standard moves, such as  9...f6  in this case. In contrast, the text lets White retain his powerful central knight on e5 for the rest of the game. }
10. axb5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 cxb5
{ After  11...Nxc3  12.Qc2  Nxb5  13.e3  White soon recovers the pawns with a clear positional plus. }
12. Ba3 Re8 13. e4 Nf6 { This time  13...Nxc3  is strongly met by  14.Qf3  . }
14. Qb1
{ A rare, but good place for the queen, where she overprotects the e4-pawn and exerts some pressure along the b-file.   14.f4  at once was also possible   Whereas the tempting  14.Nxf7  doesn't yield more than a draw after  14...Kxf7  15.e5  Nd5  16.Qh5+  Kg8  17.Be4  g6  18.Bxg6  hxg6  19.Qxg6+  Kh8  20.Rfe1  Nxc3  21.Re3  Bb7  , since both  22.g4   @@StartBracket@@and  22.Rxc3  Nc6  23.g4  Qh4  @@EndBracket@@  Ne2+  23.Rxe2  Nc6  24.Re3  Qh4  let Black parry the mate on the h-file - Eljanov. }
14... a6 15. f4 Qc7 { The immediate  15...Bb7  fails to  16.Nxc4  . } 16. g4
{ White has achieved an unusually strong grip on the centre, combining a centralized knight with a heavy pawn centre. In consequence, nothing speaks against a full-scale attack on the kingside, where Black is rather short of defenders. }
16... Bb7 17. g5 Nfd7 18. Ra2
{ A neat way of including the second rook in the attack by preparing to swing along the second rank. }
18... Nc6 19. Raf2 Rab8
{ For his part, Black prepares the only possible attempt for counterplay, the ...b5-b4 advance. }
20. Qd1 a5 21. Qh5 Ndxe5
{ Thus Black assures ...b5-b4 on the next move, but the clearance of the f-file will play heavily against him in the further course of the game.   Instead,  21...g6  22.Qh6  b4  23.f5  leads to a crushing attack after  23...exf5  24.exf5  Nf8  25.Ng4  - Eljanov   So the awkward-looking  21...Nd8  was the only way to keep up the fight, when White could consider  22.Ng4  , preparing the advance f4-f5.   By the way, had Black opted for  21...Nd8!  , then the analogous  22.Rf3  would have failed to  22...Bxe4  . }
22. fxe5 b4 23. Bb2 Rbd8 24. Rf3
{ White refrains from the materialistic  24.Rxf7  Re7  25.R7f4  Qb6  with unclear play, and simply sends the rook to h3. }
24... g6
{ Or  24...bxc3  25.Rh3  , when both   @@StartBracket@@  25.Bxc3  is also possible@@EndBracket@@  25...cxb2   @@StartBracket@@and  25...h6  26.gxh6  g6  27.Qg5  Qe7  28.h7+  Kh8  29.Bc1  @@EndBracket@@  26.Qxh7+  Kf8  27.Qh8+  Ke7  28.Rxf7+  Kxf7  29.g6+  are fatal for Black - Eljanov. With the text Akopian prepares a light square blockade at the cost of a pawn, but it soon proves insufficient. }
25. Qh6 f5 26. gxf6 Qf7 27. Qe3
{ Supporting the d4-pawn and preparing a final assault with h4-h5. } 27... Rd7
28. h4 Red8 29. h5 bxc3 30. Bxc3 Nxd4 31. Rg3
{ Now the g6-pawn falls, and the rest is rather easy for White. } 31... Nb5 32.
hxg6 hxg6 33. Qh6 Qh7 34. Rxg6+ Kh8 35. Bxa5 Ra8 36. Qg5 Rg8 37. f7
{ A nice intermediate move to divert the black queen from the h-file. } 37...
Rxf7 38. Rxf7 Rxg6 { Obviously  38...Qxf7  runs into the reply  39.Rh6+  . }
39. Qd8+ Rg8 40. Rxh7+ Kxh7 41. Qh4+ Kg6 42. Bd2 *

