[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "A.Kotov-I.Boleslavsky  USSR Championship,  Moscow 1945  Trompowsky’s Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The same idea is often applied by Black in the Pirc; e.g.  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.Be3  c6  5.Qd2  b5  6.Bd3  Nbd7  , delaying ...Bg7 until the moment is right, such as when White castles short. }
1... Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 d6
{ A modest, but fully playable reply to the Trompowsky. Nowadays,  3...c5  and  3...d5  are more frequent options. }
4. f3 Nf6 5. e4 g6 6. Qd2 Nbd7
{ Aware that Bh6 might be in the air, Boleslavsky delays  6...Bg7  and develops the queenside first. }
7. Bh6
{ White is eager to start a kingside attack, but it made sense to bring out a few more pieces first; e.g. starting with  7.Nc3  . }
7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 c5
{ Black responds to the flank attack with a counterstrike at White's centre. We saw a similar case in Milu-Zaitsev. }
9. c3
{ This attempt to maintain the pawn centre is strongly punished by the opponent's next move.   After  9.d5  Qb6  and an opportune ...e7-e6, Black grabs the initiative too.   But the developing  9.dxc5  Nxc5   @@StartBracket@@or  9...Qa5+  @@EndBracket@@  10.Nc3  was reasonable. }
9... Qb6 10. Qd2
{ A sad retreat for White, but due to his lagging development it was the only way to avoid material losses. In contrast, with his queen's knight already on d2 or a3, he could have played 10. Nc4 at this point. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 e5
{ Kotov gets no time to rest. Now the absence of his dark-squared bishop is strongly felt. }
12. Na3
{ 12.d5  O-O  , preparing ...Nh5 and ...f7-f5, yields Black a definite initiative   While in the event of  12.Nc3  , he could try  12...d5  as in the game; e.g.  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.exd5  O-O  with interesting compensation for the pawn.   With  12.Na3  White was probably hoping for  12...exd4  13.Nc4  Qc5  14.b4  , followed by 15. Qxd4, but Black has a much stronger move at his disposal. }
12... d5
{ One more central strike, preventing Nc4 and clearing the e-file for future actions towards the enemy king. }
13. dxe5
{ After  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.dxe5  Ne3  15.Nc4  Nxc4  16.Bxc4  Nxe5  17.Qe2  Qb4+  , followed by ...O-O, White is also in trouble - Ftacnik. }
13... Nxe5 14. Bb5+
{ Seeing that  14.exd5  O-O  , followed by ...Re8@@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@ , yields Black a strong attack, Kotov tries to bring out his pieces quickly. }
14... Kf8
{ There was nothing wrong with  14...Bd7  15.Bxd7+  Nexd7  , followed by ...O-O and ...Rfe8+, but Boleslavsky wants the bishop on b5 as a future target. }
15. exd5 Kg7 16. Ne2
{ Or  16.O-O-O  Bf5  , followed by ...Rac8+ with a great attack. } 16... a6 17.
Bc4
{ Both  17.Ba4  Bf5  , preparing ...Nd3+   And  17.Bd3  Qxb2  cause White even bigger problems. }
17... Re8 18. Rd1
{ This lets Black land a strong tactical blow.   18.Kf1  Bf5  19.Rd1  was essential - Ftacnik, although after  19...Rac8  it is in fact not easy to save White; e.g.  20.b3  Qd6  21.Qb2  fails to  21...b5  . }
18... Bh3 { White's dubious opening strategy receives its final punishment. }
19. Kf1
{ Ftacnik also analyses  19.f4  Bxg2  20.fxe5  Rxe5  21.Rf1  Bxf1  22.Kxf1  Rf5+  with a decisive attack. }
19... Nxf3 20. Qf4
{ The attempt to prevent Black's next move in the game by  20.Qc3  fails to  20...Re3  . }
20... Ng4 21. Qxf3 Ne3+ 22. Ke1 Bxg2 23. Qf2 Bxh1
{ With an extra exchange and the attack still intact, the rest is easy for Black. }
24. Rd3 Qb4+ 25. Rd2 Rac8 26. Bb3 Bxd5 27. Bxd5 Nxd5 28. Qd4+ Qxd4 29. Rxd4 Nf6
