[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "I.Glek-Ch.Lutz  German League 1992  Sicilian Defence, Kan Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ This encounter is taken from my book 'Play the Sicilian Kan' and can be regarded as a model game for that opening variation. Just like most other Open Sicilians, White has to play aggressively to aspire at any advantage, a fact that often leads to his centre being exposed to a counterblow, as on move 18 in this game. }
6. Bd3
{ A typical deployment in the Kan, which was possible on the previous move as well. }
6... Nf6 7. f4 d6
{ Black opts for a Hedgehog set-up.   The sharper  7...b5  8.e5  b4  is also popular in practice. }
8. O-O b5 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Kh1 Nbd7 11. Bd2 Be7 12. Rae1
{ A natural choice, by which White brings his last piece into play, thus getting ready for actions in the centre and on the kingside.   Even so,  12.b4  , preparing a2-a4 to establish a queenside grip, is probably a more critical try. }
12... Nc5
{ A clever move with several functions: an exchange on d3 is enabled; the threat of 13...b4 winning a pawn is created; and the d7-square is vacated for the other knight in the event of e4-e5.   In contrast, the immediate  12...O-O  would invite  13.e5  . }
13. b4
{ White forces the swap on d3 in order to stabilize his centre.   Instead,  13.e5  is well met by the discrete  13...Nfd7   While after  13.a3  O-O  14.Rf3  Rfe8  15.Rh3  g6  , preparing ...Bf8-g7, Black has no major problems. }
13... Nxd3 14. cxd3 O-O
{ An approximately equal position has emerged. Admittedly the exchange on d3 reinforced White's centre, but on the other hand he will miss that bishop in a future kingside attack. }
15. Rc1
{ The further course of the game suggests that  15.g4  at once might be more precise. Here Black should favour the prophylactic  15...Rfe8   @@StartBracket@@avoiding both  15...d5  16.e5  , and  15...e5  16.Nf5  , followed by  16...--  17.g5  @@EndBracket@@  16.g5  Nd7  17.f5  Bf8  18.fxe6  fxe6  19.Rc1  Qd8  , intending ...Ne5 and ...Rc8 with a compact position. }
15... Qd7 16. g4
{ A tempting flank advance, but Black turns out to be well prepared.   16.Nb3  Rac8  17.Be3  , followed by Bd4, was a safer choice. }
16... e5 17. Nf5
{ Or  17.fxe5  dxe5  18.Nf5  Rfd8  19.g5  Ne8  with counterplay against d3 and b4. }
17... exf4 18. Rxf4
{ 18.g5  obviously failed to  18...Qxf5   @@StartBracket@@while after  18.Kg1  Bd8  both  19.Bxf4   and  19.g5  Bb6+  20.d4  Nxe4  @@EndBracket@@  19...d5  20.e5  d4  21.exf6  dxc3  , followed by 22... Re8, favour Black.   Finally,  18.Bxf4  can be met in the same way as the text. }
18... d5
{ A key move of the game, by which Black secures a lot of counterplay along the central files and the h1-a8 diagonal, with a distracting effect upon White's attack. In fact, the idea of responding to g2-g4 with ...d7-d5 at some moment has quite an old record in the Sicilian, and Dvoretsky covered the subject rather extensively in 'Opening Preparation'. }
19. g5 dxe4 20. dxe4
{ The consistent  20.gxf6  failed to  20...exd3+  21.Ne4  Qxf5  22.Rxf5  dxe2  23.fxe7  Bxe4+  24.Kg1  Bxf5  25.exf8=Q+  Kxf8   While  20.Nxe7+  Qxe7  21.gxf6  exd3+  22.Ne4  Qxf6  yields Black a strong initiative; e.g.  23.Qxd3  Qd8  with ...f7-f5 coming up. }
20... Nxe4
{ An intuitive sacrifice that proves to be tactically well-founded. } 21. Nxe7+
{ After  21.Nxe4  Bxg5  White will soon have to return more material; e.g.  22.Rg1  f6  23.h4  Rae8  24.hxg5  Rxe4  25.Rxe4  Qxf5  26.Rg4  Re8  etc. }
21... Qxe7 22. Nxe4 Rae8 23. Kg1
{ Or  23.Re1  f5  24.gxf6  Rxf6  and the knight is doomed. } 23... Bxe4 24. Re1
{ Glek had put his hopes in this new pin, but it is not nearly as effective as the previous one. }
24... Qxg5+ 25. Rg4 Bd3 { Black maintains his material advantage. } 26. Bxg5
Bxe2 27. Rg3 Bh5 28. Be7 f5 29. Rge3 Rf7 30. Bc5 Rxe3 31. Rxe3
{ Opposite-coloured bishops are famous for their drawing effect, but with one pair of rooks still on the board, White should be helpless against the connected passed pawns. }
31... Rd7 32. Ra3 Rd2
{ By  32...Rd1+  33.Kf2  Rd2+   Or  33...f4  Black would have made significant progress. At this point both players probably suffered from time trouble. }
33. Rxa6 Bf3 34. h4 h6 35. a4 { Exchanging more pawns. } 35... bxa4 36. Rxa4
Rg2+ 37. Kf1 Rg4 38. Be7 Re4 39. Ra7 f4 40. Bd6
{ Despite reasonable chances for a draw, the official scoresheet indicates that White lost at this moment. In any case, the turbulent conclusion of the game doesn't take away its instructive merits. }
*

