20... Nxe4
{ An intuitive sacrifice that proves to be tactically well-founded. } 21. Nxe7+
{ After  21.Nxe4  Bxg5  White will soon have to return more material; e.g.  22.Rg1  f6  23.h4  Rae8  24.hxg5  Rxe4  25.Rxe4  Qxf5  26.Rg4  Re8  etc. }
21... Qxe7 22. Nxe4 Rae8 23. Kg1
{ Or  23.Re1  f5  24.gxf6  Rxf6  and the knight is doomed. } 23... Bxe4 24. Re1
{ Glek had put his hopes in this new pin, but it is not nearly as effective as the previous one. }
24... Qxg5+ 25. Rg4 Bd3 { Black maintains his material advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "L.D.Nisipeanu-R.Dautov  German League 2003  Caro-Kann Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3
{ The King's Indian Attack, a practical choice when you are not up to a heavy theoretical discussion. }
2... d5 3. Nd2 e5 4. Ngf3 Bd6
{ A logical set-up, which exploits the support that ...c7-c6 gives to the pawn centre. }
5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Re1 Bg4
{ Other main options are  8...Nbd7  and  8...a5  , preparing ...Na6-c5, in both cases waiting with the queen's bishop until the moment is right. }
9. c3
{ Here and on the following two moves,  9.h3  was more precise, in order to force the bishop to h5 - Dautov. }
9... Nbd7 10. Qc2 Qc7 11. Nf1
{ This was White's last chance for  11.h3  , when  11...Bh5   @@StartBracket@@while  11...Be6  12.Ng5  gains the bishop pair@@EndBracket@@  12.Nh4  , heading for f5, also yields him a minimal initiative. }
11... h6
{ Black prevents Ng5, so that the bishop can retreat to e6 without any risk of being exchanged. }
12. Ne3 Be6 13. Nh4 a5
{ A useful move which gains some space while awaiting the opponent's next step. }
14. Qe2
{ Aware that  14.Nhf5  yields little after  14...Bf8  , followed by ...g7-g6, White prefers to reinforce his future kingside attack with a queen transfer to f3. }
14... Rad8 15. Qf3 Bf8 16. Bf1
{ Both sides are using considerable prophylaxis.   The immediate  16.Nhf5  backfires after  16...g6  17.g4  Nc5  , hitting d3 - Dautov. }
16... Kh7
{ Black has defended his kingside rather carefully, his two last moves fulfilling the purpose of overprotecting the h6-pawn, so that Ne @@StartBracket@@h4@@EndBracket@@ -f5 can be met by ...g7-g6. }
17. g4
{ White gets on with the attack, but we will soon see that his position doesn't support such aggression.   The modest  17.h3  , preparing Ne3-g4, was a better choice - Dautov. }
17... g6
{ Covering the vital f5-square.   In contrast, the impulsive  17...dxe4  18.dxe4  Nc5  , heading for d3, runs into  19.Nef5  g6  20.Nxh6  Nfxe4  21.Qh3  with an attack - Dautov. }
18. Nef5
{ The only way to justify the previous move.   Now after  18.Nef5  there appear ideas like  18...--  19.Qh3   and  19.Nxh6  Bxh6  20.g5  , so Black must react with care. }
18... dxe4 19. dxe4 gxf5 20. gxf5 Bd5
{ A key decision, which was probably already foreseen by Dautov when making his 17th move. By returning the piece in this way, Black obtains a firm grip on the centre, and both his rooks will prove ideally placed. }
21. exd5 cxd5 22. Qh3 e4
{ Parrying the threat of Nf3-g5 and vacating the e5-square for the knight, from where it can reach several interesting destinies such as g4, f3 and d3. }
23. Kh1
{ A natural move; however, the undefended f2-pawn will soon play against White tactically.   23.Be2  Ne5  24.Ng2  was correct, improving the passive knight, when  24...Bg7  25.Bf4  Qb6  26.Qg3  Nfd7  , heading for c5, keeps Black's advantage - Dautov. }
23... Ne5 24. Bf4 Bd6
{ By now the merits of Black's 20th move are clearly appreciated. His strong pawn centre, well supported by the rest of his pieces, gives him a very dominant position, whereas White's kingside attack has reached a dead end. }
25. Be2
{ The aggressive alternative  25.Nf3  failed fatally to  25...Neg4  , so Nisipeanu opts to prevent ...Neg4. Unfortunately for him, the knight has another great destiny at its disposal. }
25... Nd3 26. Bxd6
{ A tactical oversight in time trouble.   After  26.Bxd3  Bxf4  27.Bb5  Rg8  White's game is strategically very difficult, but the text loses material. }
26... Nxf2+ 27. Kg2 Qb6
{ A clever intermediate move which lets Black simplify to an endgame with a sound extra pawn. }
28. Qg3 { Or  28.Bc7  Rg8+  29.Ng6  Qxc7  30.Kxf2  fxg6  , winning - Dautov. }
28... Rg8 29. Ng6 Rxd6 30. Qxf2 fxg6
{ A pawn down and worse on the whole board, White resigned. } *

