11... h6
{ Black prevents Ng5, so that the bishop can retreat to e6 without any risk of being exchanged. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.6 The Role of the Centre"]
[Black "Exercise #2: L.D.Nisipeanu-R.Dautov"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3rrb2/1pqn1ppk/2p1bn1p/p2pp3/4P1PN/2PPNQ2/PP3P1P/R1B1RBK1 b - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17... g6
{ Covering the vital f5-square.   In contrast, the impulsive  17...dxe4  18.dxe4  Nc5  , heading for d3, runs into  19.Nef5  g6  20.Nxh6  Nfxe4  21.Qh3  with an attack - Dautov. }
18. Nef5
{ The only way to justify the previous move.   Now after  18.Nef5  there appear ideas like  18...--  19.Qh3   and  19.Nxh6  Bxh6  20.g5  , so Black must react with care. }
18... dxe4 19. dxe4 gxf5 20. gxf5 Bd5
{ A key decision, which was probably already foreseen by Dautov when making his 17th move. By returning the piece in this way, Black obtains a firm grip on the centre, and both his rooks will prove ideally placed. }
21. exd5 cxd5 22. Qh3 e4
{ Parrying the threat of Nf3-g5 and vacating the e5-square for the knight, from where it can reach several interesting destinies such as g4, f3 and d3. }
*

