[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "A.Strikovic-R.Mascarinas  Geneva 1991  Sicilian Defence,  King’s Indian Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d3
{ The King's Indian Attack can be used against a variety of defences, including the Sicilian.   Another popular way of launching it is with  2.Nf3  and only then  2...--  3.d3  . }
2... Nc6 3. g3 d5 4. Nd2 dxe4 5. dxe4 g6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. Ngf3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9.
Re1
{ Probably the most exact choice; since  9.c3  permits  9...Qd3   While  9.Qe2  Bg4  , followed by  10.--  10...Nd4  or  10...Ne5  , also makes life a bit easier for Black.   After  9.Re1  on the other hand,  9...Bg4  can be met by  10.h3  . }
9... Qc7 10. c3 Rd8 11. Qe2 Ng4
{ Just in time, before White goes e4-e5.   A different approach is  11...e5  . }
12. Nc4 Nge5
{ 12...b6  13.Bf4  Nge5  14.Nfxe5  Nxe5  is more precise, as in L.Vogt-M.Petursson, Brocco 1990; although by  15.Ne3  e6  16.Bxe5  Bxe5  17.f4  Bg7  18.e5  Bb7  19.Rad1  White could have achieved a slight plus. }
13. Nfxe5 Nxe5 14. Bf4 Be6
