[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5
{ By this move order White avoids the sharp Botvinnik Variation arising after  4.Nc3  c6  5.Bg5  dxc4  ;   since  4.Bg5  c6  can now be met by  5.Nbd2  or  5.e3  , securing the c4-pawn. }
4... h6 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. Nc3 Bb4
{ On his part, Black refrains from transposing to the Moscow Variation with  6...c6  and takes the game to the Ragozin Defence. Who benefited from these move order tricks is only known by the players themselves. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Be2
{ More flexible than  8.Bd3  , when  8...dxc4  forces White to reply  9.Bxc4  .   Incidentally,  8.Rc1  and  8.Qb3  are also possible. }
8... dxc4 9. O-O b6
{ 9...c5  was preferable - Bartel, immediately putting some pressure on White's centre. }
10. --
