10. Ne5 { This and the following move give White a firm grip on the centre. }
10... Bb7 11. f4 Qe7
{ Black opts for a careful approach.   In the event of  11...c5  White could try  12.Bf3  Qe7  13.d5  with some initiative. }
12. Bf3 c6 13. Qc2
{ A developing move with the additional merit of enabling f4-f5. } 13... Bxc3
14. bxc3 c5 15. f5
{ White doesn't care about recovering the pawn, and tries to create opportunities on the kingside before Black is fully developed. }
15... Bxf3 16. Rxf3 Nd7
{ This accelerates White's attack.   16...exf5  17.Qxf5  Qe6  was preferable - Bartel. }
17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. f6 { Of course. } 18... e5
{ Now  18...g6  runs into  19.e4  preparing Qd2 while preventing  19...Qd5  , so Black opts for active defence. }
19. Raf1 g6 20. Rh3 Qg4 21. Rg3 Qh5 22. d5
{ After  22.Rf5  g5   @@StartBracket@@and  22...Qh4  23.Rh3  Qg4  24.Rxe5  is similar@@EndBracket@@  23.Rxe5  , White has a big advantage - Bartel. }
22... Rfe8
{ For his part, Black misses  22...e4  23.Qxe4  Rad8  with counterplay. } 23.
e4 Kh7 24. Qd2 g5 25. Rf5 Rg8 { 25...Kg6  was the last chance - Bartel. } 26.
Rxe5 Qg6 27. Rexg5 Qxg5 28. Rxg5 Rxg5 29. d6 Rd8 30. d7 b5 31. Qd6 b4 32. Qe7
bxc3 33. Qxd8 c2 34. Qh8+ Kxh8 35. d8=Q+ Kh7 36. Qd2 *

