[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "V.Antoshin-B.Ivkov  Polanica Zdroj 1970  Benoni Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7
{ The Czech Benoni, an ideal opening for players who like closed positions and aren't bothered by a space disadvantage. }
6. h3
{ With this and his next move, White aims at frustrating the typical plan ...O-O, ...Ne8, ...g7-g6, ...Ng7 and ...f7-f5.   Another popular approach is  6.g3  , followed by Bg2, Nge2, O-O and f2-f4, with completely different play. }
6... O-O 7. g4 a6
{ Black signals that he might be considering ...b7-b5 at some moment. } 8. Nf3
Nbd7 9. Bd3 Ne8 10. a3 { Copying the opponent's idea from three moves ago. }
10... g6
{ Another idea was  10...Nc7  , preparing ...b7-b5, but the text is more efficient, since it soon lets Black complete the development of all his minor pieces. }
11. Bh6 Ng7 12. Qd2 Nf6 13. b4
{ A parallel attack on both flanks can be a risky business  @@StartBracket@@cf. the game Gurevich-Piket in 'Mastering Chess Strategy' @@EndBracket@@ ;   but Black is also fine after  13.Ne2  Kh8  14.Ng3  Ng8  15.Be3  b5  as in L.Pachman-V.Ciocaltea, Harrachov 1966; e.g.  16.cxb5  axb5  17.Bxb5  f5  with a strong initiative. }
13... b6 14. Ke2
{ 14.Kf1  seems safer, followed by Kg2, and this is in fact how Gurevich dealt with the royal problem. }
14... Kh8 { Stepping off the g-file and enabling ...Ng8 if needed. } 15. Rag1
Bd7 16. Rg3 Qc7 17. Rhg1
