1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ I am sorry about bringing up this lousy line in yet another game, but it does have a tendency to produce instructive battles. }
3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. e4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ As we already discussed in Grabarczyk-Podlesny,   5...e5  is a more active choice here, which White could have avoided by playing 4. Nf3 first. }
6. Nf3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1
{ Applying the same set-up as in the abovementioned game. } 10... Qc8
{ An odd move.   10...Nbd7  , followed by ...Re8 and possibly ...Nf8-g6, was probably a better choice. }
11. Bg5 Re8 12. Rac1
