11. f3
{ A strong pawn break that undermines Black's central control and clears the f-file for the major pieces. }
11... h5
{ A useless move since the knight on g3 is about to leave the board anyway.   With  11...exf3  12.Bxf3  h5  Black could still get a decent game; e.g.  13.e4  h4  14.Nh1  Nh7  , heading for g5. }
12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. fxe4 Qxe4 14. Bd3 Qe7 15. e4
{ Thanks to his lead in development and Black's weak kingside, White is already much better. }
15... Kg7 16. Bf4 f6 17. Qd2 g5
{ The passive  17...Rh8  was called for, although Black's position remains difficult. }
18. Be3 h4 19. e5
{ Of course. Relying on his huge lead in development, White opens the position towards the enemy king. }
19... dxe5 20. dxe5 Qxe5 21. Bd4 Qa5 22. c5 { With the threat 23. Qxg5+. }
22... Kh6 23. Bxf6 Qxc5+ 24. Bd4 Qd6 25. Rxf8 Qxf8 26. Rf1
{ 'Never again would I be able to win games so easily' - Gligoric. } 26... Qe7
27. Rf6+ Kh5 28. Be2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
