[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "L.Javakhishvili-J.Avalos Parra  Gibraltar 2010  Slav Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4
{ A popular variation over the last decade. White aims to gain the bishop pair and also enjoys more space, though Black's position remains solid. }
6... Be4
{ Provoking f2-f3 before accepting the swap on g6, just as in Mateuta-Hellsten. }
7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 Qc7 9. Bd2 Bd6
{ A seemingly active place for the bishop, but this move is probably inaccurate here.   9...Be7  and  9...Nbd7  are more usual options. }
10. cxd5 exd5
{ Unfortunately,  10...cxd5  , preparing ...Nc6, now runs into  11.Nb5  , which is why the bishop would have been better off at e7.   White also has a slight edge after  10...Nxd5  11.e4  , but this might have been the least of Black's evils. }
11. O-O-O Nbd7
{ A natural developing move, but in fact it does nothing to interfere with the enemy plans.   In the event of  11...O-O  White can just reply as in the game   So  11...Qb6  , looking for a queen exchange, might be worth a try. }
12. --
