12. e4 { Of course, creating a strong pawn centre. } 12... dxe4 13. Nxg6 hxg6
14. fxe4 { Unable to prevent e4-e5, Black is already in serious trouble. }
14... Ng4 { Or  14...Bf4  15.e5  Nh5  16.Bc4  with strong pressure. } 15. e5
Be7 16. Be2 Nh6
{ After  16...Nf2  17.Rhf1  Nxd1  18.Qxf7+  Kd8  19.Qxg7  Rf8  20.Rxd1  White has a crushing advantage. }
17. g4 O-O-O 18. Kb1 Qb6 19. Qa4
{ With certain prospects for an attack, White avoids the queen's exchange. Now Black should probably have copied his opponent's previous move by 19...Kb8, making life a bit safer for his king. Instead, he tries to free himself by a knight manoeuvre, thereby forgetting about the potential of the white pawn centre. }
19... Nf8 20. d5 Bb4 { Or  20...cxd5  21.Bxh6  , followed by 22. Nxd5 etc. }
21. dxc6 bxc6 22. Nd5
{ A temporary sacrifice that opens the gates to Black's king.   22.Be3  was also strong, intending  22...Qxe3  23.Qxc6+  . }
22... Rxd5 23. Bxb4 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Ne6 25. Ba5 Qb7 26. Rd6 Kb8 27. Qd1
{ White doesn't content herself with the c6-pawn, but goes for a final attack. }
27... c5 28. Rd7 Qc6 29. Bf3 Qa6 30. Qb3+ *

