1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3
{ An initial position of the Closed Spanish has been reached.   The apparently natural  9.d4  is seen much less frequently in practice due to  9...Bg4  . }
9... h6 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8
{ Smyslov's Variation, in which Black hurries to apply some pressure down the e-file. }
12. Nf1 Bd7 13. Ng3 { A standard knight manoeuvre in this opening. } 13... Na5
14. Bc2 Nc4
{ The immediate  14...c5  is also popular in practice, with the point that the knight can sometimes retreat to c6. }
15. b3 Nb6 16. Bb2 c5 17. dxc5 dxc5 18. c4
{ With both black knights having a long journey to d4, this advance makes a lot of sense. Now both the e5-pawn and the d5-square become targets for White. }
18... Qc7 19. Bd3 Nc8
