[SetUp "1"]

19... Nc8
{ Interestingly, the same idea Nf1 had already been used by Tal:  19...Rad8  20.Qc2  b4  21.Nf1  Nh5  22.Ne3  Nf4  23.Bf1  Qd6  24.h4  Qf6  25.g3  Nd3  26.Bxd3  Qxf3  27.a3  bxa3  28.Rxa3  Bc8  29.Be2  Qf6  30.Nd5  Nxd5  31.cxd5  c4  32.bxc4  Bxa3  33.Bxa3  , followed by c4-c5 with a huge advantage, M.Tal-I.Zaitsev, USSR Championship, Alma Ata 1968. }
20. Nf1 { Heading for d5 in order to seize the centre. } 20... Na7 21. Ne3 b4
{ Since  21...Nc6  fails to  22.cxb5  - Golubev, Black must waste a tempo on securing the b-pawn. }
22. Nd5 Qd6
{ Not  22...Nxd5  23.exd5  Bd6  24.Nh4  with a strong initiative for White. }
23. Bc2 Bc8
{ 23...Nc6  was more logical, reintegrating the knight into the battle, although the sacrifice  24.Nxe5  Nxe5  25.f4  seems rather promising for White, just like in the game. }
24. Nxe5 Rxe5 25. f4 Rxd5
{ The only move; since  25...Re8  26.e5  is disastrous for Black. } 26. cxd5
Qxf4 27. e5
{ Despite his material advantage Black is in trouble due to White's great activity.   At this point the counter-sacrifice  27.e5  c4  28.exf6  c3  was perhaps worth a try, since Black's next move exposes him to a strong attack. }
27... Nh7 28. Qd3 Ng5 29. Rf1 Qh4 30. e6 Nb5
{ Or  30...f6  31.Rae1  , winning - Golubev. } 31. Rxf7 Nd6 32. Qg6 Nxh3+
{ On  32...Ndxf7  there follows  33.exf7+  Kh8  34.Qxg7+  Bxg7  35.f8=Q  - Golubev. }
33. Kf1 Nf5 34. Rxf8+ *

