1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be3
{ Quite an aggressive line, familiar to us from Beliavsky-Anand. } 6... b6 7.
Qd2 { A more flexible choice than Beliavsky's  7.e5  . } 7... Bb7 8. Bd3
{ Probably  8.e5  Ng4  9.O-O-O  is more critical, when the gambit  9...c5  10.dxc5  bxc5  11.Bxc5  Qa5  leads to a sharp battle. }
8... Na6 9. a3 c5
{ A typical counterstrike in the Austrian Attack, after which the game takes on a Benoni character. }
10. d5 Nc7 11. h3
{ A useful move that rules out ...Ng4 before castling short.   In contrast,  11.O-O-O  b5  yields Black a promising attack. }
11... b5
{ Highlighting the relationship between the b5- and e4-squares, a subject that we touched upon in Salov-Hübner with reversed colours. }
12. g4 { A careless advance.   12.O-O  was called for. } 12... --
