14. Ne5
{ A typical idea in such structures. On e5 the knight dominates the centre and facilitates an attack on the kingside. }
14... c5
{ A risky counterstrike given Black's lagging development.   14...Bxe5  15.dxe5  Nfd7  16.Ne4  is also dangerous for him   Whereas both  14...Nbd7  and  14...O-O  look like safer choices, with just a slight edge for White after  15.Bc3  . }
15. Rfe1
{ Supporting the central knight and getting ready for future actions on the kingside. }
15... O-O 16. Ne4
{ A standard attacking method - the exchange of defending pieces. } 16... Bxe5
{ This will just help the white rook join the attack with decisive effect.   While  16...Nbd7  failed to  17.Nxd7  Nxd7  18.dxc5   Correct was  16...Nxe4  17.Rxe4  cxd4  18.Qxd4  Bxe5  19.Qxe5  Nc6  20.Qg3  Ne7  , heading for f5, with chances for a successful defence. }
17. dxe5 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Nc6
{ Too late, but White's following blow was difficult to parry anyway. } 19.
Bxh6 f5
{ Or  19...gxh6  20.Rg4+  Kh8  21.Qe3  Kh7  22.Qe4+  Kh8  23.Qf4  Kh7  24.Qf6  Rg8  25.Qxf7+  Kh8  26.Rg6  etc. }
20. exf6 Rxf6 21. Rg4 { An elegant and well-calculated follow-up. } 21... Rxh6
22. Qd7 Rh7 23. h6 g5 24. Qxe6+ Kf8 25. Qf6+ Ke8 26. Qg6+
{ In view of  26.Qg6+  Rf7  27.h7  , Black resigned. } *

