[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "Di.Flores-C.Lujan  Buenos Aires 2006  English Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ We came across a similar idea in Van Wely-Guliev,  and it can also be used by Black; e.g. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  b5  instead of the more established  3...b6  . }
1... Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b4
{ A kind of improved fianchetto, which gains some extra space on the queenside. }
3... Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 c6 6. Bg2 a5 7. b5 d5
{ 7...cxb5  8.cxb5  a4  seems more consequent, followed by ...d7-d5, leaving the b5-pawn somewhat loose. }
8. Na3 { 8.bxc6  Nxc6  just helps Black. } 8... cxb5 9. cxb5 Nbd7 10. O-O Re8
{ Preparing ...e7-e5.Your move...  @@StartBracket@@+ short plan@@EndBracket@@  @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "Di.Flores-C.Lujan  Buenos Aires 2006  English Opening"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/1p1nppbp/5np1/pP1p4/8/N4NP1/PB1PPPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Rc1
{ Seizing the open file and preparing Qc2-c7. As for Black's intended pawn centre, it might actually become a burden for her later on.   In contrast,  11.Ne5  Ne4  12.d4  Nxe5  13.dxe5  Be6  leads to rather unclear play. }
11... e5 12. d3 b6
{ Probably  12...Bf8  at once was better, avoiding the weak square on c6. } 13.
Qc2 Bf8 14. Qc7
{ Without queens on the board, White's guerrilla strategy will be easier to conduct. }
14... Qxc7 15. Rxc7 Bd6 16. Rc6 Bb8 17. Rfc1 Bb7 18. Bh3
{ An elegant way of increasing the pressure at Black's camp. } 18... h5
{ Now after  18...Bxc6  19.bxc6  Nc5  20.Nb5  Re7  21.Ba3  Ng4  22.d4  White's activity and strong passed pawn more than compensate for the exchange, so Lujan instead prepares ...Ng4 to limit the annoying bishop. }
19. d4
{ A typical counterstrike softening up the dark squares, familiar from the ancient game R.Reti-F.Yates, New York 1924. }
19... Ng4
{ Curiously, from now on it is very difficult to defend Black's position.   19...e4  20.Ne5  doesn't favour her either   so the pragmatic  19...exd4  20.Bxd4  Ng4  seems like a better choice, accepting an inferior pawn structure in order to liberate the pieces. }
20. dxe5 Bxc6 21. bxc6 Nc5 22. Nb5 Rc8
{ There was the threat of 23  c7  , and  22...Bxe5  failed to  23.Nxe5  Nxe5  24.Bxe5  Rxe5  25.c7  Ree8  26.Nd6  etc. }
23. Bg2 { White shifts his focus to the long diagonal. } 23... Rxc6 24. h3 Nh6
25. Ng5 { More precise than  25.Nfd4  Bxe5  26.Nxc6  Bxb2  . } 25... Rc8 26.
Bxd5 Ra7 { If  26...Ra6  , then both  27.e6  and  27.Bb7  win for White. } 27.
Nxa7 Bxa7 28. e6 { In view of more material losses, Black resigned. } *

