1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Ne7
{ An interesting deviation from the usual 7...Nf6. On e7 the knight exerts less pressure on White's centre; on the other hand, any tactical motifs with e4-e5 are avoided. }
8. O-O Nec6
{ At first sight,  8...Nbc6  appears more natural; however, after  9.Nb3  the knight on e7 lacks a good destiny. Such a restrictive retreat is rather common in the Open Sicilian - also when Black has played ...Bd7, preparing ...Nxd4 and ...Bc6. In contrast, after the text he is ready for ...d7-d6 and ...Nd7 if White goes 9. Nb3. }
9. e5
{ White gains space but exposes his e-pawn.   Perhaps  9.Nxc6  Nxc6  10.Re1  , intending  10...Be7  11.Nd5  , was more critical. }
9... Qc7 10. Re1 Nxd4 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. Qxd4 Nc6 13. Qf4 Be7 14. Be3
{ Passive.   Black is fine after  14.Ne4  O-O  15.Nf6+  Kh8  16.Nh5  f6  17.Qg4  Rf7   But  14.Qg4  was more to the point, intending  14...O-O  when Black could choose between the cautious  14...g6  , and the more enterprising  14...h5  15.Qxg7  O-O-O  15.Bh6  . }
14... O-O 15. Ne4
