1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Ne2 Ba6 6. Ng3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d5 8.
Qf3
{ In this double-edged line of the Rubinstein Nimzo-Indian,  8.Ba3  , sacrificing a pawn in order to stop Black castling, is more popular nowadays. }
8... O-O 9. cxd5 exd5
{ 9...Bxf1  10.dxe6  wins a pawn for White;   But  9...Qxd5  might be a more promising choice; e.g.  10.e4  Qa5  11.Bxa6  Qxa6  , preparing ...Nbd7 and ...c7-c5, with roughly equal play. }
10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qe2 Nb8 12. O-O c5
