13. f3
{ The plan of creating a pawn centre remains viable in positions with less material on the board. }
13... Nc6 14. Bb2 Qd7
{ Or  14...Re8  15.e4  , when  15...dxe4  16.fxe4  cxd4  17.cxd4  Nxd4  fails to  18.Qc4  Ne6  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Nh5  with a strong initiative. }
15. e4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Qe6
{ Just as in the previous note, the central expansion is tactically justified; i.e.  16...dxe4  17.fxe4  Nxd4  18.Qf2  Ne6   @@StartBracket@@or  18...Rad8  19.Rad1  @@EndBracket@@  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Nf5  Kh8  21.Qb2  with a decisive attack - Watson. By the text Black instead prepares a light square blockade. }
17. e5 Nd7 18. Nh5 { After  18.f4  f5  Black nears his goal. } 18... Rfd8 19.
Rad1
{ The last piece joins the battle.  19.Nf4  Qh6  20.Nxd5  Ndxe5  etc was less convincing. }
19... Nf8 20. f4
{ Seeing that he can challenge Black's blockade on the next move, White finally advances his pawn majority. }
20... f5 21. g4 Ng6
{ 21...fxg4  22.f5  was terrible for Black   So perhaps he should have tried  21...Ne7  22.Ba3  Nfg6  23.Ng3  Rf8  24.gxf5  Rxf5  25.Nxf5  Nxf5  in Petrosian style, as after the text White breaks through on the kingside. }
22. gxf5 Qxf5 23. Bc1 Rf8 24. Ng3 Qh3 25. f5
{ Apart from its strategic benefits, this advance leaves Black's queen trapped on h3. }
25... Nh4 26. Rd3 Rae8 27. Bb2
{ The immediate  27.Nh5  was also strong, but White is in no hurry. } 27... Nb4
28. Rb3 Nxa2 29. Ra3 Rc8 { Or  29...Nb4  30.Nh5  etc. } 30. Rxa2 Nxf5 31. Ra3
Nh4 32. Nf5 *

