[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "A.Alekhine-F.Marshall  New York 1927  Irregular defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp3pp/4p3/3p1p2/1bPPn3/2N5/PPQNPPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

7. Ndxe4
{ White eliminates the active enemy knight, and prepares a swift development with Bf4, e2-e3, Be2 and O-O, after which he will be able to strike at the enemy centre with f2-f3.   Obviously  7.f3  Qh4+  was less suitable. }
7... fxe4 8. Bf4 O-O 9. e3 c6
{ The active  9...c5  can be met by  10.a3  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  , keeping the central control. }
10. Be2 Nd7 11. a3 Be7 12. O-O Bg5
{ A logical attempt to swap the active enemy bishop, but White has a strong reply prepared. }
13. f3
{ A powerful pawn break in the same spirit as in Van Wely-Karjakin, gaining central control and clearing the f-file towards Black's underdeveloped camp. }
13... Bxf4 14. exf4 Rxf4
{ Or  14...e3  15.g3  dxc4  16.Bxc4  Nb6  17.Qd3  and the e3-pawn is doomed. }
15. fxe4 Rxf1+ 16. Rxf1 e5
{ When you are behind in development, don't open the position!   The restrained  16...dxc4  17.Bxc4  Nb6  18.Qf2  Qe7  , followed by ...Bd7, was called for. }
17. Qd2
{ The queen joins the battle for the kingside. By now Black's defensive task is very difficult. }
17... c5 18. dxe5 d4 19. Qf4 dxc3 20. Qf7+ Kh8 21. bxc3
{ Simple and strong, keeping all the threats.   In contrast, after  21.e6  Nf6  22.e7  Qg8  things get more complicated; e.g.  23.Rxf6  Be6  24.Qxg8+  Kxg8  25.Rxe6  c2  . }
21... Qg8 22. Qe7 h6
{ 22...h6  intends  23.e6  Nf6  24.e5  Nh7  , but Alekhine has a stronger move prepared. }
23. Bh5
{ Mobilization is another basic attacking method. Now Black can hardly move. }
23... a5 24. e6 g6 { Or  24...Nf6  25.Bf7  Qh7  26.Rxf6  gxf6  27.Qf8+  . } 25.
exd7 Bxd7 26. Rf7 { In view of the coming queen check, Black resigned. } *

