[SetUp "1"]

10... e5
{ A strong advance that destabilizes White before he is properly developed. }
11. d5
{ Leaving Black with a stronghold on  c5  , but it was hard to find anything better; e.g.  11.Nf3  exd4  12.cxd4  Re8  13.Bd3  Nc6  14.Be3  Bf5  and White loses a central pawn. }
11... Nbd7 12. Bd3
{ 12.Nh3  Nc5  13.Nf2  seems more solid, when Black can choose between the simple  13...Ng4   @@StartBracket@@and the more complex  13...Nfxe4  14.Nxe4  Bf5  15.Qf2  Nxe4  16.Qxf5  Qh4+  etc - Golod@@EndBracket@@  14.Nxg4  Bxg4  15.Be3  Rc8  , keeping some advantage. }
12... Nc5 13. Bg5
{ There is nothing better; e.g.  13.Be3  Nfxe4  14.Bxe4  Qh4+   Or  13.Nf3  Nfxe4  14.Bxe4  f5  regaining the piece with a clear advantage - Rozentalis. }
13... h6 14. Bh4 Qd6 15. Ne2
{ This runs into a strong reply.  15.Nf3  Nfxe4  again works well for Black   So the uninspiring  15.Bxf6  Qxf6  16.Nf3  had to be played either here or on the previous move. }
15... Ng4
{ With the double idea of ...Ne3 and ...f7-f5. All of a sudden, White's position is very difficult to defend. }
16. Nc1 f5 17. h3 fxe4 18. hxg4 exd3 19. Nxd3 Qxd5
{ With an extra pawn, safer king and superior pawn structure, Black is winning. }
20. Nf2 Bxg4 21. O-O
{ Or  21.Nxg4  Nd3+  and the next check is decisive. The text leaves Black with a second extra pawn, making the win a matter of technique. }
21... Bf5 22. Qe2 Rae8 23. Rfe1 b6 24. a4 Bc8 25. Red1 Qc6 26. Qc4+ Kh8 27. Nd3
Bb7 28. Rd2 Ba6 29. Nb4 Bxc4 30. Nxc6 Nb3 *

