[FEN "r2qk2r/1bpnnpb1/pp1pp2p/6p1/P2PP3/2N1BN1P/1PPQBPP1/3RK2R b Kkq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... f5
{ An excellent pawn break that undermines the enemy centre while clearing the f-file and the long diagonal for Black's pieces. }
13. exf5
{ If  13.d5  , then  13...Bxc3  14.Qxc3  e5  is rather strong;   But  13.Qd3  might have been a lesser evil - Hillarp. }
13... Nxf5 { Stronger than  13...exf5  14.d5  f4  15.Bd4  etc. } 14. Qd3 O-O
15. Bc1
{ Wasting a vital tempo.  15.O-O  was better, not fearing the exchange on e3. }
15... c5
{ The story is repeated on the opposite flank. I guess that anyone who sees this game will be tempted to try out the Hippopotamus. }
16. dxc5
{ There is nothing better; since  16.d5  Bxc3+  17.Qxc3  Bxd5  leaves White without any compensation at all for the pawn - Hillarp. }
16... Nxc5 17. Qc4 Rc8 18. h4
{ Admittedly Black is having a dream position, but this desperate attack will just make his task easier.  18.O-O  must have been better, when  18...Qd7  , with the idea of ...Ne4, keeps the initiative. }
18... Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nxh4 20. Qg4 Ng6 21. Ne4 Ne5 22. Qh3
{ A tactical error; though after  22.Qg3  Nxe4  23.fxe4  Rxc2  Black is also much better - Hillarp. }
22... g4 23. Qh5 Nxe4 24. fxe4 Qf6
{ With double threats at  f2  and  c2  , Black is winning. The game concluded  24...Qf6  25.Rh2  Rxc2  26.Bxh6  Rxe2+  27.Kxe2  Qf3+  28.Ke1  g3  29.Bxg7  gxh2  30.Qh8+  Kf7  31.Qxf8+  Kg6  32.Kd2  Qxf8  33.Bxf8  Nf3+  34.Ke3  Ng1  35.Rxd6  h1=Q  and here White resigned. }
