14. d5
{ An unexpected blow; based on the fact that both  14.d5  cxd5   @@StartBracket@@and  14...exd5  drop a piece after  15.e5  .@@EndBracket@@   In contrast,  14.e5  Nd5  leads nowhere for White. }
14... c5 15. Rad1
{ Another good option was  15.d6  Bd8  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  17.e5  with a huge strategic plus. }
15... h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nh5
{ An unpleasant move for Black, who now has to hand over the e5-square in order to keep her kingside pawn structure intact. }
17... Bd8 18. dxe6 fxe6 19. Ne5 { With the irresistible threat of 20. Rd7. }
19... Bf6 20. Rd7 Qb8 21. Ng4 Bd4 22. e5
{ 22.Qxa6  Qe8  was less convincing.   After the text Black resigned, seeing that after  22.e5  Rf7  23.Nxh6+  gxh6  24.Nf6+  Kf8  25.Qg4  she is soon mated. }
