[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4
{ In the nineties, this move became a popular alternative to the more explored 5. Bg5. }
5... O-O 6. e3 c6
{ Another main reply is  6...c5  , exploiting the fact that with the bishop on f4 White exerts less pressure on the d5-pawn. }
7. Qc2 { White delays Bd3 so that ...d5xc4 can be met by Bxc4 in one go. } 7...
Nbd7 8. h3 a6 9. Rd1 h6 10. a3 dxc4
{ Kramnik's suggestion  10...Re8  seems more flexible. } 11. Bxc4 Nd5
{ A common simplification method in this opening, but here it leads to a rather passive game for Black.   Perhaps  11...b5  12.Ba2  Bb7  was more logical; e.g.  13.e4  Re8  14.Bb1  Nf8  15.b4  a5  with counterplay in L.Psakhis-E.Pigusov, Novosibirsk 1993. }
12. O-O
{ More ambitious than  12.Bg3  Nxc3  13.Qxc3  with a slight edge - Kramnik. The doubled pawns that now emerge will yield White dynamic assets such as a semi-open e-file and increased control of the crucial e5-square. }
12... Nxf4 13. exf4 Qc7 14. Ne5 Nf6
{ Or  14...c5  15.d5  Nxe5  16.fxe5  Qxe5  17.Rfe1  with a strong initiative - Kramnik. }
15. --
