[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "V.Kramnik-S.Lputian  European Team Championship,  Debrecen 1992  Queen’s Gambit Declined"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1pq1bpp1/p1p1pn1p/4N3/2BP1P2/P1N4P/1PQ2PP1/3R1RK1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. Ba2
{ With the centre completely dominated by the strong knight on e5, Kramnik initiates a kingside attack. }
15... Bd7 16. Bb1 Be8
{ 16...Rfd8  was correct, preparing the evacuation of the king; e.g.  17.Ne4  Kf8  18.Nxf6  Bxf6  19.Qh7  Ke7  and Black is still alive. }
17. d5
{ An aesthetic blow, which exploits several tactical motifs at the same time.   After  17.d5  both  17...cxd5  and  17...exd5  run into  18.Nxd5  with material gains;   Besides which there appears the threat of  17...--  18.d6  Bxd6  19.Ng4  , a fact that explains Black's next move in the game. }
17... Rd8 18. Rfe1
{ Simple and strong, bringing the last piece into the battle. } 18... Kh8 19.
dxe6
{ Black was ready for 19...cxd5, so White finally fixes a favourable pawn structure. }
19... Rxd1 20. Rxd1 fxe6 21. Ne4 g6 22. Nc5 Bxc5
{ A positional capitulation; but  22...Qc8  loses material after  23.Nxg6+  Bxg6  24.Qxg6  Bxc5  25.Qxh6+  Kg8  26.Qg5+  Kh8  27.Qxc5  - Kramnik. }
23. Qxc5 Rg8 24. Ba2 Kg7
{ There is nothing better; e.g.  24...Bf7  25.Qd6   Or  24...Nd5  25.Bxd5  exd5  26.Rxd5  . }
25. Bxe6 Rf8 26. Nd7
{ Interestingly, this is the first move with the knight since it settled on  e5  .  26.Nd7  Nxd7  27.Rxd7+  Bxd7  28.Qe7+  is hopeless. }
