[SetUp "1"]

13... d5
{ A thematic counterstrike in the Open Sicilian, which makes White's kingside attack less likely to succeed. The pawn possibly lost in this operation is usually well invested. }
14. exd5
{ Black is also fine after  14.g5  dxe4  15.Bg2  Ne8  , followed by ...Nd6. }
14... e4 15. Bg2
{ After  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Nf6  17.Bf3  Rad8  and ...Nxd5 next, Black obtains a better version of the game. }
15... Nb6 16. g5 Nfxd5 17. Nxe4 Rad8
{ In exchange for the pawn, Black enjoys excellent piece activity. } 18. Nd4
Rfe8 19. c3
{ After  19.Qg4  Bf8  20.f5  Qe5  21.Nb3  Nc4  22.g6  Nde3  Black again had counterplay in L.Psakhis-Z.Azmaiparashvili, Riga 1980. }
19... Bf8 20. Qg4 Nxc3
{ Rybka's suggestion. In contrast, the game went  20...Kh8  21.f5  Nc4  22.g6  with attacking prospects for White. }
21. Nf6+
{ Both:  21.bxc3  Bxe4;   and  21.Nxc3  Rxd4  let Black restore the material balance with a pleasant advantage. }
21... gxf6 22. gxf6+ Kh8 23. bxc3 Nd5
{ With threats at f6 and c3, Black is better - Rybka. } *

