1. c4 g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nc3 O-O 5. d3 e5 6. e4 d6 7. Nge2
{ In the English Opening White usually aims at queenside play, but here we have an exception. After castling he will try to build a kingside attack with h2-h3 and f2-f4. }
7... c6
{ Although practice favours  7...Nc6  , the text is quite logical, in order to support a central break with ...d6-d5 later on. }
8. h3 Na6 9. O-O Nc7
{ With this knight manoeuvre Black gets a bit closer to achieving ...d6-d5. }
10. f4
{ In the event of  10.d4  , one simple reply is  10...exd4   @@StartBracket@@while  10...Be6  , intending  11.d5  cxd5  12.cxd5  Bd7  and ...b6-b5 next, can also be considered@@EndBracket@@  11.Nxd4  Re8  , preparing ...d6-d5. }
10... exf4 11. Nxf4
{ On  11.Bxf4  Black could just react as in the game   Whereas  11.gxf4  is well met by  11...Nh5  , followed by ...f7-f5. At this point,  12.f5  proves quite harmless after  12...gxf5  13.exf5  Kh8  , followed by ...Rg8. }
11... Qe7
{ With the simple idea of concluding development by ...Bd7 and ...Rae8. } 12.
Kh2 Bd7 13. Qf3 Rae8 14. Be3
