[SetUp "1"]

14... d5
{ Exploiting the pin on the e-file, Black manages to break in the centre despite six enemy pieces controlling the d5-square. }
15. cxd5
{ This runs into a strong reply.   15.Bxa7  g5  16.Nh5  Nxh5  17.Qxh5  d4  18.Ne2  Ne6  , followed by ...Be5, yields Black interesting compensation for the pawn   so  15.Qf2  , with the threat of Bc5, was a safer choice; e.g.  15...b6  16.cxd5  cxd5   @@StartBracket@@contrary to the game,  16...Nfxd5  fails to  17.exd5  Qxe3  18.dxc6  etc@@EndBracket@@  17.Bd4  with roughly equal play. }
15... Nfxd5 { Of course; clearing the long diagonal for the bishop. } 16. Bxa7
{ Or  16.Ncxd5  Nxd5  17.Nxd5  cxd5  and it is White who is fighting for equality. }
16... Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nb5 18. Qf2 Nxa7 19. Qxa7 Ra8 20. Qb6
{ Obviously  20.Qxb7  fails to  20...Rfb8  21.Qc7  Be5  . } 20... Bxc3 21. Rac1
Be5
{ By now Black has a more active game.   There followed  21...Be5  22.d4  Bxf4  23.Rxf4  Rxa2  24.Qb3  Qe6  and the threat of ...Qxh3+ forced White to enter the endgame a pawn down, which Sepp went on to win. }
