1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2
{ In contrast, against  6.Bd3  Black usually prefers  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  Qb6  , exploiting White's lessened defence of the d4-pawn.   As for  6.a3  , one popular reply is  6...f6  with a kingside focus. }
6... Nge7
{ Now that the white bishop has settled on e2, it makes sense to bring the knight to f5. }
7. O-O cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5 9. Nc3 Rc8
{ Just like 5...Bd7, a useful move while awaiting White's next step. } 10. Kh1
{ Some prophylaxis before launching g2-g4.   The immediate  10.g4  is well met by  10...Nh4  11.Nxh4  Qxh4  12.Be3  f6  undermining the enemy centre. }
10... Qb6
{ Distracting White from his intended kingside advance.   10...Be7  11.g4  Nh4  12.Nxh4  Bxh4  13.Be3  O-O  , followed by ...f7-f6, has also done well in practice. }
11. Na4 Qa5 12. Bd2 Qd8 13. Be1
{ A rather passive solution to the problem with the d4-pawn, which became undefended after Black's queen sortie.   Instead, Psakhis suggests  13.Be3  , although in that case, Black will always be able to meet by g2-g4 by ...Nxe3. }
13... h5 14. a3
{ Now that Black's previous rendered the g2-g4 plan impossible, White prepares queenside play with b2-b4 and Nc5.Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
