1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3
{ Compared with the main line with  3.f4  , this branch of the Vienna leads to a strategically more complex battle, not remote from some English variations. }
3... d5
{ The most principled reaction, by which Black exploits White's temporary surrender of the centre. }
4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bd6 7. Rb1 c6 8. Nf3 O-O
{ Here and later,  8...e4  9.Nd4  causes Black a slight problem with the e-pawn. }
9. O-O Nd7 10. Re1 f5
{ A risky approach, considering that Black hasn't yet finished development.   10...Qc7  or  10...Re8  was safer. }
11. Qe2
{ Before getting on with his development, White prepares Qc4+ in order to exploit the weakened a2-g8 diagonal. }
11... h6 12. Qc4+ Kh7 13. d3 Qf6 14. a4
{ With the black knight evidently heading for b6, it makes sense to push this pawn forward. }
14... Nb6 15. Qb3 f4
{ After  15...Be6  16.c4  , followed by Bb2, White also has a more active game. }
16. --
