[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "A.Beliavsky-A.Yusupov  USSR Championship, Minsk 1987  Dutch Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 d5 5. Nf3
{ Another popular approach is  5.Nh3  c6  6.O-O  Bd6  7.Bf4  , followed by Nd2-f3. }
5... c6 6. O-O Bd6 7. b3 Qe7
{ Black prevents 8. Ba3, swapping off his 'good' bishop. } 8. Bb2
{ If White now plays  8.a4  , insisting with the idea of  Ba3  , then  8...a5  fixes a stronghold on b4. Thus White prefers to leave the bishop on  b2  for the moment. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Apparently this natural move doesn't fit in too well with Bb2.   Both  9.Qc1  followed by Ba3 and  9.Nbd2  , preparing Ne5 and Ndf3, are more popular options in practice. }
9... Bd7
{ The bishop manoeuvre ... Bd7-e8-h5 is thematic for the Stonewall, and it sometimes occurs in the French as well. }
10. Ne5 Be8 11. Nd3 { 11.e3  , preparing Ne2-f4-d3, seems better. } 11... Nbd7
12. e3
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
