[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "A.Beliavsky-A.Yusupov  USSR Championship, Minsk 1987  Dutch Defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3brk1/pp1nq1pp/2pbpn2/3p1p2/2PP4/1PNNP1P1/PB3PBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... g5
{ 'If you don't have the central position under control, it is better to avoid this kind of undertaking; otherwise you risk suffering a counterblow in the centre and coming away empty-handed. But there is no danger of this in the present case, since Black firmly controls the entire complex of central squares.' - Yusupov.   12...Ne4  13.f3  was less convincing, as  13...Nxg3  14.hxg3  Bxg3  fails to  15.Ne2  . }
13. a4
{ Resuming the plan of Qc1 and Ba3.   As for  13.f3  , preparing e3-e4,  13...Bg6  , intending ...h5-h4, looks promising for Black. }
13... Bg6 14. f4
{ Weakening the e4-square; but  14.Qc1  at once permitted  14...f4  . } 14...
Bh5 15. Qc1 Ne4
{ A Stonewall expert knows to wait with this move until the optimal moment. Here it helps him prevent 16. Ba3 once again. }
16. fxg5 Nxc3
{ Preparing a favourable exchange on e2.   In contrast,  16...Qxg5  17.Nxe4  fxe4  18.Nf4  helps White - Yusupov. }
17. Qxc3 Be2 18. Rfe1 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxg5
{ By now Black has a comfortable game, with his minor pieces superior to their white counterparts. }
20. Ba3 Bxa3 21. Rxa3 Nf6 22. Qf1 h5
{ The pinprick ...h5-h4 is enabled, a fact that motivates White to exchange queens. }
23. Qf4 Qxf4 24. gxf4
{ Or  24.exf4  Kf7  , followed by ...h5-h4, ...Rh8, ...Rag8 etc. } 24... Kf7
25. Ra2 Rg8
{ Preparing ...Rg7 and ...Rag8, with ...Ne4 as a later option. Thanks to his superior minor piece Black has a stable edge in this endgame, and Yusupov went on to win. }
