[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "W.Browne-F.Gheorghiu  Wijk aan Zee 1981  Queen’s Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. a3
{ By transposition we have reached the Petrosian Variation of the Queen's Indian. }
5... d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This leads to a more dynamic battle than  6...exd5  and could be regarded as Black's main reply to the Petrosian. }
7. e3 { Another option is  7.Qc2  , in order to play e2-e4 in a single move. }
7... Be7 8. Bb5+ c6 9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 c5 11. e4
{ Finally, White is able to set up a pawn centre. } 11... Nc6 12. Bb2 Rc8 13.
Qe2
{ From now on, whenever needed, the d4-pawn can be reinforced by a rook move to d1. }
13... cxd4 14. cxd4 O-O 15. O-O Bf6 16. Rad1 Na5
{ Some prophylaxis in view of the possible d4-d5. In contrast,  16...Nxd4  17.Bxd4  Bxd4  18.Bb5  e5  19.Nxe5  yields White a clear initiative. }
17. Rfe1 Bc6
{ Black intends ...Ba4, but now runs into an unpleasant surprise.   Again, prophylactic action was called for, either by  17...Re8  or  17...g6  . }
18. --
