[SetUp "1"]

18. d5
{ A thematic pawn sacrifice, which we already saw in Browne-Martz.   18.e5  Be7  is less convincing. }
18... exd5 19. e5 Be7 20. e6
{ Tempting and strong, in order to clear lines against the black king. } 20...
Ba4
{ 20...Be8  was more logical, bringing a defender to the kingside, although after  21.exf7+  Rxf7  22.Ne5  White keeps a clear initiative. }
21. exf7+ Rxf7 22. Qe6 Bxd1
{ Black accepts the sacrifice, since  22...Rc6  23.Bxh7+  Kf8  24.Nd4  makes things even worse for him. }
23. Bxh7+ Kxh7
{ Or  23...Kf8  24.Bg6  Rf4  25.Ng5  Bxg5  26.Be5  with deadly threats. } 24.
Qxf7 Qf8 25. Qh5+ Kg8 26. Qxd5+ Qf7 27. Qxd1
{ With an extra pawn and safer king, White won without major difficulty. } *

