[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "M.Khachiyan-H.Nakamura  Las Vegas 2006  Alekhine’s Defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1n4p1/n2pP1B1/3P4/1BP2N1P/PP2QPP1/RN3RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... f6
{ A strong pawn break that increases Black's central control and complicates White's intended attack.   Also possible is  11...Nxb3  12.axb3  f6  with similar play,   whereas  12...Bf5  permits  13.Qe3  , followed by Bh6, keeping some attacking prospects. }
12. Bf4
{ Obviously  12.exf6  exf6  , followed by ...Re8, would play into Black's hands. }
12... g5
{ Gaining some space on the kingside. The slight weakening of the light squares is not too serious, now that the bishop on b3 will soon leave the board. }
13. Bg3 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5 15. Nh2
{ 15.Nbd2  , followed by Rae1, seems more natural. } 15... c6 16. Nd2 Qe8 17.
exf6
{ The clearance of the centre will make Black's bishop pair even stronger, but White must have feared the plan of ...Qg6 and ...Bd3. }
17... exf6 18. Qxe8 Rfxe8 19. f4 Bd3 20. Rf2 h6
{ Black gets ready to meet f4xg5 by ...h6xg5, thus preventing the arrival of any white piece at e5. Nakamura later converted his slight advantage into victory. }
