[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "S.Brynell-J.Hellsten  Malmö 1997  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. a3
{ We already came across this line in Dvoretsky-Schmidt. } 7... Nc6 8. Bd3 dxe5
9. dxe5 g6
{ Quite a logical set-up against the 7. a3 line, in order to restrict the bishop on d3 and put some pressure on the e5-pawn. }
10. O-O Bg7 11. Re1 O-O 12. Qe2
{ In later games I had to face  12.b4  and  12.Be4  , both of which might be more critical. }
12... Bd7
{ Practice has seen  12...Qc7  and  12...b6  more often, but I like my move, which keeps maximum flexibility. }
13. h4
{ Preparing a kingside attack with h4-h5, but Black has a strong reply at his disposal.   13.Qe4  Nce7  , preparing ...Nf5 and ...Bc6, also looks fine for him   So  13.Bd2  , followed by Nc3, might have been White's best choice. }
13... --
