[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "S.Brynell-J.Hellsten  Malmö 1997  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1b1pbp/2n1p1p1/3nP3/7P/P2B1N2/1P2QPP1/RNB1R1K1 b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13... Qb6
{ Responding to the flank attack with action in the centre. Now 14...Nd4 is enabled, while the queen's rook can quickly join the battle. Evidently, after 12...b6 this queen sortie would not have been available, whereas in the event of 12...Qc7 Black would be one tempo down by now.   By the way,  13...Na5  causes White fewer worries after  14.Bg5  Qb6  15.Nc3  . }
14. Qe4
{ Black is also better after  14.h5  Nd4  15.Nxd4  Qxd4  , followed by ...Rac8   Or  14.Nc3  Nd4  15.Nxd4  Qxd4  16.Nxd5  exd5  with ...Rfe8 next. }
14... f5
{ Another key move, which enables a counterattack along the f-file, exploiting the lead in development. The damage to the pawn structure is less relevant. }
15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Qe3 Qc7 17. Nbd2
{ A slow move that exposes White to a deadly attack.   17.Qf4  , insisting on the queen exchange, was essential; e.g.  17...Qxf4   @@StartBracket@@or  17...Qd8  18.Qd6  , followed by Nc3@@EndBracket@@  18.Bxf4  Nd5  19.Bd6  Rfd8  20.Nbd2  Bxb2  21.Rab1  Bg7  22.Ne4  with some counterplay for the pawn. }
17... Ng4 18. Qe2
{ Other squares were no better; e.g.  18.Qc5  Bd4   @@StartBracket@@or  18.Qe4  Rf4  , followed by ...Raf8@@EndBracket@@   Or  18.Qg5  e5  and the queen is trapped by ...Bh6 or ...Bf6 on the next move. }
18... Nd4 19. Qd1 Bc6 { Black's pieces coordinate perfectly. } 20. Be4 Rad8 21.
Bxc6 bxc6 22. Kf1 { Or  22.Qa4  Rxf3  and the queen finally enters on h2. }
22... Nxf3 23. gxf3 Qh2 *

