[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "S.Sulskis-A.Galkin  European Championship,  Batumi 2002  Caro-Kann Defence "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nppbp/6p1/3P2Pn/Q7/2N3N1/PP1P1P1P/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10... e6
{ Responding to White's flank attack with action in the centre.   10...Ne5  11.Be2   @@StartBracket@@or  10...Nxg3  11.hxg3  , followed by Qh4, was less accurate@@EndBracket@@   While  10...Nb6  11.Qh4  Nxd5  12.Nxh5  gxh5  13.Bg2  also favours White - Lukacs.   But  10...Nc5  11.Qh4  Bxc3  12.bxc3  Qxd5  was possible; e.g.  13.d4  Rd8  14.Be2  Na4  15.Bd2  Ng7  16.O-O  Nf5  - Galkin. }
11. d4
{ If  11.Nxh5  gxh5  12.Qh4  Ne5  , both  13.Bg2   @@StartBracket@@and  13.Qxh5  exd5  , preparing ...Bg4/f5@@EndBracket@@  13...Ng6  , intending  14.Qxh5  Nf4  , favour Black. }
11... Nb6 12. Qd1 Nxg3
{ Now that White can't easily mount an attack down the h-file, Black decides to keep his pawn structure intact. }
13. hxg3 exd5 14. Be3
{ 14.Bg2  Re8+  15.Kf1  was preferable, although after  15...Be6  , intending ...Rc8-c4 as well as ...f7-f6, Black has counterplay - Galkin. }
14... Re8 15. Qd2 Bf5
{ The greedy  15...Qxg5  was also possible; e.g.  16.O-O-O  Qe7  17.Bh6  Bh8  18.Bb5  Bd7  with a clear edge - Lukacs. }
16. Bb5 Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. O-O-O b5
{ Black hurries to start his own attack, even at the cost of a pawn. } 19. Nxb5
Rb8 20. Nc3 Re7 21. Bf4 { Disrupting the plan of ...Reb7. } 21... Rb6 22. Rde1
{ White's only chance is to use the e-file for counterplay. } 22... Reb7 23.
Qe3 Bxd4 24. Qe8+ Qxe8 25. Rxe8+ Kg7 26. Na4 Rxb2
{ Of course not  26...Rb4  27.Bd6  - Galkin. } 27. Nxb2 c3
{ A tempting idea, but White can defend after this.   27...Rxb2  was correct; e.g.  28.Rhe1  Rb1+  29.Kd2  c3+  30.Ke2  Rb2+  31.Kd1  Rxa2  32.Bd6  h5  33.gxh6+  Kh7  and Black keeps the advantage - Galkin. }
28. Nd3 Bxd3 29. Rb8 Rb2 30. Rd1 Rc2+ 31. Kb1 Rd2+
{ Black has to settle for a draw, since  31...Bf5  fails to  32.Rxd4  Rxf2+  33.Kc1  Rf1+  34.Rd1  etc. }
32. Kc1 Rc2+ 33. Kb1 Rd2+ 34. Kc1 *

