[White "Exercises Chapter 3"]
[Black "A.Dreev-S.Volkov  Samara 1998  Slav Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 a6 5. c5
{ A logical reply to the Chebanenko Slav, now that 5...b6 6 cxb6 axb6 isn't available for Black. As a consequence, he prepares the central break ...e7-e5 instead. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bf4 Nh5
{ Just in time: before White plays h2-h3, providing the bishop with a shelter on h2. }
7. Bd2 Nhf6 8. h3 e5 9. b4
{ Black's point is that  9.dxe5  Ne4  10.Nxe4   @@StartBracket@@the attempt to hang on to the pawn by  10.b4  fails to  10...Nxd2  11.Qxd2  a5  @@EndBracket@@  10...dxe4  11.Ng5  Nxc5  12.b4  Ne6  13.Nxe4  Qd4  14.Nd6+  Bxd6  15.exd6  O-O  is about equal - Volkov. }
9... Qe7
{ After  9...e4  10.Ng1  , followed by Bf4 and e2-e3, White might be slightly better, so Black prefers to maintain the central tension. Next he could consider ...g7-g6, followed by ...Bg7, with pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
10. dxe5 { 10.Be3  seems safer, followed by g2-g3 and Bg2. } 10... Nxe5 11.
Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Na4
{ With the dual idea of Nb6 and Bc3, but Black has a strong reply prepared. }
12... Ne4
{ When one knight leaves, another arrives. This phenomenon appears in many different openings; for example, in the IQP structures when Black plays ...Na5 or ...Nb4 and White replies Ne5. }
13. Be3 { Not  13.Nb6  Qf6  14.Be3  Qc3+  etc. } 13... Be7 { Very nice. } 14.
Qd4
{ Now the intended  14.Bd4  runs into  14...Bh4  with the deadly threat of ...Qxg3. }
14... Qf5 15. Qd3 Bf6 16. g4
{ This helps Black's queen to a better square.   16.Rc1  was preferable - Volkov. }
16... Qe5 17. Rd1
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
