1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8.
Qc2 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. f3 Ng6
{ We have reached a main position in the Exchange Variation with Nge2 against the Queen's Gambit. }
12. e4
{ At this point White usually continues  12.Rad1  , supporting an opportune e3-e4, but In this game he prefers to set up the pawn centre at once. }
12... dxe4 13. fxe4 Be6
{ 13...c5  is less appropriate due to  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Nd5  , when  15...cxd4  runs into the reply  16.Nc7  . }
