[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qr1k1/pp2bppp/2p1bnn1/6B1/3PP3/2NB4/PPQ1N1PP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... Ng4
{ Black wishes to soften up White's centre by ...c6-c5, but seeing that the immediate  14...c5  permits  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.e5  Bg5  17.Bb5  Re7  18.d5  and 19. e6 with an initiative, he first removes the knight from f6. In retrospect, White should have preferred 14 h3 and then mobilized the queen's rook. }
15. Bxe7
{ Or  15.Bc1  c5  16.Bb5  Qc7  17.g3  Red8  18.d5  Bc8  with a slight edge for Black thanks to his control of the dark squares, V.Neverov-B.Gelfand, Uzhgorod 1987. }
15... Qxe7 16. Qd2
{ In view of the threat ...Ne3 White has no time for the desirable  16.e5  . }
16... c5
{ A key move which fixes a favourable pawn structure;   since neither  16...c5  17.Bb5   @@StartBracket@@nor  17.h3  cxd4  @@EndBracket@@  cxd4  18.Nxd4  Red8  works at all well for White. }
17. d5 Bd7 18. h3 N4e5
{ Thanks to his stronghold on e5 and the bad bishop on d3, Black is already a bit better. }
19. Nf4 Qg5 20. Nxg6 Qxg6
{ Pert has observed that he can soon mobilize for an attack on the enemy kingside, whereas White has no obvious plan to follow. }
21. Kh1 Rad8 22. Qf2 b6 23. Bb1
{ A sad place for the bishop.   Perhaps White should have tried  23.Bb5  instead; e.g.  23...Bxb5  24.Nxb5  Qxe4  25.Nc7  with ideas like  25...Re7   @@StartBracket@@and  25...Rf8  26.Rde1  @@EndBracket@@  26.d6  . }
23... Bc8 24. Rfe1 Qh6 25. Qd2 Qh4 26. Rf1 Rd6
{ A nice rook lift that enhances the coming attack. } 27. Qf2 Qh5 28. Nb5 Rh6
29. Qg3 Rg6 30. Qh2 Ba6 31. a4 Bxb5 32. axb5 Qe2
{ Black wins a pawn, while maintaining his huge positional plus. } 33. d6 Rxd6
34. Rxd6 Qxf1+ 35. Qg1 Qxb5 36. Qd1 h6 37. Qd5 Qf1+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Restriction"]
[Black "4: Restriction "]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Introduction@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. --
{ Just like the battle for the centre, the concept of restriction isn't exclusive to the opening phase, and I covered its role in the middlegame quite extensively in 'Mastering Chess Strategy'.Basically, restriction means that you don't let your opponent carry out the moves or plans that he is aiming for. In the context of opening play, we can divide the restrictive measures into three distinct types:   ♟️ Restriction of the opponent's development @@StartBracket@@including castling@@EndBracket@@ .   ♟️ Restriction of a specific enemy piece.   ♟️ Restriction of the opponent's general plans.   Evidently, the two latter types are relevant during middlegame and endgame play as well, whereas the first type is exclusive to the opening. In this chapter we will come across restrictive measures of all three types, sometimes even intertwined within the same game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "Restriction of castling "]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Throughout this book we have seen many games where the prevention of the opponent's castling had a huge effect on the battle; e.g. Dvoretsky-Schmidt @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/4p3/3nq3/8/P2B4/1P3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bb5+!  @@EndBracket@@, Psakhis-Gofshtein @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/pppnb1pp/2n1b3/3N4/2P2P2/5NP1/PP1Q2BP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bc5!  @@EndBracket@@, Firman-Itkis @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppq2ppp/2n1b3/3pP3/8/1N2B3/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bc5!  @@EndBracket@@, Vaisser-Illescas @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/p1q2ppp/3b4/3B4/3Q4/4P3/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Ba6!  @@EndBracket@@, Ovetchkin-Efanov @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppq3np/4b1p1/3p4/2P5/5N2/P1Q1BPPP/1R3RK1 w kq - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Qa4+!  Qc6  21.Qa3  @@EndBracket@@, and Kundin-Kostanovich @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/p3qppp/3b1n2/3pp3/5Bb1/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 4 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bb5+!  @@EndBracket@@ .  Here are some more examples on the subject. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "A.Yusupov-T.Wedberg  Stockholm 2003  Colle’s Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. c4 Be7 7. Nc3
{ As mentioned in Vera-Romero, the Colle is by no means an insipid opening, despite its peaceful looks.   By playing  7.Nc3  at this moment, White prepares to meet  7...O-O  with  8.d5  when  8...exd5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Bxd5  11.Bxh7+  Kxh7  12.Qxd5  yields him a pleasant advantage, whereas other Black 9th moves produces some kind of inferior Benoni due to the placement of the black bishops. }
7... d5
{ 7...cxd4  8.exd4  d5  is more popular, when play usually continues  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Ne5   @@StartBracket@@  10.Bb5+  Bc6  is less promising@@EndBracket@@  O-O  11.Qh5  @@StartBracket@@or  11.Qg4  with a sharp battle.@@EndBracket@@  The drawback to the immediate  7... d5 will be well displayed by this game. }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ While  8...cxd4  9.Bb5+  is annoying for Black   8...Nxd5  9.e4  Nxc3  10.bxc3  O-O  was probably a lesser evil. Similar positions often arise in the Petrosian Variation of the Queen's Indian @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.a3  @@EndBracket@@, but there White has wasted a move on a2-a3, so he should be slightly better here. }
9. Bb5+
{ White violates the principle of not moving the same piece twice in the opening, but with good reason. This check either leaves Black without castling or undermines the d5-pawn. }
9... Kf8
{ Wedberg opts for the former.   9...Nc6  10.Ne5  Rc8  11.Qa4  Qc7  12.Qxa7  is just disastrous for Black   While the natural  9...Nbd7  runs into  10.dxc5  bxc5  11.Ne5  with the idea  11...O-O  12.Nxd7  Nxd7  13.Nxd5  .   Finally,  9...Bc6  is strongly met by  10.Qa4  Bxb5  11.Qxb5+  , when  11...Qd7   @@StartBracket@@  11...Nbd7  12.dxc5  bxc5  13.Rd1  again leads to a problem with the d5-pawn@@EndBracket@@  12.Ne5  Qxb5  13.Nxb5  Na6  14.Rd1  also favours White; e.g.  14...O-O  15.Nc6  Rfe8  16.b3  Kf8  17.Bb2  with strong pressure in N.Sulava-C.Debray, French Team Championship 2009. }
10. Be2
{ Prophylaxis against an annoying ...c5-c4;   i.e.  10.b3  c4  11.bxc4  a6  12.Ba4  dxc4  , and 13...b5 next, with some queenside activity for Black. }
10... Nbd7 11. b3
{ Of course. On b2 the other bishop will control the long diagonal and discourage Black's natural plan of ...g7-g6 and ...Kg7. }
11... a6 12. Bb2 Rc8 13. Rc1 h5 14. h3
{ With his last move Black probably hoped for  14.Ne5  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Ng4  when  16.Bxg4  hxg4  17.Qxg4  d4  , intending ...Rh4, yields him some counterplay; but Yusupov prevents that idea. }
14... Kg8 15. Ne5
{ Activating the knight and preparing Bf3, with increased pressure on the hanging pawns. Due to his badly placed king, it is already difficult to find a good plan for Black. }
15... cxd4 16. Qxd4
{ The right recapture, so as to keep the long diagonal open. } 16... Bc5 17.
Qf4 Nf8
{ Both  17...Bd6  18.Nxf7   @@StartBracket@@and  17...Nxe5  18.Qxe5  d4  19.exd4  Qxd4  20.Qg5  @@EndBracket@@ favour White. }
18. Bf3 Ne6 19. Qf5 g6
{ Doing a favour to the bishop on b2, but the queen was annoying on f5. } 20.
Qd3 Ng5 21. Rfd1
{ Yusupov isn't bothered about the exchange on f3, and brings the last piece into the battle. }
21... Nxf3+
{ Or  21...Bd6  22.Bxd5  Nxd5  23.Nxd5  Rxc1  24.Rxc1  Bxe5  25.Bxe5  Bxd5  26.Qxd5  etc. }
22. Nxf3
{ With the rook on e8 instead of h8, this would be a normal fighting position. Here, in contrast, Black's disconnected rooks and the tactical motifs along the a1-h8 diagonal spell big problems for him. }
22... Qe7
{ Black's first tactical mistake in the game, and a decisive one.   The prophylactic  22...Be7  was called for, when  23.Na4  , followed by Bd4, is one possible way for White to work on his advantage. }
23. b4
{ A nice strike, which exploits the fact that 22...Qe7 left the bishop on b7 overloaded to the defence of c8 and d5. }
23... Bxb4 24. Nxd5 Nxd5 25. Rxc8+ Bxc8 26. Qxd5 { Even simpler than  26.Bxh8 }
26... Rh7 27. Qd8+ Qf8 28. Qxf8+ Bxf8 29. Rd8
{ In view of  29.Rd8  Bf5  30.Ba3  , Black resigned. } *

