[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "P.Ricardi-J.Hellsten  Santiago 2006  Catalan Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 a6
{ With this and the following move, Black declares his intention to hang on to the c4-pawn.   A calmer approach is  5...Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.Qc2  a6  , when Black resolves the development of his queen's bishop after both  8.Qxc4   @@StartBracket@@and  8.a4  Bd7  9.Qxc4  Bc6  @@EndBracket@@  b5  9.Qc2  Bb7  . }
6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 { Also possible is  7.e3  , followed by Qe2, Rd1 and e3-e4. }
7... Bb4
{ In my search for a reply to the Catalan, this rare move had attracted my attention.   7...Rb8  , preparing ...b7-b5, is much more popular; e.g.  8.e4  Be7  9.Qe2  b5  10.Rd1  O-O  11.d5  exd5  12.e5  Nb4  13.exf6  Bxf6  with a double-edged battle, as occurred in several games. }
8. e4
{ Ricardi plays just the move that I was trying to prevent!   An earlier game of mine went  8.Qc2  O-O  9.Rd1  Be7  @@StartBracket@@ vacating the b4-square for the knight @@EndBracket@@  10.e4  b5  11.Qe2  Re8  12.Bf4  Nb4  13.Ne1  and a draw was agreed in J.Gustafsson-J.Hellsten, European Team Championship, Gothenburg 2005. }
8... Bxc3
{ Accepting the challenge.   The simple  8...O-O  was also reasonable; e.g.  9.d5   @@StartBracket@@or  9.e5  Nd5  @@EndBracket@@  exd5  10.exd5  Ne7  , with unclear play in both cases. }
9. bxc3 Nxe4 10. Ne5
{ Being two pawns down, White should of course act energetically.   After  10.Qc2  Nd6  , followed by ...O-O, Black has no problems. }
10... Nxe5 { Not  10...Nxc3  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Qf3  etc. } 11. Bxe4 Nd7
{ Here I definitely underestimated my opponent's next move.   By  11...Nd3  12.Ba3  c5  Black could have tried to return the pawns to facilitate his development, a common strategy when facing gambits. At this point,  13.Bxd3   @@StartBracket@@while  13.Qh5  h6  insisting on the idea of ...O-O@@EndBracket@@   @@StartBracket@@or  13.dxc5  Qa5  14.Bb4  Qc7  15.c6  Nxb4  16.cxb4  O-O  also looks okay for Black@@EndBracket@@  cxd3  14.Bxc5  b6  15.Ba3  Bb7  16.Qxd3  Qd5  17.f3  Rc8  , preparing ...f7-f6 and ...Kf7, seems about equal. }
12. Ba3
{ A typical restriction method, that we already came across in Vaisser-Illescas with reversed colours, among others. }
12... Nf6
{ Despite the two extra pawns and the absence of direct enemy threats, it is not easy to find a plan for Black here. With the text I transfer the knight to the good d5-square, though that doesn't solve the problem of the uncastled king, of course.   An alternative was  12...c5  13.dxc5  Nf6  in the spirit of the note to Black's 11th move, although after  14.Bf3  Qxd1  15.Raxd1  Nd5  16.Rfe1  White keeps the pressure; e.g.  16...Nxc3  17.c6  Nxd1  18.cxb7  Rb8  19.bxc8=Q+  Rxc8  20.Bxd1  with a favourable endgame. }
13. Bg2 Nd5 14. Qg4 Qf6 15. Qe2
{ Having lured the black queen to f6, White now creates the double threat of Bxd5 and Qxc4.   Less to the point was  15.Bxd5  exd5  16.Rae1+  Be6  17.f4  g6  18.f5  gxf5  19.Rxf5  O-O-O  and Black defends. }
15... Nxc3
{ The ensuing complications favour White thanks to his better development;   but  15...c6  16.Qxc4  was depressing for Black. }
16. Qxc4 Nb5 17. Bb4 { Of course, keeping ...O-O out of the question. } 17...
Qxd4
{ An oversight in a difficult position.   17...Nxd4  was equally bad due to  18.Rad1  e5  19.Rxd4  exd4  20.Qxc7  with decisive threats   While after  17...Bd7  18.a4  Qxd4  19.Rfc1  Qxc4  20.Rxc4  Nd6  21.Rxc7  White keeps a huge advantage. }
18. Bc6+
{ A nice blow which converts White's initiative into something more tangible. }
18... Bd7
{ Or  18...bxc6  19.Qxc6+  Qd7  20.Qxa8  Nd6  21.Rac1  O-O  22.Qb8  with an easy win. }
19. Bxb5 Qxc4 20. Bxc4
{ Material is about even, but Black's pawns are rather unfortunately distributed to put up much resistance to White's mighty bishop pair. }
20... O-O-O
{ I was already a bit disillusioned with the course of events and overlooked  20...c5  preparing ...b7-b5 and ...c5-c4, with some minimal counterplay. }
21. Rfc1 Ba4 22. Bc3 Rhg8 23. Rab1 h5 24. h4 Rd7
{ A useless move which lets White break through on the queenside.   24...c6  and ...Bb5 was the last chance. }
25. Be2 g6 26. Bf3 c6 27. Rb4 Bb5 28. a4 a5
{ Or  28...Bd3  29.Be5  Re7  30.Bxc6  etc. } 29. Rxb5
{ In view of  29.Rxb5  cxb5  30.Be5+  Kd8  31.Bf6+  , Black resigned. } *

