[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "Ma.Carlsen - C.Deepan Chakkravarthy  Dubai 2004  Sicilian Defence,  Rossolimo Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ By his last move White sidestepped the Sveshnikov, whose adherents can also play  3...e5  here. }
4. Bb5 { Finally White settles for a Rossolimo, and now intends 5. e5. } 4...
e5
{ In this sense,  4...Qc7  is the most frequent choice in practice, while the game move invites the opponent to surrender the bishop pair to gain a lead in development. }
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 Nxe4 { The only way of recovering the pawn. } 7. Nxe4 Qd4
8. O-O
{ Another direction is  8.Qe2  Qxe5  9.f4  ,   or even  9.d4  , with complex play. }
8... Qxe5
{ Give Black two extra tempi and he will be just fine after ...Be7 and ...O-O. Thus Carlsen invests a pawn to increase his lead in development. }
9. d4 cxd4
{ It seems that  9...Qxd4  was preferable; e.g.  10.Qf3   @@StartBracket@@perhaps  10.Qe2  Be6  11.Bg5  could be tried instead, in similar fashion to the game@@EndBracket@@  Be7  11.Bg5  f6  12.Rad1  Qxb2  13.Nd6+  Bxd6  14.Rfe1+  Kf7  15.Rxd6  Rf8  , preparing ...Kg8, and Black was okay in R. Ovetchkin-D.Kokarev, Voronezh 2003. }
10. Re1 Be6
{ After  10...Be7  11.Bg5  O-O  12.Nf6+  Bxf6  13.Rxe5  Bxe5  14.Qe2  White keeps an initiative in the endgame, but this was probably a lesser evil for Black, as we will see next. }
11. Bg5
{ Simple and strong - White prevents the opponent's ...O-O-O and also creates the threat of 12. Nf6+.   Other moves fail to pose any problems for Black; e.g.  11.f4  Qd5  12.Ng5  O-O-O   Or  11.Ng5  Qd5  12.Qg4  Kd7  as in N.Ristic-P.Kovacevic, Yugoslav Team Championship 1994. }
11... Be7
{ The natural  11...Qd5  is strongly met by  12.Bf6  paralysing Black's game; e.g.  12...d3   @@StartBracket@@or  12...c5  13.c3  d3  14.c4  intending  14...Qxc4  15.Bxg7  - Postny@@EndBracket@@  13.c4  Qa5  14.Bc3  Qd8  15.Re3  Qh4  16.Qxd3  Rd8  17.Qe2  with a dangerous initiative in O.Kurmann-J.Markos, Zürich 2010. }
12. f4
{ By  12.Nf6+  Bxf6  13.Rxe5  Bxe5  14.f4  Bc7  15.f5  , intending  15...Bxf5  16.Qe1+  Be6  17.Qb4  , White could have secured an advantage in the endgame, but Carlsen goes for more. }
12... Qd5
{ Unfortunately for Black, after  12...Qc7  13.Bxe7  Kxe7  14.Qxd4  Qb6  White has  15.Nc5  . }
13. Bxe7 Kxe7 14. f5 Qxf5
{ Now that  14...Bxf5  runs into  15.Nc3+  , Black has to accept the trade of the f- and d-pawns, which lets White's queen onto the stage with devastating effect. }
15. Qxd4 Qd5
{ Or  15...Rhd8  16.Qb4+  Ke8  17.Rad1  with Nd6+ next - Postny. The text aims at a queen's exchange, but White easily avoids that and keeps his attack going. }
16. Qb4+ c5 17. Nxc5 a5 18. Qa3 Qd4+ 19. Kh1 Qb4 20. Qe3
{ In this hopeless position Black resigned.   There could have followed  20.Qe3  Qg4  21.h3  Qg6  22.Qa3  Ke8  23.Qb3  with decisive threats. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "Exercise #1: Carlsen, Ma vs. Deepan Chakkravarthy, J."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/2p5/2p1q3/4N3/8/PPPP1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

9. d4
{ Give Black two extra tempi and he will be just fine after ...Be7 and ...O-O. Thus Carlsen invests a pawn to increase his lead in development. }
9... cxd4
{ It seems that  9...Qxd4  was preferable; e.g.  10.Qf3   @@StartBracket@@perhaps  10.Qe2  Be6  11.Bg5  could be tried instead, in similar fashion to the game@@EndBracket@@  Be7  11.Bg5  f6  12.Rad1  Qxb2  13.Nd6+  Bxd6  14.Rfe1+  Kf7  15.Rxd6  Rf8  , preparing ...Kg8, and Black was okay in R. Ovetchkin-D.Kokarev, Voronezh 2003. }
10. Re1 Be6
{ After  10...Be7  11.Bg5  O-O  12.Nf6+  Bxf6  13.Rxe5  Bxe5  14.Qe2  White keeps an initiative in the endgame, but this was probably a lesser evil for Black, as we will see next. }
11. Bg5
{ Simple and strong - White prevents the opponent's ...O-O-O and also creates the threat of 12 Nf6+.   Other moves fail to pose any problems for Black; e.g.  11.f4  Qd5  12.Ng5  O-O-O   Or  11.Ng5  Qd5  12.Qg4  Kd7  as in N.Ristic-P.Kovacevic, Yugoslav Team Championship 1994. }
*

