[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "S.Brynell-J.Barkhagen  Swedish Team  Championship 2008  Queen’s Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 b5
{ A interesting alternative to the more common  5...Bb4+  or  5...Be7  . At the cost of a few tempi, Black achieves the exchange of the influential c4-pawn. }
6. cxb5 Bxb5 7. Bg2 d5 8. O-O Nbd7
{ The most accurate choice;   Since both:  8...Bd6   and  8...Be7  give White the additional option of  9.Nc3  Ba6  10.b4  , cramping Black on the queenside - Avrukh. }
9. Nc3 Bc6
{ But this is misguided, as the bishop had no reason to leave the active f1-a6 diagonal yet.   Several games saw  9...Ba6  10.Re1  Bb4  @@StartBracket@@or Be7/Bd6@@EndBracket@@, followed by ...O-O. }
10. Bb2 Bb7
{ Black prepares ...c7-c5, a structurally sound idea but risky on this occasion due to White's lead in development.   10...Be7  was safer, both here and on the next move. }
11. Rc1 c5 12. Na4
{ Forcing the exchange of pawns on White's terms, which will yield him considerable activity.   12.dxc5  Bxc5  was less ambitious. }
12... cxd4 { Or  12...Rc8  13.dxc5  Nxc5  14.Qd4  keeping the pressure. } 13.
Nxd4 Rc8 14. Qd3
{ Natural and strong - White connects his rooks for the battle of the c-file, and also enables an annoying Qb5 or Qe3 later on. }
14... a6
{ Preventing 15. Qb5, but this additional tempo loss will be strongly felt in the further course of the game.   After  14...Be7  15.Qb5  Rb8  16.Nc6  Bxc6  17.Qxc6  O-O  18.Qa6  Nb6  Black is still worse, but at least his king has reached safety. }
15. Rxc8 Qxc8 16. Rc1 Qa8
{ Just as in the previous game, if Black is given two tempi he will have no problems after ...Be7 and ...O-O. How can White prevent that? }
17. Qe3
{ A key move that prepares a sacrifice on e6.   The alternative  17.Rc7  Bd6  was less constructive. }
17... Be7
{ Or  17...Bd6  18.Nxe6  fxe6  19.Qxe6+  Be7  20.Rc7  with the devastating threat 21 Bxf6. }
18. Bh3
{ The threat is stronger than its execution; after  18.Nxe6  fxe6  19.Qxe6  Nf8  Black can still defend. }
18... Ne4
{ Seeing that  18...O-O  runs into  19.Nxe6  fxe6  20.Bxe6+  Rf7  21.Rc7  with huge material losses, Black intercepts the enemy queen. }
19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Bxe6
{ By means of a minimal sacrifice White has managed to open the gates to Black's king, and prevent ...O-O. Actually, the occupation of the e6-square  @@StartBracket@@ or e3 with reversed colours @@EndBracket@@  with a minor piece tends to have a strong restrictive effect on the opponent's development, a fact that motivates similar sacrifices in the Open Sicilian, among others. }
20... Nf8
{ Inviting the white knight to the party;   but the threat of  20...--  21.Bxd7+  Kxd7  22.Nb6+  had to be parried   and  20...Ndf6  21.Rc7  , preparing Qb6, was also grim for Black. }
21. Nb6 Qa7
{ Both  21...Qb8   @@StartBracket@@and  21...Qd8  @@EndBracket@@  were strongly met by  22.Bxd5  Now, in contrast, the capture on d5 would let Black swap the queens, so Brynell adjusts his plans. }
22. Rc7 Qb8
{ Or  22...Nxe6  23.Rxe7+  Kxe7  24.Nxd5+  Bxd5  25.Qxa7+  Kd6  26.Ba3+  Ke5  27.f3  with an easy win. }
23. Rxb7 Qxb7 24. Bxd5 { Black's camp is being completely demolished. } 24...
Qc7 25. Bxe4 Ne6
{ 25...Bc5  26.Bg6+  leads to mate   While after  25...Qc5  26.Bd4  Qg5  27.Bc6+  Kd8  28.Qc3  the black king is doomed. }
26. Bd5 { In view of  26.Bd5  Nc5  27.Bxg7  , Black resigned. } *

