[Black "Exercise #2: Brynell, S. vs. Barkhagen, J."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "q3kb1r/1b1n1ppp/p3pn2/3p4/N2N4/1P1Q2P1/PB2PPBP/2R3K1 w k - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17. Qe3
{ A key move that prepares a sacrifice on e6.   The alternative  17.Rc7  Bd6  was less constructive. }
17... Be7
{ Or  17...Bd6  18.Nxe6  fxe6  19.Qxe6+  Be7  20.Rc7  with the devastating threat 21 Bxf6. }
18. Bh3
{ The threat is stronger than its execution; after  18.Nxe6  fxe6  19.Qxe6  Nf8  Black can still defend. }
18... Ne4
{ Seeing that  18...O-O  runs into  19.Nxe6  fxe6  20.Bxe6+  Rf7  21.Rc7  with huge material losses, Black intercepts the enemy queen. }
19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Bxe6
{ By means of a minimal sacrifice White has managed to open the gates to Black's king, and prevent ...O-O. Actually, the occupation of the e6-square  @@StartBracket@@ or e3 with reversed colours @@EndBracket@@  with a minor piece tends to have a strong restrictive effect on the opponent's development, a fact that motivates similar sacrifices in the Open Sicilian, among others. }
20... Nf8
{ Inviting the white knight to the party;   but the threat of  20...--  21.Bxd7+  Kxd7  22.Nb6+  had to be parried   and  20...Ndf6  21.Rc7  , preparing Qb6, was also grim for Black. }
21. Nb6 Qa7
{ Both  21...Qb8   @@StartBracket@@and  21...Qd8  @@EndBracket@@  were strongly met by  22.Bxd5  Now, in contrast, the capture on d5 would let Black swap the queens, so Brynell adjusts his plans. }
22. Rc7 Qb8
{ Or  22...Nxe6  23.Rxe7+  Kxe7  24.Nxd5+  Bxd5  25.Qxa7+  Kd6  26.Ba3+  Ke5  27.f3  with an easy win. }
23. Rxb7 Qxb7 24. Bxd5 { Black's camp is being completely demolished. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1 Restriction of Castling"]
[Black "N.Short-L.Oll  Parnu 1996  Scandinavian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Be2
{ Short opts for a modest set-up, delaying the fight for the initiative until a later stage of the game.   4.d4  , followed by Nf3 and Bc4, is the main line here. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. h3 Bf5 7. O-O Nbd7
{ A simple alternative was  7...e6  8.d4  Bd6  and ...O-O next. } 8. d4 e6 9.
Nh4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bf4
{ Depriving the black queen and bishop of their standard posts on c7 and d6. }
11... Rd8
{ A natural move in this structure, but here it has the drawback of taking a vital retreat square from the queen, a fact that White immediately exploits.   11...Be7  was preferable;   Or even  11...Bb4  12.Qd3  Qf5  - Short. }
12. a3 Nb6
{ This runs into a strong reply.   After  12...Be7  13.b4  Qf5  14.Qd2  Black is also in trouble, since  14...Nd5   @@StartBracket@@and  14...e5  15.dxe5  Nxe5  16.Qe3  is equally unpleasant for him@@EndBracket@@  15.Nxd5  cxd5  16.g4  Qf6  17.g5  Qf5  18.Bg4  leaves his queen trapped.   In contrast, the pragmatic  12...Rc8  13.b4  Qd8  looked quite acceptable, with ...Be7 and ...O-O just around the corner. }
13. Be5
{ Intercepting the black queen from the f5-square, which means that 14. b4 has become a mortal threat. }
13... Nbd5 14. Nxd5 exd5
{ A third inaccuracy, which yields White an open e-file to operate on.   The usual recapture  14...cxd5  was also dubious due to  15.b4  Qb6  16.c4  dxc4  17.Qa4+  - Khalifman.   Thus  14...Qxd5  15.c4  Qd7  should have been preferred - Short. }
15. b4 Qb6
{ Without any intention to bore the reader, here we have one more case where Black is about to reach safety by ...Be7 and ...O-O. How can White prevent that from happening? }
16. c4
{ By means of the threat of c4-c5, Short manages to clear new lines towards the enemy king. The isolated pawn that now arises on d4 is a less relevant factor. }
16... dxc4
{ Forced; since  16...Rd7  17.c5  Qd8  18.b5  , followed by Qa4, Rab1 etc. leads to a crushing white initiative on the queenside. }
17. Bxc4 Be7
{ After  17...Bd6  18.Qc2  Bxe5  19.dxe5  Nd5  White is just in time for  20.e6  - Khalifman. }
18. Qc2
{ 18.Qc2  is a key move, which stops  18...O-O  on account of  19.Qxg6  . Thus Black is forced onto the defensive. }
18... Kf8 19. Rae1 Nd5 20. Re2
{ The idea of doubling rooks on the open file is very logical, but  20.Re4  was a more active way of doing it - Short.   On the other hand, the concrete  20.Bxd5  Rxd5  21.Bxg7+  Kxg7  22.Rxe7  Rxd4  23.Qc3  Rd8  24.Rfe1  might have been even more promising - in this major piece endgame White is far more active, and he has the safer king. }
20... Bf6 21. Rfe1 Kg8
{ 21...Kg8  provides the king with a flight square on h7, so that  22.Bxd5  can be met by  22...Rxd5  from now on.   In contrast,  21...Bxe5  22.dxe5  Nf4  @@StartBracket@@otherwise 23.e6@@EndBracket@@  23.Rd2  Qc7  24.Qd1  Ke7  25.Rd6  yields White a huge advantage. }
22. Re4 { Admitting the inaccuracy two moves ago. } 22... Rh4
{ After a tenacious defence, all finally goes astray.   Khalifman suggests  22...a5  as an improvement;   while  22...Kh7  , preparing ...Rhe8, seems possible as well, keeping up the fight. }
23. Bxd5 cxd5
{ Perhaps Black had planned  23...Rxd5  24.Bxf6  Rxe4  25.Qxe4  gxf6  , only to discover that  26.Qe8+  Kg7  27.Re7  wins for White; e.g.  27...Qxd4  28.h4  - Khalifman. }
24. Rxh4 Bxh4 25. Bc7 Rc8
{ Or  25...Bxf2+  26.Kxf2  Qxd4+  27.Kf1  Rc8  28.Be5  , keeping the extra material. }
26. Re8+ Rxe8 27. Bxb6 axb6 28. Kf1
{ In this endgame Black's weak queenside pawns make it impossible for him to set up a fortress, so White is winning. }
28... Ra8 29. Qb3 Rd8 30. Ke2 Bf6 31. Kd3 Kf8 32. Qa4
{ In view of  32...--  33.Qa7  next, Black resigned. } *

