{ After a tenacious defence, all finally goes astray.   Khalifman suggests instead of the text move 22...Rh4,  22...a5  as an improvement;   while  22...Kh7  , preparing ...Rhe8, seems possible as well, keeping up the fight. }
23. Bxd5 cxd5
{ Perhaps Black had planned  23...Rxd5  24.Bxf6  Rxe4  25.Qxe4  gxf6  , only to discover that  26.Qe8+  Kg7  27.Re7  wins for White; e.g.  27...Qxd4  28.h4  - Khalifman. }
24. Rxh4 Bxh4 25. Bc7 Rc8
{ Or  25...Bxf2+  26.Kxf2  Qxd4+  27.Kf1  Rc8  28.Be5  , keeping the extra material. }
26. Re8+ Rxe8 27. Bxb6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "Restriction of specific pieces "]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ As we saw in the previous games, the restriction of an opponent's castling had quite a radical impact on the battle. In contrast, the restriction of a specific enemy piece tends to have a more long-term effect on the game, one that can leave the affected side suffering even into the endgame. Let's start with a basic method of this type. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "T.Radjabov-Eu.Torre  Calvia Olympiad 2004  Pirc Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Na6
{ A common reply to the Austrian Attack, by which Black prepares ...c7-c5 without obstructing the bishop on c8. }
7. e5
{ An aggressive choice.   The main line goes  7.O-O  c5  8.d5  Bg4  , preparing ...Nc7, ...Rb8 and, if possible, ...b7-b5. }
7... dxe5
{ This and the next move provide an easy solution to the problem with the threatened knight, but also leaves White with an extra pawn in the centre.   The restrained  7...Nd7  , insisting on the ...c7-c5 idea, is more common in practice. }
8. fxe5 Nd5 9. Nxd5
{ The most ambitious try, to gain some space before Black gets ...c7-c5 in. }
9... Qxd5 10. c4 Qd8 11. h3
{ A typical restriction method, which leaves the bishop on c8 short of a good destiny. It is used in many different openings and in fact we already came across it in Andersson-Portisch and Polugaevsky-Dorfman.   In contrast, after  11.O-O  Bg4  Black has an easier task; e.g.  12.Be4  c6  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Qb6   Or  14...Qc7  , followed by ...Rad8 and possibly ...c6-c5. }
11... f6
{ A sensible pawn break, reducing some of White's space advantage.   11...c5  12.d5  Qc7  13.Qe2  Nb4  14.Bb1  was less convincing. }
12. exf6 exf6 13. O-O c6
{ Preparing ...Nc7 in order to get the offside knight into play.   After  13...c5  14.d5   @@StartBracket@@or  13...f5  14.Bc2  White should also be slightly better@@EndBracket@@   While the flexible  13...Re8  can be met by  14.Kh1  intending  14...f5  15.Bg5 }
14. Bf4 Nc7 15. Qb3
{ Another sensible developing move, with the additional merit of again restricting the bishop on c8. }
15... Kh8 16. Rad1 Ne6 17. Be3 Qc7 18. Rfe1
{ White brings the last piece into the battle, and prepares to meet ...Nf4 by Bf1.   Erenburg also suggests  18.d5  . }
18... Nf4
{ On this square the knight will just become exposed.   Preferable was  18...Ng5  19.Nh2  Qg3  20.Kh1  with only a slight white advantage - Erenburg. }
19. Bf1 b6
{ With d4-d5 hanging in the air, Black should have taken prophylactic measures.   After  19...Rd8  20.d5  cxd5  21.cxd5  Qd6  22.Rd4  White remains on top - Erenburg; but in the game he will obtain an even bigger advantage. }
20. d5
{ Finally, the time is ripe for the inherent plan in the position: converting the pawn majority into a passed pawn. }
20... cxd5 21. cxd5 Qd6 22. Qc4
{ An accurate follow-up, which attacks the knight and threatens Qc6 at the same time. }
22... Nh5
{ This loses material; but after  22...g5  23.Qc6  Qxc6  24.dxc6  Black's game is also difficult due to the dangerous passed pawn and White's clearly more active pieces. }
23. g4 b5
{ Since  23...Ng3  fails to  24.Bf4  , Black's fate is practically decided. }
24. Qc6 Qg3+
{ Or  24...Qxc6  25.dxc6  Ng3  26.Bc5  Rg8  27.Bxb5  etc - Erenburg. } 25. Bg2
Bxg4 26. Bf2 Qf4 27. hxg4 Qxg4 28. Qe6 { The rest is easy. } 28... f5 29. Ne5
Qg5 30. Nf7+ Rxf7 31. Qxf7 h6 32. Qe7 Qg4 33. Qh4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "Exercise #1: T.Radjabov-Eu.Torre"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/n5p1/4P3/2PP4/3B1N2/PP4PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. h3
{ A typical restriction method, which leaves the bishop on c8 short of a good destiny. It is used in many different openings and in fact we already came across it in Andersson-Portisch and Polugaevsky-Dorfman.   In contrast, after  11.O-O  Bg4  Black has an easier task; e.g.  12.Be4  c6  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Qb6   Or  14...Qc7  , followed by ...Rad8 and possibly ...c6-c5. }
11... f6
{ A sensible pawn break, reducing some of White's space advantage.   11...c5  12.d5  Qc7  13.Qe2  Nb4  14.Bb1  was less convincing. }
12. exf6 exf6 13. O-O c6
{ Preparing ...Nc7 in order to get the offside knight into play.   After  13...c5  14.d5   @@StartBracket@@or  13...f5  14.Bc2  White should also be slightly better@@EndBracket@@   While the flexible  13...Re8  can be met by  14.Kh1  intending  14...f5  15.Bg5 }
14. Bf4 Nc7 15. Qb3
{ Another sensible developing move, with the additional merit of again restricting the bishop on c8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "Exercise #2: T.Radjabov-Eu.Torre"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2r1k/p1q3bp/1pp2pp1/8/2PP1n2/1Q2BN1P/PP4P1/3RRBK1 w - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

20. d5
{ Finally, the time is ripe for the inherent plan in the position: converting the pawn majority into a passed pawn. }
20... cxd5 21. cxd5 Qd6 22. Qc4
{ An accurate follow-up, which attacks the knight and threatens Qc6 at the same time. }
22... Nh5
{ This loses material; but after  22...g5  23.Qc6  Qxc6  24.dxc6  Black's game is also difficult due to the dangerous passed pawn and White's clearly more active pieces. }
23. g4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "E.Geller-H.Mecking  Palma de Mallorca  Interzonal 1970  Spanish Opening "]
[Result "*"]

{ In the previous game we saw Radjabov successfully restricting the opponent's light-squared bishop, while in the following encounter, Geller directs his attention to the queen's knight. Moreover, the second half of the game will show us a great deal about restriction in general. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Na5
{ The Chigorin Variation, just as popular today as 100 years ago! } 10. Bc2 c5
11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Nc6
{ Nowadays,  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  Nc6  is a more frequent continuation, with Black securing some counterplay along the c-file.   This has even made  12.d5  a popular choice, in order to close the centre at once. }
13. d5 Na5
{ The knight returns, but the remainder of the game will show us the drawbacks to this decision.   13...Nd8  is much more common, with the future plan of ...Ne8, ...g7-g6, ...Ng7, f7-f6 and ...Nf7, discovered by Rubinstein at the beginning of the previous century. }
14. b3
{ A clever piece of restriction directed at the knight on a5. From now on, the typical idea of ...c5-c4 and ...Nb7-c5 will be met by b3-b4!, exploiting the fact that ...c4xb3 en passant is no longer available. Moreover, a regrouping with ...Nc4-b6 is now also impossible.   The immediate  14.Nf1  gives Black fewer worries after  14...Nc4  , or  14...c4  with ...Nb7-c5 next. }
14... Bd7
{ 14...g6  , preparing ...Nh5, is a different idea analysed by A.Filippov. }
15. Nf1 { White gets on with his intended kingside attack. } 15... Nb7 16. Ng3
c4 17. b4 Rfc8
{ A rather cooperative move.   By  17...g6  Black could have complicated the opponent's attack to a considerable extent; e.g.  18.Nh2  a5  19.Bh6  Rfc8  20.Qf3  Ra6  21.a3  Rca8  22.Nf5  Bd8  with a tense battle in M.Zufic-B.Lengyel, Budapest 2002. }
18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Nh2 a5 20. Re3
{ The rook joins the kingside attack and also eyes the sensitive c3-square. }
20... axb4 21. cxb4 Bxf5
{ Geller writes that Black could have waited with this exchange, but also mentions that the doubling of rooks on the a-file would not have made much sense due to a2-a3.   In any case,  21...g6  22.Rg3  Kh8  23.Nh6  Be8   Or perhaps  21...Kh8  followed by ...Ng8 and g7-g6, seems more tenacious than the text, with a slight hope of reintegrating the knight in Rubinstein style by ...f7-f6 and ...Nd8-f7 later on. }
22. exf5 c3 23. Ng4
{ The exchange of knights will liberate the e4-square for the rook, where it will prevent Black's intended ...Qc4. }
23... Be7 24. Nxf6+ Bxf6 25. Re4
{ Before resuming his kingside attack, White prevents 25...Bg5 as well as a positional sacrifice with ...e5-e4. As a consequence, Black is limited to passive defence. }
25... Qd7 26. Qf3 Rc7 27. h4 Qe7 { Parrying the threat of g4-g5. } 28. g3 Nd8
{ As Geller says, on d8 the knight has a single destiny: back to b7!   28...Rac8  , followed by 29...Rc4, seems preferable, although strategically speaking Black's task remains very difficult due to his passive knight. }
29. a3
{ This and the following moves aim at creating a 'second front' on the queenside. }
29... Rcc8 30. Rb1 Rc7 31. Qe2
{ By a simultaneous attack at the b5- and c3-pawns, White aims at diverting the black queen from the h4-d8 diagonal, so that g3-g4 can be launched later on. }
31... Rb8 32. Rb3 Qd7 33. Qf3 Be7 34. Re3
{ After  34.Rxc3  Rxc3  35.Qxc3  Rc8  Black obtains some minimal counterplay. }
34... Bf6 35. Re4 { Of course not  35.Rbxc3  Rxc3  36.Rxc3  e4  . } 35... Be7
36. g4 f6
{ Practically forced, in view of the threat 37. g5, but this means the end for the c3-pawn now that the bishop can no longer settle at f6.   Of course  36...Bxh4  failed to  37.g5  . }
37. Re3 Nf7 38. Rbxc3 Rbc8 39. Be4
{ Finishing off Black's last hope of counterplay: ...e5-e4 followed by ...Ne5. By now White's extra pawn and attacking potential make the win a matter of time. }
39... Bd8 40. Bd2 Rc4 41. Rxc4 Rxc4
{ In the event of  41...bxc4  Geller had prepared  42.Rc3  , followed by Bb1-a2 and Qe4, besieging the c4-pawn. }
42. Rc3 Bb6 43. Rxc4 bxc4 44. g5 fxg5 45. hxg5 Bd8 46. Qh5 c3 47. Be3 h6
{ With  47...Nh8  48.g6  h6  Black could have avoided a direct assault at his king, but that would be a cruelty to the poor knight, which has already suffered enough in this game. }
48. f6
{ In view of  48.f6  Nxg5  49.Bxg5  hxg5  50.Qh7+  with a quick mate, Black resigned. }
*

