[Black "Exercise #2: E.Geller-H.Mecking"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r2bk1/1nqb1ppp/p2p1n2/1p1PpN2/1Pp1P3/2P2N1P/P1B2PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

19. Nh2 a5 20. Re3
{ The rook joins the kingside attack and also eyes the sensitive c3-square. }
20... axb4 21. cxb4 Bxf5
{ Geller writes that Black could have waited with this exchange, but also mentions that the doubling of rooks on the a-file would not have made much sense due to a2-a3.   In any case,  21...g6  22.Rg3  Kh8  23.Nh6  Be8   Or perhaps  21...Kh8  followed by ...Ng8 and g7-g6, seems more tenacious than the text, with a slight hope of reintegrating the knight in Rubinstein style by ...f7-f6 and ...Nd8-f7 later on. }
22. exf5 c3 23. Ng4
{ The exchange of knights will liberate the e4-square for the rook, where it will prevent Black's intended ...Qc4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "A.Suetin-L.Shamkovich  USSR Championship, Kiev 1964  Scandinavian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

{ Here is one more game from older times, where Black's queen's knight again falls victim to restrictive measures. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Nxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ 4...g6  is another direction in this Scandinavian line  @@StartBracket@@ with an Alekhine flavour @@EndBracket@@ . }
5. c4 Nb6 6. c5 Bxf3
{ This early exchange yields White a clear initiative.   Today, the more elastic  6...N6d7  is preferred; e.g.  7.Qb3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nc6  with a sharp battle. }
7. Qxf3 Nd5 8. Qb3
{ Provoking light square weaknesses on the enemy queenside. Such a 'punishment' with Qb3 is rather common in openings with an early development of the black queen's bishop, such as the Slav.   In contrast,  8.Bc4  c6  9.Nc3  e6  is less dangerous for Black. }
8... b6
{ The active  8...Nc6  fails to  9.Qxb7  Nxd4  10.Bb5+  Nxb5  11.Qc6+  - Suetin. }
9. Bg5 { Restricting the opponent's development with ...e7-e6. } 9... Qd7
{ Perhaps Black should have tried  9...h6  10.Bc4  c6  11.Bh4  g5  12.Bg3  e6  instead, accepting a slight weakening of his kingside structure in order to speed up development. }
10. Nc3 e6 11. Nxd5
{ At this moment, Suetin must have already had his strong 13th move in mind.   Again,  11.Bc4  c6  was less promising. }
11... Qxd5
{ Or  11...exd5  12.O-O-O  , followed by Re1+ with a strong initiative. } 12.
Qxd5 exd5 13. c6 { A key move that paralyses the enemy queenside. } 13... Be7
{ Now  13...Nxc6  obviously fails to  14.Bb5  Kd7  15.Rc1  , so Black has to develop the opposite flank first. }
14. Be3 { 14.Bxe7  Kxe7  15.Rc1  Kd6  or  14.Bf4  Bf6  was inferior - Suetin. }
14... Kd8 15. Rc1 Re8 16. g3
{ By  16.Be2  Bb4+  17.Kd1  Re6  18.Bf3  Rxc6  19.Bxd5  Rxc1+  20.Kxc1  c6  21.Bxf7  White could reach an endgame with a sound extra pawn, but Suetin wants more.   After  16.g3  , the analogous  16...Bb4+  is met by  17.Ke2  , intending  17...Re6  18.Bg2  Rxc6  19.Rxc6  Nxc6  20.Bxd5  Kd7  21.Rc1  etc. }
16... Bg5 17. Bg2
{ White's main priority is to keep the c6-pawn on the board.   After  17.Kd2  Bxe3+  18.fxe3  Ke7  19.Bg2  Kd6  20.Rhf1  Nxc6  21.Rxf7  Rf8  Black defends. }
17... Bxe3 18. fxe3 Rxe3+ 19. Kd2 Re6 20. Rhf1
{ Exploiting the fact that both captures on c6 lose material, White brings the last piece into the battle.   Less accurate was  20.Bxd5  Rd6  , followed by ...Rxd4+, when the knight could be developed via a6-c5 later on. }
20... f6 21. Rf5 Rd6 { Or  21...Nxc6  22.Rxd5+  Ke7  23.Rh5  etc. } 22. Rxd5
Rxd5 23. Bxd5
{ By skilful play Suetin has managed to swap off the opponent's active pieces, while keeping his c6-pawn alive. Over the following moves Black manages to activate his rook, but not the knight, whose absence in the battle proves fatal for him. }
23... Ke7
{ The immediate  23...Na6  fails to  24.Re1  and  24...--  25.Bf7  . } 24. Bg2
Na6 25. a3 { A last piece of restriction aimed at the poor knight. } 25... Rd8
26. Re1+ Kd6
{ Moving the king into a mating net; but after  26...Kf8  27.Kc3  Re8  28.Rxe8+  Kxe8  29.Kc4  and  30. Kd5 Black is also lost due to his absent knight. }
27. b4 { With the inevitable threat of 38. d5 and 39. Re6 mate. } 27... b5 28.
d5 Nc5 29. bxc5+ Kxc5 30. Re7 *

