[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2 Restriction of Specific Pieces"]
[Black "V.Milov-V.Kotronias  Gibraltar 2009  Nimzo-Indian Defence "]
[Result "*"]

{ In the next game, White, by some clever pawn play, manages to isolate both a rook and a bishop from the battle. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 d5 6. a3 Bd6
{ A provocative reply, by which Black declares that he is not bothered about c4-c5.   The text move has lately become a popular alternative to the main line with  6...Be7  . }
7. c5 Be7 8. b4
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain is not in vain, as Black might be about to play ...b7-b6 or ...a7-a5. }
8... Nbd7
{ Black prepares ...e6-e5, hitting the base of the opponent's pawn chain. However, practice has shown that, in this particular line, an attack at its edge tends to be more efficient; e.g.  8...b6  9.Ng3  c6  10.Be2  a5  11.Rb1  Nbd7  12.O-O  axb4  13.axb4  Ba6  with approximate equality, E.Bareev-V.Kramnik, Monte Carlo @@StartBracket@@ rapid @@EndBracket@@ 2003. }
9. Ng3
{ 9.Nf4  is also possible, heading for d3 if needed, but with Black apparently aiming for ...e6-e5, it makes sense to enable Nf5, depriving him of his 'good' bishop. }
9... a5
{ Again  9...c6  , preparing ...b7-b6, ...a7-a5, ...Ba6 etc, was more to the point, but Black follows his outlined plan. }
10. b5
{ The space gained by this advance will be of great value later on in the game. }
10... e5 11. Be2
{ Now it turns out that  11.Nf5  drops a pawn after  11...exd4  12.exd4  Nxc5  so White just gets on with his development. }
11... exd4 12. exd4 Re8 13. O-O b6
{ Liberating the d6-square. In the event of  13...Nf8  at once, White could proceed as in the game, starting with  14.f4 }
14. c6 Nf8
{ Black prepares ...Ng6, ...Bd6 etc, with some kingside activity; however... }
15. f4
{ A cold shower for the opponent. White intends f4-f5 which will leave the bishop on c8, and indirectly the rook on a8, terribly restricted. }
15... Ne6
{ If Black tries to avoid such a scenario by  15...g6  , then after  16.f5  Bxf5  17.Nxf5  gxf5  18.Rxf5  Ng6  19.Bd3  he is clearly worse anyway - Scherbakov. }
16. Kh1 { The immediate  16.f5  obviously failed to  16...Nxd4  . } 16... Ne4
{ Otherwise Black will be asphyxiated by f4-f5. } 17. Ncxe4 dxe4 18. Be3
{ Not  18.d5  Nd4  with unnecessary complications. } 18... Bf6 19. f5
{ White sticks to his plan, without bothering about the d4-pawn. } 19... Nxd4
20. Bc4 a4
{ The prophylactic  20...Rf8  is well met by  21.Rc1  Kh8  22.Qe1  Qe7  23.Qf2  Qe5  24.Rcd1  Rd8  25.Rd2  , preparing Rfd1, when 'Black is helpless as he is playing without two pieces' - Scherbakov. }
21. Qh5 Qe7 22. Bxd4
{ Milov's play in this game is very logical, and teaches us something about priorities in chess. Three moves ago it was worth a pawn to keep restricting the opponent's forces, whereas on this occasion, he has no concern about surrendering the bishop pair in order to eliminate the opponent's most active piece.   22.Rad1  Nc2  was less convincing. }
22... Bxd4 23. Rae1 e3 24. Rf4 Rd8
{ Or  24...Bc3  25.Re4  Bxe1  26.Qxf7+  etc. } 25. h3
{ 25.Rd1  was another good option - Scherbakov; but White is not in a hurry, and first rules out any back rank surprises. }
25... Bc3
{ After  25...Kh8  26.Ne4  g6  27.Qh6  White's attack is also decisive; e.g.  27...Bg7   @@StartBracket@@Or  27...Bxf5  28.Ng5  @@EndBracket@@  28.Qxg7+  Kxg7  29.f6+  - Scherbakov. }
26. Re4 Qf6 27. R1xe3
{ With the inevitable threat of 28. Re8+. The rest is just agony for Black. }
27... g6 28. fxg6 Kf8
{ 28...hxg6  29.Re8+  mates.   While  28...Qxg6  fails to  29.Rxc3 } 29. gxf7 *

