[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.3 More Restriction Methods"]
[Black "More restriction methods "]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ The number of possible restriction methods in chess is practically unlimited, just like the number of possible plans. The next two games feature methods of a more defensive nature. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.3 More Restriction Methods"]
[Black "A.Ardeleanu-R.Zelcic  Schwarzach 2005  Caro-Kann Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Qf3 dxe4
{ Faced with a curious sideline, Zelcic opts for a typical pawn structure of the Caro-Kann.   Both  3...Nf6  and  3...e6  are possible too, whereas  3...d4  4.Bc4  probably favours White. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. d4 Ngf6 6. c3
{ After  6.Bc4  Nb6  7.Nxf6+  gxf6  8.Bb3  Qxd4  White might not have enough compensation for the pawn. }
6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Nf6 8. Qc2 Bg4
{ Black secures an active post for his bishop and, more importantly, interferes with the opponent's Ng1-f3. Interestingly, Petrosian had already played like this in 1960. }
9. Ne2
{ The knight has to content himself with a different route.   After  9.h3  Bh5  10.Bd3  Qd5  11.f3  e6  , followed by ...Bd6, Black was even a bit better in M.Szymanski-A.Deviatkin, Warsaw @@StartBracket@@ rapid @@EndBracket@@ 2005. }
9... Bh5
{ Securing the bishop in advance from a possible Ng3; although  9...e6  10.Ng3  Qd5  should be fine as well; e.g.  11.h3  Bh5  12.Nxh5  Qxh5  13.Be2  Qg6  with a solid game for Black. }
10. Nf4 Bg6 11. Nxg6
{ After  11.Qb3  Qc7  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.g3  e6  14.Bf4  Qb6  Black has also been doing fine in practice. }
11... hxg6 12. Bf4
{ Just like in Short-Oll, White hurries to complicate Black's typical set-up with ...Qc7 and ...Bd6. }
12... e6 13. Qb3 Bd6
{ Admittedly there was nothing wrong about  13...Qb6  , but the text is more ambitious. }
14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. g3
{ It transpires that after  15.Qxb7  Rb8  16.Qxa7  Rxb2  , Black's active pieces and the exposed enemy king more than compensate for the pawn. }
15... O-O-O 16. Bg2 Rh5
{ 16...e5  17.O-O-O  was less promising.   With  16...Rh5  Zelcic seizes the fifth rank, and prepares to meet  17.O-O-O  by  17...Ng4  , a fact that explains White's next move. }
17. h3 Rf5 { The opponent's O-O-O is again frustrated. } 18. Rf1
{ An unfortunate defence of the f2-pawn.   18.Qc2  was called for. } 18... Re5+
{ Exploiting the tactical motif  18...Re5+  19.dxe5  Qd2  , Zelcic revokes White's right to castling, in similar fashion to  9. Bb5+ in Yusupov-Wedberg. }
19. Kd2 Rb5 20. Qc2 e5
{ Of course. Now White seems to be completely lost, but Ardeleanu finds the only sensible defence. }
21. Rad1 exd4 22. Kc1 d3 23. Qd2
{ The loss of a pawn could not be avoided, but at least the king feels a bit safer after the artificial castling. }
23... Qe6 { 23...c5  , preparing ...c5-c4, was an interesting alternative. }
24. b3 Re5 25. Rfe1 Ne4 26. Bxe4 Rxe4 27. Rxe4 Qxe4 28. Qe3 Qxe3+
{ This exchange yields White reasonable drawing chances in the rook endgame.   By  28...Qf5  Black would have kept a clear advantage, since  29.Qxa7  Qe5  wins on the spot. }
29. fxe3 Rd5 30. Kd2 Rf5 31. Kxd3 Rf3 32. Rg1
{ White is still worse, but he eventually saved a draw. } *

