[SetUp "1"]

18... Re5+
{ Exploiting the tactical motif  18...Re5+  19.dxe5  Qd2  , Zelcic revokes White's right to castling, in similar fashion to  9. Bb5+ in Yusupov-Wedberg. }
19. Kd2 Rb5 20. Qc2 e5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.3 More Restriction Methods"]
[Black "E.Sveshnikov-M.Rytshagov  Tallinn (rapid) 2002  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d6
{ The dynamic  6...c4  7.Bc2  Qc7  8.Qe2  g5  is another option in this topical branch of the Alapin Sicilian. }
7. exd6 Qxd6 8. O-O
{ Currently  8.Na3  Be6  9.d4  is a more popular choice, when  9...cxd4  is met by  10.Nb5  Qd7  11.Bxe6  Qxe6+  12.Be3  and Nbxd4 next, with a lead in development. }
8... Be6
{ A typical idea in this line, in order to swap the active enemy bishop. } 9.
Na3
{ The Alapin has its own logics, and this odd move is important in several of its variations.   The stereotyped  9.Bxe6  Qxe6  10.Re1  offers less after  10...Qd7  , followed by ...e7-e6. }
9... Bxb3 10. axb3 { On  10.Qxb3  Black can just proceed as in the game. }
10... Qd3
{ A well-known restriction method, that dates back to the ancient game L.Paulsen-P.Morphy, New York  @@StartBracket@@ 6th matchgame @@EndBracket@@  1857. Black obstructs the white d-pawn, at least for the moment, and also avoids an annoying knight jump to b5 or c4.   In contrast, on  10...e6  there can follow  11.d4  cxd4  12.Nb5  Qd7  13.Bf4  Nd5  14.Bg3  Rc8   @@StartBracket@@or  14...a6  15.c4  , winning a piece@@EndBracket@@  15.Nbxd4  Nxd4  16.Qxd4  f6  17.Rfd1  Bc5  18.Qe4  with a clear advantage for White - Rogozenco. }
11. Re1
{ Or  11.Ne1  Qd7  12.Nc4  Nxc4  13.bxc4  e6  with similar play to the game. }
11... e6 12. Re3 Qd7
{ Over the last few moves, Black moved his queen to a safer square on d7 and, with ...e7-e6, got one step closer to completing his development. On the other hand, White's position wasn't substantially improved by the rook manoeuvre to e3. }
13. Nc4 Nxc4 14. bxc4 Rd8
{ Rogozenco also suggests the simple   14...Be7  when  15.d4   @@StartBracket@@while  15.Qa4  O-O  16.Rb1  , copying Sveshnikov's play in the game, can be met by  16...Qd6  , frustrating the b2-b4 advance@@EndBracket@@  Rd8  16.Rd3  cxd4  17.cxd4  O-O  looks fine for Black. }
15. Qa4
{ Instead of  15.d4  Be7  , with similar play to the previous note, Sveshnikov prepares b2-b4. }
15... Be7 16. Rb1 O-O 17. b4 b6
{ Even simpler was  17...cxb4  18.cxb4  Ne5  19.b5  Nxf3+  20.Rxf3  Bc5  with equality - Rogozenco. }
18. bxc5
{ This move is tactically flawed.   White should probably have tried  18.b5  , gaining some space. }
18... Bxc5
{ Black takes the initiative; exploiting the fact that  18...Bxc5  19.d4  is impossible due to  19...Nxd4  . }
19. Re1 e5
{ Black misses  19...Ne5  20.Qxd7  Nxf3+  21.gxf3  Rxd7  with a favourable endgame.   Even  19...Qd3  repeating our main theme, was interesting for him. }
20. Ba3 { White is just in time to simplify the position. } 20... Bxa3 21. Qxa3
Rfe8 22. d4
{ In view of  22.d4  exd4  23.cxd4  Rxe1+  24.Rxe1  Nxd4  25.Nxd4  Qxd4  26.Qxa7  Qxc4  , the players agreed to a draw. }
*

