[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.3 More Restriction Methods"]
[Black "P.Keres-L.Schmid  Bamberg 1968  Sicilian Defence, Morra Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

{ Another common restriction method is a pawn sacrifice on a central file. This is the subject of the next two games. }
1. d4
{ The e5-e6 sacrifice seen below occurs in a variety of opening lines, such as the Alekhine:  1.e4  Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.c4  Nb6  6.e6   The Rossolimo Sicilian:  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  Nf6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  Bg4  8.d4  cxd4  9.cxd4  d5  10.e5  Ng8   @@StartBracket@@or  10...Nd7  @@EndBracket@@  11.e6   The Slav:  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.c4  dxc4  4.Nc3  a6  5.e4  b5  6.e5  Nd5  7.a4  Bb7  8.e6   And the Grünfeld:  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Qb3  dxc4  6.Qxc4  O-O  7.e4  a6  8.e5  b5  9.Qb3  Nfd7  10.e6  .   Occasionally it is Black who effects it; e.g.  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.g3  Bg7  4.Bg2  O-O  5.Nf3  d6  6.O-O  Nbd7  7.Nc3  e5  8.Qc2  Re8  9.Rd1  e4  10.Nd2   @@StartBracket@@or  10.Ng5  @@EndBracket@@  e3  . }
1... c5 2. e4 cxd4 3. Nf3
{ After an irregular opening sequence, a kind of delayed Morra Gambit has been reached.   At this point,  3.Nf3  d6  ,  3...e6  and  3...Nc6  should all lead to a standard Sicilian battle; instead, Schmid tries a more ambitious move. }
3... Nf6 4. e5 Ne4
{ Black's point - the knight is installed on a good central post; and he is ready to meet  4...Ne4  5.Nxd4  by  5...Qa5+  . }
5. Qxd4 d5 6. Nbd2
{ Practice has also seen  6.exd6  Nxd6  7.Bf4  Nc6  8.Qd2  with a slight initiative. }
6... Nc6 7. Bb5 Bf5
{ In Caro-Kann style, Schmid activates the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e7-e6. }
8. O-O a6
{ Too ambitious - Black should have prioritized development over the bishop pair.   8...e6  was called for; e.g.  9.Qa4  Qb6  10.Nxe4  @@StartBracket@@otherwise 10...Nc5 is possible@@EndBracket@@  10...Bxe4  11.Nd4  Rc8  12.Be3  Bc5  13.c3  a6  14.Bxc6+  bxc6  15.b4  Bxd4  16.Bxd4  Qb5  with approximate equality. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 { Keres hurries to exploit his lead in development. }
10... Qd7 11. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Or  11...dxe4  12.Ng5  , winning a pawn, since  12...Qd5  runs into  13.c4  .   After  11...Bxe4  Black was perhaps hoping for  12.Ng5   @@StartBracket@@or  12.Nd4  c5  @@EndBracket@@  Bf5  , followed by ...e7-e6, but Keres has a much stronger move prepared. }
12. e6
{ A key move. At the price of a mere pawn, White obstructs the opponent's development. Moreover, he forces a minor piece exchange on e4, which will clear the d-file to the benefit of his better-developed forces. }
12... Qxe6
{ Or  12...fxe6  13.Ne5  Qb7  14.Re1  Qb5  15.Rxe4  dxe4  16.Qxe4  with huge compensation for the exchange. }
13. Ng5 Qg6
{ Moving the queen away from the vulnerable queenside.   After  13...Qd7  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bf4  e6  16.Rad1  Qb7  17.Qxe4  Be7  18.Rd3  White's advantage is indisputable, but in the game Black will suffer worse problems. }
14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bf4 { Development and prevention of ...e7-e5. } 15... f5
{ Hanging on to the e4-pawn while preparing ...Kf7, an idea that White restricts with his next move. }
16. Qc4 c5 17. Rad1
{ More mobilization.   In contrast,  17.Qxc5  Qe6  , followed by  18.--  18...g6  or  18...Rg8  , yields Black some slight hope of concluding development. }
17... Qc6 18. f3
{ A decisive blow. As soon as the second white rook enters the battle, Black will be doomed. }
18... h6
{ 18...exf3  19.Rxf3  just helps White   While on  18...e6  Keres had prepared  19.Rd6  Bxd6  20.Qxe6+  Kd8  21.Rd1  with a deadly attack. }
19. fxe4 Qxe4 20. Qxc5 e6
{ Or  20...e5  21.Qc7  , eyeing d7, just like in the game. } 21. Qc7 Be7 22.
Rd7 Bd8 23. Rxd8+
{ This temporary sacrifice finally converts White's strong initiative into something more tangible. }
23... Rxd8 24. Qxg7 Rf8
{ Obviously  24...Qd4+  failed to  25.Qxd4  Rxd4  26.Be5 } 25. Bxh6 Qd4+
{ The only move; since  25...Rf7  runs into  26.Qg8+  Ke7  27.Bg5+ } 26. Qxd4
Rxd4 27. c3 Rd6 28. Bxf8 Kxf8 29. Re1
{ Restricting the black rook.   With two extra pawns, Keres easily won the rook endgame after  29.Re1  Kf7  30.Kf2  Kf6  31.Ke2  e5  32.Rd1  Rb6  33.b3  Kg5  34.c4  etc. }
*

