[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.3 More Restriction Methods"]
[Black "F.Nijboer-J.Hector  Wijk aan Zee 2003  Spanish Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ One of the oldest Spanish variations, which was sometimes used by Steinitz in his time. }
4. c3 Bb6 { 4...Nf6  and the sharp  4...f5  are more popular options. } 5. d4
exd4 6. cxd4 Nce7
{ Preparing ...c7-c6 and ...d7-d5, an idea which White prevents with his next move. }
7. d5 Nf6
{ After  7...c6  8.Ba4  d6  9.Nc3  Nf6  10.Bg5  White also has a more active game. }
8. Nc3 a6 9. Ba4
{ The correct retreat square, so as to keep preventing ...d7-d6. } 9... O-O
{ After  9...O-O  , both  10.Bg5   @@StartBracket@@ and  10.O-O  d6  @@EndBracket@@  10...Ng6  , followed by ...h7-h6, should be fine for Black, but Nijboer has a stronger move prepared. }
10. d6 { A key advance that severely obstructs Black's queenside development. }
10... cxd6 11. Bg5
{ Of course,  11.Qxd6  Bc7  and 12...d5 next wasn't White's intention. } 11...
Ng4
{ Preparing ...f7-f6 in order to release the annoying pin, but this will leave the kingside more vulnerable; besides which, it does nothing to solve the problem with the queenside pieces.   Nijboer indicates  11...d5  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.exd5  d6  14.O-O  with a clear advantage for White; even so Black would have much more activity than in the game after, let's say,  14...Kh8  and 15...Rg8 next. }
12. O-O f6 13. Bf4 Ne5 14. Rc1
{ White keeps ignoring the d6-pawn, and just brings more pieces to the battle. }
14... Bc7 15. Nd5 N7c6 { Or  15...Nxd5  16.Bb3  followed by Bxd5 -Wedberg. }
16. Nxc7 Qxc7 17. Nd4
{ By means of the threat of 18. Nf5 White provokes a further weakening in Black's kingside. }
17... g6 18. Bh6 Re8 19. Bb3+ Nf7
{ This looks awkward; but  19...Kh8  failed to  20.f4  Qb6  21.fxe5  , when both  21...dxe5   @@StartBracket@@and  21...Nxd4  22.exf6  @@EndBracket@@  22.Rxf6  are fatal for Black - Nijboer. }
20. Nf5
{ A strong sacrifice, motivated by the fact that Black is still one rook and one bishop down in the battle. }
20... Re6
{ Practically forced; since  20...gxf5  21.exf5  , followed by 22. Qh5, is terminal. }
21. Bf4 { Now Black has no other choice than to accept the 'gift'. } 21... gxf5
22. exf5 Kf8
{ An early resignation; but  22...Re7  23.Qg4+  led to a decisive attack; e.g.  23...Kh8   @@StartBracket@@or  23...Kf8  24.Bxf7  Rxf7  25.Bh6+  Ke7  26.Rfe1+  @@EndBracket@@  24.Qh4  Ng5   @@StartBracket@@  24...Kg7  runs into  25.Rc3  @@EndBracket@@  25.Bxg5  fxg5  26.Qh6  Qd8  27.f6  - Nijboer. }
23. fxe6 dxe6 24. Qh5 Nfe5 25. Rfd1
{ The last piece joins the party, and prevents the consolidating 25...Qf7. }
25... d5 26. Bxe5 fxe5 27. Rc3 Ke7 28. Bxd5
{ In view of  28.Bxd5  exd5  29.Qxh7+  and  30. Rxd5+ next, Black resigned. } *

