[White "4.4 Restriction of Plans"]
[Black "Restriction of plans "]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Finally, let us see two positional masterpieces by Karpov and Petrosian, which feature all three types of restriction mentioned at the beginning of this chapter, with emphasis on preventing the opponent's plans. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.4 Restriction of Plans"]
[Black "A.Karpov-V.Smyslov  USSR Team Championship 1972  Petroff’s Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nf6
{ Quite a passive way of treating the Petroff.   6...d5  is the main line, either here or on the previous move. }
7. h3
{ A simple piece of restriction directed at the bishop on c8, and one which we already saw in Radjabov-Torre. }
7... O-O 8. O-O c5
{ This advance doesn't contribute a lot to Black's position and might even harm his pawn structure.   8...Re8  , followed by ...Nbd7-f8, was a more solid choice. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Re1
{ With  10.Re1  White maintains the central tension, aware that after  10...cxd4  11.Nb5  , followed by 12. Nbxd4, Black doesn't have sufficient activity to compensate for the IQP on d6.   Less promising was  10.d5  Nb4  11.Bc4  Bf5  etc. }
10... a6
{ Black prepares ...b7-b5, an idea that Karpov will prevent with great fervour over the following moves. }
11. d5
{ First the knight should be dislodged from  c6  , since the immediate  11.a4  permits the annoying  11...Nb4  . }
11... Na7
{ Here this piece will be a problem child for the rest of the game.   11...Nb4  was more active, although after  12.Bf1  Bf5  13.Re2  a5  @@StartBracket@@ a sad necessity in view of the threat of 14 a3 @@EndBracket@@  14.Bf4  Re8  15.a3  Na6  16.Nd2  , preparing Nc4, White has a pleasant edge anyway. }
12. a4 Bd7 13. a5 Re8
{ Or  13...Nb5  14.Na4  seizing the b6-square and leaving the enemy knight useless on b5. At this point, neither  14...Qxa5   @@StartBracket@@Nor  14...Nxd5  15.c4  @@EndBracket@@  15.Rxe7  works for Black. }
14. Bf1
{ This and the subsequent moves with the other bishop are rather typical in the present structure. On f1 and h2, the bishops are active and, at the same time, protected from any enemy threats. }
14... h6
{ Smyslov intends 15...Bf8 in order to swap rooks, and first rules out an annoying pin with Bg5. Unfortunately, the problem with the queen's knight will become more evident the fewer pieces remain on the board.   In this sense,  14...Nb5  seems preferable, redirecting it to c7, now that  15.Na4  no longer works due to  15...Qxa5  . }
15. Bf4 Bf8 16. Rxe8
{ Obviously  16.Qd2  Rxe1  17.Rxe1  failed to  17...Qxa5  . } 16... Qxe8 17.
Bh2 Qd8 18. Nd2 Qc7
{ Some prophylaxis against the imminent 19. Nc4, but Karpov has other plans. }
19. Nde4
{ Swapping the opponent's most active piece, consistent with the note to Black's 14th move. }
19... Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bf5 21. Nd2 Re8 22. c3
{ Seeing that Black can't undertake much, White takes his time. } 22... Qd8 23.
Qb3 Qd7 24. c4
{ After  24.Nc4  Nc8  White doesn't really make progress on the queenside, and Black's bad knight would actually be doing a good defensive job on c8, protecting the weak points at d6 and b6. With the text Karpov instead prepares a breakthrough on the queenside, an idea which will become evident five moves later. }
24... Nc8 25. g4
{ A useful prelude to the next move, increasing White's light square control and providing the king with a flight square on g2. }
25... Bh7 26. Bd3 Bxd3
{ Black has to accept the exchange of another active piece, since  26...f5  27.Qc2  doesn't favour him. }
27. Qxd3 g6 28. Rb1
{ Finally, the rook gained access to b1, and now b2-b4, clearing its way towards the b7-pawn, can't be prevented. }
28... Bg7 29. b4 cxb4 30. Rxb4 Qc7 31. Nb3
{ Protecting the a5-pawn and preventing ...Qc5 at the same time. By the way, the fact that Black can't get his knight to c5 had to be considered when playing b2-b4. }
31... Be5
{ A liberating attempt with  31...b6  fails to  32.axb6  Nxb6  33.c5  so Smyslov opts to swap the powerful bishop on h2. }
32. Bxe5 Rxe5 33. Kg2 g5
{ Preparing ...Ne7-g6-f4, but this idea is powerfully prevented by Karpov's next move.   Black should have preferred either  33...Qe7  34.Nd4  Qc7  , with a waiting game   Or  33...b6  , trying to improve the knight, when  34.Ra4  keeps the advantage. }
34. Qd4
{ With this small move,  34.Qd4  , White gets ready to meet  34...Ne7  by  35.Qb6  winning a pawn and forcing the exchange of queens at the same time. Thus Smyslov is limited to passive defence, which would have been easier to conduct with the g-pawn still on g6. }
34... Qe7 35. Nd2 Re1 36. Rb3 Re2 37. Kf3 Re5
{ In view of the threat  377...--  38.Ne4  , the rook has to retreat. } 38. Re3
f6
{ After  38...Rxe3+  39.fxe3  followed by 40. Ne4, the black knight is badly missed on d7. }
39. Ne4 Kg7 40. Kg2
{ 40.Kg2  creates the threat of  40...--  41.Ng3  Rxe3  42.Nf5+   Another good option was  40.Ng3  Rxe3+  41.fxe3  and 42. Nf5+ next. }
40... Qc7
{ This loses on the spot; though after  40...Kg8  41.Ng3  , heading for f5.   Or even  41.Kf1  intending Ke2-d3 and Rf3, Black's task also remains very difficult. }
41. Rf3 b5 42. axb6
{ In view of  42.axb6  Qxb6   @@StartBracket@@or  42...Nxb6  43.Nxf6  , heading for e8@@EndBracket@@  43.Qxb6  Nxb6  44.Nxd6  with a hopeless endgame, Black resigned. }
