[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.4 Restriction of Plans"]
[Black "T.V.Petrosian-E.Gufeld  USSR Championship,  Moscow 1961  King’s Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e4 O-O 5. Bg5 d6
{ Incidentally, had Black played  5...h6  , then after  6.Be3  , followed by f2-f3 and Qd2, White gains a tempo for his development thanks to the attack on h6. }
6. Qd2
{ At first sight, White appears to be preparing a kingside attack with Bh6 and h4-h5, but the idea behind his set-up is quite different: to restrict Black's typical counterplay with ...e7-e5, ...Nh5, ...f7-f5 etc, now that the bishop on g5 can't be easily chased away. }
6... c5
{ A natural reaction, which takes the game into Benoni or Benko waters, depending on Black's preferences. }
7. d5 Qa5
{ 7...e6  and  7...b5  are more popular options, in accordance with the previous note. }
8. Bd3 a6 9. Nge2 e5
{ Such a closure of the centre will leave Black rather short of counterplay. A more modern approach is  9...b5  in Benko style or the flexible  9...Nbd7  first. }
10. O-O Nbd7 11. a3
{ The first step to a future queenside expansion with b2-b4. } 11... Nh5
{ With his last move Black signalled the plan of ...f7-f5, to which Petrosian finds a subtle antidote. }
12. f3
{ Thus White enables the idea of a kingside grip by g2-g4 and Ng3; more importantly  12.f3  prepares to meet  12...f5  by  13.exf5  gxf5  14.Qc2  with an annoying attack on f5, now that the f2-f3 move has ruled out the reply 14...e4.   In contrast,  12.Be7  Re8  13.Bxd6  failed to  13...Qb6  - ChessBase. }
12... Bf6
{ Gufeld vacates g7 for the knight in advance of g2-g4, but now his kingside pieces become a bit awkwardly placed.   Perhaps  12...Qc7  was more promising, when  13.g4   @@StartBracket@@probably Petrosian wouldn't have proceeded so straightforwardly, perhaps preferring another useful move like  13.Kh1  while awaiting Black's next step@@EndBracket@@  Nhf6  14.Ng3  can be met by  14...b5  15.cxb5  c4  , recovering the pawn on the next move with some counterplay. }
13. Bh6 Ng7 14. g3
{ No hurry. White keeps the option of g3-g4, and also enables the f3-f4 breakthrough, depending on Black's coming play. }
14... Rb8 15. Kh1
{ Another piece of restriction, or prophylaxis if you prefer.   With his king safe from any checks on the g1-a7 diagonal after  15.Kh1  White gets ready to meet the intended  15...b5  by  16.cxb5  axb5  17.b4  when  17...cxb4   @@StartBracket@@while  17...Qa6  18.Nxb5  wins a pawn since  18...Rxb5  runs into  19.a4  @@EndBracket@@  18.axb4  Qxb4  19.Be3  followed by 20. Rfb1, traps the black queen.   In contrast,  15.a4  would be less flexible. }
15... Qc7 16. b3
{ Preventing the idea of  16...b5  17  cxb5  c4  . As a result, Black has to forget about queenside counterplay, and now turns his attention to the opposite flank. }
16... Be7 17. Rab1 Kh8
{ Just like five moves ago,  17...f5  is strongly met by  18.exf5  gxf5  19.Qc2  so Gufeld takes preparatory actions. }
18. Rb2 { The immediate  18.b4  permits  18...b5  19.cxb5  c4  . } 18... Nf6
19. b4
{ With the black knight having just left the queenside, the time is right to strike there. }
19... Ng8 20. Be3 f5
{ At last.   After the more cautious  20...b6  21.bxc5  bxc5  22.Rxb8  Qxb8  23.Rb1  , and Qb2 next, White is clearly better - ChessBase. }
21. bxc5 dxc5 22. Rfb1 Nf6
{ At this point,  22...b6  is strongly met by  23.Na4   While  22...fxe4  23.Nxe4  Rxf3  24.Rb6  Nf5  25.Bg5  leads to a clear initiative for White. }
23. Rb6 Bd6
{ In view of lines like  23...Nd7  24.d6  Bxd6  25.Nd5  , Black decides to blockade the d-pawn. }
24. Bh6 Rf7
{ Unpinning the knight in order to enable a later ...Nf5.   If  24...fxe4  25.Nxe4  Nxe4  26.Bxe4  Rf7  in the same spirit, then White has the restrictive  27.g4  - ChessBase   Whereas it is not clear what Black gains from  24...Nd7  25.R6b2  . }
25. Ng1
{ Thus White prepares Nh3-g5 on some occasions.   The prophylactic  25.Kg2  was interesting too; e.g.  25...fxe4  26.Bxg7+  @@StartBracket@@ ruling out ...Nf5 @@EndBracket@@  26...Kxg7  27.Nxe4  Nxe4  28.Bxe4  , intending Nc3, Bd3 and Ne4, with a pleasant advantage. }
25... f4
{ A suicidal attack.   25...fxe4  was called for, when  26.Nxe4  Nxe4  27.Bxe4  Nf5  28.Nh3  keeps a clear initiative. }
26. gxf4 Nd7
{ Perhaps Gufeld had overlooked something in the line  26...exf4  27.Rxd6  Qxd6  28.Bxf4  Nxe4  29.Bxd6  Nxd2  30.Bxb8  Nxb1  31.Bxb1  with a huge edge for White in the endgame. }
27. fxe5 Bxe5
{ Or  27...Nxb6  28.exd6  Qxd6  29.e5  Qd8  30.Bg5  Qc7  31.d6  Qc6  32.Be4  etc.   At this point, after  27...Bxe5  , Black perhaps expected  28.R6b3  Nh5  with some dark square play in exchange for the pawn; however... }
28. Re6
{ Surprising, and very strong. On e6 the rook severely obstructs Black's play and is ready to sacrifice itself on e5 whenever the knight leaves d7;   e.g.  28.Re6  Nf8   @@StartBracket@@or  28...Nf6  29.Rxe5  Qxe5  30.Bf4  @@EndBracket@@  29.Rxe5  Qxe5  30.f4  Qh5  31.f5  gxf5  32.Be2  Qg6  33.Nf3  with a crushing advantage. }
28... b5
{ This counterattack is bound to fail, but it was difficult to give Black good advice. }
29. cxb5 c4 30. Rc6 Qd8 31. Bxc4
{ With three extra pawns and superior activity, the rest is easy for White. }
31... Qh4 32. Rc1 Nh5 33. Bg5 { Forcing Black into a useless sacrifice. } 33...
Ng3+ 34. Kg2 Nxe4 35. Nxe4 Qxh2+ 36. Kf1 Rxf3+ 37. Nxf3 Qh1+ 38. Kf2 *

