1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3
{ 4.O-O  is more flexible, when the plan of c2-c3 and d2-d4 is sometimes discarded in favour of other set-ups; e.g. after  4...Bg7  5.Re1  e5  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.d3  , followed by Nbd2-c4. }
4... Nf6 5. Qe2 Bg7 6. e5
{ White should rather prefer  6.O-O  O-O  7.d4  ;   or even the flexible  7.Rd1  first. }
6... Nd5 7. Qc4
{ This early pawn-grabbing runs into a strong antidote.   7.O-O  O-O  8.d4  seems more natural, although Black has few problems after  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  d6  . }
7... Nc7 8. Bxc6
{ After  8.Qxc5  b6  9.Qc4  Nxe5  the pawn trade clearly favours Black - Matulovic. }
8... dxc6 9. Qxc5
