[Black "R.J.Fischer-M.Matulovic  Palma de Mallorca  Interzonal 1970  Sicilian Defence,  Rossolimo Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppn1ppbp/2p3p1/2Q1P3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

9... Qd3
{ Of course, immobilizing White's queenside forces and preventing 10. O-O } 10.
Qe3 Bf5 11. Qxd3 Bxd3
{ Despite the exchange of queens White is still under pressure due to his cramped development. In the following moves, Fischer finds the only way of challenging the annoying bishop on d3. }
12. Kd1 Ne6 13. Ne1 Nf4 14. Nxd3
{ Avoiding  14.g3  Be2+  15.Kc2  Nh3  , when White must even be careful of a mate on d1. }
14... Nxd3 15. f4
{ Seeing that both  15.Kc2  and  15.Ke2  are well met by  15...O-O-O  , Fischer tries a radical solution. }
15... Bh6
{ Matulovic turns down the offer.   After  15...Nf2+  16.Ke2  Nxh1  17.d4  , preparing Be3, Nd2 etc, the position is far from clear. }
16. Kc2 Nxc1 17. Re1
{ A clever intermediate move.   In contrast,  17.Kxc1  Bxf4  wins a pawn for Black. }
17... O-O-O
{ 17...Bxf4  18.g3  probably leads to the game   while  17...Nxa2  18.g3  Nxc3  19.bxc3  yields White compensation for the pawn - Matulovic. }
18. Kxc1 Bxf4 19. g3 Bh6 20. Kc2 Rd5
{ 20...Rd5  intends  21.d4  c5  . After inventive play from both sides Black has ended up with a slight initiative in the endgame, which later finished in a draw. }
