[Result "*"]

1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ From the English we have transposed to the Panov Attack in the Caro-Kann. }
5... Nc6 6. Bg5 dxc4
{ A risky, but quite popular choice.   6...e6  and  6...Be6  are safer options. }
7. d5 { A gambit with  7.Bxc4  is possible as well. } 7... Ne5 8. Qd4 Nd3+
{ 'Don't swap a developed piece for an undeveloped one' is a possible addition to the existing opening principles.   Practice favours  8...h6  9.Bh4  Ng6  , when both  10.Bxf6   @@StartBracket@@and  10.Bg3  e5  @@EndBracket@@  exf6  11.Bxc4  Bd6  , followed by ...O-O, should be okay for Black. }
9. Bxd3 cxd3 10. Nf3
{ Speeding up development; the pawn can wait.   After  10.Qxd3  g6  11.Bxf6  exf6  12.Nf3  Bd6  13.O-O  O-O  Black has less to worry about. }
10... g6 11. Bxf6 exf6 12. O-O Bg7
{ With the white queen still on d4,   12...Bd6  clearly fails to  13.Ne4  . }
13. --
