[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "F.Nijboer-S.Ernst  Groningen 2004  Petroff’s Defence "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p3n2/2Pp4/3P4/3B1N2/PPQ2PPP/RNB2RK1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. c6
{ Severely restricting the enemy queenside. Contrary to Suetin-Shamkovich here Black is able to liquidate the c6-pawn, but only at the cost of permitting White a strong initiative on the kingside. }
11... Qd6 12. Ne5 Ng4 13. Bf4
{ 13.Nxg4  Bxg4  14.Bxh7+  Kh8  15.Bf5  Bxf5  16.Qxf5  Nxc6  is less effective - Huzman. }
13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxc6 15. Nc3
{ Stronger than the obvious  15.Bxh7+   Since after  15.Nc3  Black can't avoid the capture on h7 anyway due to the additional threat of  15...--  16.Nxd5  Qxd5  17.Be4  . }
15... Be6 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Bd3
{ With the strong threat of Qe2 @@StartBracket@@d1@@EndBracket@@-h5. } 17...
Nd7
{ 17...Qd7  was more tenacious, although after  18.Qe2  Kg8  19.Qh5  f5  20.Rfe1  White keeps a strong initiative. }
18. Qe2 Kg8 19. Bb5 Qb7 20. Bxg7
{ This temporary sacrifice leads to an extra pawn for White, and further exposure of the enemy king. }
20... Kxg7 21. Bxd7 Bxd7 22. Qxe7 c6 23. Rae1
{ 23.f4  Rfe8  24.Qg5+  Kf8  25.f5  was a good alternative - Huzman. } 23...
Rae8 24. Qg5+ Kh7 25. Re3
{ With a crushing advantage.   There followed  25.Re3  Rg8  26.Qh5+  Kg7  27.Rg3+  Kf8  28.Qh6+  Ke7  29.Re1+  Kd8  30.Rxg8  Rxg8  31.Qf6+  Kc8  32.Qxf7  Rxg2+  33.Kh1  Rg4  34.f3  Rxd4  35.Re8+  Kc7  36.Qe7  c5  37.Qe5+  and Black resigned, in view of the imminent mate. }
