1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. Qb3
{ A viable alternative to the main line with  5.b3  .   The gambit  5.Qc2  Bb7  6.Bg2  c5  7.d5  has recently also become very popular in practice. }
5... c6
{ An interesting reaction - Black plans to recapture on d5 with the c-pawn after ...d7-d5, thus reaching a Slav structure where his light-squared bishop would outstrip its white counterpart. }
6. Bg5
{ 6.Bf4  is more popular, when Black often delays ...d7-d5 for a few moves, starting with  6...Be7  . }
6... d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bxf6
{ White hurries to swap on f6 before ...Be7xf6 is possible. } 8... Qxf6 9. Nc3
Qd8
{ Rather passive.   S.Halkias-E.Postny, Mureck 1998, saw the inventive  9...Qe7  heading for b4 or b7, and after  10.a3  Qb7  11.Bg2  Nd7  12.O-O  Be7  13.Rfe1  O-O  Black had little to worry about. }
10. Ne5 { Seizing the centre and eyeing the opponent's Achilles' heel on c6. }
10... Bd6
