[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-O.Panno  Mendoza 2004  Modern Defence "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. c4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 f5
{ A double-edged variation that has gained popularity in recent years. White's pawn structure has been damaged and, while the position remains closed, his bishop pair won't be much of an asset, a fact that explains my next move. }
6. e4 fxe4 7. f3 e5
{ 7...exf3  8.Nxf3  , followed by 9. Bd3 and 10. O-O, would fully justify White's gambit   but  7...d6  8.fxe4  Nf6  was a safer choice, with complex play. }
8. dxe6
{ Sticking to the idea of opening the position for the bishops.   Obviously  8.fxe4  failed to  8...Qh4+   while  8.d6  Nc6  9.Nh3  Qa5  didn't please me either. }
8... Qe7
{ A sharp choice. After  8...dxe6  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.Bg5+  Ke8  11.O-O-O  White should be slightly better.   Whereas  8...Nc6  is well met by  9.Nh3  Nf6  10.fxe4  , when both  10...O-O   @@StartBracket@@and  10...Nxe4  11.Qd3  @@EndBracket@@  11.Bh6  Re8  12.Bd3  , followed by 13.O-O, yield him a slight initiative. }
9. Nh3
{ Development first. After  9.exd7+  Bxd7  , followed by  10.--  10...Nc6  and  11.--  11...O-O-O  , it is Black who is ahead in development. }
9... Nf6 10. Be2 exf3
{ Much safer was  10...dxe6  11.O-O  e5  12.Nf2  O-O  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Qd5+  Kg7  15.Qxe4  Bf5  16.Qe3  with just a minimal edge for White. }
11. Bxf3 dxe6
{ Or  11...Qxe6+  12.Kf2  O-O  13.Re1  Qxc4  14.Kg1  d5  15.Bg5  Nbd7  16.Nf4  with a strong initiative. }
12. O-O Nbd7
{ After  12...O-O  13.Bh6  Rd8  14.Qe2  e5  15.Bg5  Black is again under strong pressure. }
13. --
