1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 Nf6 4. Be2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+
{ In order to set up a pawn centre quickly, White moves the bishop again.   6.Re1  , followed by Bf1, is another option. }
6... Nc6
{ 6...Bd7  is much more common, when, after the swap on d7, White can prepare d2-d4 by either Re1 or Qe2. }
7. d4 a6
{ 7...Nxe4  obviously fails to  8.d5  a6  9.Bd3   but  7...O-O  8.d5  Nb8  is interesting, followed by ...e7-e6, with some kind of Benoni battle where Black might have more counterplay than in the game. }
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Re1 cxd4 10. cxd4 O-O
{ Or  10...Bg4  11.Nbd2  O-O  12.h3  Bxf3  13.Nxf3  with a slight advantage. }
11. --
