[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "J.Hellsten-N.De Firmian  Bermuda 1997  Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/4ppbp/p1pp1np1/8/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. h3
{ Restricting the bishop on c8.   In contrast, after  11.Nc3  Bg4  12.Be3  Nd7  , preparing ...Qb6 and ...c6-c5, Black obtains counterplay. }
11... Nd7
{ After  11...Bd7  12.Nc3  Rb8  13.b3  Qa5  14.Bd2  Qh5  15.e5  White took the initiative in R.Kaula-B.Wilk, Polish Team Championship 1999. }
12. Nc3 c5 13. Be3
{ 13.d5  is less appropriate due to  13...Rb8  with some black pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
13... Rb8 14. Qd2 cxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4
{ Such an exchange rarely favours Black; but after  15...Ne5  16.Bxe5  dxe5  17.Qe2  , preparing b2-b3 and Nd2-c4, White has a pleasant advantage. }
16. Nxd4 Bb7 17. Rad1 Nf6 18. Qg5
{ With the dual intention of 19. e5 and 19. Nf5. } 18... e6
{ Thus Black responds to both enemy ideas; since after  18...e6  19.e5  can be met by  19...Nd5  . On the other hand, the d6-pawn becomes rather weak.   Anyway, after  18...Qc7  19.Nf5  White also has the initiative. }
19. Nb3
{ Clearing the d-file towards the d6-pawn, while preparing Na5-c4 later on. }
19... Qe7 20. Rd2 Rfd8 21. Na5 Kg7 22. Red1 h6
{ Helping the white queen to a better square.   After  22...Ba8  23.Nc4  d5  24.exd5  Bxd5  Black would just be minimally worse. }
23. Qe3 Ba8 24. Nc4 Ne8 25. b3 Kh7 26. Rd3
{ Preparing Qd2 with increased pressure on d6.   There followed  26.Rd3  Qc7  27.h4  Bc6  losing a pawn, but:   27...Rbc8  28.h5  also favoured White  28.Qd2  Bb5  29.Nxb5  axb5  30.Nxd6  Nxd6  31.Rxd6  Rxd6  32.Qxd6  Qxd6  33.Rxd6  with a sound extra pawn in the endgame, although after a series of errors I finally had to concede a draw. }
