[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Bb5 Bc5
{ 4...Bb4  and  4...Nd4  are more frequent reactions to the Four Knights Game. }
5. O-O O-O 6. Nxe5 Re8
{ After  6...Nxe5  7.d4  Bd6  8.f4  White soon regains the piece, with some initiative. }
7. Nf3
{ 7.Nxc6  dxc6  is quite risky; e.g.  8.Bc4  Nxe4  9.Nxe4  Rxe4  10.Bxf7+  Kh8  with some initiative for the pawn. }
7... Nxe4 8. d4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Be7
{ 9...Bf8  is more natural, keeping the e-file clear for the rook. } 10. d5
{ The only way to fight for an advantage - White gains some space and expels the black knight from the centre. }
10... Nb8 11. Bf4 a6 12. Ba4 Bf6
{ 12...b5  13.Bb3  d6  seems preferable, followed by ...Nd7 to reactivate the knight, although after  14.Nd4  Bb7  15.c4  bxc4  16.Ba4  Rf8  17.Nf5  Bf6  18.Rb1  White had some initiative in S.Conquest-J.Garriga Nualart, Olot 1994. }
13. --
