[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "G.Maroczy-H.Pillsbury  Nuremberg 1896  Four Knights Game "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqr1k1/1ppp1ppp/p4b2/3P4/B4B2/2P2N2/P1P2PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. d6
{ A powerful advance that severely restricts Black's queenside pieces, in particular the bishop on c8. It is for this reason that 12 Ba4! was essential on the previous move, in order to keep preventing ...d7-d6, just like in Nijboer-Hector. }
13... c6
{ Now the knight on b8 becomes restricted too.   A lesser evil was  13...cxd6  , when White could consider  14.Qxd6  Bxc3  15.Rad1  followed by Bb3, with excellent compensation for the pawn. }
14. Bb3 b5 15. Qd2 Bb7 16. Ng5
{ Maroczy utilizes the threat at f7 to bring his knight to e4, where it will complicate Black's intended ...c6-c5. }
16... Rf8 17. Ne4 a5 18. a3 Na6 19. Rae1
{ Since Black can't easily connect his rooks, it makes sense to work on the open file. }
19... c5 20. Bd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 b4 22. Re3
{ White just ignores the enemy attack on the queenside, and starts preparing a final assault on the opposite flank. }
22... Bxc3
{ A serious mistake - without this bishop there will be nobody defending the king.   For better or worse,  22...bxa3  had to be tried. }
23. Rxc3
{ 23.Nxc3  bxc3  24.Bg5  was another good option, followed by a deadly Bf6; e.g.  24...Qc8  25.Bf6  gxf6  26.Rg3+  Kh8  27.Qf5  Qd8  28.Rh3  with mate. }
23... bxc3 24. Bg5 Nc7
{ Forced; since any queen move, such as  24...Qc8  , runs into  25.Nf6+  , when both  25...Kh8   @@StartBracket@@and  25...gxf6  26.Bxf6  h6  27.Qf5  @@EndBracket@@  26.Qf5  g6  27.Qh3  h5  28.Nxh5  lead to a quick mate. }
25. Qc4 Qe8 26. dxc7
{ Again  26.Nf6+  was possible, though the text wins easily as well. } 26...
Qe5 27. Rd1 Rfe8 28. Rxd7 Kh8 29. Qxf7 Qxg5 30. f4 Qg4 31. h3 Qxd7 32. Qxd7
Rxe4 33. c8=Q+ *

