[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "V.Anand-G.Kamsky  Las Palmas  (11th matchgame) 1995  Sicilian Defence, Najdorf Variation "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1p2bppp/p2ppn2/q7/3QPP2/2N1B3/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R w - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. Qb6
{ A key move that prevents ...b7-b5, Black's only active plan, and leaves the enemy pieces rather cramped. }
12... Qxb6 13. Bxb6 Ne8
{ Parrying the threat of 14 Bc7.   Neither  13...Nd7  14.Bc7   @@StartBracket@@nor  13...e5  14.f5  was any good for Black@@EndBracket@@   While  13...Bd7  14.e5  dxe5  15.fxe5  Nd5  16.Nxd5  exd5  17.Bf3  Rac8  18.Bxd5  Bf5  19.Bb3  clearly favours White - Anand. }
14. e5
{ Increasing the pressure on Black's camp and, for the long term, restricting his knight on e8. }
14... d5 15. f5 Bd7 16. Bg4
{ More precise than  16.fxe6  fxe6  17.Bg4  , when  17...Bc8  , followed by ...g7-g6 and ...Ng7, lets Black liberate himself to some extent. Now in contrast, ...g7-g6 will always fail to f5-f6. }
16... Bc8
{ Retreating the bishop doesn't seem right, but the threat of   16...--  17.fxe6  fxe6  18.Nxd5  had to parried.   Instead,  16...exf5  17.Bf3  and Nxd5 next clearly favours White   While  16...Bb4  is strongly met by  17.fxe6  Bxe6  18.Nxd5  Bxg4  19.Rd4  , recovering the piece with a clear advantage due to the miserable knight on e8. }
17. Rhf1 a5
{ Perhaps preparing ...a5-a4 and ...Ra6 in order to expel the annoying bishop, but White easily prevents this idea with his next move. }
18. Na4 f6
{ Complicating the game when behind in development tends to be a bad idea, though Black was short of good alternatives; e.g.  18...Ra6  19.Be2   Or  18...exf5  19.Bxf5  Be6  20.Nc5  and White wins material. }
19. fxe6 fxe5 20. Nc3 Bg5+
{ On the natural  20...Rxf1  21.Rxf1  Nf6  Anand had prepared the nice blow  22.Rxf6  , when  22...gxf6   @@StartBracket@@ while after  22...Bxf6  23.Nxd5  a4  24.c4  the black pieces prove decisively restricted@@EndBracket@@  23.Nxd5  Kf8  24.Nxe7  Kxe7  25.Bc5+  leads to a new white queen. }
21. Kb1 Nf6 22. Nxd5 { A well-calculated temporary sacrifice. } 22... Nxg4 23.
Rxf8+ Kxf8 24. Nc7 Ra6 25. Bc5+
{ A key part of White's combination, which moves the black king away from the e-pawn. }
25... Kg8 { 25...Be7  runs into  26.Rd8  . } 26. Nxa6 Bxe6
{ Or  26...bxa6  27.e7  Kf7  28.Rd8  etc. } 27. Nc7
{ Anand later converted his extra exchange into a full point. } *

