[SetUp "1"]

9... O-O
{ Black simply continues with the development, seeing that if White takes the pawn, then her king will be subject to an annoying check on b4.   Instead,  9...dxc4  10.Qxc4  is less appealing   Whereas the game continued  9...Qa5  10.cxd5  exd5   ➡️ @@StartBracket@@even worse is  10...O-O  11.d6  @@EndBracket@@   ➡️ @@StartBracket@@Or  10...Nxd5  11.Qxg7  Bf6  12.Bb5+  Ke7  13.Bg5  etc@@EndBracket@@  11.Bb5+  Kf8   ➡️@@StartBracket@@White exploits the fact that after  11...Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Black has no good recapture@@EndBracket@@  12.O-O  Be6  13.Be5  with a clear advantage due to Black's badly placed king. }
10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nxd5
{ 11.Be2  Be6  12.O-O  with a slight advantage is objectively better. } 11...
Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Bb4+ { A key move that severely exposes the white king. } 13. Ke2
Qb6
{ 13...Qb6  intends to meet  14.Qd4  Bc5  .  With 14...Be6 coming up next, Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. }
