[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "E.Bareev-A.Mikhalchishin  European Team Championship,  Plovdiv 2003  Queen’s Gambit Accepted "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4
{ The most straightforward reaction to the Queen's Gambit Accepted. } 3... Nf6
{ A popular reply, which leads to play reminiscent of the Alekhine's Defence, but with a stronghold on d5 for Black.   3...e5  is the other main direction. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 6. Bd3
{ In the event of  6.Bb3  Black usually continues  6...Nc6  7.Be3  Bf5  , exploiting the opponent's absence on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
6... Nc6 7. Ne2
{ Since  7.Nf3  is well met by  7...Bg4  , White brings the knight to e2.   7.Be3  Nb4  8.Be4  f5  9.exf6  exf6  , followed by ...f6-f5, is another frequently played line. }
7... Bg4 { Before settling with the bishop on e6, Black provokes f2-f3. } 8. f3
Be6 9. Nbc3 Bd5
{ Preparing ...e7-e6.   Practice also sees  9...Bc4  with the same purpose   while  9...Qd7  10.Ne4  Bd5  11.Nc5  Qc8  , followed by ...e7-e6, is yet another option. }
10. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ Or  10...Nxd5  11.a3  e6  12.O-O  with a slight white advantage - Bareev, though this may be Black's safest choice. }
11. Be4 Qd7
{ Your move... @@StartBracket@@The exercise starts on the next variation@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "E.Bareev-A.Mikhalchishin  European Team Championship,  Plovdiv 2003  Queen’s Gambit Accepted "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kb1r/pppqpppp/1nn5/4P3/3PB3/5P2/PP2N1PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. e6
{ A timely pawn sacrifice that complicates Black's kingside development. }
12... fxe6 { Obviously  12...Qxe6  now fails to  13.d5  . } 13. Bxc6
{ A surprising exchange, but it helps White in quickly installing the other bishop on e5, thus keeping his central grip. Other moves, such as  13.Qc2  , permit  13...g6  and 14...Bg7 with normal development. }
13... Qxc6 14. Bf4 Nd5 15. Rc1 Qb6 16. Be5 Rg8
{ Bareev was ready to sacrifice another pawn in order to keep the initiative, but Mikhalchishin gives priority to his development.   Instead,  16...Qb4+  17.Kf2  ;   Or  16...Ne3  17.Qa4+  c6  18.Kf2  leads nowhere for Black.   While after  16...Qxb2  17.O-O  Ne3  18.Qa4+  , both  18...b5   @@StartBracket@@and  18...c6  19.Rfe1  , followed by 20. Rab1@@EndBracket@@  19.Qa6  Nxf1  20.Qc6+  Kf7  21.Kxf1  , preparing Nf4, offer White excellent compensation for the material. }
17. Nc3 c6
{ Again,  17...Qxb2  yields White clear compensation after  18.Nxd5  exd5  19.O-O  c6  20.Rb1  Qxa2  21.Rxb7  - Bareev. }
18. Qe2 g5 19. O-O Rg6
{ Reinforcing the kingside.   White also keeps the initiative after  19...Bg7  20.Bxg7  Rxg7  21.Qe5  Kf7  22.Ne4   Or  19...Nf4  20.Qe4  Bg7  21.Bxg7  Rxg7  22.g3  Nd5  23.Na4  , with 24. Nc5 next - Bareev. }
20. Kh1 Nf4 21. Qc2 Bg7 22. Na4
{ Heading for the excellent square on c5.   There followed  22.Na4  Qb5  23.Bxg7  Rxg7  24.Nc5  Rg6  25.Rfe1  b6  26.a4  Qb4  27.Nxe6  Qd6  28.Nxf4  gxf4  29.Re4  with a slight but enduring advantage, which Bareev later converted into a win. }
