[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "W.Steinitz-C.Von Bardeleben  Hastings 1895  Italian Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ A sharp version of the Italian, which has kept its popularity to modern times, in particular at club level.   7.Bd2  Bxd2+  8.Nbxd2  d5  leads to quieter play. }
7... d5
{ This counterstrike will just accelerate White's attack.   The main line goes  7...Nxe4  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.d5  Bf6  10.Re1  Ne7  11.Rxe4  d6  with a heavy theoretical battle. }
8. exd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Be6
{ Or  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Qb3  Bxa1  12.Bxf7+  Kf8  13.Ba3+  Ne7  14.Rxa1  , followed by Re1, and White wins. }
10. Bg5 { Development with tempo. } 10... Be7
{ At this point  10...Qd7  11.Bxd5  Bxd5  12.Re1+  Kf8  was Black's safest choice, but he prefers a more obvious reply. }
11. --
