[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "W.Steinitz-C.Von Bardeleben  Hastings 1895  Italian Game"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/ppp1bppp/2n1b3/3n2B1/2BP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Bxd5
{ Clearing the e-file is White's main priority.   Of course,  11.Bxe7  Ncxe7  was less powerful. }
11... Bxd5
{ After  11...Bxg5  12.Bxe6  fxe6  13.d5  exd5  14.Nxg5  Qxg5  15.Re1+  , intending  15...Ne7  16.Nxd5  , Black is also in big trouble. }
12. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ Or  12...Bxg5  13.Re1+  Be7  14.Nxe7  Nxe7  15.Qe2  with an improved version of the game. }
13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Re1 f6 15. Qe2 Qd7
{ White has managed to keep Black's king in the centre, and should now act quickly before the latter consolidates with ...Kf7 and ...Rhe8. }
16. Rad1
{ Zaitsev's suggestion, which aims at a quick d4-d5.   In contrast, the game continued  16.Rac1  c6   @@StartBracket@@however, by  16...Kf7  Black would have obtained excellent chances of survival@@EndBracket@@  17.d5  cxd5  18.Nd4  Kf7  19.Ne6  and Steinitz went on to win, with a final combination that has become a classic. }
16... Kf7 { Or  16...c6  17.d5  cxd5  18.Rxd5  etc. } 17. Qc4+ Nd5 18. Ne5+
fxe5 19. dxe5
{ With double threats at d5 and e6, White is winning.   19.dxe5  Ke6  fails to  20.Qg4+  . }
