[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "J.Lundin-Th.Ernst  Karlstad 2010  Grünfeld Defence "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rqk2r/p2bppbp/1pn3p1/8/3P4/4P1P1/P3NPBP/1RBQ1RK1 w k - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Bd2
{ Restricting ...Na5-c4 is White's main priority here.   Less to the point was  13.e4  O-O  14.Be3  Na5  with ...Nc4 next. }
13... O-O 14. Rc1
{ The rook had fulfilled its duty on b1 and now helps White in disputing the open file. }
14... e6
{ After  14...e5  15.d5  Na5  16.Bb4  , followed by d5-d6, White has the initiative. }
15. Qb3 b5
{ A typical idea, but here it is badly timed due to White's strong reply.   15...Qf6  , connecting the rooks, seems preferable   but not  15...Qe7  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Bb4  etc. }
16. Rc5 a6 17. Qc3 Qb6 18. Rc1 Na7
{ A bad location for the knight, where it even becomes a target on the next move.   18...Ne7  was called for, when White could proceed as in the game. }
19. Rc7
{ As often happens, the victory in the fight for the open file leads to the seizure of the seventh rank. }
19... Bf6
{ The ...Bd8 plan is one tempo too slow, though Black was short of good options anyway. }
20. Qc5
{ This wins material; but  20.Qa5  Qxa5  21.Bxa5  was even stronger, when Black loses a whole piece. }
20... Qxc5 21. R1xc5 Be7 22. Rxa7 Bxc5 23. dxc5 Bc6 24. Rxa6
{ White later converted his material advantage into victory.   At this point  24.Rxa6  Bxg2  25.Kxg2  Rxc5  fails to  26.Bb4  . }
*

