[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "A.Khalifman-V.Filippov  Russian Team Championship 1995  Semi-Slav Defence"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1k2r/pp3ppp/2p1p1n1/8/1BP1q3/8/PP1QBPPP/R3K1NR w KQkq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10. Nh3
{ An excellent move that takes the f4-square from the enemy pieces, while continuing development.   In contrast,  10.O-O-O  Qf4  lets Black swap queens   and  10.Nf3  Nf4  isn't convincing either. }
10... f6
{ Creating a haven for the king on f7.   Most other moves, such as  10...Qxg2  , are well met by  11.O-O-O  , just as in the game. }
11. O-O-O Kf7 12. f3 Qh4
{ Or  12...Qe5  13.f4  Qc7  14.Bd6  Qd8  15.c5  with a clear edge - Khalifman. }
13. Bc5 { Enabling the powerful knight manoeuvre Nf2-e4. } 13... e5 14. Nf2 f5
15. g3 Qf6
{ After  15...Qh6  16.Be3  f4  17.gxf4  , both  17...Nxf4  and   17...exf4  18.Bd4  18.Nd3  clearly favour White - Khalifman. }
16. Rhf1
{ A 'mysterious' rook move that aims at bringing the knight to e4 anyway. }
16... Na6
{ 16...Nd7  was safer, enabling a later ...Nf6, although  17.Ba3  Qe6  18.Qc2  , with the double idea of 19 Rd6 and 19 Bd3, maintains excellent compensation for White. }
17. Ba3 Be6 18. Ne4 fxe4
{ Or  18...Qd8  19.Ng5+  Kf6  20.Qc3  Qb6  21.f4  , winning - Khalifman. } 19.
fxe4 Nf4 20. gxf4 Rhd8 21. Bd6 Kg8 22. fxe5 Qh4 23. --
{ At this point, there followed  23.Qf4  Qxf4+  24.Rxf4  with a superior endgame, which White went on to win.   However, the simple  23.Qe3  , preparing Rf2 and Rdf1, would have left Black with a hopeless position at once - Khalifman. }
