[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "A.Shirov-P.Eljanov  Moscow 2010  Caro-Kann Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5
{ We already came across this line in Bologan-Dizdarevic. There Black preferred  5...Ne7  , followed by ...Bg6 and ...Nf5, whereas on this occasion he strikes immediately at the white pawn chain. }
6. Be3 Nd7 7. O-O Ne7
{ Here and on the previous move,  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bg6  9.c4  yields White some initiative. }
8. c4
{ This is indeed a key advance in the current variation, in order to open the position for White's better developed forces.   In contrast,  8.c3  Nc6  , followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O, yields Black fewer problems. }
8... dxc4 9. Na3 c3 10. Nb5
{ Not  10.bxc3  Nd5  , when Black wins a tempo by attacking the c3-pawn   but a gambit with  10.Bg5  was interesting as well. }
10... Nd5 11. Nxc3 Nxc3
{ 11...Nxe3  12.fxe3  Be7  seems safer, as in A.Morozevich-G.Kamsky, Moscow 2008, which continued  13.Qb3  O-O  14.Qxb7  Rb8  and it was actually Black who decided whether or not to repeat moves. }
12. bxc3 Be7 13. dxc5 Bxc5
{ 'Big mistake' - Shirov.  13...O-O  14.Nd4  was a lesser evil, with just a slight white advantage - Golubev. }
14. --
