[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2b1Pb2/8/2P1BN2/P3BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Qa4
{ 14.Qa4  prevents  14...O-O  on account of  15.Rfd1   or  15.Rad1  .   In this sense  14.Bb5  Bxe3  15.fxe3  a6  was less convincing. }
14... Bxe3
{ The attempt to castle queenside by  14...Qc7  15.Rfd1  O-O-O  runs into  16.Nd4  Nxe5  17.Nb5  Qb6  18.Bxc5  Qxc5  19.Qa5  - Golubev.   After  14...Bxe3  Black was perhaps hoping for  15.fxe3  O-O  16.Rad1  Nc5  , but Shirov has a much stronger move prepared. }
15. Rad1 a6
{ Black parries the threat of  15...--  16.Rxd7  Qxd7  17.Bb5  , but the troublesome pin along the d-file remains. }
16. fxe3 b5 17. Qf4 Qc7
{ Or  17...O-O  18.g4  Bg6  19.h4  with a strong kingside attack, just like the game. }
18. g4 Bg6 19. h4 h5
{ After  19...h6  20.h5  Bh7  21.g5  Bf5  22.e4  Black is also under pressure. }
20. Rd6 hxg4 21. Nd4 Nc5
{ By his clever 20th move White secured the vital e5-pawn, and the attempt to attack it by  21...Qc5  now fails to  22.Nxe6  fxe6  23.Rxe6+  , followed by Rxg6.   Instead,  21...O-O  seems preferable, when  22.Bxg4  maintains the attack - Golubev. }
22. Qxg4 Qe7
{ Eljanov must have missed White's next move.   For better or worse,  22...O-O  23.h5  Be4  24.h6  Bg6  had to be tried. }
23. Bf3
{ 23.Bf3  not only attacks the rook, it also creates the threat of  23...--  24.Bc6+  Kf8  25.Qxg6  . }
23... Rxh4
{ This move fails fatally; though after  23...O-O  24.Bxa8  Rxa8  25.h5  Be4  26.h6  Black would be lost anyway. }
24. Bc6+ Kf8 25. Qxg6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises Chapter 4"]
[Black "G.Sosonko-R.Hübner  Tilburg 1979  Catalan Opening"]
