1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 a6 6. O-O b5
{ 6...Nc6  is more popular, familiar to us from Ricardi-Hellsten. } 7. Ne5 Nd5
{ An alternative is  7...c6  ; e.g.  8.Nxc6  Qb6  9.b3  cxb3  10.Na5  Ra7  11.Nxb3  Rd7  12.e4  Bb7  13.Qe2  Be7  , as seen a few times in practice. }
8. Nc3 { Nowadays,  8.a4  Bb7  9.b3  is more frequent here. } 8... c6
{ A rather slow move that lets White take a clear initiative.   8...Bb7  is much more popular, when  9.Nxd5  exd5  10.e4  dxe4  11.Qh5  g6  12.Nxg6  fxg6  13.Qe5+  Qe7  14.Qxh8  Nd7  leads to a double-edged battle. }
9. Nxd5 exd5
{ Or  9...cxd5  10.e4  Bb7  11.Qh5  , when  11...Qc7   @@StartBracket@@and  11...g6  runs into  12.Nxg6  fxg6  13.Qe5  @@EndBracket@@  12.exd5  Bxd5  13.Bxd5  exd5  14.Re1  is bad for Black - Sosonko. }
10. e4 Be6 11. a4
{ A typical Catalan advance, which softens up the black pawn phalanx. } 11...
b4
{ The desirable  11...Be7  fails to  12.axb5  cxb5  13.exd5  Bxd5  14.Nxf7  Kxf7  15.Qh5+  etc - Sosonko. }
12. exd5 Bxd5
{ Too materialistic.   For better or worse  12...cxd5  13.Nxc4   @@StartBracket@@although the sharper  13.f4  can also be considered - Sosonko@@EndBracket@@  13...Be7  , followed by ...O-O, had to be tried. }
13. --
