1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 e6 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bf4 a6
{ In most opening variations a fianchetto is completed immediately, but here  7...Bg7  permits  8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Qb3  with good results for White in practice. }
8. e4
{ The most ambitious, trying to break in the centre before Black is developed.   After  8.a4  Bg7  normal Benoni play is reached. }
8... b5 9. Qe2 Nh5
{ White's previous move made 10. e5 a real threat, so Black takes preventive action. }
10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bh6 Bf8 12. Qe3
{ In this opening, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is usually an achievement for White. }
12... Bxh6 13. Qxh6 b4
{ Since the immediate  13...Qf6  is strongly met by  14.e5  dxe5  15.Ne4  - Franco.  Black first expels the enemy knight from c3, but in doing so creates an outpost for White on c4.   The flexible  13...Nd7  was preferable - Yusupov. }
14. Nd1 Qf6 15. Nd2
{ With the dual intention of  15...--  16.Nc4  and  16.g3  , restricting the knight on h5. }
15... Bd7
{ Again  15...Nd7  seems more natural, although after  16.g3  Ne5  17.Be2  Ng4  18.Bxg4  Bxg4  19.Ne3  White keeps the advantage - Yusupov. }
16. --
