1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 a6 7. O-O b5
{ As mentioned elsewhere in the book, this is a rather risky line for Black.   The ...b7-b5 advance works better if prepared by  7...Qc7  or  7...Nbd7  . }
8. Bf3 Ra7 9. a4
{ Immediately hitting Black's fragile queenside before he is comfortably developed. }
9... b4 10. Na2 d5
{ Securing the b4-pawn, at the cost of allowing White a certain dominance in the centre.   Perhaps  10...e5  11.Nb3  Rb7  was more promising, although after  12.c3  bxc3  13.Nxc3  Be6  14.Nd5  Bxd5  15.exd5  Qb6  16.Nd2  , heading for c4 @@StartBracket@@-a5@@EndBracket@@ , White had the initiative in S. Vajda-C.Florescu, Bucharest 2000. }
11. e5 Nfd7 12. Bf4 Be7 13. Bg4
