1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6
{ Quite a popular choice in contemporary practice, in order to find out straight away how Black is going to recapture on c6. }
4... dxc6 5. d3
{ If White is bothered by a bishop move to g4 then he could play  5.h3  here, although in that case Black obtains the additional option of  5...e5  , when  6.Nxe5  runs into  6...Qd4  . In contrast, after the text Black would have to prepare ...e7-e5 by ...Bg7. }
5... Bg4 6. Nbd2
{ Another option is  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  , followed by Nd2-c4. } 6... Bh6
{ A curious deviation from the normal 6...Bg7. Black aims at equalizing by exchanges, but the remainder of the game shows us that things aren't that simple. }
7. h3 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 Bxc1 9. Qxc1 Qa5+
{ If  9...Nf6  , then  10.Qh6  is a bit annoying - Finkel. } 10. c3 Rd8
{ The point of Black's previous move; now after  10...Rd8  11.Qe3  Nf6  , thanks to the pressure at d3, he would manage to castle. However... }
11. O-O { An intuitive pawn sacrifice motivated by the lead in development. }
11... Rxd3
