12. e5
{ With the simple, but powerful idea of preventing ...Nf6. As a result, Black's development is seriously hampered.   In contrast,  12.Ne5  Rd8  13.Qf4  Nf6   or  12.Qf4  Nf6  13.Qb8+  Rd8  14.Qxb7  Qb6  is less convincing. }
12... Qd8
{ 12...e6  , preparing a quick ...Ne7, was preferable, despite the weakening of the d6- and f6-squares. There can follow  13.Ng5  Qc7  14.Qf4  Rd5  15.Rfe1  h6  16.Ne4  g5  17.Qg3  Qxe5  18.Qxe5  Rxe5  19.Nd6+  Ke7  20.Rxe5  Kxd6  21.Re2  with just a slight edge for White in the endgame - Finkel. }
13. Qf4 { Threatening both  13...--  14.e6  and  14.Ng5  . } 13... Qd7 14. e6
{ The e-file and the h2-b8 diagonal are cleared for the major pieces, and the knight gets access to e5. }
14... Qxe6 15. Rfe1 Qf5 { Or  15...Qd6  16.Ne5  , winning - Finkel. } 16. Qb8+
Rd8 17. Qxb7 Qd7 18. Qb3 Nh6
{ Overprotecting the f7-pawn.   After  18...Nf6  19.Ne5  Qd5  20.Qa4  , the double threat of  20...--  21.Nxc6  and  21.Rad1  is more than Black can take. }
19. Rad1 Qc7 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Qb7
{ Finally, White regains the material, with some interest. } 21... O-O 22. Qxa7
Qd5 23. Qxe7 Qxa2 24. Ng5
{ Eyeing both the h7-pawn and the e4-square.   The straightforward  24.Qxc5  Qxb2  25.Qxc6  was less ambitious. }
24... Nf5 25. Qxc5 Qxb2 26. Nxh7 Ra8 27. Nf6+ Kg7 28. Qxc6
{ White later converted his two extra pawns into victory. } *

