[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. A Few Words on Opening Preparation"]
[Black "Plans, set-ups, guidelines and move orders"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Every opening has its particular logic, which can be translated into plans, set-ups and minor guidelines. These should be carefully studied alongside with the 'theory' moves, in order to obtain a complete picture of the opening involved. In 'Strategia', Mark Dvoretsky advocates the study of typical positions, with a similar pawn structure, piece configuration, etc. Such a task is easily accomplished by examining complete, annotated games with a certain typical position in common.An additional, interesting approach is to study a certain opening using the games of a specific player; for example, the Grünfeld by Svidler or the Open Sicilian by Anand. You can then gradually 'copy' their repertoire, seeing how Svidler responds to 4. Bf4, the way Anand handles the Sveshnikov, etc.When studying openings, we should pay special attention to their inherent, basic plans. Some examples:   ➡️ The ...f7-f5 advance in the King's Indian.    ➡️ The d4-d5 break in IQP positions.  ➡️  The ...f7-f6 break in the French.    ➡️  The Nbd2-f1-h2 manoeuvre in the King's Indian Attack.   ➡️  The minority attack with b4-b5 in the Queen's Gambit Exchange Variation.    Having acquired some basic knowledge about the opening in question, you will start noticing the 'right' and 'wrong' moments for the application of these plans. For example, the ... f7-f5 advance in the King's Indian often works better when White has castled short, and it tends to lose some of its power when the d-file is open, just to name a few cases. The Nbd2-f1-h2 manoeuvre in the King's Indian Attack is often powerful when White has achieved the e4-e5 advance, but not so much when it is Black who has a pawn on e5.    Another important issue is the choice of set-ups within a particular opening. For example, in the classical Benoni lines Black is often happy to develop his queen's bishop to g4, and then follow up with ...Nbd7. However, this proves impossible if White chooses a set-up with an early h2-h3 or f2-f3. On such occasions, Black could instead consider a set-up with ...Na6-c7 and ...Bd7.In the King's Indian Sämisch with an early ...c7-c5, d4-d5, White has a slight problem with the king's knight. Thus he might keep it on g1 for a while, waiting to see whether Black plays ...Nbd7, on which he could reply Nh3 followed by Nf2, exploiting the fact that ...Bxh3 is unavailable for the moment. In contrast, if Black prefers a set-up with ...Na6, as in the previous Benoni example, then the white knight could choose the e2-g3 route instead.Again, talking about the King's Indian Sämisch with White, an aggressive set-up with Qd2, O-O-O, Nge2, g2-g4, and Ng3 can be very effective if Black has played ...e7-e5 @@StartBracket@@and White has responded d4-d5@@EndBracket@@. In contrast, after ...c7-c5, White usually avoids such a set-up due to Black's menacing bishop on g7, and opts for short castling instead.In some Slav lines with e2-e3 White restricts Black's intended ... Bf5 by an early Bd3, thus the black bishop often goes to g4 instead. In similar fashion, if White plays h2-h3 early on in the Scandinavian, Black's intention of ...Bg4 can be modified with ...Bf5.In the Pirc with 4. Be3 White has a ready-made, dangerous plan in Qd2, f2-f3, O-O-O, Bh6, h4-h5 etc. Thus Black often delays the natural ...Bg7 and ...O-O until a later stage of the game, starting with 4...c6 . In contrast, against the classical set-ups with 4. Nf3 he rarely waits with ...Bg7, since a white attack along the h-file becomes less feasible once the knight settles on f3.     When studying new opening lines, try to establish 'mini-rules' or simple guidelines that facilitate your understanding of them. For example, in the Classical Variation @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/5b2/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w - - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5  of the Caro-Kann, Black should usually react to h2-h4 with ...h7-h6, and very rarely with ...h7-h5. On the other hand, in the Advance Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  of the same defence, h2-h4 is often more efficiently met by ...h7-h5, than by ...h7-h6.   With Black in the Classical Philidor  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  playing ...c7@@StartBracket@@c6@@EndBracket@@-c5 is normally a dubious idea from a structural point of view, but once White signals his attacking intentions by advancing f2-f4, then ...c7@@StartBracket@@c6@@EndBracket@@-c5 becomes much more reasonable, in order to organize quick counterplay.  As for playing White in IQP positions, if Black hurries to block the d4-pawn by ...Nb4-d5, then the typical plan of d4-d5 has to be discarded, and we could consider a kingside attack instead, with moves like Ne5, Rd3-h3 etc. On the other hand, if Black keeps the knight on c6 and continues his queenside development by ...b7-b5, ...Bb7 etc, then his control of the e5-square makes the previous plan less feasible, while the d4-d5 advance becomes relevant again.   When building your repertoire, also be careful with move-orders. For example, if you enjoy playing the Slav against  1.d4  , then you could consider 1...c6 as a reply to  1.c4  c6  , although in that case you must also be ready for  2.e4  . Now, if by chance you like the Old Indian too, then  2...e5  is a possible choice; e.g.  3.Nf3  d6  4.d4  Nd7  , transposing to that opening. Otherwise you should continue  2...d5  , when it is White who has to think about move orders. If he plays  3.exd5  here, then Black could consider  3...Nf6  , transposing to a sideline of the Scandinavian, where  4.dxc6  Nxc6  is regarded as risky for White - who is left with  4.d4  , when after  4...exd5  we have finally ended up in an initial position of the Panov Attack of the Caro-Kann. However, if this is not to White's taste, then he should prefer  3.cxd5  , after which Black has nothing better than  3...exd5  4.exd5  Nf6  , entering a kind of accelerated Panov Attack, where White often continues  5.Bb5+  or  5.Qa4+  , trying to hang on to the d5-pawn.   Now let's presume that you didn't like the look of this line and that, by coincidence, with the white pieces you enjoy playing the Rossolimo Sicilian. In that case, you could consider meeting  1.c4  by  1...e5  instead, followed by a quick ...Bb4, getting you into familiar territory, albeit with reversed colours.   However, White could also start his English opening with  1.Nf3  , ruling out  1...e5  . The attempt to prepare it by  1...Nc6  unfortunately permits  2.d4  , when a Chigorin with  2...d5  seems like the best choice, and that might not be part of your repertoire. White could also play  2.e4  , when  2...e5  is probably the best reply, but now you must be prepared for a Spanish or Italian, among others. Fortunately, there is a much simpler solution at hand:  1...d5  , followed by  2...c6  , by which you easily reach the Slav structure that we talked about in the first place!   Considering the situation from the English player's perspective, if he likes the positions arising after  1.c4  e5  , then  1.c4  is clearly the right way for him to start the game. In the opposite case, he could play  1.Nf3  first and only then c2-c4, thus sidestepping Black's 1...e5. However, this also means that a set-up with g2-g3, Bg2, e2-e3 and Ng1-e2 will no longer be available for him, among other things. Time for him to check his priorities.Summing up, move orders play an important role when building an opening repertoire. }
